[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Introduction@@HeaderEnd@@Hello dear student!  Welcome to my opening course on 1.d4!  First, you should get to know people who are responsible for this course a bit better!  Profile and Achievements  My name is Angelika Valkova, but you also might know me as Angelika Chessborn, because I am a chess Streamer on Twitch. I come from Nikopol, Ukraine, and live in Karlsruhe, Germany. I study at Karlsruhe Institute of Technology and have achieved a Master's degree in Philology at Kyiv Polytechnic Institute in December 2020.  I started playing chess at the age of  5. I am a Candidate for the Masters of Sports of Ukraine, bronze champion of Ukraine in the youth categories. I also won some open tournaments, such as Schachtürken-Cup 2016 @@StartBracket@@group B@@EndBracket@@, and St. Pauli Open 2014 @@StartBracket@@group B@@EndBracket@@. I am the Women Blitz champion of Württemberg 2019 and Women Team champion of Germany 2018, and 2019. I play for SF Deizisau in the first Women’s Bundesliga. Moreover, I am the Head of Women Chess in the Federation of Württemberg and also help in the organisation of chess events in Germany.  Besides being an active chess player myself, I help other people to improve their chess skills. I've been coaching children and adults since 2015.  Until last summer I was playing chess without any deep opening knowledge or much preparation/studying. Since last year I’ve been working with GM Gyula Pap, who taught me that it is essential to have a solid knowledge of openings in order to achieve higher goals in chess. It was the moment when I started to dig deeper into my favourite opening with the White pieces and here we are. :@@EndBracket@@  By the way, GM Gyula Pap, who is my coach, is a big contributor to this course. The variations you will learn here were created in cooperation with him and were endorsed by him. Gyula Pap is a Hungarian grandmaster with a peak rating of 2578 who was also a second of Richard Rapport.  In addition to giving you a comprehensive1.d4  repertoire, being a students of this course also makes you eligible to participate in live sessions organized by myself and GM Gyula Pap in the Chessable Classroom. A thread will be opened in the course discussion forum where students can submit their questions and games and some of these will then be discussed in the live session.  In the first month after the course publication, two live sessions are planned. The first will be open to all the students. The second merely to those who have purchased the video version of the course. Depending on the experience from the first month of the live sessions and the demand of the students, we will decide whether more sessions will be held in the future.  So, now you found out some information about the people standing behind this course, you are probably wondering which lines the course consists of. }
1. d4
{ This course is a full repertoire on  1.d4  and is followed up by 2.c4 in the case of Black’s main responses  1...d5  2.c4  or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.c4  , so it is a very classical repertoire in that sense.   However, as you will see against some of the first moves of Black  1...d6  or  1...g6  we are even going to transpose to 1.e4 territory, so you’ll be able to learn about a wide variety of different positions and structures.Actually, this was one of the main ideas of my coach, when he helped me to choose the lines for the course: that I should not only learn opening variations, but about the game in general, and having a great diversity among the arising positions from different lines can be very useful for this purpose.So, if you are looking for a positional, attacking, or tricky repertoire as a whole, then you are not in the right place. :  (The course consists of all the above, but summarising its concept with one of those categories is not possible. Besides variety, another point of my coach was that we shouldn’t give Black what he wants, so we picked systems which can be very unpleasant to face if Black has one clear goal with their opening choice and is not able to adjust quickly. Let me explain more of it in detail:)     Against the ever-popular KID @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  where Black players are into a double-edged fight, with hopes to attack White’s king, we are going to play the flexible Averbakh variation  5.Be2  where it will be basically impossible for Black to launch an attack against our king. On the other hand, the opposite of it can happen pretty often, which is not what Black really wants. Our study is split intoBlack's sidelines andthe main lines after  5...O-O  6.Bg5  c5  .   Against the Benkő Gambit @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  where Black’s main idea is to open the a and b-files with an early pawn sacrifice and get a very strong and active counterplay on the queenside, we don’t accept the pawn but play  4.Qc2  with the idea of playing e4 and keep the initiative for ourselves, as we'll see inthe Benkö chapter.   Against the Slav, well, it is hard to do anything special when Black wants to play a solid opening. We go @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nbd2  A very flexible move employed by GM Rapport a few times. We are taking away quite a few variations for Black after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  as the Chebanenko Slav  4...a6  or the Classical Slav  4...dxc4  . These moves work very poorly here, and as you will see inthe Slav chapter: what seems like an easy thing, to develop the problematic c8-bishop, is actually not so simple.   Against the Grünfeld @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  we are playinga variation which is going to make the well-known ...c5-break a serious mistake in two consecutive moves. Even if Black finds the correct way to play, it will lead to a slightly worse endgame without serious winning chances, which is not something Black is looking for by playing this sharp opening.   If Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  and plans to just play a slow opening and later outplay us, we will sharpen up the game by playing  2.e4  Bg7  3.h4  and will immediatelyask some questions on the kingside.   If Black plays the Dutch @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...f5  we play  2.Nc3  and instead of the complex, strategic fight Black is normally aiming for, we immediately threaten 3.e4 and play in amuch more direct manner than what Black would like to see.   Against the Chigorin Defence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  Nc6  where Black wants to immediately create some imbalance on the board and have active piece play, we are going straight intoa very calm endgame where we will have the advantage with the pair of bishops.   Against the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  , well, the range of Black’s possible responses against any of White’s main moves  4.Qc2  ,  4.e3  or  4.Nf3  is pretty wide, so we’ll go for the forgotten line  4.Qb3  where, if Black wants equality, they have to reply with  4...c5  andas we'll see that will often result in a Hedgehog-type of game, which may not be to the liking of the Nimzo players.   Against the Triangle System @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  , where Black is hoping to sharpen things up very quickly after  4.Nf3  dxc4  or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4  6.Bd2  Qxd4  we are going to play the 'harmless'  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  reaching the Carlsbad structure, andwill try to prove that to develop that c8-bishop is actually not so simple.   Against the Budapest Gambit @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e5  , not only we will not try to keep our extra pawn, but withan almost unexplored concept we are even ready to sacrifice an exchange to keep the initiative for ourselves.  This repertoire could be suitable for the players starting from the beginner level since we want to play with a healthy pawn structure, safe king and keep the initiative. Also, having advantages like the bishop pair or more space are useful things to learn at the beginning of your journey as a player. The most common mistakes from both OTB and online chess are covered as well, so many of these lines are very likely to occur in your games.On the other hand, the upper limit should be at least 2300, since I would like to become a WGM. :@@EndBracket@@ For that reason, in most of the lines, we looked for new ways and improvements with the help of my coach in order to get an objective advantage, so that I can be able to pose real opening problems to players who are much higher rated than me.I hope you will decide to start the journey of 1.d4 opening together with me! I am looking forward to helping you to build your opening repertoire and to improve your opening skills! }
