1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6
{ The most classical move order in the QGD, also known as the Orthodox Queen's Gambit Declined. A very old, ever-popular, solid and perfectly sound opening, which will probably get another boost in popularity since it is the recommendation of IM Sielecki in his recently published 'Keep It Simple for Black' course.Black is fighting for the centre in the classical way, putting pawns there and supporting them with pieces, not giving up space or any other advantage for free. }
4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 c6
{ The most common move order, but after  5...Be7  or  5...Nbd7  we can reach the same positions as in the  5...c6  line.   5...Be7  is already giving up on the ...Bd6 variations, while  5...Nbd7  is closing the c8-bishop's diagonal temporarily, also taking away some possible lines from Black.Please note that  5...Nbd7  6.Nxd5??  would be a huge blunder, since after  6...Nxd5!  7.Bxd8  Bb4+  8.Qd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  Kxd8-+  we ended up one piece down. }
6. e3
{ So, here we are, the starting position of this opening variation. In the Carlsbad structure @@StartBracket@@the one you can currently see on the board@@EndBracket@@, White has two main ideas:1. Play the minority attack on the queenside, which means that White will attack with the 'a-b' pawns against Black's 'a-b-c' pawns, hence the label of the attack. The main goal is to eventually create a weakness on c6 and put Black in a tricky situation. Usually, only one weakness is not enough to win the game, but once Black is stuck with defending that c6-pawn, White can create other threats in the centre or on the kingside.2. Play for the e4-break, which we will do with the help of the f3-move, intending not to get an isolated pawn in the centre in case of ...dxe4, but to be able to keep our central structure very healthy by answering fxe4.Black's main idea against the minority attack @@StartBracket@@a flank attack@@EndBracket@@ is to try to organise counterplay on the other side of the board, so against our king. Instead, when White is pushing for f3-e4, as we will see, they have to counterattack in the centre by playing ...c5 or ...b5-...b4 to kick our knight from c3 and weaken the e4-square. }
6... Be7
{ Black is protecting the f6-knight one more time, so on ...Bf5, Qf3 will do nothing. Instead,  6...Nbd7  changes nothing: after  7.Bd3  Be7  we are back to our current line. }
7. Bd3
{ Stopping the bishop's development to f5. Our other option was to play with  7.Qc2  , but Black plays  7...h6!  there and, even though being tricked is a strong word here @@StartBracket@@since we are still in a completely normal position@@EndBracket@@ against the IM Sielecki's recommended move order 6...h6, we want to playthose lines without Qc2. }
7... Nbd7
{ The most common move in the position. Black can still play with ...O-O in the next move, but they also keep the option of playing with ...Nh5. On  7...O-O  we play  8.Nge2  , since  8.Qc2  h6!  is still something we don't want. }
8. Nge2
{ Basically, this is the moment where White has to decide to play with Nge2 and f3-e4, or Nf3 and the minority attack. My recommendation is to play with Nge2. In the Nf3 lines, Black has found many new, interesting ways to play; I found it especially hard to crack Black's plans connected with ...Ne4. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ Once again, it was important to start with this move instead of the more popular  9.Qc2  , since we want to keep our queen on d1 in case Black ever wants to play ...h6! }
9... Re8
{ I believe this is the position you'll get most often fromthe QGD 3...Nf6 system. }
10. Qc2
{ Finally we can make this move since we are ready to face ...h6 thanks to an important tactical idea! }
10... Nf8 11. f3
{ Preparing e4, but we have to be careful. One of the basic ideas to check when we are ready to push the pawn is what happens after dxe4-fxe4, Ng4! }
11... Ng6
{ Black trapped our bishop on g5 and their next move is ...h6, so we have to hurry with e4! }
12. e4 dxe4 13. fxe4 Ng4 { We are ready for this. } 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qd2
{ Covering the e3-square, and we will kick back the knight in the next move with 16.h3. It is very important that on  15...c5  we have  16.h3!  and  16...cxd4?  is just losing to  17.Nd5!+-  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "07 Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Be7
{ The Alatortsev variation of the QGD. Black's idea is to change the order of the development of the knight and the bishop. This way, White can't play with Bg5 or, even if we can, it will mean that our knight has to go to f3. This is a problem for us in particular, since I advise you to play the Carlsbad structures with Nge2. }
4. cxd5
{ As against every other option for Black on the 3rd move, I suggest taking on d5 right away, creating the Carlsbad structure and limiting our opponent's choices. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ It is very important to bring this bishop outside of the pawn chain; ...g5 is not available this time, so we play with Bf4. }
5... Nf6
{ Black is protecting the d5-pawn. Therefore, from this moment on, we have to take ...Bf5 into account in every move. We have two ways to address that idea:  physically stop this move by playing Qc2 or Bd3  when the bishop comes to f5, we'll try to disturb it by playing Nge2-Ng3 and h4, or by playing f3 and then later e4/g4. }
6. e3
{ The other logical option would be  6.Qc2  , but after  6...Nh5!  we have to go back to some passive square with our bishop, so I don't like this that much. }
6... Bf5
{ The bishop arrived at f5. Now our task is to bother this piece, and definitely no Bd3 for now! }
7. Nge2 c6 8. Ng3 Bg6
{ If instead  8...Be6  , then we can play  9.Bd3  and our opening was a success. We managed to keep that light-squared bishop passive, and we'll play for f3-e4 later. }
9. h4 { Continuing our attack on the light-squared bishop. } 9... h6
{ In general, our task is much easier when Black protects their bishop by playing h6. }
10. h5
{ Fixing the pawns on g7 and h6 gives our knight control over the very important f5-square. }
10... Bh7 11. Bd3
{ And once we have a target or a certain idea in mind @@StartBracket@@placing the knight on f5@@EndBracket@@, suddenly the exchange of bishops is in our favour. }
11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Nf5
{ We have a big advantage and a kingside attack is coming. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "08 Triangle System #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c6
{ The Triangle System. Black is keeping a lot of options with this move order. Just to name a few:  4.Nf3  dxc4  is the Noteboom variation.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  is the Marshall Gambit.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  f5  is the Stonewall.  Since our repertoire is based on playing the Carlsbad structure, thankfully we don't have to learn any of these massively complicated opening lines. }
4. cxd5 cxd5
{ Black can go for the Exchange Slav with this move. However, it is very rare, because Black already played ...e6, so they can't develop their bishop to f5 or g4, which are the main lines of that opening variation. }
5. Bf4
{ Black can play many different move orders from this position. As a rule of thumb, I can say that the main point is that, when they play ...Bd6 after already having played ...Nc6, then we can take on d6 and play with f4. However, if Black plays ...Bd6 without ...Nc6, then we should play with Bg3. }
5... Nf6
{ If instead  5...Bd6  , since the knight is still on b8, we play with  6.Bg3! }
6. e3
{ As long as Black is not moving their f8-bishop, we are not moving our g1-knight either! Therefore, we keep the option of taking on d6 and then playing f4 before the knight comes to f3.   For example, if  6...a6  , we can just continue with  7.Bd3  and we have one more useful waiting move in reserve, Rc1. }
6... Bd6
{ According to our rule, with the black knight still on b8, we are not going to take this bishop. The point is that after  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Bd3  O-O  9.f4  @@StartBracket@@this is the reason why we keep our knight on g1@@EndBracket@@ with the knight on b8, Black has the strong  9...b6!  with the idea of ...Ba6, and they are very close to equality after that exchange. }
7. Bg3 O-O
{ After  7...Nc6  there wouldn't be any ...Ba6, so we could go  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.Bd3  O-O  11.f4  . }
8. Bd3
{ It is also possible to start with  8.Nf3  , but it is better to prevent any Ne4 ideas from Black immediately. }
8... Nc6 9. Nf3 a6
{ If instead  9...Re8  , then our standard reaction is  10.Ne5!  with f4 to follow and Black has a very passive position.   In case of  9...b6  we don't have to do anything special, since ...Ba6 is not an idea anymore.  10.O-O  Bb7  11.Rc1  keeping the tension and inviting Black to take on g3:  11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  Qe7  13.a3⩲  and we a small but stable advantage because of our better light-squared bishop and our chances to create some play on the queenside. }
10. Rc1
{ Just a very useful waiting move! If Black wants to take on g3, they have to open the file for our rook! }
10... Qe7 11. Ne5 Bxe5
{ If instead  11...Bd7  , then we can just play  12.O-O  Rac8  and  13.f4!  with the idea of Bh4, and Black is already in serious trouble. }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 f6
{ Undermining our centre is a must. Otherwise, Black can't develop their pieces. However, at the same time the position is opening for our pair of bishops . }
14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Bh4
{ White has a clear the advantage with the pair of bishops and some serious pressure on Black's centre can arise very soon. For example, O-O, Kh1 and then e4 already looks pretty tempting. }
*

