[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "10 Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines of the Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing to the Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Our strategy in this opening variation is to play for e4. We can prepare for this by playing Ne2-g3, f3 and, very often, even a rook lift via a2. If we can manage to do so, and can even push e5, then our position is just much better. Black's goal is obviously to stop this idea, or to prepare for the moment when we are playing e4 to attack our centre by using some tactical tricks. }
8... c5
{ Black can also start with  8...b6  , but eventually they will have to play ...c5, so we will transpose to  8...c5  . One sample line is  8...b6  9.Ne2  Ba6  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  c5  12.f3  Re8  13.Ng3  Nc6  and we are back to  8...c5  . }
9. Ne2 b6
{ This is Black's most logical move. They want to exchange their bad bishop for our strong piece on d3. When I say bad bishop, I mean that Black's central pawn is on a light square @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@, therefore seriously restricting the scope of the c8-bishop. If we look at the same thing in our camp, we can say that our bishop on d3 is good, since our central pawns are on dark squares @@StartBracket@@c3-d4-e3@@EndBracket@@.Of course, that also means that if the other bishop is not outside of this chain, it is, on paper, a bad bishop. Of course, this is not so clear in our case, since our play is all about pushing e4, and then the c1-bishop could become a very strong piece. }
10. O-O Ba6 11. f3
{ Black is exchanging their bad bishop and White is preparing to push e4. Everything is going very logically. }
11... Re8
{ It is always useful to include this move for Black. The rook helps to slow down e4. }
12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6
{ That's what Black should do: attack the e4 and d4-squares many times to make it as difficult as possible for White to break through. }
14. Bb2 { We are doing the same: all forces to support the e4 and d4-squares. }
14... c4
{ The most popular move in the position, but it looks dubious and just makes our play much easier. }
15. Qe2 b5 16. Rae1
{ My suggested improvement over  16.e4  . More detailshere. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "11 Tarrasch Defence #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. dxc5
{ As I said, there have been many new developments in the main lines starting with  6.g3  , so it makes sense to go for a lesser-known line that can't bring us many surprises and will guarantee a small edge. }
6... Nf6
{ For now Black is just protecting the pawn on d4, and wants to recapture on c5 in the next move. }
7. Be3 { But we are not giving up on that pawn anymore! } 7... Qa5
{ Targeting the pawn on c5 one more time. } 8. Nd4
{ And we are defending it by tactical means.  8...Bxc5  is not possible because of  9.Nb3+- }
8... Ne4
{ Black is threatening both c5 and c3, but we have a solution to keep the extra material. }
9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qa4 { Forcing the exchange of Black's strongest piece. } 10...
Qxa4 11. Nxa4
{ White keeps the extra pawn, and will finish the development by playing Bd4-e3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "12 Tarrasch Defence #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. dxc5
{ As I said, there have been many new developments in the main lines starting with  6.g3  , so it makes sense to go for a lesser-known line that can't bring us many surprises and will guarantee a small edge. }
6... d4
{ The absolute main line. Black is not wasting time in protecting this pawn, but rather pushes it to a protected square. }
7. Na4
{ Protecting the c5-pawn. This is one of the rare cases when it is better to go with the knight to the rim than to the centre. On e4, the knight would be more exposed to attacks like ...Qd5 or ...Bf5. Our next goal is to play e3 to exchange the d4-pawn and finish our development. }
7... Bxc5
{ By far the best move in the position is to take back the pawn immediately. Instead,  7...Nf6  is not addressing our next move  8.e3  at all and after  8...Bg4  9.Be2  Black is already in trouble:  9...b5  is just losing to the nice  10.Nxd4!  , while after  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2P5/N2p2b1/4PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxc5  10.O-O  Be7  11.Nxd4  Bxe2  12.Nxe2±  we ended up with an extra pawn.   7...Bf5  is a little bit better than ...Nf6, but still very dubious.  8.e3  d3  was the idea behind ...Bf5, but after  9.a3!  stopping ...Nb4 ideas, it is hard to come up with anything active for Black. A possible line is  9...Nf6  10.b4  Qd5  11.Nc3±  with the idea of pushing b5 and then Nd4 and collect the pawn on d3. }
8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 Qxc5 10. e3
{ The other main line is  10.a3  , which leads to a more complicated play, but  10.e3  just seems very logical. There will be no central pawns anymore and that should favour our bishop pair. }
10... dxe3
{ Black is forced to take, otherwise is just losing the pawn on d4. } 11. Qxe3+
{ It is also very good that simplifying the position comes with a queen exchange. The queen can work pretty well together with the knights, so with this trade, our opponent is also losing chances for active counterplay. }
11... Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 Nf6
{ This is somewhat less precise than  12...Nge7  . White can use their slight initiative to create some weaknesses in the opponent's camp. }
13. Bb5
{ We don't mind giving up the pair of bishops if we can isolate Black's queenside pawns. }
13... O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O
{ Playing for 2 results. Black's task is pretty difficult here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "13 Semi-Tarrasch Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6 4. cxd5
{ We take on d5 now, as we are aiming for the Carlsbad structure. In case of  4.Bg5  , we would give Black the possibility to play with  4...dxc4!  and then the game would take a completely different direction. }
4... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch, an absolutely sound alternative to the much more regular and popular  4...exd5  . This move is only played in 10% of the games, compared to the 90% ofthe Tarrasch 4...exd5. It is quite shocking, but I believe the reason is that the Semi-Tarrasch is really an opening for the highest level and for professional chess.Even though Black doesn't have too many winning chances in general, the position is very solid and a good weapon to neutralise the dangerous, attacking 1.d4 players. }
5. e4
{ Of course, there is no reason not to push e4 if we can do it without any downside. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black is developing with a tempo and finally trades this bishop. Instead,  8...Nc6  9.Be2  Bb4+  10.Bd2  Bxd2  11.Qxd2  O-O  12.Rd1  transposes to  8...Bb4+  . }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Rd1
{ A rare move, only the 5th most popular in the position. The main lines are  11.Bc4  or  11.Be2  . I have seen it from Rapport first, but Kramnik and recently Giri also employed this variation.The main point of this move is to stay as flexible as possible. Black has a few different ways to put their pieces, and with this useful move we are basically saying to Black that first, they will show us what they want, and then we will react accordingly. We don't give up on the d5 idea, but we also don't give up on putting our bishop on d3 to play against the black king. }
11... Nd7
{ Of course, against this move d5 is less effective, since the knight is already blockading the pawn, but in this case we can switch to the Bd3 idea. }
12. Bd3 Nf6
{ Instead,  12...b6  will transpose intothe main line after  13.O-O  Bb7  14.Qe3  . }
13. e5 { We don't even have to castle. We can start the attack immediately. }
13... Nd5 14. Ng5 h6
{ If instead  14...g6?  , then  15.h4!  and Black is already in a lot of trouble. }
15. Ne4 { O-O, Bb1 and Qd3 to come, and we have a very dangerous initiative. }
