[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "14 Slav #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... e6
{ Now we have the opportunity to enter a Closed Catalan by playing  5.g3  , and we can play  5.e3  as well, which would lead us to Anti-Meran territory. Of course, there is a lot of theory after both moves, and our intention with 4.Nbd2 was not to enter main lines. }
5. Qc2 { Preparing to play e4! } 5... Nbd7
{ Instead,  5...Be7  is more passive and less flexible. That bishop could go to d6 and b4 as well.  6.e4  dxe4  7.Nxe4  Nxe4  8.Qxe4  c5  9.Be3  with O-O-O to follow and White will have a nice attack against the black king. }
6. e4
{ The threat is e5 when Black's f6-knight has no square to go to, so taking on e4 is forced. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ By far the best move.  7...Be7  is very passive:  8.Nxf6+  Nxf6  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Bd2!  where we can castle long in the next move and prepare for a kingside attack with g4-g5.   7...Bb4+  is also inaccurate because we can cover the check with  8.Nc3!  O-O  9.Be2  and we keep our slight edge thanks to our space advantage in the centre. }
8. Qxe4
{ It is worth comparing this position with a better-known variation where we are getting the same structure: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e3  e6  5.Nf3  Nbd7  6.Qc2  Bd6  and here, even though not the main move, a perfectly playable sideline for White is to play  7.e4  dxe4  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Qxe4  .In this variation, White played e4 in 2 moves, and Black used that extra tempo for the very useful developing move ...Bd6. We have an improved version here, as we could play e4 in one go thanks to Nbd2 protecting the c4-pawn. @@StartBracket@@We didn't have to protect it with e3.@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Bb4+ { This is the most logical move. Black is developing with a tempo. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 c5
{ This move is inaccurate, since the knight can't recapture on c5 right away. }
11. dxc5 Qc7
{ Instead,  11...Nxc5?  is bad, because  12.Qe5!  is a double attack and we are winning material. }
12. Qd4 { Attacking on g7 and not letting Nc5 come with a tempo. } 12... O-O
{ Instead, if  12...e5  , then  13.Qd6  Qxc5  14.Ne4!  Qxd6  15.Nxd6+  Ke7  16.O-O-O  with a slightly better endgame for White because of the queenside majority. }
13. Be2 Nxc5 14. b4
{ Kicking back the knight and pushing forward our pawn majority. } 14... Nd7
15. O-O { Ne4-d6 with Rfd1 or c5 to follow is very nice for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "15 Slav #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Bg6
{ This move is still kind of okay, but it gives up the pair of bishops without any compensation for it.  5...Bg4  is similarly giving up the bishop without a fight:  6.h3!  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Nxg6  hxg6  9.Bg2⩲ }
6. Qb3 Qc7
{ Black has to play this move and go for a solid but passive position.   Instead,  6...Qb6?  is already bad though.  7.Qh3!  One of the main tricks of the Nbd2 system is that, by leaving the 3rd rank open, the queen can create double threats using the h3-square.  Nbd7  8.Nxg6  fxg6  9.e3±  With a clearly better position for White. Not only do we have the bishop pair, but also a much better structure. }
7. Nxg6 { Securing the bishop pair advantage. } 7... hxg6 8. g3
{ We will play for e4 so, of course, our bishop's natural square is g2. We are also protecting the h2-pawn along the way. }
8... e6 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O Be7 11. e4
{ There is no reason to delay this move. The knight will have to go from d2 anyway, so our c1-bishop can develop. }
11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nf6 14. Bf3
{ We have a small but long-lasting edge here, because of the bishop pair and the space advantage in the centre. We will have 2 potential ideas to break Black's position. Once they castle, we can consider the plan Kg2-h4-Rh1 and starting active operations on the kingside, but we can also play for b4-b5 to weaken the long diagonal and make our bishop on f3 even stronger. }
