[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "21 Nimzo-Indian #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... Nc6
{ Protecting the bishop on b4 and attacking d4 at the same time, since after ...Nxd4, Qxb4 is not an option: we lose the queen to ...Nc2+. }
5. e3
{ Maybe the most important move to remember of the whole 4...Nc6 variation!  5.Nf3  would be inaccurate because of  5...Ne4!  and Black will take on c3 with the bishop doubling our pawns, and then support their knight with ...f5.By playing e3, we keep the option to kick out the knight from e4 with f3. }
5... O-O
{ Instead,  5...Ne4?!  is exactly the move we prepared against! After  6.Bd3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  f5  8.Ne2±  we'll continue O-O, f3 and later e4. Without the knight on e4, Black's position will be very passive. }
6. a3 Bxc3+
{ Black can insist on keeping the bishop with  6...Ba5  , but after  7.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@with the threat of b4@@EndBracket@@ they will have to eventually take on c3. }
7. Qxc3 a5
{ A normal move for Black, but since it was not in our immediate plans to play with b4, it just gives us extra time to finish the development. }
8. Bd3 d6 9. Ne2
{ This is the setup we want, since it makes the f3-e4 plan possible. } 9... e5
10. f3
{ With O-O and e4 coming, we have a clear advantage, because we enjoy more space and the pair of bishops. Since this position has not been tested in practice yet, I decided to finish the trainable line here. Nevertheless, you'll find more details about how the game can develophere. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "22 Nimzo-Indian #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... c5
{ This is by far the best move for Black, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre at the same time. Also, ...Nc6 will be a much more natural developing move once the knight is not blocking the c-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ The only try for the advantage. We keep Black busy with their bishop. } 5...
Nc6
{ The most natural developing move. Black is still keeping their options: they can play with ...Bxc5 later as well, but they don't give up on the ...Ne4 idea either.   The immediate  5...Bxc5  is possible, but it will transpose after  6.Nf3  with either  Nc6  7.Bg5  or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2b5/2P5/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  7.Bg5  when eventually Black will play ...Nc6. }
6. Nf3
{ Pretty much the only normal developing move we have. If  6.Bg5  , then  6...h6!  and Black is already taking over the initiative. Both  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Rc1  Bxc5  and  7.Bh4  g5!  8.Bg3  Ne4  are preferable for Black. }
6... Ne4
{ Since we don't want a horrible structure, we have to give Black the bishop pair after this move. }
7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2
{ The next moves can happen in all possible orders. Anyway, Black will play ...Bxc5, ...O-O and ...b6-...Bb7 to reach the main line, but there are some inferior possibilities as well. }
8... Bxc5 9. g3
{ Our bishop will be much more active on the long diagonal than it would be after e3-Be2. It is also worth mentioning that, with the bishop on c5, the ...f5-...f4 push is a very legit idea for Black and much more dangerous when we have a pawn on e3, and not on g3. }
9... b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O
{ The move order I used for Black gives our opponent 2 extra opportunities, but with the same idea: trading the g2-bishop. }
12. Rac1
{ More flexible than  12.Rfd1  for example, because sometimes @@StartBracket@@especially in the case of ...f5@@EndBracket@@ we want to keep the d1-square for the queen. }
12... Rc8
{ This move means that Black is probably not playing with ...f5, so we can bring the other rook to d1. }
13. Rfd1 Na5
{ If Black went back to  13...f5  , then  14.e3!  stopping f4-  14...Qe7  and  15.a3!  with the idea of retreating the queen and attacking the bishop with b4. }
14. Qa4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Be7 16. Nde4
{ White has a small but obvious advantage, with some pressure on the d7-pawn. }
*

