[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "23 Benko Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ The sharpest and most tactical line of the whole 4.Qc2 variation. } 7... Ng4
8. Nxd5 Nxe5
{ 8...Bb7?  is a mistake, as later Black can't take on e5 anymore. After  9.Bxc4  Nc6  10.Nf3  Be7  11.Qf5  h5  12.O-O+-  White has complete central domination. Black is just lost. The point is that  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb1p1ppp/2n5/2pNP3/2B3n1/5N2/PPQ2PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ngxe5  is not possible due to  11.Nxe5  Nxe5  12.Qe2!  and with f4 coming in the next move, we are taking the e5-knight because of the pin. }
9. Qe4 d6 10. Nf3
{ After  10.f4  White can still take a piece, but Black will have excellent counterplay in this line.  10...f5  11.Qe3  Be6  12.Nc3  Nbc6  13.fxe5  Nd4  with decent compensation for the piece. }
10... Nc6 11. Bxc4 Be7 12. O-O
{ I prefer this position to the one with 10.f4. Here we have the initiative and Black can't even castle now, because of tactical reasons. }
12... Bb7 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bb5+ Kf8
{ 14...Nd7?  15.Nf6+  gxf6  16.Qxb7+-  Black can't castle and Bxd7 is a winning threat. }
15. Bf4
{ Black's king safety, or rather the lack of it, offers White the easier game and long-term compensation. Rad1 and Rfe1 are easy follow-up moves to play, and then we'll also probably move the queen away from the pin, to introduce Nxe7 ideas. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "24 Benko Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... d6
{ 5...g6  doesn't really have independent value. Either  6.Bxc4  d6  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  will transpose or after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppp1p/5np1/2pP4/2B1P3/8/PPQ2PPP/RNB1K1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.O-O  Black will eventually play d6, so we'll just transpose again. }
6. Bxc4 g6
{ Instead,  6...Nbd7  doesn't change much, since Black will have to play g6 eventually. After  7.Nf3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.Re1  we transpose back to 6...g6. }
7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ I find this the smartest move order. We are not afraid of ...Bg4, and ...Ng4 is not yet a move for Black, so we can delay h3. Depending on Black's reaction, we can also choose between d2 and c3 squares for our knight. }
9... Nbd7 10. h3
{ Once the knight lands on d7, we have to watch out for the ...Ng4-...Ne5 idea, which is typical for this opening and can potentially give our opponent some decent counterplay! For example,  10.Nc3  Ng4!  would give Black chances to create some play! }
10... Nb6 11. Bf1 { Of course we don't give up our bishop for a knight! } 11...
e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6
{ Better than  12...fxe6  13.Be3  Bb7  14.Nc3±  and Black's three central pawns are very shaky. Our idea is to attack them or ruin Black's structure with a well-timed e5-push. }
13. Nc3 d5
{ Of course, Black is not waiting for Bf4 and Rad1 to be left with a weak backward-pawn on d6. }
14. e5 Nfd7
{ If  14...Bf5  15.Bd3  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  Ne8  17.a4±  the d5-pawn has concrete problems. }
15. Bg5 Qb8 16. Bf4
{ Black can't push the central pawns but, besides that, it's hard to see any active plan.White, on the other hand, has quite a few improving moves and ideas. Those include bringing the rook to d1 and pushing the a-pawn, thus increasing the pressure on the d5-pawn, or placing the knight on d6. }
