[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "25 Grünfeld Defence #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... c5
{ In this position,  5...c5  is much more logical than a move before because the bishop is already on g7. It was played in 729 OTB games according to my database, even by very strong Grandmasters. However, it is still a mistake! }
6. dxc5 { With the threat of taking on d5 as well. } 6... Qa5
{ The most logical move, preparing ...Ne4 and putting huge pressure on the c3-knight. Instead,  6...dxc4  is very bad, and leads to a horrible endgame for Black:  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.e4  Be6  9.Nd4!  and Black's structure will be very bad.  9...Nfd7  10.Nxe6+  fxe6  11.O-O-O  with a huge advantage for White. }
7. cxd5
{ Despite all the scary threats we can just take the second pawn! It simply works! }
7... Nxd5
{ Everything is hanging in our position, so taking this knight is basically forced. }
8. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 9. Bd2
{ Obviously we can't take the bishop because of ...Qxc3+ and we are completely lost. }
9... Bxd2+
{ This happens in a lot of games, which is very logical: if Black doesn't know the theory @@StartBracket@@5...c5 is already a sign of that@@EndBracket@@ then it is not so easy to find  9...Be6  . }
10. Qxd2 Qxc5
{ Instead,  10...Qxd2  doesn't create a big test for us:  11.Kxd2!   @@StartBracket@@very strangely, out of 28 OTB games, 27 have seen  11.Nxd2  which is good, but taking with the king is so much easier@@EndBracket@@  11...O-O  12.e4  With Ke3 and Rc1 to follow, we have a winning position. }
11. Rc1 { Bringing the rook into the game with a huge tempo. } 11... Qf5
{ Only move. } 12. Nd4 Qd7 { And again, only move for Black. } 13. Qh6
{ A very nice move, preventing Black's short castle. The knight is not really hanging on d4 since, if Black takes it, their bishop on c8 will drop as well. }
13... Qxd4 14. Rxc8+ Kd7 15. Rc3
{ We threaten to win the queen with Rd3, so Black's king has to go back to e8. }
15... Ke8 16. g3 Nc6 17. Bg2
{ With a winning position for White, since we can castle and Black can't. } *

