[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "32 Old Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Nbd7 4. e4
e5 5. Nf3
{ Developing to the most natural square. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 with the knight at any moment. }
5... g6 { Black chooses to play a King's Indian Defence with ...Nbd7. } 6. Be2
Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ After very natural developing moves, we are at a crossroads now. Many moves and variations are possible for White, of course. Some of them would transpose to big KID lines, which I don't want at all. I'll recommend one system that I believe is quite unpleasant for Black. }
8. Qc2
{ The Qc2-Rd1 setup is a nice way to continue the development. The queen will protect the e4-pawn, while the rook will come to oppose the black queen on the d-file and protect the d4-square. }
8... Re8
{ This is still an okay move, but in the next move Black has to be precise not to get into something really bad. }
9. Rd1 c6
{ 9...exd4!  is the best reply, and after  10.Nxd4  we are transposing back to the 8...exd4 line. }
10. d5 { This move is very unpleasant for Black. } 10... c5
{ Now you can see that Black lost time regarding their kingside play, because they moved the rook to e8, when it would actually stand much better on f8.   Instead,  10...cxd5  is horrible, just opening squares and offering us targets on the queenside:  11.cxd5±  With Nd2-c4, Nb5, and a4-a5 coming, Black is in big trouble. }
11. Bg5 h6 12. Bd2 { We have clear play on the queenside. } 12... Nh7 13. g3
{ Preparing to meet f5 with Nh4. } 13... Rf8 14. Rf1 f5
{ An instructive mistake from Black. } 15. Nh4
{ If Black doesn't want to lose a pawn,  15...Qf6  is forced, but then  16.f4  is coming with great power! }
