[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "33 Czech Benoni"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... Be7
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  , then we still play  6.Be2  and after  6...Be7  we transpose back to the main line. }
6. Be2
{ I like this move order. It keeps the h4-h5 option alive and also, once the f6-knight goes away, we have the Bg4 idea, exchanging our bad bishop. }
6... Nbd7 7. h4
{ As we have seen in earlier lines, keeping the king in the centre is not so unusual for this opening. Instead, we play h4, which gains some space on the kingside, stops ...Bg5 ideas from Black, and sometimes it can be followed up by g4-g5. }
7... h5
{ Or  7...Nf8  8.g3  Anticipating ...Ng6.  8...h5  9.Bg5±  We will finish the development in the next moves by playing f3-Nh3-Nf2, and then can start playing on the queenside with a3-b4.   We could also reply @@StartFEN@@r1bqkn1r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h5  , but that is rushing things a little bit. Black can play  8...h6  and then create some blockade on the g5-square. }
8. g3 g6 9. Nh3 Kf8 10. f3 Kg7 11. Nf2 a6 12. Be3
{ I believe this is a good moment to stop, but I'll show more some possible continuations inthe trainable line. This setup is ideal for us, with chances to play for g4 or b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "34 Modern Benoni #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The Modern Benoni, an asymmetrical opening. Black willingly takes less space in the centre, but they are building their hopes in active counterplay, which normally can come in 2 different ways: either from the queenside @@StartBracket@@playing for ...b5@@EndBracket@@ or from the centre @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ Instead, Black can also start with  6...a6  , but after  7.a4  g6  8.Bf4  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.e3  we are just transposing to  6...g6  . }
7. Bf4
{ My choice against the Benoni is the line with 7.Bf4. It has two main ideas. Most of the time we don't play e4 at all, therefore preventing one of Black's main sources of counterplay  @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and we are already eyeing the d6-pawn. This way, after the bishop leaves f8 and is not protecting the pawn on d6 anymore, we can do some havoc with Qa4+.Black is at crossroads here. They have two completely different ways to play against the Bf4 system. }
7... a6
{ This move is the most solid option. Black completely stops the Qa4 idea. On the other hand, they will not have the ...Na6-c7 idea, which could be very useful to support the ...b5-break. }
8. a4
{ Preventing ...b5 is a must for us. We can't give Black free play on the queenside. }
8... Bg7 9. h3
{ Since we want to play with e3, we need a retreat square for our bishop in case Black attacks it with a potential ...Nh5. }
9... O-O 10. e3
{ You can clearly see what we want in this variation: fighting against Black's active counterplay, and eventually bringing the knight to c4 to attack d6. There is no ...b5 now, and Black can't attack e4 since it is an empty square, so they have to look for some other kind of counterplay. }
10... Ne8
{ Black is defending the d6-pawn with the knight. Therefore, a development with ...Nd7 and even ...Ne5 will be possible thanks to the e8-knight being a very good blockader of the potential passed pawn on d5. }
11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O Ne5
{ Black continues with their idea. This is Serbian GM Aleksandar Indjic's favourite plan. }
13. Bxe5 Bxe5
{ Instead,  13...dxe5  is also possible, but the bishop will not help much in the defence of Black's weakened queenside.  14.a5!  It is important to isolate the c5-pawn and free the a4-square for our knight.  14...Nd6  15.Nd2  f5  16.Nc4  with Na4 to follow. Black has some serious problems to solve. }
14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Ne4
{ Transferring the knight to c4, and attacking the c5-pawn along the way. }
15... b6 16. Nd2 Nd6 { Of course, not  16...Qxd5??  17.Bf3+-  . } 17. Qc2
{ With the positional threat of pushing a5. } 17... a5 18. e4
{ At some point, we will exchange the strong knight on d6 by playing Nc4. Our main break-through idea is to play f4, which can be supported by a rook lift to the kingside via the 3rd rank. }
