[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "36 Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... Bb7 4. d5
{ We close the b7-bishop, and don't allow Black to transpose into a Queen's Indian with moves such as  4.Nf3  . }
4... e6
{ The most logical move for Black, attacking the centre and opening up the f8-bishop.   4...g6?  fails to react to the central situation and just enters a very bad version of the King's Indian Defence.  5.e4  Bg7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Be2  We simply develop and keep our advantage. There is no reason to go into any kind of messy play by pushing e5 so early. Black would welcome any kind of small chaos on the board.  e6  8.O-O  exd5  9.exd5⩲  With a nice plus for White, because of the bad bishop on b7 and the space advantage. }
5. a3 { Of course! We don't want that bishop on b4 pinning our knight. } 5...
exd5 6. cxd5 Bd6
{ 6...Bc5?!  The bishop is completely misplaced here. We should just avoid playing e4 too quickly. That would weaken the g1-a7 diagonal, plus offer a target for the rook once it goes to e8.  7.g3!  O-O  8.Bg2  Re8  9.Nf3  a5  Preventing b4, but once again we don't mind the bishop staying on c5. It puts absolutely no pressure on our centre.  10.O-O±  We can play b3-Bb2, then probably Nh4 to target the f5-square, and later start pushing the e- and f-pawns. }
7. Nf3 { Not allowing the bishop to e5! } 7... O-O 8. g3 c6
{ Undermining the centre and trying to activate the b7-bishop. } 9. Bg2
{ Instead,  9.dxc6  dxc6  10.Bg2  c5  doesn't give much of an edge for White. }
9... cxd5
{ Black is up a pawn, but their position looks strange, and White can develop their play quite smoothly. }
10. O-O Na6 11. Nb5 Be7 12. b4
{ We will place the bishop on b2 and then try to exploit the weakness of the f5-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "37 Budapest Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Bc5
{ By far the best move for Black, forcing e3 and with that closing the diagonal for our c1-bishop. }
5. e3 { Again, Black has to do something: h3 is a threat. } 5... Nc6
{ This natural developing move is the main line. Black is ready to recapture on e5. }
6. Nc3
{ The second most popular move in the position, the first one being  6.Be2  . My recommendation involves a small trick which is very easy to fall into. }
6... Ngxe5
{ The most common and most logical move in the position. Black was ready to take on e5, so why wait? Here comes the point of starting with 6.Nc3 instead of 6.Be2: placing the bishop on the more active square d3 makes a pretty big difference! }
7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. f4
{ Preparing the d3-square for the bishop, but it is also very important that the knight can only go to g6 or c6. When we are building the centre with pawns on e4 and f4, Black's knight would be much better placed on c5 or f6, attacking our e4-pawn. Our opponent would have that chance if we waited for them to play ...d6 and then retreat to d7. }
8... Ng6
{ This square is more passive than c6. On the other hand, at least the knight will not allow us to force weakening moves around the king. }
9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O d6 11. Kh1
{ It is always useful to step out of the diagonal. } 11... f5
{ With this move Black is saying that they are not going to allow e4 for free. However, even after a central exchange, our pieces will be much more active. }
12. Bd2 a6
{ Black doesn't really have any active ideas, so the best they can do is to make some useful waiting moves. }
13. Qc2 { Eyeing the f5-pawn, and thus keeping the rook passive on f8. } 13...
Bd7 14. Rae1 Kh8 15. e4
{ White has mobilised its forces, so now we go for e4. This guarantees a nice initiative which can lead very quickly to an attack against the black king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "38 Dutch Defence #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... d5
{ One of the main lines. Black stops the e4-break, but on the other hand, they are creating a weakness on e5. }
3. Bf4
{ A very natural developing move, which immediately controls the weakened e5-square and introduces the Nb5 idea. This can be a very annoying move for Black if they want to play a plan with ...c5, since they will have to react to Nb5 with ...Na6 to cover the c7-square, but then they can't kick out the knight with ...a6. }
3... a6
{ Black has two main ideas in this position: to play with ...a6 and prepare for ...c5, or to play a Stonewall setup. }
4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6
{ In the next move Black is ready to push ...c5. Of course, they want to do it before developing their bishop, since in this way the recapture on c5 will not waste a tempo. }
6. Bd3
{ We are just developing normally. In case Black does nothing, we can continue with O-O, Ne2 and c4. }
6... c5
{ This happens in 99% of the games. However, Black has an interesting idea, only played in a couple of games, which requires a completely different reaction from us:  6...Nbd7  Black wants to take back on c5 with the knight.  7.O-O  c5  . Here in case of  8.dxc5  Nxc5  Black has a very nice control over the centre, and is much better prepared for our Ne2-c4 idea.   8.Be2!?  is my suggestion instead, with the idea that ...c4 will not come with a tempo and we can undermine it immediately.  8...c4  9.a4!  with b3 to follow, and we have a nice position.   If Black tries to keep the tension with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1n2pp/p3pn2/2pp1p2/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  , then we play  9.Na4!  with the idea of taking on c5 and then playing ...c4.  9...c4  10.Ng5!  forcing the knight to an awkward square.  10...Nf8  11.b3  and White has a strong initiative. }
7. dxc5
{ Our standard reaction to ...c5. We don't want Black to gain a lot of space by playing ...c4 and ...b5 on the queenside! }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O
{ For the time being, our position doesn't look so impressive, since Black has  very nice control in the centre, but Ne2 and c4 are coming. Even if the pawn structure will be symmetrical after that, because the pawn is on f5 and not on f7 Black will have to deal with the very weak pawn on e6 and with the weak square on e5. }
8... Nc6 { 8...O-O  9.Ne2  Nc6  just transposes to  8...Nc6  . } 9. Ne2 O-O 10.
c4 Nb4
{ This is the main line for Black. At least they take our bishop on d3, which could potentially be a very annoying piece on the a2-g8 diagonal, targeting the e6-pawn. }
11. a3 Nxd3 12. Qxd3
{ We have many easy improving moves to make. We'll bring the rooks to the centre, our knights have nice outposts in the middle of the board, and then maybe later we can expand on the queenside by means of b4 and c5. }
