[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "39 Dutch Defence #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg5 { Anticipating both  3...e6  and  3...g6  . } 3... d5 4. f3
{ We want to play e4 in the next move and play a dynamic opening.   The main move is  4.Bxf6  but after  4...exf6  Black found a good setup with ...Nc6-...Be6-...Qd7 and ...O-O-O. Even though, of course, that is also a playable line for White, that character of the game is very different and not necessarily something which I really like for White. }
4... c5
{ Very logical. Black is attacking the d4-square, which is often our weak square when we put a pawn on f3 instead of a knight. }
5. e4
{ There is a huge tension in the centre, with many captures possible, so it is already a critical part of the game. }
5... dxe4 6. dxc5
{ We are ahead in the development, so opening the position should be in our favour. }
6... Qa5 7. Qd2 Nc6 8. O-O-O
{ Our king is already in safety, while its colleague is very far from achieving this in the near future. }
8... Qxc5 9. Bb5 a6 10. Ba4 Be6 11. Bxc6+
{ Using the fact that the bishop is already on e6, so Nge2-d4 can come with tempo. }
11... Qxc6 12. Nge2
{ We are fully developed, whereas Black has issues with their king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "40 Classical Dutch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ Black has to play this move order to reach the Classical Dutch against us, since on  1...f5  we answer  2.Nc3! }
2. c4 f5 3. a3
{ A very rare move. The majority of the games feature  3.g3  or  3.Nf3  . Our idea is to play with Nc3 and not to allow the bishop to come to b4. }
3... Nf6
{ 3...d5  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Bg5  is analysed viathe 3...Nf6 move order.   The same can be said about  3...b6  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  , which is foundhere. }
4. Nc3 b6
{ The main move, and the position we will get can be also reachedvia the English Defence! }
5. Bf4 Bb7
{ And here we are! @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  e6  2.c4  b6  3.a3  Bb7  4.Nc3  f5  5.Bf4  Nf6  , so we can play the same variation against the Classical Dutch and the English Defence. }
6. e3
{ Thanks to the bishop on f4, Black faces serious issues with the c7-pawn in this variation. }
6... d6
{ Trying to restrict the f4-bishop, but this move doesn't work well together with the development of the bishop on b7. The kingside and central light squares are going to be very weak. }
7. Nf3 Nbd7
{ 7...h6  stops the Ng5 idea, but creates more weaknesses on the light squares.  8.Bg3!  It is so hard to make a move with Black here, and we just stepped out from the g5 tempo.  8...Nbd7  9.d5!  Breaking Black's position on the light squares.  9...e5  10.Nh4+-  Black's position has too many holes. }
8. Ng5 { We can already start attacking Black! } 8... Qe7 9. Nb5
{ With a huge advantage for White. One possible nice line is going like this:  9...Kd8  10.c5!  bxc5  11.dxc5  Nxc5  12.Nxd6!  cxd6  13.Bxd6  Qd7  14.Bxc5!  with a winning position for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "41 Keres Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... c5
{ The most logical move. Black understands that they will have to take on d2 at some point, so they are starting the fight in the centre even before that exchange takes place. }
4. a3 { We are gaining the bishop pair. } 4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 cxd4 6. Nf3
{ If we took  6.Qxd4  , then after  6...Nf6  at some point ...Nc6 can come with a tempo. That's why we prefer to recapture on d4 with the knight. }
6... Nf6
{ 6...Nc6?!  is inaccurate:  7.Nxd4  Nf6  8.Nxc6!  bxc6  9.c5!  With Qc2 and Bf4 to follow, Black has problems on the dark squares. }
7. Nxd4 O-O 8. f3
{ The main line is  8.e3  and  8.f3  was only played in 6 games according to my database, but scored a pretty impressive 6-0. The point is that we want to play with e4! and build a perfect centre, while e3 is a somewhat more modest approach. }
8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ If instead  9...dxc6  , then  10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.Bf4  and thanks to the dark-squared bishop we have a clear advantage in that endgame. }
10. c5 { Fixing the black pawns, and creating a strong square on d6. } 10...
Ba6 11. Kf2 { Next is e4 and we will put pressure on Black on the d-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "42 Philidor & Pirc: 2...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6
{ A very flexible first move, and quite an annoying one against some particular repertoires. 'Unfortunately', ours is one of those repertoires.   Black is keeping a lot of options with this move. For example, if  2.c4  they can play  2...e5  , which is quite a double-edged system giving serious counterchances for Black. Also  2.c4  f5  is possible as well, transposing the game into Dutch territory, where we play with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  and not with  2.c4  .   The main move 1.d4 players are playing here is  2.Nf3  , preventing ...e5 and allowing some minor defences like  2...Bg4  . That is not an issue for us, but  2...Nf6  is! Black will play the KID and, since our knight is already on f3, we can't playthe Averbakh system against it. So, we pretty much have no other real choice than playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e4  and go to 1.e4 territory, allowing our opponent to play the Pirc or the Philidor Defence. }
2. e4 g6 3. h4
{ As we can see inthe 1...g6 chapter, this is how we go when our opponent wants to play the Modern Defence. }
3... h6 4. Be3
{ A flexible developing move. I don't want to play Nc3 yet, since it would give Black the chance to play with ...a6-...b5 and then ...Bb7. Of course, this is nothing special, but at least is something active for Black. }
4... Bg7 5. Ne2
{ Again flexible, keeping the knight on b1. For example,  5.Nc3  a6  would transpose into a main line of an opening called Tiger's Modern, with way over 100 OTB games.   Instead, after  5.Ne2  @@StartBracket@@which is by no means a worse move than Nc3@@EndBracket@@ we have exactly zero games. Then, you can understand that it was not a difficult choice to make here. }
5... a6 { Completely harmless when there is no knight on c3. } 6. c4
{ Occupying more space in the centre. Eventually, c4 can be a nice square for our bishop. }
6... b5 7. h5 { Weakening the f5-square for our knight. } 7... g5 8. Ng3 bxc4
9. Bxc4 e6 10. O-O
{ With much better development. We will bring the knight into the game in the next move by playing Nc3, and then we go for active operations like f4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "43 Philidor: 3...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6
{ A very flexible first move, and quite an annoying one against some particular repertoires. 'Unfortunately', ours is one of those repertoires.   Black is keeping a lot of options with this move. For example, if  2.c4  they can play  2...e5  , which is quite a double-edged system giving serious counterchances for Black. Also  2.c4  f5  is possible as well, transposing the game into Dutch territory, where we play with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  and not with  2.c4  .   The main move 1.d4 players are playing here is  2.Nf3  , preventing ...e5 and allowing some minor defences like  2...Bg4  . That is not an issue for us, but  2...Nf6  is! Black will play the KID and, since our knight is already on f3, we can't playthe Averbakh system against it. So, we pretty much have no other real choice than playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e4  and go to 1.e4 territory, allowing our opponent to play the Pirc or the Philidor Defence. }
2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Black wants to play the Philidor not allowing White to exchange queens! } 4.
f4 { This is a very nice inclusion before Nf3. } 4... e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ We are taking with the queen, since it is very well placed in the centre. Now it supports the e5-break and frees the way to our long castle. Also, let's not forget that Black's knight is already on d7, so our queen is not vulnerable to ...Nc6 tempo attacks. }
6... c6
{ The only good option for Black. After other moves, they are much worse or simply lost. }
7. Bd2
{ A surprisingly rare move compared to the main  7.Be3  . We still just want to play O-O-O next move, but without exposing our bishop on e3 to ...d5 exd5 ...Bc5 ideas.   Note that  7.e5  was not that effective anymore, because ...c6 is a big improvement in Black's position. For instance,  7...dxe5  8.fxe5  Bc5  9.Qh4  is the main move, but Black is doing fine after  9...Qe7  10.Bf4  Bb4  . }
7... d5 { This is the main line. Black wants to develop their bishop to c5. }
8. O-O-O
{ As the gameSharapov-Nesterets illustrates,  8.exd5  would give Black some extra options.  8...Bc5  9.Qd3  and  9...Qe7+  . }
8... Bc5
{ 8...c5?  is basically losing:  9.Qa4  d4  10.e5!  The cleanest!  dxc3  11.Bxc3  We sacrificed a piece but we have such a huge development lead that, according to the engine, we are already in +5, so resignable territory.  11...Ng4  12.Bc4+-  With a variety of winning threats. }
9. Qd3 Ng4
{ Going after material before finishing development is rarely a good idea! }
10. exd5 Nf2 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Ne4
{ The key move of the variation. We will take back all the material with interest. }
13... Nxd1 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. Bb4 { Black will lose both knights. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "44 Modern Defence #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4
{ My choice against 1...g6 is very direct and doesn't give Black many options to go wrong or to avoid our preparation. Of course, 1.d4 players are expected to play  2.c4  but, for us, it is not so easy: Black could still transpose to the Dutch with  2...f5  , where we play with 2.Nc3 and not 2.c4.   Also, I found many little lines for Black which we have to meet differently. To show you a few examples:  2.c4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  f5  . If we want to avoid this line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  , then Black can play  3...Nc6  , which is a rare but interesting line, or  3...d6  4.Nc3  e5  . }
2... Bg7 3. h4
{ A very direct way. Our main goal is to push this pawn up to h6 and force Black's bishop back to f8. }
3... d6
{ This move is basically saying that nothing happened on the board with this 3.h4 move, which is not really true.   3...Nf6?  stops h5 but, as the black pawn is not on d6 yet, White can gain a huge advantage with  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Gaining more central control by attacking the knight.  5...Nb6  6.h5  Eventually Black didn't manage to stop this move!  6...d6  7.h6  Bf8  8.f4±  The position resembles the 4 Pawns Attack against the Alekhine Defence, but we can say it is an improved version for us. Our 5th pawn on h6 gives us a huge space advantage and a much better position. }
4. h5 { Black is already facing serious difficulties. } 4... gxh5
{ This move kind of never works for Black, and will always give us a better position. After this, Black has their structure ruined and their king can't castle short anymore.   Instead,  4...c5  is now really bad, because we'll have an extra tempo compared to the 3...c5 variation.  5.dxc5!  Qa5+  6.c3  Qxc5  7.h6!  Bf8  8.Be3  Qc7  and now, instead of the knight on f6, Black has a pawn on d6. Then we don't have to waste time in protecting d4, but can immediately play  9.c4!±  with Nc3 to follow and have a brilliant Maróczy setup.   4...Nf6  is also bad: we can just play  5.h6!  Bf8  6.Nc3±  and Black's position is extremely passive, while we have gained a lot of space on the kingside. }
5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be3
{ We are not in a rush to take back on h5. Qd2 and O-O-O are coming, and then the most unpleasant for Black would be if our knight could reach h5, which is not impossible at all!  @@StartBracket@@Nge2-Ng3-Nxh5 and hitting the bishop@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "45 Modern Defence #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4
{ My choice against 1...g6 is very direct and doesn't give Black many options to go wrong or to avoid our preparation. Of course, 1.d4 players are expected to play  2.c4  but, for us, it is not so easy: Black could still transpose to the Dutch with  2...f5  , where we play with 2.Nc3 and not 2.c4.   Also, I found many little lines for Black which we have to meet differently. To show you a few examples:  2.c4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  f5  . If we want to avoid this line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  , then Black can play  3...Nc6  , which is a rare but interesting line, or  3...d6  4.Nc3  e5  . }
2... Bg7 3. h4
{ A very direct way. Our main goal is to push this pawn up to h6 and force Black's bishop back to f8. }
3... d5
{ The best move in the position. Black is immediately counterattacking in the centre. }
4. e5
{ It was not in our interest to play  4.exd5  and after  4...Qxd5  enter a very weird Scandinavian where we played h4 for basically no reason. }
4... h5
{ This move gives White the necessary time to stabilise in the centre, so I believe  4...c5!  is clearly the right way to go for Black. }
5. Nc3
{ We put some extra pressure on the d5-pawn, thus making c5 more difficult to play for Black. }
5... c5
{ They try it nevertheless!   Instead,  5...Nh6  allows us to develop and stabilise.  6.Bf4  Now the e5-pawn is protected. Obviously, one of the main points of 5...c5 is to weaken and take that pawn.  6...Nf5  7.Nf3±  Everything is under control and Black's position remains pretty passive. }
6. dxc5 d4 7. Nb5 Nc6 8. Nf3 { Very logical, protecting e5 and attacking d4. }
8... Nxe5
{ Or  8...Bg4  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Bxf3  11.Qxd8+  Rxd8  12.gxf3±  with a huge advantage for White because of the 4 vs 2 queenside majority. }
9. Nbxd4 Qa5+
{ Black is taking back the pawn, but we will have some serious development lead. }
10. c3 Qxc5 11. Be3
{ Black will have to move their queen again because of the Nf5/Ne6 threat, so our opponent can't really catch up on development. }
