[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "46 Mexican Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5 square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... e6 { Black's main move by far. } 4. a3
{ Stopping ...Bb4 and preparing to play Nc3. With this, we don't allow Black to play in Bogo Indian-style with ...Bb4, ...d6-...e5 and so on. Instead, they will have to develop the bishop on g7 and play a King's Indian type of position. }
4... d6 5. Nc3 g6 6. d5
{ A rare move, but it is the most compatible with our repertoire. If instead  6.e4  or  6.g3  , then we will enter a King's Indian Defence with an extra tempo since Black is going to play ...e5 in 2 moves and not in 1.Having said that, we used that extra tempo to play a3, which is definitely somewhat helpful in many lines, but it doesn't make as big a difference as to make it worth it to learn a completely new system against the KID. }
6... Ne7 7. dxe6
{ We don't want to wait for Black to play ...e5 and transpose into the KID! }
7... fxe6 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O
{ This position is almost completely unexplored, but I like that our bishops will be great on the long diagonals, whereas Black will not have the usual KID-type of counterplay against our king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted: 3...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... a6
{ Black wants to protect the pawn with ...b5 and develop their bishop to b7. This was once considered to be a very reliable equaliser against 3.Nf3, but modern engines have changed that evaluation. }
4. e3 b5
{ Black can also play  4...Bg4  now since the knight is pinned and White doesn't have Ne5. Following  5.Bxc4  e6  6.h3  Bh5  7.O-O  ,either now or on the next move after Be2, Black will develop their knight to f6 and we will transpose tothe 3...Nf6 4.e3 Bg4 variation. }
5. a4 { We are immediately starting to undermine Black's queenside. } 5... Bb7
{ Developing and protecting the rook on a8. } 6. b3
{ We are winning the pawn back with this move. } 6... cxb3
{ The move is very logical. Black wants to get rid of the whole queenside and make a draw, but they will face concrete problems very soon. }
7. axb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bxa8 9. Bxb5+ c6
{ The first inconvenient move for Black. They have to close the bishop's diagonal.  9...Bc6?  is just losing:  10.Bxc6+  Nxc6  11.d5!  Nb4  12.Qxb3  Nxd5  13.Ne5!  with the threat of Qb5+  13...Qa8  14.e4+-  and the knight can't move because the f7-pawn is falling.   Or @@StartFEN@@3qkbnr/2p1pppp/8/3P4/1n6/1Q2PN2/5PPP/1NB1K2R b Kk - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...c5  13.dxc6  Nxc6  14.O-O+-  and if Black could make 4 moves in a row, then the position would be completely equal but, since it is not possible, they have to resign. }
10. Bc4 e6 11. Qxb3 Nf6 12. O-O
{ Black has to be very careful here. It is not easy to finish the development without losing material. }
12... Be7
{ 12...Bd6?  is already losing material or a lot of time.  13.Ba3!  O-O  14.Bxe6!  and Black is losing a pawn:  14...Bxa3  15.Qxa3+-  . }
13. Ng5 { Putting maximum pressure on the f7 and e6-squares. } 13... c5
{ 13...O-O?  is not working.  14.Bxe6   @@StartBracket@@according to the engine  14.e4  is even stronger, but I believe that the endgame we will get is good enough@@EndBracket@@  14...fxe6  15.Nxe6  Qd5  16.Qxd5  Nxd5  17.Nxf8  Kxf8  18.Ba3+-  With excellent winning chances. }
14. Nc3
{ With huge pressure on Black's position. Instead,  14...cxd4  15.exd4  Bd5  is losing a pawn after  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Qb5+  Nbd7  18.Bxd5  Nxd5  19.Qxd5±  .   The best move according to the engine is  14...Nd5  and after  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Bb5+  Bc6  17.Nf3  Black is most likely still going to lose a pawn; for instance,  17...c4  18.Bxc6+  Nxc6  19.Qa4  Qd7  20.Qa8+  Nd8  21.e4±  breaking up the centre and we will soon collect Black's loose c-pawn. }
14... O-O { This is still not good: } 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Bxe6+ Ke8 17. d5
{ Black's king is stuck in the centre, and we already have 2 pawns for the piece. }
*

