{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... a6
{ Black wants to protect the pawn with ...b5 and develop their bishop to b7. This was once considered to be a very reliable equaliser against 3.Nf3, but modern engines have changed that evaluation. }
4. e3 b5
{ Black can also play  4...Bg4  now since the knight is pinned and White doesn't have Ne5. Following  5.Bxc4  e6  6.h3  Bh5  7.O-O  ,either now or on the next move after Be2, Black will develop their knight to f6 and we will transpose tothe 3...Nf6 4.e3 Bg4 variation. }
5. a4 { We are immediately starting to undermine Black's queenside. } 5... Bb7
{ Developing and protecting the rook on a8. } 6. b3
{ We are winning the pawn back with this move. } 6... e6
{ Black has to continue the development instead of liquidating the queenside. However, keeping the pair of extra a-pawns will give us chances to fight for the advantage. }
7. bxc4 bxc4 8. Bxc4 Nf6 9. O-O c5
{ In order to equalise, Black has to make this move at some point. } 10. Nbd2
{ Vacating the b1-square for the rook and freeing the queen from the defence of the f3-knight so both major pieces can disturb the b7-bishop. White has a very harmonious setup. }
10... Nbd7 11. Rb1
{ When the knight is still on b8,  11.Qb3  is a good move: a clear tempo on the b7-bishop without any issues while also supporting the move Ba3  (stopping ...c5-ideas)  . It is also a good move even though Black has already moved the knight to d7, and has ...Rb8 as a counter-tempo, but at the end, White can play Qd3! gaining time by attacking the a6-pawn.However, in the current position with ...Nbd7 and ...c5 played for Black, it is better to attack the bishop on b7 with the rook.  11...Rb8!  Setting up discovered attacks against the Qb3.  12.Qd3  cxd4!  This is annoying. Black doesn't have to take care of the a6-pawn immediately.  13.exd4  a5=  With the isolated-pawn well blockaded @@StartBracket@@the d5-square is under control@@EndBracket@@, Black has no problems in this position.   After @@StartFEN@@1r1qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/p3pn2/8/P1Bp4/3QPN2/3N1PPP/R1B2RK1 w k - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nxd4  Ne5=  followed by taking the bishop on c4, Black is completely fine. }
11... Qc7
{ Black is protecting the bishop with the queen, so the rook can stay in its ideal place on a8, protecting the a6-pawn, and ready to join the game once it opens up. }
12. Ba3 Be7 13. Qe2
{ The downside of playing ...Qc7 is that the queen will not feel very comfortable after Rfc1. White keeps an annoying initiative. }
