[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted: 3...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... Bg4
{ This move is pretty bad, but let's see how to counter it. By attacking the f3-knight, Black is fighting for the centre, so it has at least some point. }
4. Ne5 { Gaining a tempo on the bishop and also attacking the c4-pawn. } 4...
Be6
{ The only retreat which is worth analysing, since Black wants at least to keep their extra pawn.  4...Bh5?  5.g4!  Bg6  6.Bg2  c6  7.Na3+-  followed by Naxc4. The position is already +3 according to the engine. Black is playing around with the bishop while we are developing and already built a massive dominance in the centre.   4...Bf5?  is not better. We have many good solutions, but I like the engine's approach:  5.e4!  Bxe4  6.Nc3  Bg6  7.Bxc4  e6  7.Qb3±  and White is much better. Black has problems on b7, e6, and f7. }
5. e4
{ Occupying the centre and threatening d5. Also, Bxc4 became a possibility. }
5... b5
{ Again, not good, but the only move worth knowing something about. Instead,  5...f6??  is losing on the spot:  6.Qh5+  g6  7.Nxg6  hxg6  @@StartBracket@@  7...Bf7  8.Qb5+  c6  9.Qxb7  hxg6  10.Qxa8+-  @@EndBracket@@  8.Qxh8  Qxd4  9.Nc3+-  And White is up an exchange for no compensation.   5...Nf6  just allows us to take back the pawn with central dominance.  6.Nc3  c6  7.Bxc4  Bxc4  8.Nxc4±  . }
6. a4 c6 7. axb5 cxb5 8. Nc3 { Every move comes with some threat! } 8... Bd7
{ Black has managed to protect the pawn on b5, but is losing to an unexpected tactical trick. }
9. Nxf7 Kxf7 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qd5+
{ Picking up the rook, and with an exchange up, our position will be completely winning. }
