[White "1) Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted: 3...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... c5
{ Since this move is relatively rare in the QGA, I tried to find a way where we can achieve an edge without having to remember too much. }
4. e4
{ The other 2 options were  4.d5  and  4.e3  with good chances for an advantage, but less forcing. }
4... cxd4
{ By far the main and the best move in the position. Black is entering an endgame where, at worst, they will be slightly worse without any major issues.  4...Bg4?  is very bad:  5.Bxc4  e6  6.d5!  is a clear advantage for White, since we can take back with a piece on d5.   4...Nf6  is more solid, but still not enough to reach a good position:  5.e5  Nd5  6.Bxc4  e6  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Bg5  Be7  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.dxc5!  Qxc5  11.Nbd2  is clearly better for White, because of our space advantage in the centre and Black's passive bishop on c8. }
5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4
{ Our main threat is Nb5 in this position, so it is normal that Black's two good options are  6...a6  and  6...Bd7  . }
6... e5
{ This move is inaccurate. Black is forcing us to the square where we wanted to go anyway. }
7. Nb5 Na6 8. Bxc4
{ And Black is struggling here, because the a6-knight is very unfortunate. }
8... Bd7 9. Be3 { Attacking a7. } 9... Rc8 10. Be2 Bb4+
{ 10...Nb4  is a mistake, because we can play  11.Nxa7!  and after  11...Nc2+  12.Kd2  Nxa1  13.Nxc8  Bxc8  14.Nc3  we are trapping the knight on a1 and will have an extra pawn. }
11. N1c3
{ And since Black can't protect the a7-pawn now, the best they can do is to enter a forced line which will lead to a worse endgame. }
11... Bxb5 12. Bxb5+ Ke7 13. Bxa7 Rxc3
{ This simplifying sequence doesn't solve Black's problems. Our bishop pair offers us better prospects. }
14. bxc3 Bxc3+ 15. Ke2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1
{ With a clear advantage for White, because the bishop pair is much stronger in these situations @@StartBracket@@pawns on both sides of the board@@EndBracket@@ than the pair of knights. }
*

