8... Bd6 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Qe7 { Now ...e5 is a threat. } 11. Ne5
{ We are preventing it, and it will be hard to get rid of that knight. } 11...
Bxe2 12. Qxe2
{ Nxc6 is a positional threat now. It is not clear what Black should do with the c6-knight. Here is a sample line:  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Nd7  14.Ba3!  Since the long diagonal is blocked by our own pawn, the bishop is going for a better diagonal.  14...Nb4   @@StartBracket@@  14...Nc5??  loses on the spot due to  15.Qb5+-  and a knight drops.  @@EndBracket@@  15.Qb5  Taking advantage of the pin.  15...c5  16.Rc1  With the idea of taking on b4 and invading the seventh rank.  16...Rad8!  A very strong move, suggested by the computer. Basically, this is the only way for Black to achieve a decent position.  17.Qxb7  Qh4  Stepping out of the pin, so the d7-knight can finally take part in the game.  18.Bxb4  cxb4  19.Qb5  Stopping ...Nxe5 for now.  19...a6  20.Qa5  Qg5  21.a3  Activating the a1-rook.  21...bxa3  22.Rxa3  Nxe5  23.Qxa6⩲  Black is pretty active and definitely has some compensation, but I would still take White with the extra pawn.   If Black is too materialistic, then they will have a hard time defending a very passive position: @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1nqppp/4p3/1Qp1P3/1n6/BP2P2P/P4PP1/RNR3K1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...b6  17.Bxb4!  cxb4  18.Rc7  Rfd8  19.Nd2±  The d7-knight is in big trouble.   Black doesn't solve their problems with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pppnqppp/4p3/1Q2P3/1n6/BP2P2P/P4PP1/RN3RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...a5  16.Qxb7  Nxe5  17.Nc3⩲  With serious issues with Black's queenside pawn structure, whereas White has very easy moves to follow up, like Rac1, Rfd1, and, if needed, Qe4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted: 3...Nf6 4.e3 Bg4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... Nf6
{ Instead, Black can also play  3...a6  and after  4.e3  Nf6  we just transpose back to the main line, or  3...c6  , which would lead us to the Slav Chapter.  3...b5  is also possible, but after  4.a4!  Black has no other reasonable move than  4...c6  and it once again leads to the Slav.For some weird reason,  3...Nc6?  is quite often played too, but it is not a transposition tothe Chigorin because we have  4.d5!  Nb8   @@StartBracket@@  4...Nb4  is losing the knight to  5.Qa4+  @@EndBracket@@  5.e4±  with already a clear advantage.     @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  is another move which was tried many more times than it should have been. We shouldn't forget that Black kind of gave up central control with ...dxc4. That's why Black's main idea is to challenge the centre with the ...c5 move at some moment, and ...Bf5 is not helping.  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4±  with a clear advantage for White. We will play O-O, Qe2 and then e4. }
4. e3 Bg4
{ In this variation Black doesn't want to challenge our centre by playing ...c5. Instead, their idea is ...e5 once they finish development. }
5. Bxc4 { We have the Bxf7+ & Ne5+ trick in this position. } 5... e6
{ 5...Nc6?  is preventing Bxf7 by controlling the e5-square, but after  6.Qb3!  Black can't protect both the f7 and the b7-pawn. }
6. h3
{ 6.O-O  or  6.Be2  is also a good move order for the setup I want to employ here, but since we always play h3, why not start with that. }
6... Bh5 7. O-O
{ The main theoretical line starts with  7.Nc3  , but since I want to put my knight on d2, there were no move order finesses for me in this position. :@@EndBracket@@ }
7... a6
{ Since I can't say that I chose the most active line against this variation, it is even possible for Black to play ...a6 @@StartBracket@@cover the b5-square to avoid checks@@EndBracket@@ and then ...c5. }
8. Be2 c5
{ We still should welcome this direction of the game, since our choice in the main line will be also dxc5 and exchanging the queens. }
9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ This position is much trickier than it can look at first sight. It is symmetrical, which means that we can always count on the advantage that we started the game, so normally we'll have the chance to create some initiative and our play is quite easy. }
11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Bd2
{ Na4-Rac1-Nc5 is one possible idea here to gain the pair of bishops. } 12...
O-O 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4
{ We will take on g6, put the bishop on the long diagonal and put pressure on Black there. Our advantage is small, but it is very unpleasant to defend such endgames with Black. }
*

