{ Instead, Black can also play  3...a6  and after  4.e3  Nf6  we just transpose back to the main line, or  3...c6  , which would lead us to the Slav Chapter.  3...b5  is also possible, but after  4.a4!  Black has no other reasonable move than  4...c6  and it once again leads to the Slav.For some weird reason,  3...Nc6?  is quite often played too, but it is not a transposition tothe Chigorin because we have  4.d5!  Nb8   @@StartBracket@@  4...Nb4  is losing the knight to  5.Qa4+  @@EndBracket@@  5.e4±  with already a clear advantage.     @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  is another move which was tried many more times than it should have been. We shouldn't forget that Black kind of gave up central control with ...dxc4. That's why Black's main idea is to challenge the centre with the ...c5 move at some moment, and ...Bf5 is not helping.  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4±  with a clear advantage for White. We will play O-O, Qe2 and then e4. }
4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6
{ This move is perfectly fine. If Black plays 6...c5 in the next move, we will just transpose into themain line 5...c5. }
6. O-O b5
{ This is also quite a popular move for Black, but it is pretty rare at the highest level, which probably means it is not so good. }
7. Be2
{ I like this retreat the most. The bishop can come to f3 after we play Ne5. }
7... Bb7 8. a4
{ This is usually the reason why early ...b5 moves are risky in the QGA. By attacking this pawn and forcing it to b4, we will have nice target squares like c4 and c5. }
8... b4 9. Ne5
{ With the idea of playing Bf3. Also, the most ideal scenario for our knights in this structure is to occupy the b3 and c4-squares, and now we are one step closer to it. }
9... Nbd7 10. Bf3
{ By exchanging light-squared bishops we are further weakening Black's position @@StartBracket@@e.g. the c6-square@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bxf3
{ Instead,  10...Ne4  is not keeping the bishops much longer on the board.  11.Nd2!  Nxe5  12.Bxe4  Bxe4  13.Nxe4  is a clear advantage for White because of the weaknesses on the c-file. }
11. Qxf3 c5 12. Nd2 cxd4 13. exd4
{ Black still has big questions to solve regarding their development. White has some serious pressure in this position. }
