1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... Nf6
{ Instead, Black can also play  3...a6  and after  4.e3  Nf6  we just transpose back to the main line, or  3...c6  , which would lead us to the Slav Chapter.  3...b5  is also possible, but after  4.a4!  Black has no other reasonable move than  4...c6  and it once again leads to the Slav.For some weird reason,  3...Nc6?  is quite often played too, but it is not a transposition tothe Chigorin because we have  4.d5!  Nb8   @@StartBracket@@  4...Nb4  is losing the knight to  5.Qa4+  @@EndBracket@@  5.e4±  with already a clear advantage.     @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  is another move which was tried many more times than it should have been. We shouldn't forget that Black kind of gave up central control with ...dxc4. That's why Black's main idea is to challenge the centre with the ...c5 move at some moment, and ...Bf5 is not helping.  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4±  with a clear advantage for White. We will play O-O, Qe2 and then e4. }
4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O cxd4
{ Black is immediately clarifying the situation in the centre. This definitely has the advantage that it for example avoids my suggestion, the dxc5 complex with queen exchange and a slightly better endgame.On the other hand, since we are just about to start developing our pieces on the queenside, we'll have the chance of doing it in the most ideal way, since we know the exact structure already.   However, as we'll see inthe main lines,   6...a6  is more challenging for White, as Black is not showing their cards yet. }
7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1
{ We are developing our pieces to their most natural squares. } 9... a6
{ This move is a little bit slow. Black wants to play with ...b5 and ...Bb7, but we can make it very difficult for them. }
10. Ne5
{ Freeing the f3-square for the queen, and also kind of preventing Black to develop their knight to its most natural square, c6. }
10... Nbd7
{ If instead  10...Nc6  we go  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bf4⩲  and we switch to positional play with moves like Rc1 and Na4, attacking the weak black pawns on the queenside. }
11. Bf4 { We have many good moves in the position and this is one of them. }
11... Nb6
{ Black is transferring the knight to d5 to blockade our isolated pawn. } 12.
Bb3 Nbd5 13. Bg5
{ With Qf3 and Rad1 to follow, we put big pressure on Black's position and especially on the d5-square. It will also be difficult to find a good place for the c8-bishop. }
*

