4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O cxd4
{ Black is immediately clarifying the situation in the centre. This definitely has the advantage that it for example avoids my suggestion, the dxc5 complex with queen exchange and a slightly better endgame.On the other hand, since we are just about to start developing our pieces on the queenside, we'll have the chance of doing it in the most ideal way, since we know the exact structure already.   However, as we'll see inthe main lines,   6...a6  is more challenging for White, as Black is not showing their cards yet. }
7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1
{ We are developing our pieces to their most natural squares. } 9... Nc6
{ The most common move. The knight develops to its most natural square. } 10.
a3
{ A very useful move to play in structures when we have an isolated pawn. It is preventing the ...Nb4-...Nbd5 blockading idea and also, since d5 is one of our main ideas in the position, we have to prepare an answer to d5 Na5. An extra square on the diagonal for the bishop will do the job. }
10... a6
{ This move is more ambitious than  10...b6  , because Black also wants to gain some space on the queenside and have the ...b4 or ...Na5-...Nc4 idea at some point. However, they will simply not be in time to place their bishop comfortably on the long diagonal. }
11. Ba2
{ Anticipating and waiting for ...b5! Instead,  11.d5  is not giving White much, if anything at all.  11...exd5  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Bxd5  Bf6  and Black is more or less fine. }
11... b5
{ This was Black's idea, and even though it is not good, what else to recommend? Whatever Black would come up with, we could just continue with Bg5, Qd3, Rad1, Bb1 with big initiative. }
12. d5
{ Thanks to the loose pieces in Black's position, this idea works very well and gives White a big advantage. }
12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ Instead,  13...Be6  is losing right away after  14.Nxe7+  Qxe7  15.Ng5!+-   The best move according to the engine is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/4bppp/p1n2n2/1p1N4/8/P4N2/BP3PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ra7  , which is not really a human move, to just give up the e7-bishop and suffer.  14.Be3!  Rd7  15.Nxe7+  Nxe7  16.Qc2±  with a clear advantage for White. The bishop pair is super strong. }
14. Qxd5
{ The queen on d8 is doing an important job by protecting the bishop on e7, so we wouldn't mind a queen exchange at this moment, since we would win a piece on the next move. :@@EndBracket@@ }
14... Bb7 { 14...Qxd5  15.Bxd5  and then taking on c6 will win the e7-bishop. }
15. Qh5
{ And we have a huge @@StartBracket@@according to the computer, winning@@EndBracket@@ initiative. Bg5 is coming in the next move with great power, preparing the g5-square for the knight.   For example,  15...Qd6  16.Bg5!  Rad8   @@StartBracket@@  16...Bxg5  17.Nxg5  Qg6  18.Qxg6  hxg6  19.Nxf7!  Rxf7  20.Rad1  is crushing, with Rd7 to follow@@EndBracket@@  17.Bxe7  Nxe7  18.Ng5!  Qg6  19.Qxg6  Nxg6  20.Nxf7!  this tactic works even here:  20...Rxf7  21.Rad1!  Rxd1  22.Rxd1  Bc6  23.Rd8  Nf8  24.Rd6  Be8  25.Rxa6+-  is a technically winning endgame for White. }
