[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted: 5...c5 6.O-O a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted, a very solid choice for Black. One practical benefit of this opening is that Black gets to decide the character of the game. I mean that, if you prepare for a QGA as Black, then most probably you'll get a QGA. :@@EndBracket@@ However, against  2...e6  or  2...c6  or whatever else, White still has many options to surprise Black.I believe that, besides the undeniable solid character of this opening, the fact that you can virtually guarantee it in practice has made it quite popular again at the highest level. Interestingly, mainly among players from the USA: GMs Wesley So, Dominguez, and Nakamura frequently play it and with decent results. }
3. Nf3
{ The other main line is  3.e4  but it leads to sharper and more theoretical play, with many different types of options for Black. }
3... Nf6
{ Instead, Black can also play  3...a6  and after  4.e3  Nf6  we just transpose back to the main line, or  3...c6  , which would lead us to the Slav Chapter.  3...b5  is also possible, but after  4.a4!  Black has no other reasonable move than  4...c6  and it once again leads to the Slav.For some weird reason,  3...Nc6?  is quite often played too, but it is not a transposition tothe Chigorin because we have  4.d5!  Nb8   @@StartBracket@@  4...Nb4  is losing the knight to  5.Qa4+  @@EndBracket@@  5.e4±  with already a clear advantage.     @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  is another move which was tried many more times than it should have been. We shouldn't forget that Black kind of gave up central control with ...dxc4. That's why Black's main idea is to challenge the centre with the ...c5 move at some moment, and ...Bf5 is not helping.  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4±  with a clear advantage for White. We will play O-O, Qe2 and then e4. }
4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ Black has to make a big decision here. If they take on d1, then they will bring our rook into the game with tempo but will keep the option to castle. Instead, in the case of ...Bxc5, they are not giving this tempo, but their king will remain in the centre. Of course, given it is an endgame, doesn't look like a big deal, but that king on e7 can get unpleasant checks from a3, and retreating the bishop to e7 will be also impossible.   It is hard to say which one is the better way:  7...Qxd1  is more popular overall, but recently there are more games with  7...Bxc5  on the highest level. }
7... Bxc5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Be2
{ We have at least 4 alternatives which are interesting and have the same value as this move, but since the bishop never has anything to do on c4, let's play the move that is always useful. }
9... Ke7 10. Ne5
{ Again a very useful move. The knight is not active on f3, as that square rather belongs to the bishop. Our optimal setup is placing our knights on c4 and b3, attacking and taking a lot of squares away from the dark-squared bishop. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nc4 b6
{ The main move and the best, but it is already not easy to find, because the combination of the b6-pawn and the c5-bishop looks weird. Instead,  11...b5?  is simply bad:  12.Na5!±  and Bf3 is coming, with big issues for Black on c6.   11...Rd8  12.Nc3  with the idea of Na4!,  12...b5  13.Na5  Nb8  this already doesn't look right for Black,  14.Nb3⩲  . }
12. Nc3 a5
{ Again, extremely difficult to play like this if you don't know the theory. Black is seemingly just weakening further squares, but actually bringing the bishop to a6 is crucial.   12...Bb7?!  allows White to take the bishop on c5:  13.Na4!  Bd5  14.Nxc5  Bxc4  15.Bxc4  Nxc5  16.Bd2⩲  The pair of bishops vs pair of knights fight is a scenario we should welcome. }
13. Na4
{ We will still take the bishop on c5, but Black will get more activity. }
13... Ba6 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. b3
{ Stabilising the knight and preparing to play Ba3. We can see now that the king would be much better placed on g8 in this particular line. }
15... Nfe4 16. Ba3 Nc3 17. Bd3
{ Nxb6 is a big threat now, so Black has to give up their other bishop as well. }
17... Bxc4 18. Bxc4
{ Black's knights are pretty well placed, but if this activity is gone, we'll just have a clear edge. }
*

