[White "2) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6: 5...c6 6.e3 Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... a6
{ This move came into fashion more or less 10 years ago. Of course, it is still not the most popular move, but a very respectable alternative to all the main moves likethe 3...Be7 line, the 3...Nf6 line orthe 3...c6 Triangle. Black's main idea is to force White to make a decision with the c4-pawn, as now Black wants to take it and is prepared to protect it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ Instead of this move, White has many other options. However,  4.e3  would close the bishop on c1,  4.Nf3  and  4.Bf4  would allow Black to take on c4 and defend with ...b5, and  4.c5  would lead to positions not really compatible with our repertoire. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ Another point of playing 3...a6 instead ofthe most popular 3...Nf6 can be seen here: we couldn't develop our bishop to g5, only to f4. Of course, it is not the end of the world. }
5... c6 6. e3 Bf5
{ Looks logical. As we will see in this chapter and also in the other variations which will feature the Carlsbad structure, the c8-bishop is going to be a key piece regarding the evaluation of the position. If it can develop normally and be exchanged for White's light-squared bishop, then generally Black has no problems at all, but if not, White keeps a stable advantage. }
7. g4
{ In general, we don't want to exchange light-squared bishops, only if the circumstances greatly improve for us. Why is that? Because Black's pawn chain on b7-c6-d5 is big-time restricting the activity of this bishop, so we are interested in keeping it on the board. }
7... Be6
{ We managed to force the bishop back to a very short diagonal. :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. h4
{ Gaining more space on the kingside and anticipating an ...h5 push from Black, so now after we meet it with g5, they can't separate our pawns anymore by playing ...h4 there. }
8... Qb6
{ Is not a good move, but we can learn a clever idea here, which can be used in many different openings against ...Qb6. In case of some more regular move, like  8...Nd7  , we can just continue with g5 expanding on the kingside, and then follow it up with Qb3, O-O-O, and Nf3 with an attacking position. }
9. a3
{ So we are not protecting the pawn directly, just improving our position a little bit! }
9... Qxb2 10. Na4 { There was some poison in that b2-pawn. :@@EndBracket@@ } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6: 5...c6 6.e3 Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... a6
{ This move came into fashion more or less 10 years ago. Of course, it is still not the most popular move, but a very respectable alternative to all the main moves likethe 3...Be7 line, the 3...Nf6 line orthe 3...c6 Triangle. Black's main idea is to force White to make a decision with the c4-pawn, as now Black wants to take it and is prepared to protect it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ Instead of this move, White has many other options. However,  4.e3  would close the bishop on c1,  4.Nf3  and  4.Bf4  would allow Black to take on c4 and defend with ...b5, and  4.c5  would lead to positions not really compatible with our repertoire. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ Another point of playing 3...a6 instead ofthe most popular 3...Nf6 can be seen here: we couldn't develop our bishop to g5, only to f4. Of course, it is not the end of the world. }
5... c6 6. e3 Bd6
{ This move is by far the main line here. Black first wants to develop and then solve the problem of the c8-bishop with the help of the ...Ne7 move. }
7. Qf3
{ I've only found 5 games in the database with this move, but once we understand that our main strategical goal for the opening is to restrict the c8-bishop, then it makes perfect sense! }
7... Ne7 { Black is preparing to play ...Bf5. } 8. h4
{ We go with the indirect way again! Instead,  8.g4  would not be so good, because  8...Bxf4  9.Qxf4  and we can't keep our position compact after Black plays  9...h5!  . }
8... h5
{ Securing the f5-square for the bishop by stopping our g4 move. Instead,  8...Bf5  was not achieving the aim of activating the bishop, because White can play  9.g4!  and the bishop has to go back to passivity. }
9. Bd3 Bf5
{ It looks like that despite all the finesses we tried, Black is outsmarting us. }
10. Bxf5 Nxf5 11. O-O-O
{ Black has managed to solve the problem of the c8-bishop, so strategically they are doing pretty well. The problem is that they are very far behind in development and thanks to the 'problem-solver' ...h5 move, they can't even castle now. Our next move is e4, opening files and attacking the king. }
*

