{ This move is by far the main line here. Black first wants to develop and then solve the problem of the c8-bishop with the help of the ...Ne7 move. }
7. Qf3
{ I've only found 5 games in the database with this move, but once we understand that our main strategical goal for the opening is to restrict the c8-bishop, then it makes perfect sense! }
7... Nf6
{ This is not really a challenging move. We just have to prevent ...Bg4, and we can do it by very simple means. }
8. h3 O-O 9. Bd3
{ We are controlling both possible active destinations of the c8-bishop, so we can consider our opening play a success. }
9... Bxf4 10. Qxf4
{ In this setup, the most effective plan is the minority attack, so we go for it. We have a normal game ahead with light-squared bishops on the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6: 5...Nf6 6.e3 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... a6
{ This move came into fashion more or less 10 years ago. Of course, it is still not the most popular move, but a very respectable alternative to all the main moves likethe 3...Be7 line, the 3...Nf6 line orthe 3...c6 Triangle. Black's main idea is to force White to make a decision with the c4-pawn, as now Black wants to take it and is prepared to protect it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ Instead of this move, White has many other options. However,  4.e3  would close the bishop on c1,  4.Nf3  and  4.Bf4  would allow Black to take on c4 and defend with ...b5, and  4.c5  would lead to positions not really compatible with our repertoire. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ Another point of playing 3...a6 instead ofthe most popular 3...Nf6 can be seen here: we couldn't develop our bishop to g5, only to f4. Of course, it is not the end of the world. }
5... Nf6 6. e3 c5
{ This move is the recommendation of GM Max Warmerdam in his excellent course. However, unless our opponent knows that course inside-out, we can just keep a nice advantage. }
7. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Black's idea is to develop quickly, and then push ...d4 and completely equalise the position. }
8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O d4
{ After both sides have castled, Black is going for simplifications. If they waited for one more move, let's say with  10...Be6  , then White is ready to play  11.Ne5  and make that ...d4 break much harder. }
11. exd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4
{ The endgame looks harmless at first sight, but White can put some unpleasant pressure on Black. }
13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Rfd1 Bxc3 15. bxc3
{ The bishop pair is very strong and the b7-pawn is a nice target. } *

