[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...a6: 5...Nf6 6.e3 Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... a6
{ This move came into fashion more or less 10 years ago. Of course, it is still not the most popular move, but a very respectable alternative to all the main moves likethe 3...Be7 line, the 3...Nf6 line orthe 3...c6 Triangle. Black's main idea is to force White to make a decision with the c4-pawn, as now Black wants to take it and is prepared to protect it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ Instead of this move, White has many other options. However,  4.e3  would close the bishop on c1,  4.Nf3  and  4.Bf4  would allow Black to take on c4 and defend with ...b5, and  4.c5  would lead to positions not really compatible with our repertoire. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ Another point of playing 3...a6 instead ofthe most popular 3...Nf6 can be seen here: we couldn't develop our bishop to g5, only to f4. Of course, it is not the end of the world. }
5... Nf6 6. e3 Bd6
{ If instead of this normal developing move, Black tried  6...Bf5  , after  7.Qb3  there is no comfortable way to protect the pawn on b7, so they will have to make some concessions. }
7. Bg5
{ With this move we want to transpose into Carlsbad territory, obviously a tempo down in comparison withthe 3...Nf6 chapter, but that ...a6 extra move for Black is not going to change anything.   Please note that  7.Qf3  is not so good here because Black hasn’t played ...c6 yet, so we have to be ready for a potential ...c5 in every move and I don't like that very much. }
7... Be6
{ This is the only move with independent value in this position. Black is protecting the pawn on d5, which was hanging because of the pin. The knight will be developed to d7 only later, so this bishop can go to f5 or g4 anytime. If instead  7...c6  , then  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Qc2  h6  10.Bh4  Re8  11.Nge2  and even though, as I said, it's not a direct transposition because Black has an extra ...a6 included, these kinds of positions are discussed inthe 3...Nf6 chapter. }
8. Bd3 O-O
{ A rare but solid move for Black. I don't think our opponent can expect equality here, though, since they will have problems with the e6-bishop.  8...Nd7  is the main move and we'll study itin the next trainable lines. }
9. Nge2
{ A key move! In case of  9.Nf3  Black would have chances to play ...Bg4 in the future. It is not so easy to prevent it by playing an eventual h3 because after ...h6 and then ...g5 our dark-squared bishop can only retreat to g3. Then our structure would be ruined after a trade on that square. }
9... Nbd7
{ 9...c6  10.Qc2  h6  11.Bf4  c5  The computer likes such move but seemingly it just gives a clear plus for White.  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.dxc5  Qxc5  14.Nd4  The blockading square is an excellent outpost for the knight.  14...Nc6  15.Nce2⩲  The d4-square is under control, with one knight occupying it and the other knight as a backup. White has a small but clear advantage with the better structure. Another option is @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1p3pp1/p1pbbn1p/3p4/3P1B2/2NBP3/PPQ1NPPP/R3K2R_b_KQ_-_0_11@@EndFEN@@ 11...Qe7  Black has to waste a move to make ...Nbd7 possible.  12.O-O  Nbd7  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Nf4⩲  Black is solid but definitely not equal with such a bad bishop on e6. Our next moves are a3-Na4-Rfc1-b4 and expanding on the queenside. }
10. h3
{ Avoiding potential ...Bxh2+ tricks after castling.  10.O-O?  Bxh2  11.Kxh2  Ng4±  picking up the g5-bishop. }
10... Re8
{ 10...Qe7?  Black has to be wary of playing this move too early.  11.f4!  Now f5 is a huge threat and Black also has to protect the d5-pawn because of the pin on the f6-knight.  11...Nb6  12.O-O±  With e4 coming on the next move, Black's position is already close to lost. }
11. O-O h6 12. Bf4 Qe7 13. Rc1 c6 14. Na4
{ With ideas like Qb3 or Nc5 coming, White has a pleasant position. The e6-bishop is extremely passive and it is hard to see how Black can improve it. }
*

