[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6: 5...Bb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6
{ The most classical move order in the QGD, also known as the Orthodox Queen's Gambit Declined. A very old, ever-popular, solid and perfectly sound opening, which will probably get another boost in popularity since it is the recommendation of IM Sielecki in his recently published 'Keep It Simple for Black' course.Black is fighting for the centre in the classical way, putting pawns there and supporting them with pieces, not giving up space or any other advantage for free. }
4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 Bb4
{ This line is rare, but it is completely different from Black's 3 other options at this point. Besides, it is a perfectly normal developing move, so it is worth covering. }
6. Qb3
{ Black's moves were exactly the same as if we had started the game as a Ragozin. Let me show you this line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  Bb4  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  is the main line of the Ragozin Defence, which is a very popular opening at the highest level. Now, if we look at our position, we managed to 'trade' the Nf3 move for Qb3, and therefore we can put immediate pressure on Black's position. }
6... Nc6
{ We should always welcome the knight to c6, if it is in front of the c7-pawn. :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. e3 h6
{ Black has to try to justify why they put their knight on c6. If they play slowly, like  7...O-O  8.Bd3  , then our pieces are just perfect, and we will play for our usual Nge2-O-O and then f3-e4. }
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxd5
{ There is some development advantage for Black here, but our position is completely sound, without any weaknesses. Therefore, I @@StartBracket@@and, more importantly, the machine@@EndBracket@@ couldn't find enough compensation for Black. }
9... Be6 10. Qf3
{ Bb5 and Nge2 are coming. Black has no compensation for the missing pawn. } *

