4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 Bb4
{ This line is rare, but it is completely different from Black's 3 other options at this point. Besides, it is a perfectly normal developing move, so it is worth covering. }
6. Qb3
{ Black's moves were exactly the same as if we had started the game as a Ragozin. Let me show you this line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  Bb4  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  is the main line of the Ragozin Defence, which is a very popular opening at the highest level. Now, if we look at our position, we managed to 'trade' the Nf3 move for Qb3, and therefore we can put immediate pressure on Black's position. }
6... c5
{ The most logical, completely in the spirit of the Ragozin, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre. Instead,  6...Bxc3?!  just gives us the bishop pair for free:  7.Qxc3  O-O  8.e3  c6  9.Bd3  and Black just exchanged their very important dark-squared @@StartBracket@@good@@EndBracket@@ bishop and is left with their bad c8-bishop, which is seriously restricted by Black's central formation. }
7. dxc5
{ The position is very concrete, so it is good to create threats and develop quickly. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O
{ The king is out from the pin, so the c3-knight is attacking the d5-pawn. }
8... Qa5 { Getting out from the pin and attacking c3 and c5. } 9. Bxf6
{ The bishop had lost purpose on g5, so it is better to ruin Black's structure and sidestep any potential ...Ne4. }
9... gxf6 10. Nxd5 Qxc5+ 11. Qc2
{ With this move, we are forcing the queen trade. Still, as the better-developed side, Black will be able to show some compensation for the missing pawn. }
11... Qxc2+ 12. Kxc2 Bf5+ 13. Kc1
{ Black has to be fast: if we can play f3-e4 and block the b1-h7 diagonal, then our king will be just completely safe on b1. }
13... Rc8 14. Nxf6+ Ke7 15. e4
{ There are no dangerous discovered checks with the knight, so even though Black will take back the pawn, we'll keep one extra. }
15... Kxf6 16. exf5 Ne5+
{ 16...Ba5!?  A very tricky move, suggested by the computer. At first, it is hard to see its point; however, when we are looking for a move, we can suddenly see some difficulties.  17.Nh3!  This is obviously not the first move that comes to mind, but more natural alternatives had some issues.  17...Rhd8  18.Rxd8  Rxd8  19.Bc4⩲  White keeps the extra pawn, with great winning chances.   Instead, @@StartFEN@@2r4r/pp3p1p/2n2k2/b4P2/8/8/PP3PPP/2KR1BNR w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Ne2  Ne5+  18.Kb1  Ng4!  and we have problems protecting f2. Obviously,  @@StartFEN@@2r4r/pp3p1p/2n2k2/b4P2/8/8/PP3PPP/2KR1BNR w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Nf3  is nothing for White:  17...Nd4+  18.Kb1  Nxf3  19.gxf3  Rhd8=  and even though we are up a couple of pawns, they are on the same file. :@@EndBracket@@ Finally, on  @@StartFEN@@2r4r/pp3p1p/2n2k2/b4P2/8/8/PP3PPP/2KR1BNR w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Kb1  Black can play  17...Rcd8  18.Bd3  Nb4!  and things are not clear at all. }
17. Kb1 Rhd8
{ 17...Ng4  doesn't pose any problems for us.  18.Nh3±  Be2 is coming in the next move and Black hasn't achieved anything with ...Ng4. }
18. Rxd8 Rxd8 19. Be2
{ The idea is to finish the development by playing f4 and then Nf3. } 19... Rd2
{ 19...Kxf5  20.Nh3  Guarding the f2-pawn is critical.  20...Rd2  21.Bd1⩲  With Bc2 and then Rd1 we will neutralise Black's activity and will enter the endgame with an extra pawn. }
20. Kc1
{ The rook is not stable on d2. Black already has to watch out for a3-b4 ideas. }
