11... Ne4
{ This move leads to a completely different position from what Black would normally like to play @@StartBracket@@dangerous counterplay against our centre, coming from the queenside, in the form of ...b5-...a5-...Ba6 and later ...b4-...c5.@@EndBracket@@ }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxe4
{ Now I recommend keeping the bishop on the board, since if  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Ng3  then Black doesn't have to weaken their position with ...f5, but they can play  14...Nf6! }
13... dxe4 14. Bc4 Nb6 15. Ba2 Bg4 16. h3 Bxe2 17. Qxe2
{ With a pleasant edge for White: b4-b5 can be our next idea after bringing the rook to c5. }
