[White "3) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6: 5...c6 6.e3 h6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6
{ The most classical move order in the QGD, also known as the Orthodox Queen's Gambit Declined. A very old, ever-popular, solid and perfectly sound opening, which will probably get another boost in popularity since it is the recommendation of IM Sielecki in his recently published 'Keep It Simple for Black' course.Black is fighting for the centre in the classical way, putting pawns there and supporting them with pieces, not giving up space or any other advantage for free. }
4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 c6
{ The most common move order, but after  5...Be7  or  5...Nbd7  we can reach the same positions as in the  5...c6  line.   5...Be7  is already giving up on the ...Bd6 variations, while  5...Nbd7  is closing the c8-bishop's diagonal temporarily, also taking away some possible lines from Black.Please note that  5...Nbd7  6.Nxd5??  would be a huge blunder, since after  6...Nxd5!  7.Bxd8  Bb4+  8.Qd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  Kxd8-+  we ended up one piece down. }
6. e3
{ Black has 4 different ways to play here:1. They can play  6...Be7  , breaking the pin and playing all the way without ...h6.2. They can play with  6...h6  first and then ...Be7, or start with ...Be7 but include ...h6 at some moment later, so we have to be alert not to make a move we would want to play against ...Be7 but not against ...h6 @@StartBracket@@Qc2! will be mainly this move@@EndBracket@@.3. They can play with  6...Bd6  , and here ...h6 will not be a big deal since once we play Qc2-Bd3, the h7-pawn will be hanging because of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal, so Black will eventually push ...h6.4. They can play  6...Bf5  and enter a solid but not very nice-looking endgame. }
6... h6
{ Instead,  6...Bd6  has no independent value.  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Qc2  h6  9.Bh4  Re8  10.Nge2  and we transpose back to the  6...h6  line. }
7. Bh4 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2
{ It is very important that we play without Qc2. Black's pawn is not on h7 anyway, so there is no reason we should rush with that move. Instead, we are finishing our kingside development. }
9... Re8
{ Instead,  9...Bg4?  is not good. Generally, it is not good against Nge2 setups because we can simply play  10.f3  and gain a tempo for our central play, but it is an even worse move when Black plays with ...h6, since the g6-square is not available for the bishop to retreat.  10...Bh5  11.Nf4!  and the bishop can't even go to g6.  11...g5  12.Nxh5  gxh4  13.Nxf6+  Bxf6  14.O-O±  with a much better position for White. Black's kingside is not in good shape. }
10. O-O a5 { A possible improvement for Black over  10...Nbd7  . } 11. Rc1
{ Similarly to Black, we are also making a useful waiting move, not committing ourselves with  11.f3  yet, since then Black could play  11...b5!  . If we played  12.a4?!  similarly tothe 10...Nbd7 line, then Black tricked us, since they have played ...a5 instead and the knight is much better on b8 than on d7 because now Black has the plan ...Na6-...Nb4! }
11... b5
{ Without f3 being played this move is not really effective at all, and here all our pieces are perfectly placed to meet this idea. }
12. a4 b4 13. Nb1
{ We can see why 11.Rc1 was more useful than 11.f3: we have finished our development, have an harmonious setup and Black can't break on c5. }
13... Bb7 14. Nd2 Nbd7 15. Nb3
{ Black is doing very badly positionally speaking: many weak squares and pawns. }
*

