6. e3
{ Black has 4 different ways to play here:1. They can play  6...Be7  , breaking the pin and playing all the way without ...h6.2. They can play with  6...h6  first and then ...Be7, or start with ...Be7 but include ...h6 at some moment later, so we have to be alert not to make a move we would want to play against ...Be7 but not against ...h6 @@StartBracket@@Qc2! will be mainly this move@@EndBracket@@.3. They can play with  6...Bd6  , and here ...h6 will not be a big deal since once we play Qc2-Bd3, the h7-pawn will be hanging because of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal, so Black will eventually push ...h6.4. They can play  6...Bf5  and enter a solid but not very nice-looking endgame. }
6... h6
{ Instead,  6...Bd6  has no independent value.  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Qc2  h6  9.Bh4  Re8  10.Nge2  and we transpose back to the  6...h6  line. }
7. Bh4 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2
{ It is very important that we play without Qc2. Black's pawn is not on h7 anyway, so there is no reason we should rush with that move. Instead, we are finishing our kingside development. }
9... Re8
{ Instead,  9...Bg4?  is not good. Generally, it is not good against Nge2 setups because we can simply play  10.f3  and gain a tempo for our central play, but it is an even worse move when Black plays with ...h6, since the g6-square is not available for the bishop to retreat.  10...Bh5  11.Nf4!  and the bishop can't even go to g6.  11...g5  12.Nxh5  gxh4  13.Nxf6+  Bxf6  14.O-O±  with a much better position for White. Black's kingside is not in good shape. }
10. O-O a5 { A possible improvement for Black over  10...Nbd7  . } 11. Rc1
{ Similarly to Black, we are also making a useful waiting move, not committing ourselves with  11.f3  yet, since then Black could play  11...b5!  . If we played  12.a4?!  similarly tothe 10...Nbd7 line, then Black tricked us, since they have played ...a5 instead and the knight is much better on b8 than on d7 because now Black has the plan ...Na6-...Nb4! }
11... Nbd7
{ 11...Nh5  is also possible.  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Qd2!  again switching back to the f3-e4 idea. Without the dark-squared bishops, we don't really have to be afraid of ...b5, since it would weaken the dark squares. A sample line to see our next moves:  13...Nd7  14.Rce1  Nf8  15.Na4!  b6 or c5 are nice locations for this knight  15...Nf6  16.Nb6  Ra7  17.f3⩲  . }
12. Bg3
{ A nice waiting move. Again, we still don't commit ourselves to play f3 and allow Black to meet it with ...b5! }
12... Nf8
{ Instead,  12...Nh5?  is losing a pawn to  13.Nxd5  Nxg3  14.Nxe7+!  while  12...b5  is losing to  13.Nxb5!  cxb5  14.Bc7+-  . }
13. Kh1 { Still waiting! This move is anyway very useful for a future f3-e4. }
13... Bd6
{ Instead, on  13...Nh5  we can play  14.Be5  f6  15.Bf4  and thanks to the weakened light squares on the kingside we keep our advantage. }
14. Qd2 { We are ready to play f3-e4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6: 5...c6 6.e3 Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6
{ The most classical move order in the QGD, also known as the Orthodox Queen's Gambit Declined. A very old, ever-popular, solid and perfectly sound opening, which will probably get another boost in popularity since it is the recommendation of IM Sielecki in his recently published 'Keep It Simple for Black' course.Black is fighting for the centre in the classical way, putting pawns there and supporting them with pieces, not giving up space or any other advantage for free. }
4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 c6
{ The most common move order, but after  5...Be7  or  5...Nbd7  we can reach the same positions as in the  5...c6  line.   5...Be7  is already giving up on the ...Bd6 variations, while  5...Nbd7  is closing the c8-bishop's diagonal temporarily, also taking away some possible lines from Black.Please note that  5...Nbd7  6.Nxd5??  would be a huge blunder, since after  6...Nxd5!  7.Bxd8  Bb4+  8.Qd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  Kxd8-+  we ended up one piece down. }
6. e3
{ So, here we are, the starting position of this opening variation. In the Carlsbad structure @@StartBracket@@the one you can currently see on the board@@EndBracket@@, White has two main ideas:1. Play the minority attack on the queenside, which means that White will attack with the 'a-b' pawns against Black's 'a-b-c' pawns, hence the label of the attack. The main goal is to eventually create a weakness on c6 and put Black in a tricky situation. Usually, only one weakness is not enough to win the game, but once Black is stuck with defending that c6-pawn, White can create other threats in the centre or on the kingside.2. Play for the e4-break, which we will do with the help of the f3-move, intending not to get an isolated pawn in the centre in case of ...dxe4, but to be able to keep our central structure very healthy by answering fxe4.Black's main idea against the minority attack @@StartBracket@@a flank attack@@EndBracket@@ is to try to organise counterplay on the other side of the board, so against our king. Instead, when White is pushing for f3-e4, as we will see, they have to counterattack in the centre by playing ...c5 or ...b5-...b4 to kick our knight from c3 and weaken the e4-square. }
6... Bf5
{ For a very long time, this move was considered to be inaccurate, but later, Kramnik brought it back into fashion. This is really for high level: who would like to suffer for a draw with a worse structure straight out of the opening?! }
7. Qf3
{ Very important to remember this move! Otherwise, Black has just developed their bishop to a nice square. }
7... Bg6 8. Bxf6 { Creating the doubled pawns. } 8... Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6
{ This is not a fun endgame to play for Black, but, of course, when a draw is a great result with Black and White is a dangerous attacking player, this opening is definitely an option. }
10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Nh4
{ Targeting the f5-square, which can't be controlled by black pawns anymore. }
11... Be7 12. Ne2 { The other knight is coming to f5 too! } 12... f5
{ Black makes their bishop incredibly passive, but it is still not so easy to break their position. }
13. Nf3
{ With this move White keeps more winning chances than in the main line, where after  13.g3  Bxh4  14.gxh4  Nf6  , even though Black's position is extremely ugly, it is also very hard to break. }
13... Nf6 14. a3
{ Preventing ...Bb4+ ideas. Our bishop will go to h3 next, and then we can also start manoeuvring with our knights to put some pressure on the f5-pawn. }
*

