{ The most common move in the position. Black can still play with ...O-O in the next move, but they also keep the option of playing with ...Nh5. On  7...O-O  we play  8.Nge2  , since  8.Qc2  h6!  is still something we don't want. }
8. Nge2
{ Basically, this is the moment where White has to decide to play with Nge2 and f3-e4, or Nf3 and the minority attack. My recommendation is to play with Nge2. In the Nf3 lines, Black has found many new, interesting ways to play; I found it especially hard to crack Black's plans connected with ...Ne4. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ Once again, it was important to start with this move instead of the more popular  9.Qc2  , since we want to keep our queen on d1 in case Black ever wants to play ...h6! }
9... Re8
{ I believe this is the position you'll get most often from the QGD 3...Nf6 system. }
10. Qc2
{ Finally, we can make this move since we are ready to face ...h6 thanks to an important tactical idea! }
10... Nf8 11. f3
{ Preparing e4, but we have to be careful. One of the basic ideas to check when we are ready to push the pawn is what happens after dxe4-fxe4, Ng4! }
11... Ng6
{ Black trapped our bishop on g5 and their next move is ...h6, so we have to hurry with e4! }
12. e4 dxe4 13. fxe4 Ng4 { We are ready for this. } 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qd2
{ Covering the e3-square, and we will kick back the knight in the next move with 16.h3. It is very important that on  15...c5  we have  16.h3!  and  16...cxd4?  is just losing to  17.Nd5!+-  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Nf6: 5...c6 6.e3 Be7 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6
{ The most classical move order in the QGD, also known as the Orthodox Queen's Gambit Declined. A very old, ever-popular, solid and perfectly sound opening, which will probably get another boost in popularity since it is the recommendation of IM Sielecki in his recently published 'Keep It Simple for Black' course.Black is fighting for the centre in the classical way, putting pawns there and supporting them with pieces, not giving up space or any other advantage for free. }
4. cxd5
{ 4.Bg5  and  4.Nf3  are the other main lines, but we immediately go for the Carlsbad structure. }
4... exd5 5. Bg5 c6
{ The most common move order, but after  5...Be7  or  5...Nbd7  we can reach the same positions as in the  5...c6  line.   5...Be7  is already giving up on the ...Bd6 variations, while  5...Nbd7  is closing the c8-bishop's diagonal temporarily, also taking away some possible lines from Black.Please note that  5...Nbd7  6.Nxd5??  would be a huge blunder, since after  6...Nxd5!  7.Bxd8  Bb4+  8.Qd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  Kxd8-+  we ended up one piece down. }
6. e3
{ So, here we are, the starting position of this opening variation. In the Carlsbad structure @@StartBracket@@the one you can currently see on the board@@EndBracket@@, White has two main ideas:1. Play the minority attack on the queenside, which means that White will attack with the 'a-b' pawns against Black's 'a-b-c' pawns, hence the label of the attack. The main goal is to eventually create a weakness on c6 and put Black in a tricky situation. Usually, only one weakness is not enough to win the game, but once Black is stuck with defending that c6-pawn, White can create other threats in the centre or on the kingside.2. Play for the e4-break, which we will do with the help of the f3-move, intending not to get an isolated pawn in the centre in case of ...dxe4, but to be able to keep our central structure very healthy by answering fxe4.Black's main idea against the minority attack @@StartBracket@@a flank attack@@EndBracket@@ is to try to organise counterplay on the other side of the board, so against our king. Instead, when White is pushing for f3-e4, as we will see, they have to counterattack in the centre by playing ...c5 or ...b5-...b4 to kick our knight from c3 and weaken the e4-square. }
6... Be7
{ Black is protecting the f6-knight one more time, so on ...Bf5, Qf3 will do nothing. Instead,  6...Nbd7  changes nothing: after  7.Bd3  Be7  we are back to our current line. }
7. Bd3
{ Stopping the bishop's development to f5. Our other option was to play with  7.Qc2  , but Black plays  7...h6!  there and, even though being tricked is a strong word here @@StartBracket@@since we are still in a completely normal position@@EndBracket@@ against the IM Sielecki's recommended move order 6...h6, we want to playthose lines without Qc2. }
7... Nbd7
{ The most common move in the position. Black can still play with ...O-O in the next move, but they also keep the option of playing with ...Nh5. On  7...O-O  we play  8.Nge2  , since  8.Qc2  h6!  is still something we don't want. }
8. Nge2
{ Basically, this is the moment where White has to decide to play with Nge2 and f3-e4, or Nf3 and the minority attack. My recommendation is to play with Nge2. In the Nf3 lines, Black has found many new, interesting ways to play; I found it especially hard to crack Black's plans connected with ...Ne4. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ Once again, it was important to start with this move instead of the more popular  9.Qc2  , since we want to keep our queen on d1 in case Black ever wants to play ...h6! }
9... Re8
{ I believe this is the position you'll get most often from the QGD 3...Nf6 system. }
10. Qc2
{ Finally, we can make this move since we are ready to face ...h6 thanks to an important tactical idea! }
10... Nf8 11. f3
{ Preparing e4, but we have to be careful. One of the basic ideas to check when we are ready to push the pawn is what happens after dxe4-fxe4, Ng4! }
11... Ng6
{ Black trapped our bishop on g5 and their next move is ...h6, so we have to hurry with e4! }
12. e4 dxe4 13. fxe4 Be6
{ Now we can't really play in the standard way, since after  14.Rad1  Ng4!  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Qd2  Black has the very strong  16...c5!  and now we can see why it was a crucial difference for Black to include ...Be6:  17.h3  can be met by  17...cxd4!  and the knight can't jump to d5 with a tempo because the bishop is controlling that square. }
14. Bxf6
{ Of course, it is not ideal to give up the bishop, but it is our best try for an advantage. }
14... Bxf6 15. e5
{ We put our central pawns on dark squares so our light-squared bishop can operate nicely around them. }
15... Be7 16. Rad1 Qb6 17. Kh1
{ Getting out from the pin, and planning to meet ...c5 with d5! } 17... Rad8
18. h3
{ A useful move, preventing ...Bg4 ideas as well as opening the back rank. It is important to note that  18...c5?  is still not possible because of  19.d5!  , and Black can't take the pawn because White has an intermediate capture on g6. }
*

