4. cxd5
{ As against every other option for Black on the 3rd move, I suggest taking on d5 right away, creating the Carlsbad structure and limiting our opponent's choices. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ It is very important to bring this bishop outside of the pawn chain; ...g5 is not available this time, so we play with Bf4. }
5... Nf6
{ Black is protecting the d5-pawn. Therefore, from this moment on, we have to take ...Bf5 into account in every move. We have two ways to address that idea:  physically stop this move by playing Qc2 or Bd3  when the bishop comes to f5, we'll try to disturb it by playing Nge2-Ng3 and h4, or by playing f3 and then later e4/g4. }
6. e3
{ The other logical option would be  6.Qc2  , but after  6...Nh5!  we have to go back to some passive square with our bishop, so I don't like this that much. }
6... c6 7. Bd3
{ Now the queen and the bishop are doing a perfect job together, stopping both ...Bf5 and ...Nh5. }
7... O-O 8. h3
{ Preparing Nf3, and we don't have to worry about ...Nh5 anymore. } 8... Nbd7
9. Nf3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8
{ This is a very standard regrouping in the Carlsbad: the knight is going to g6 and Black will try to create some counterplay on the kingside. }
11. Qc2 Ng6 12. Bh2 { The point of h2-h3. } 12... Bd6
{ A better version ofthe previous line for Black because the knight is already on g6. White is fine anyway. }
13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rab1 a5 15. a3
{ Reinforcing the idea of b4 and playing for the minority attack, which Black tried to slow down by means of ...a5. }
15... Qe7
{ Black's idea is to play ...Ne4, then ...Nh4 and look for counterplay on the kingside. }
16. Na4
{ Thanks to our pawn on h3, in many of the variations I analysed, that bishop on c8 posed a certain danger to our kingside. So eventually I decided it is better to trade it off; then there would be no more sacrifices or wild attacks on the kingside. }
16... Ne4 17. Nb6 Rb8 18. Nxc8 Rbxc8
{ Our king is safe. Let's play on the queenside. } 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4
{ We will continue the standard minority attack with Rfc1, Qb3 and eventually b5. }
