{ The other logical option would be  6.Qc2  , but after  6...Nh5!  we have to go back to some passive square with our bishop, so I don't like this that much. }
6... Bf5
{ The bishop arrived at f5. Now our task is to bother this piece, and definitely no Bd3 for now! }
7. Nge2 c6 8. Ng3 Bg6
{ If instead  8...Be6  , then we can play  9.Bd3  and our opening was a success. We managed to keep that light-squared bishop passive, and we'll play for f3-e4 later. }
9. h4 { Continuing our attack on the light-squared bishop. } 9... h6
{ In general, our task is much easier when Black protects their bishop by playing ...h6. }
10. h5
{ Fixing the pawns on g7 and h6 gives our knight control over the very important f5-square. }
10... Bh7 11. Bd3
{ And once we have a target or a certain idea in mind @@StartBracket@@placing the knight on f5@@EndBracket@@, suddenly the exchange of bishops is in our favour. }
11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Nf5
{ We have a big advantage and a kingside attack is coming. } *

