10. h4 h6 11. h5 { Preparing the f5-square for the knight. } 11... Bh7 12. Bd3
{ Same story. Once our knight can go to f5, we are happy to exchange the bishops. }
12... Bxd3 { Black let White trade and went for  12...Bd6  inMatlakov-Berkes. }
13. Qxd3 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nf5 Qe6 16. f3
{ With a kingside attack to follow, with moves like g4, Kf2 and Ne2-f4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Be7"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Be7: 5...Nf6 6.e3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Be7
{ The Alatortsev variation of the QGD. Black's idea is to change the order of the development of the knight and the bishop. This way, White can't play with Bg5 or, even if we can, it will mean that our knight has to go to f3. This is a problem for us in particular, since I advise you to play the Carlsbad structures with Nge2. }
4. cxd5
{ As against every other option for Black on the 3rd move, I suggest taking on d5 right away, creating the Carlsbad structure and limiting our opponent's choices. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ It is very important to bring this bishop outside of the pawn chain; ...g5 is not available this time, so we play with Bf4. }
5... Nf6
{ Black is protecting the d5-pawn. Therefore, from this moment on, we have to take ...Bf5 into account in every move. We have two ways to address that idea:  physically stop this move by playing Qc2 or Bd3  when the bishop comes to f5, we'll try to disturb it by playing Nge2-Ng3 and h4, or by playing f3 and then later e4/g4. }
6. e3
{ The other logical option would be  6.Qc2  , but after  6...Nh5!  we have to go back to some passive square with our bishop, so I don't like this that much. }
6... O-O 7. Bd3 c5
{ Black is willing to play with an IQP for a short time, as their pieces are well-positioned for a quick ...d4-break which has the potential to completely equalise the position. Instead,  7...c6  8.h3  is transposing to the 6...c6 line.   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/5n2/3p4/3P1B2/2NBP3/PP3PPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4?!  , even though it solves the problem of the bishop, will invite a pawn storm on the kingside. For instance,  8.Nge2  c6  9.f3  Bh5  10.g4  Bg6  11.h4  with a serious attack on the kingside. }
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nge2
{ I prefer the e2-square here. Let's compare: if Black wants to play  9...Bg4  , after  10.h3  Bxe2  we can recapture  11.Nxe2  and  11...d4  is not coming with a tempo anymore.   If instead  9.Nf3  Bg4  and then  10.h3  Bxf3  , we have to recapture  11.Qxf3  , which is still okay but not as ideal as the previous example. }
9... Nc6
{ Black is ready to push ...d4 on the next move. In this move it was not possible yet because, even though the d4-square was controlled enough times, there was a Bxh7+ tactic at the end of the line, picking up the queen. }
10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 Bxe2
{ Black has to take on e2 because  11...Bh5?  drops a pawn.  12.g4!  Bg6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.g5±  and even though we weakened our kingside a little bit, an extra pawn is an extra pawn. }
12. Nxe2 d4 13. Rc1
{ It's a nice bonus to have this move before entering the symmetrical structure. }
13... Bb6 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Bc4
{ White has a small but annoying edge thanks to the pair of bishops in this open position. }
*

