[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Be7"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Be7: 5...c6 6.Qc2 Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Be7
{ The Alatortsev variation of the QGD. Black's idea is to change the order of the development of the knight and the bishop. This way, White can't play with Bg5 or, even if we can, it will mean that our knight has to go to f3. This is a problem for us in particular, since I advise you to play the Carlsbad structures with Nge2. }
4. cxd5
{ As against every other option for Black on the 3rd move, I suggest taking on d5 right away, creating the Carlsbad structure and limiting our opponent's choices. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4
{ It is very important to bring this bishop outside of the pawn chain; ...g5 is not available this time, so we play with Bf4. }
5... c6 { Black wants to play ...Bf5 in the next move. } 6. Qc2
{ We can prevent ...Bf5 by playing Qc2, since there is no ...Nh5 idea in the position yet. }
6... Bd6
{ Black is losing a tempo with their bishop, but they are vacating the e7-square for the knight with the idea of supporting ...Bf5. }
7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Ne7 9. Bd3
{ We are again just in time to prevent the development of Black's bishop. }
9... b6
{ Black wants to exchange the bishop via a6, but at the same time they are weakening the c6-pawn. That's a key thing to understand. It is fine with us if Black can eventually trade the bishops; the main thing is that, in the meantime, we can gain some other advantage, or provoke some other weakness in our opponent's position. }
10. Nf3 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Rac1
{ We'll simply double on the c-file and put pressure on Black's queenside. }
13... Nd7 14. Rc2 Rfe8 15. Rfc1
{ Our f3-knight is the only piece not doing much at this moment. Our next goal is to transfer it to d3, where it can help with the b4-push. }
*

