[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 4.cxd5 Qxd5? #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... Qxd5
{ Not a good move, as we have seen in many previous chapters already. It's not a great idea to fight for important central squares with the queen at this early stage of the game. }
5. Nf3 { Covering the d4-square, so we can break the pin with Bd2. } 5... Nf6
6. g3 c5 7. Bg2 cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ In this symmetrical structure we have a small lead in development, and the difference between the g2 and c8 bishops gives us a nice edge. }
8... Qa5 { Black wants to develop with ...Nc6! } 9. Ne5 { We don't want that! }
9... O-O 10. O-O Rd8 11. Qf4
{ The difference between the light-squared bishops gives White the typical 'Catalan-edge'. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 5...Ba5?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Ba5
{ The bishop doesn't really belong on b6. } 6. b4 Bb6 7. Nf3 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ Somehow, the b6-bishop should move to e7 and break the pin. Then Black would have an acceptable position. }
8... c6 { Black had to defend against the Bxf6-Qxf6, Nxd5 idea. } 9. Qc2
{ In these Carlsbad structures, the future of the c8-bishop is always crucial, so this move is very logical to keep that piece passive. }
9... O-O 10. e3
{ We have a very normal Carlsbad structure, except that Black has a wandering bishop on b6, which should be on e7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 5...Bxc3 & 6...Ne7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7
{ The knight is more passive here than on f6, but it supports the Bf5 idea. Also, once White starts pushing pawns in the centre, the knight on e7 is not that exposed to a quick e4-e5 as it would be on f6. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 Bf5 { Black is exchanging their bad bishop. } 9. Ne2
{ We always go with the knight to e2 in this system, since our main idea is to play with f3-e4 in the centre, or sometimes play with f3-g4. In any case, the pawn, and not the knight, belongs to f3. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c5 11. O-O Nd7
{ If Black is putting their knights on passive squares like these, we don't have to rush with the f3-e4 play. The only point of Black's play here is precisely placing their knights on safer squares, away from that pawn storm. }
12. a4
{ We can try to put some pressure on the queenside. After all, we have a semi-open file to work with. }
12... Re8 13. Ba3 Rc8
{ Instead,  13...c4  stabilises our centre. In such cases, no matter how the knights are standing, we can go for the f3-e4 plan:  14.Qb1  Qc7  15.f3  With a stable centre it is very easy to play for e4. }
14. Rfb1 b6 15. a5
{ We are putting unpleasant pressure on the queenside, moves like Qa6 and Nf4 are on the agenda. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 7...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing tothe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 Bf5
{ Black develops their bishop and would be very happy to see Bd3, since after the exchange they won a tempo compared toour main lines, where our opponent has to play ...b6 @@StartBracket@@so wasting a move@@EndBracket@@ before they can offer the exchange by playing ...Ba6. }
8. Ne2 { No Bd3! We'll play against the f5-bishop. } 8... O-O 9. f3 Re8
{ With this move Black is anticipating g4, and planning to counter it with a sacrifice. }
10. g4 Bxg4 11. fxg4 Nxg4 12. Rg1
{ Black can even take 3 pawns for the piece, but once their g4-knight disappears, it will actually be White who can start attacking on the kingside. }
12... Qh4+ 13. Ng3 Nxe3 14. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 15. Kd2
{ Black is playing with 2 pieces. Now it will be White's turn to attack the lonely black king. }
*

