4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing tothe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Our strategy in this opening variation is to play for e4. We can prepare for this by playing Ne2-g3, f3 and, very often, even a rook lift via a2. If we can manage to do so, and can even push e5, then our position is just much better. Black's goal is obviously to stop this idea, or to prepare for the moment when we are playing e4 to attack our centre by using some tactical tricks. }
8... c5
{ Black can also start with  8...b6  , but eventually they will have to play ...c5, so we will transpose to  8...c5  . One sample line is  8...b6  9.Ne2  Ba6  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  c5  12.f3  Re8  13.Ng3  Nc6  and we are back to  8...c5  . }
9. Ne2 Nc6
{ With this move Black is saying that they are not planning the light-squared bishops trade, which is very much in our favour. }
10. O-O Re8 11. f3 { We are just making our standard moves. } 11... b6 12. Ra2
{ The rook can go anywhere on the second rank, wherever it is needed to support the e4-break. }
12... Bb7 13. Ng3 Rc8 14. Re2
{ If Black is doing nothing, we'll play Bb2 and Kh1, further preparing the e4-break. }
14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Na5 16. Kh1
{ Nice prophylactic move, so the d4-pawn will not be hanging with a check. Therefore, we can also protect it by tactical means. }
16... Nc4 17. e4
{ And Black is strategically lost here. They couldn't stop our break in the centre, and they will have to face a huge attack on the kingside. It is a very important tactical detail that  17...dxe4  18.fxe4  Qxd4  is not working because of  19.e5!  with the idea of Bxh7+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 7...O-O without ...b6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing tothe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Our strategy in this opening variation is to play for e4. We can prepare for this by playing Ne2-g3, f3 and, very often, even a rook lift via a2. If we can manage to do so, and can even push e5, then our position is just much better. Black's goal is obviously to stop this idea, or to prepare for the moment when we are playing e4 to attack our centre by using some tactical tricks. }
8... c5
{ Black can also start with  8...b6  , but eventually they will have to play ...c5, so we will transpose to  8...c5  . One sample line is  8...b6  9.Ne2  Ba6  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  c5  12.f3  Re8  13.Ng3  Nc6  and we are back to  8...c5  . }
9. Ne2 c4
{ This is played very often, but I consider this move a serious strategical mistake. There is no more pressure on our d4-pawn, so it is much easier to achieve the e4-break since we only have to support the e-pawn with our pieces. }
10. Bc2 Nc6 11. O-O
{ White has a very easy and promising play. Ng3-f3 and then e4 are coming with initiative on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 13...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing tothe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Our strategy in this opening variation is to play for e4. We can prepare for this by playing Ne2-g3, f3 and, very often, even a rook lift via a2. If we can manage to do so, and can even push e5, then our position is just much better. Black's goal is obviously to stop this idea, or to prepare for the moment when we are playing e4 to attack our centre by using some tactical tricks. }
8... c5
{ Black can also start with  8...b6  , but eventually they will have to play ...c5, so we will transpose to  8...c5  . One sample line is  8...b6  9.Ne2  Ba6  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  c5  12.f3  Re8  13.Ng3  Nc6  and we are back to  8...c5  . }
9. Ne2 b6
{ This is the most logical move from Black. They want to exchange their bad bishop for our strong piece on d3. When I say bad bishop, I mean that Black's central pawn is on a light square @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@, therefore seriously restricting the scope of the c8-bishop. If we look at the same thing in our camp, we can say that our bishop on d3 is good, since our central pawns are on dark squares @@StartBracket@@c3-d4-e3@@EndBracket@@.Of course, that also means that if the other bishop is not outside of this chain it is on paper a bad bishop. Of course, this is not so clear in our case, since our play is all about pushing e4, and then the c1-bishop could become a very strong piece. }
10. O-O Ba6 11. f3
{ Black is exchanging their bad bishop and White is preparing to push e4. Everything is going very logically. }
11... Re8
{ It is always useful to include this move for Black. The rook helps to slow down e4. }
12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nbd7
{ This move is passive and not good at all, but it shows very well that when we are playing e4, we have to watch out for tricks: if there are no tricks, we are just doing very well! }
14. e4
{ Asking to be played, since both e4 and d4 are under control, we are just gaining a big advantage.   Instead,  14.Bb2!  is the correct move, as shown inthe following trainable. }
14... dxe4 15. fxe4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nc5
{ The unpleasant surprise! Our queen is not protected and we will lose the e4-pawn on the next move! }
*

