{ This is Black's most logical move. They want to exchange their bad bishop for our strong piece on d3. When I say bad bishop, I mean that Black's central pawn is on a light square @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@, therefore seriously restricting the scope of the c8-bishop. If we look at the same thing in our camp, we can say that our bishop on d3 is good, since our central pawns are on dark squares @@StartBracket@@c3-d4-e3@@EndBracket@@.Of course, that also means that if the other bishop is not outside of this chain, it is, on paper, a bad bishop. Of course, this is not so clear in our case, since our play is all about pushing e4, and then the c1-bishop could become a very strong piece. }
10. O-O Ba6 11. f3
{ Black is exchanging their bad bishop and White is preparing to push e4. Everything is going very logically. }
11... Re8
{ It is always useful to include this move for Black. The rook helps to slow down e4. }
12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6
{ That's what Black should do: attack the e4 and d4-squares many times to make it as difficult as possible for White to break through. }
14. Bb2 { We are doing the same: all forces to support the e4 and d4-squares. }
14... c4
{ The most popular move in the position, but it looks dubious and just makes our play much easier. }
15. Qe2 h5
{ Typical move for the variation. Black wants to play ...h4 at some point and kick out our knight from the perfect g3-square. }
16. Qf2 { Setting up an X-ray attack against the f7-pawn. } 16... Qd7
{ Black is protecting f7. } 17. Rae1 b5 18. e4
{ This move works because of tactical reasons! } 18... dxe4 19. fxe4 h4 20. Nf5
Nxe4 21. Qf4 { And Black is losing here. } 21... Nf6 22. Qg5
{ There is no way to defend the g7-square without losing a lot of material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined 3...Bb4: 13...Nc6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Bb4
{ A rare move, but it can easily transpose to well-known openings. For example,  4.Nf3  Nf6  is the starting position of the recently very popular Ragozin Defence, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nf6  would simply transpose into one of the main lines ofthe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
4. cxd5
{ We clarify the situation in the centre and avoid being tricked into some opening we don't play. }
4... exd5 5. a3 { We want to gain the bishop pair. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most natural square for the knight, and this way we are transposing tothe Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Our strategy in this opening variation is to play for e4. We can prepare for this by playing Ne2-g3, f3 and, very often, even a rook lift via a2. If we can manage to do so, and can even push e5, then our position is just much better. Black's goal is obviously to stop this idea, or to prepare for the moment when we are playing e4 to attack our centre by using some tactical tricks. }
8... c5
{ Black can also start with  8...b6  , but eventually they will have to play ...c5, so we will transpose to  8...c5  . One sample line is  8...b6  9.Ne2  Ba6  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  c5  12.f3  Re8  13.Ng3  Nc6  and we are back to  8...c5  . }
9. Ne2 b6
{ This is Black's most logical move. They want to exchange their bad bishop for our strong piece on d3. When I say bad bishop, I mean that Black's central pawn is on a light square @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@, therefore seriously restricting the scope of the c8-bishop. If we look at the same thing in our camp, we can say that our bishop on d3 is good, since our central pawns are on dark squares @@StartBracket@@c3-d4-e3@@EndBracket@@.Of course, that also means that if the other bishop is not outside of this chain, it is, on paper, a bad bishop. Of course, this is not so clear in our case, since our play is all about pushing e4, and then the c1-bishop could become a very strong piece. }
10. O-O Ba6 11. f3
{ Black is exchanging their bad bishop and White is preparing to push e4. Everything is going very logically. }
11... Re8
{ It is always useful to include this move for Black. The rook helps to slow down e4. }
12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6
{ That's what Black should do: attack the e4 and d4-squares many times to make it as difficult as possible for White to break through. }
14. Bb2 { We are doing the same: all forces to support the e4 and d4-squares. }
14... Na5
{ Simply a strategical mistake. The knight looks nice on c4, but it does exactly nothing against the e4-break. }
15. e4 Nc4 16. Bc1
{ It's not a shame to go back. This diagonal is very nice for our bishop now. }
16... cxd4 17. cxd4 b5 18. e5 Nd7 19. f4
{ With f5-f6 and a huge attack to follow, the knight on c4 is completely out of the game. }
*

