{ We don't need to fear for our bishop anymore:  9...Nh5  10.Bh2  . } 9... Bd7
10. O-O
{ Even though the pawn structure is symmetrical, our minor pieces, especially the bishops, are much more active. }
10... Qb6 11. a3
{ No need to worry about the b2-pawn:  11...Qxb2??  blunders the queen:  12.Na4!+-  . }
11... Na5
{ The idea of going to c4 is even less effective with the queen on b6 because Black can't support the knight by playing ...a6-b5. Instead,  11...Rfc8  is coveredhere. }
12. Ne5 { Activating the knight and controlling the c4-square. } 12... Rfc8
{ The pawn was still poisoned!  12...Qxb2??  13.Nxd7!  Nxd7  14.Bxh7+!  This unexpected move helps White to trap the queen on b2.  14...Kxh7  15.Qd3+  The queen protects the c3-knight with tempo. Black's queen can't escape.  15...Kg8  16.Rfb1+-  The queen is trapped.   Even worse is @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1nbppB/4p3/n2p4/3P1B2/P1N1P2P/1q3PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kh8  15.Na4!  Qb5  16.Bd3+-  Threatening the queen and Qh5. White has a decisive advantage. }
13. Qe2 { Black can't support ...Nc4 with more pieces in this position. } 13...
Be8 14. Bg5
{ White's idea is to push the f-pawn and develop an initiative on the kingside. On the other hand, Black can't do much on the queenside because their queen is misplaced on b6. }
*

