{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c6
{ The Triangle System. Black is keeping a lot of options with this move order. Just to name a few:  4.Nf3  dxc4  is the Noteboom variation.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  is the Marshall Gambit.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  f5  is the Stonewall.  Since our repertoire is based on playing the Carlsbad structure, thankfully we don't have to learn any of these massively complicated opening lines. }
4. cxd5 cxd5
{ Black can go for the Exchange Slav with this move. However, it is very rare, because Black already played ...e6, so they can't develop their bishop to f5 or g4, which are the main lines of that opening variation. }
5. Bf4
{ Black can play many different move orders from this position. As a rule of thumb, I can say that the main point is that, when they play ...Bd6 after already having played ...Nc6, then we can take on d6 and play with f4. However, if Black plays ...Bd6 without ...Nc6, then we should play with Bg3. }
5... Nf6
{ If instead  5...Bd6  , since the knight is still on b8, we play with  6.Bg3! }
6. e3
{ As long as Black is not moving their f8-bishop, we are not moving our g1-knight either! Therefore, we keep the option of taking on d6 and then playing f4 before the knight comes to f3.   For example, if  6...a6  , we can just continue with  7.Bd3  and we have one more useful waiting move in reserve, Rc1. }
6... Nc6 7. Bd3
{ The bishop is waiting on f8, so our knight is waiting on g1! } 7... Bd6
{ Instead, Black had only 1 waiting move left:  7...a6  . We can reply with  8.Rc1  and then Black has to decide where to develop their f8-bishop. }
8. Bxd6 { We were waiting for this! } 8... Qxd6 9. f4
{ Our knight will have the very strong e5-square, while Black's ...Ba6 idea is gone. }
9... O-O 10. Nf3 a6 11. Ne5 b5
{ Hundreds of games went like this online. Here we don't have to castle: our king will be perfectly safe on f2, so we can start our kingside attack. }
12. g4 Bb7 13. g5 Ne4
{ Forcing a long tactical sequence which will end up in our favour. } 14. Nxe4
dxe4 15. Bxe4 Qb4+ 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Nxe5 18. Bxb7 Nc4+
{ Black was building their hopes on this intermezzo, but the endgame is still clearly worse for them, even with equal material. }
19. Ke2 Rab8 20. Be4 Nxb2 21. Rhc1
{ The bishop is dominating the knight in such positions with pawns on both sides of the board. }
*

