[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Triangle Slav"]
[Black "Triangle System: 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bf4 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c6
{ The Triangle System. Black is keeping a lot of options with this move order. Just to name a few:  4.Nf3  dxc4  is the Noteboom variation.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  is the Marshall Gambit.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  f5  is the Stonewall.  Since our repertoire is based on playing the Carlsbad structure, thankfully we don't have to learn any of these massively complicated opening lines. }
4. cxd5 exd5
{ Regarding the development of the c8-bishop, ...c6 is the most useful 3rd move that Black can play against us. It protects the d5-pawn, and also very often, when the bishop comes to f5, we could counter it by playing Qb3. Here, ...c6 opens the possibility for Black to simply block it with ...Qb6 without weakening the pawn structure on the queenside. }
5. Bf4
{ The best we can do is to continue the development! The only option to stop ...Bf5 is to play  5.Qc2  , but here Black plays  5...Bd6!  and we are struggling with our c1-bishop! }
5... Nf6 6. e3
{ If instead  6.Qc2  , then I couldn't find any promising ideas for White after  6...g6!  with ...Bf5 to follow. }
6... Bf5
{ The only challenging move. After  6...Bd6  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Bd3!  we can prevent the development of the c8-bishop.  8...O-O  9.h3!  with Nf3 to follow, and we'll play for the minority attack. }
7. Nge2 { With the idea of Ng3 and h4! } 7... Nh5
{ Black not only prevents Ng3 but also threatens to capture our f4-bishop. } 8.
Be5 Nd7 9. h3
{ We have the huge threat of g4, and also vacate the h2-square for our bishop. }
9... Nhf6 10. Ng3
{ White is gaining a tempo on the f5-bishop.  10.Bh2  Be7  is OK for Black. For example:  11.Nf4  Ne4!  12.g4  Bh4!  or  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nbppp/2p5/3p1b2/3PnN2/2N1P2P/PP3PPB/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bd3  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Bxd3  14.Nxd3  b5  15.Ne5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Bf6=  . Another option is  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nbppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/3P4/2N1P2P/PP2NPPB/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.g4  Be4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bg2=  . }
10... Bg6
{ Leaving the ideal diagonal makes White's task very easy.  10...Be6  11.Bf4  h6  Intending ...g5.  12.h4⩲  Preventing ...g5. With Bd3 next, White has a comfortable advantage. }
11. Bf4 Be7 12. Bd3
{ The idea is to play Nf5 and gain the advantage of the bishop pair. } 12...
Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O 14. f3
{ Once our light-squared bishop is off the board, the minority attack is not such a dangerous option because a b4-push would weaken the c4-square and Black could take advantage of it by playing ...b5-Nb6-Nc4. Therefore, now it is time to play in the centre with the f3-e4 break. }
14... Re8 15. O-O Nf8
{ Black's idea is to play ...Ng6 and take our strong bishop. } 16. Nf5
{ Providing the h2-square for the bishop, followed by Rad1 and e4 with a nice initiative in the centre. }
*

