7. Nge2 { With the idea of Ng3 and h4! } 7... Qb6
{ If instead  7...Bd6  , we can simply continue with  8.Ng3!  since  8...Bxf4  is not yet an option because of  9.Nxf5  and after  8...Bg6  9.h4  h5  10.Be2⩲  Black has no easy choice here:  10...O-O  would leave the h5-pawn unprotected and if  10...Bxf4  11.exf4  White has the unpleasant f5 idea. }
8. Qd2 Nbd7
{ This move is quite inaccurate because we can just follow in the footsteps ofthe 7...Nbd7 line. Taking on b2 will be very risky for Black. }
9. Ng3 Bg6 10. h4 h5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3
{ So everything goes in the same way as in the above mentioned7...Nbd7 line, but Black has an extra move with ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@since we lost one move with our queen, Qd1-d2 and only then recapture on d3@@EndBracket@@.   However, now  12...Qxb2?  is extremely risky.  13.Rb1  Qa3  14.O-O  and White already has a decisive advantage, according to the computer. One logical continuation is  14...Bb4  15.Rb3  Qa5  16.Rfb1  Bxc3  17.Rxc3  O-O  18.Ra3  Qd8  19.Rxb7+-  . }
12... g6 13. e4 dxe4 14. Ngxe4 Be7 15. O-O-O
{ Because of Black's king position, we have a very serious initiative. } *

