{ The Triangle System. Black is keeping a lot of options with this move order. Just to name a few:  4.Nf3  dxc4  is the Noteboom variation.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  is the Marshall Gambit.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  f5  is the Stonewall.  Since our repertoire is based on playing the Carlsbad structure, thankfully we don't have to learn any of these massively complicated opening lines. }
4. cxd5 exd5
{ Regarding the development of the c8-bishop, ...c6 is the most useful 3rd move that Black can play against us. It protects the d5-pawn, and also very often, when the bishop comes to f5, we could counter it by playing Qb3. Here, ...c6 opens the possibility for Black to simply block it with ...Qb6 without weakening the pawn structure on the queenside. }
5. Bf4
{ The best we can do is to continue the development! The only option to stop ...Bf5 is to play  5.Qc2  , but here Black plays  5...Bd6!  and we are struggling with our c1-bishop! }
5... Bf5
{ So, we couldn't prevent this bishop from coming to f5.  6.Qb3  is not a dangerous idea because of  6...Qb6  and Nge2-g3 is not even legal yet because our pawn is on e2. Therefore, we are left with the option of playing f3 and then later e4 or g4 to make life more difficult for the f5-bishop. }
6. f3 Nf6
{ Developing and stopping e4. There is no way to further support e4, so we switch to the g4 idea. }
7. g4 Be6
{ If this bishop leaves the b1-h7 diagonal, we already achieved a lot! } 8. e3
Bd6 9. Qd2 h5 10. Bxd6
{ We have to be alert, since the automatic  10.g5?  would be a serious positional blunder because of  10...Bxf4!  11.exf4  Ng8!  with ...Ne7 to follow. Now Black could blockade our kingside pawns, and therefore they would lose their power. }
10... Qxd6 11. g5 Ng8 12. h4 Ne7 13. Qh2
{ We have a nice middle- or endgame ahead, with a space advantage on the kingside. Our next goal is to regroup a knight to f4, something we can achieve by playing Nh3 and Ne2. }
*

