4. cxd5 exd5
{ Regarding the development of the c8-bishop, ...c6 is the most useful 3rd move that Black can play against us. It protects the d5-pawn, and also very often, when the bishop comes to f5, we could counter it by playing Qb3. Here, ...c6 opens the possibility for Black to simply block it with ...Qb6 without weakening the pawn structure on the queenside. }
5. Bf4
{ The best we can do is to continue the development! The only option to stop ...Bf5 is to play  5.Qc2  , but here Black plays  5...Bd6!  and we are struggling with our c1-bishop! }
5... Bd6
{ The most common move of the position. Black is exchanging the dark-squared bishops and then wants to play ...Bf5. }
6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. Qb3
{ Since Black has both ...Ne7 and ...g6 available to support ...Bf5, now we are trying to stop this idea by putting pressure on the b7-pawn, and exploiting the fact that the black queen can't meet this move by going to b6. }
7... Qe7 { Black is protecting b7 and getting ready to play ...Bf5. } 8. e3 Bf5
9. Nge2 { Our only idea is to disturb the f5-bishop with Ng3! } 9... h6
{ Trying to hide the bishop on h7 immediately, so h4 does not come with a tempo. }
10. Ng3 Bh7
{ If instead  10...Bg6  , then  11.Nce2!  intending to transfer the knight to f4.  11...Nf6  12.Nf4  Bh7  13.Bd3!  securing the f5-square  13...Bxd3  14.Nxd3⩲  with Nf5 and Nc5 ideas. White has a pleasant edge. }
11. Nh5 { It is very hard to meet this move! } 11... g6 12. Nf4
{ The bishop on h7 is extremely awkward. Bd3 and O-O are coming and then we can decide whether to play with f3-e4 or go for the minority attack. }
