3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move is the favourite of young Indian Grandmasters Nihal Sarin and Gukesh, but was also played a few times by World Champion Magnus Carlsen. }
6. Bg5
{ We have to play like this because  6.g3  Nc6  would transpose into the main lines of the Tarrasch, which we don't want to play at all! }
6... c4 { This is a mistake. Black is not ready to face e4. } 7. e4
{ Black can't keep their position together after this move. } 7... dxe4
{ Instead,  7...Bb4  has never been tried yet, but it is logical. I'll show you one sample line if Black plays perfectly:  8.Bxf6  gxf6   @@StartBracket@@  8...Qxf6  just lost a piece because of  9.Qa4  Nc6  10.exd5+-  @@EndBracket@@  9.exd5  Qxd5  10.Be2  Rg8  11.O-O!  looks a little bit risky, but just leads to a winning endgame.  11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  Bh3  13.Re1  Rxg2  14.Kh1  Rg8  15.Bxc4+  Kd7  16.Bxd5  Bg2+  17.Kg1  Bxf3+  18.Kf1  Bxd1  19.Raxd1+- }
8. Ne5 Be7
{ Instead,  8...Be6  is not better:  9.Qa4+  Nbd7  10.Bxc4+-  leads to a huge advantage for White, whose initiative is very dangerous. }
9. Bxc4 O-O 10. Qb3
{ White is very active and according to the computer the position is already  +2.  For instance, on  10...Qe8  we can just play  11.Nb5  . }
