13... cxd4 { Taking this pawn is very risky. } 14. Rad1 c5
{ In order to keep the extra pawn, Black has to allow their king to be even more open. }
15. Qa6+ Kb8 16. Qb5+ Ka8 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. Qc6+
{ The point of this check is to force the king to b8, so once we take with the knight on d4, Nc6 will be an immediate threat. }
18... Kb8 19. Qxc5
{ Here, for instance, if  19...Qd6  , simply  20.Qxd4  Qxd4  21.Nxd4  and Black doesn't have time to take on a2 because Nc6+ is coming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Tarrasch Defence"]
[Black "Tarrasch Defence: 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nf3 Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move is the favourite of young Indian Grandmasters Nihal Sarin and Gukesh, but was also played a few times by World Champion Magnus Carlsen. }
6. Bg5
{ We have to play like this because  6.g3  Nc6  would transpose into the main lines of the Tarrasch, which we don't want to play at all! }
6... Be6
{ The best move for Black, protecting the d5-pawn. Now, Bxf6 will not ruin their structure anymore, as they can recapture with the queen, and are preparing to play ...c4. Then, in case of an eventual e4 dxe4, the bishop is also protecting the c4-pawn. Instead,  6...Nc6  doesn't do anything about the d5-pawn, so White is just better after  7.Bxf6  gxf6   @@StartBracket@@  7...Qxf6  8.Nxd5  Qd8  9.dxc5  is a healthy extra pawn for White.  @@EndBracket@@  8.e3±  with a much better structure. }
7. Bxf6
{ I like this concrete approach; the main move is  7.e3  and then Black can reply  7...c4  . I don't really like those positions: Black can get a dangerous initiative on the queenside. Instead, we'll try to use our development lead and quickly open the position. }
7... Qxf6 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Qf4
{ The only good move for Black. The position is very concrete, so it requires some precise play. If  9...Qd8  , then  10.Qa4  Bd7  11.Bb5  gives White a nice initiative. Instead,  9...Qf5  is simply very illogical since it walks into the bishop's diagonal  10.Bd3±  . }
10. Bb5+ { Developing with a check and getting ready to castle. } 10... Nc6
{ Again the only move. If  10...Nd7  then  11.Neg5!  with Qe2 to follow is very bad for Black. }
11. Qe2
{ Protecting the knight on e4 and preparing some tricks, like d5, against the black king. }
11... cxd4 { This move is not really challenging for us. } 12. Nxd4 Bb4+ 13.
Kf1
{ Our king will quickly find a good square on g2, so the rook will be ready to join the game from h1. }
13... O-O 14. Nxe6
{ We are creating a very bad structure for Black, and a very strong square for our knight on e4. }
14... fxe6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. g3
{ Black is facing a very unpleasant defence in a very strong knight vs bishop position. }
*

