[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Tarrasch Defence"]
[Black "Tarrasch Defence: 5...Nc6 6.dxc5 sidelines #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. dxc5
{ As I said, there have been many new developments in the main lines starting with  6.g3  , so it makes sense to go for a lesser-known line that can't bring us many surprises and will guarantee a small edge. }
6... Be6
{ With the same idea as  6...Nf6  , but this is not as challenging because the bishop is much less annoying than the knight was on e4 or g4. }
7. Be3 Nf6 8. Nd4
{ We want the d4-square for our bishop at the end of the day. } 8... Rc8 9. Qa4
{ Pinning the knight and in some cases the a7-pawn can easily fall. } 9... Bd7
10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Qf4
{ Keeping the d4-square for the bishop. Taking on  a7  is too greedy and also a huge mistake:  11.Qxa7??  d4  12.O-O-O  Ra8!-+  Black is winning material. }
11... Bd7
{ 11...Ne4  With the idea of cutting White's queen off the queenside and reinforcing ...Qa5+.  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Qe5+  It seems that a single pawn on e4 is not enough to block our queen out of the game.  13...Be7  14.Rd1  Qa5+  15.Bd2  Qxc5  Black takes back the pawn just to lose a maybe even more important one in the next move.  16.Qxg7  Rf8  17.e3+-  Followed by Be2 and O-O. White is completely winning with the extra material and safer king. }
12. Rd1
{ The easiest solution. White is giving back the pawn but enters a very favourable IQP position. }
12... Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Rxc5 14. e3 O-O 15. Bd3
{ With O-O to follow. We have firm control over the d4-square and Black's worst piece in such structures, the light-squared bishop, is still on the board, which guarantees White a clear, long-term advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Tarrasch Defence"]
[Black "Tarrasch Defence: 5...Nc6 6.dxc5 d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5
{ The Tarrasch Defence. Black is willing to have an isolated pawn, and they want to compensate for it with active piece play and a potential attack against the king in the middlegame.That could have been a short description of this opening variation a few years ago, but there have been many developments and new lines appearing in the last couple of years, mainly thanks to the efforts of Russian GM Daniil Dubov. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. dxc5
{ As I said, there have been many new developments in the main lines starting with  6.g3  , so it makes sense to go for a lesser-known line that can't bring us many surprises and will guarantee a small edge. }
6... d4
{ The absolute main line. Black is not wasting time in protecting this pawn, but rather pushes it to a protected square. }
7. Na4
{ Protecting the c5-pawn. This is one of the rare cases when it is better to go with the knight to the rim than to the centre. On e4, the knight would be more exposed to attacks like ...Qd5 or ...Bf5. Our next goal is to play e3 to exchange the d4-pawn and finish our development. }
7... b5 { Black wants to use the unusual placement of the knight on a4. } 8.
cxb6 axb6 { With the threat of ...b5 trapping the knight! } 9. e3
{ Continuing the development and controlling the b5-square at the same time. }
9... Bb4+
{ Instead,  9...b5  is a tricky but very bad move.  10.Bxb5!  Qa5+  and it looks like that Black is winning a piece but after  11.Nc3!+-  they actually have to resign because our bishop is protected, Black's knight is hanging on c6 with a check and the d4-pawn is also hanging. }
10. Bd2 Bd7
{ Black is still aiming at our knight, but we can simply parry these threats. }
11. Bb5 Ra5 { Forcing exchanges, which we don't mind at all. } 12. Bxb4 Nxb4
13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. b3 dxe3 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Nxb6+ Kc7 17. Nc4
{ And we keep our extra pawn, with excellent winning chances. } *

