{ Protecting the c5-pawn. This is one of the rare cases when it is better to go with the knight to the rim than to the centre. On e4, the knight would be more exposed to attacks like ...Qd5 or ...Bf5. Our next goal is to play e3 to exchange the d4-pawn and finish our development. }
7... Bxc5
{ By far the best move in the position is to take back the pawn immediately. Instead,  7...Nf6  is not addressing our next move  8.e3  at all and after  8...Bg4  9.Be2  Black is already in trouble:  9...b5  is just losing to the nice  10.Nxd4!  , while after  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2P5/N2p2b1/4PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxc5  10.O-O  Be7  11.Nxd4  Bxe2  12.Nxe2±  we ended up with an extra pawn.   7...Bf5  is a little bit better than ...Nf6, but still very dubious.  8.e3  d3  was the idea behind ...Bf5, but after  9.a3!  stopping ...Nb4 ideas, it is hard to come up with anything active for Black. A possible line is  9...Nf6  10.b4  Qd5  11.Nc3±  with the idea of pushing b5 and then Nd4 and collect the pawn on d3. }
8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 Qxc5 10. e3
{ The other main line is  10.a3  , which leads to a more complicated play, but  10.e3  just seems very logical. There will be no central pawns anymore and that should favour our bishop pair. }
10... dxe3
{ Black is forced to take, otherwise is just losing the pawn on d4. } 11. Qxe3+
{ It is also very good that simplifying the position comes with a queen exchange. The queen can work pretty well together with the knights, so with this trade, our opponent is also losing chances for active counterplay. }
11... Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 Nf6
{ This is somewhat less precise than  12...Nge7  . White can use their slight initiative to create some weaknesses in the opponent's camp. }
13. Bb5
{ We don't mind giving up the pair of bishops if we can isolate Black's queenside pawns. }
13... O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O
{ Playing for 2 results. Black's task is pretty difficult here. } *

