11... Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 Nge7 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O Bg4
{ Both sides are developing in the most natural way. In the gameSarana-Fridman Black decided he'd rather play with one weakness after  14...Be6  15.Bxe6  fxe6  than against the bishop pair. }
15. Nd4
{ As long as the bishop pair is on the board, we are okay with all kind of exchanges. }
15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Rfd8
{ In case of  16...Nc6  we play  17.Bc3  and the knight is perfectly dominated by our bishop. }
17. Be3 Nd5 18. Bg5 { We don't give the bishop! } 18... f6 19. Bd2
{ We have a small advantage. There are no real instructions for such positions, because they really have to be tested in practice. The general guidelines are: be patient and keep the bishop pair while slowly pushing the pawns on the kingside. Black's play is probably even more difficult. }
