[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Semi-Tarrasch Defence"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch Defence: 6...Be7?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6 4. cxd5
{ We take on d5 now, as we are aiming for the Carlsbad structure. In case of  4.Bg5  , we would give Black the possibility to play with  4...dxc4!  and then the game would take a completely different direction. }
4... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch, an absolutely sound alternative to the much more regular and popular  4...exd5  . This move is only played in 10% of the games, compared to the 90% ofthe Tarrasch 4...exd5. It is quite shocking, but I believe the reason is that the Semi-Tarrasch is really an opening for the highest level and for professional chess.Even though Black doesn't have too many winning chances in general, the position is very solid and a good weapon to neutralise the dangerous, attacking 1.d4 players. }
5. e4
{ Of course, there is no reason not to push e4 if we can do it without any downside. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... Be7 { Too passive and 'lazy' move. } 7. Qg4
{ Black is facing immediate problems with the defence of the g7-pawn. } 7... g6
{ Instead,  7...O-O?  is just very bad.  8.Bh6  g6   @@StartBracket@@  8...Bf6  is already losing to  9.e5+-  @@EndBracket@@  9.Bxf8  Bxf8  10.Bc4±  and we are just up a clear exchange.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4p3/8/3PP1Q1/2P5/P4PPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  is a little bit trickier, but still pretty bad for Black:  8.Qxg7  Bf6  9.Qh6  exd4  10.Nf3!  This developing move with the idea of pushing e5 is very strong and important.  10...dxc3  11.e5  Be7  12.Bc4  with a huge advantage for White. }
8. Bc4 { Developing and anticipating Black's ...e5. } 8... c5
{ Instead,  8...e5?  fails to  9.Qf3!  and the pawns on e5 and f7 are hanging. }
9. Nf3 cxd4 10. cxd4 O-O 11. O-O e5
{ It is not good, but otherwise, White would play e5 and start a very dangerous attack on the kingside. }
12. Qg3 exd4 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Ne5 { The simplest way to win the game. } 14...
Be6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nxg6
{ White is delivering mate or winning a lot of material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Semi-Tarrasch Defence"]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch Defence: 6...b6?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6 4. cxd5
{ We take on d5 now, as we are aiming for the Carlsbad structure. In case of  4.Bg5  , we would give Black the possibility to play with  4...dxc4!  and then the game would take a completely different direction. }
4... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch, an absolutely sound alternative to the much more regular and popular  4...exd5  . This move is only played in 10% of the games, compared to the 90% ofthe Tarrasch 4...exd5. It is quite shocking, but I believe the reason is that the Semi-Tarrasch is really an opening for the highest level and for professional chess.Even though Black doesn't have too many winning chances in general, the position is very solid and a good weapon to neutralise the dangerous, attacking 1.d4 players. }
5. e4
{ Of course, there is no reason not to push e4 if we can do it without any downside. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... b6 { A pretty slow move. } 7. Nf3 Bb7 8. Bb5+
{ Good to remember this idea! First, we are provoking Black to play ...c6, closing the long diagonal, and only then do we put the bishop on its most ideal square, d3. }
8... c6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 c5
{ The only critical try from Black. Otherwise White would grab the initiative by playing e5. }
12. d5
{ The key move! Black can only choose between 2 different types of worse positions here. }
12... exd5 13. exd5 Qxd5
{ 13...h6  14.c4⩲  The protected passed pawn on d5 creates great difficulties for Black and a stable edge for White. }
14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Re1
{ Black is worse here because of the weakness of their king. } *

