5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... c5 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ This looks like a completely natural move, putting more pressure on our centre, but actually, this move almost loses the game for Black. }
8. d5 { Black has big problems with the knight! } 8... Nb8
{ Since it was played quite regularly in online games, I decided to give a little bit complicated but crushing line for White here. }
9. Ne5 { Bb5+ is a huge threat now. } 9... a6 { Black is stopping it. } 10.
Nxf7 { A bolt from the blue! } 10... Kxf7 11. dxe6+ Ke8 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qe5 Rg8
{ Everything is forced: Black doesn't have alternatives. } 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Rd1
{ Bringing a new piece into the attack. } 15... Qb6 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Qg5+ Ke8
18. Bc4
{ If  18...Nc6  we don't rush but play  19.O-O  with threats like  19...--  20.Rd7  or  20.e7  . }
18... Bxe6 19. Qf6
{ White will win back the piece on the next move with a crushing position. } *

