4... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch, an absolutely sound alternative to the much more regular and popular  4...exd5  . This move is only played in 10% of the games, compared to the 90% ofthe Tarrasch 4...exd5. It is quite shocking, but I believe the reason is that the Semi-Tarrasch is really an opening for the highest level and for professional chess.Even though Black doesn't have too many winning chances in general, the position is very solid and a good weapon to neutralise the dangerous, attacking 1.d4 players. }
5. e4
{ Of course, there is no reason not to push e4 if we can do it without any downside. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black is developing with a tempo and finally trades this bishop. Instead,  8...Nc6  9.Be2  Bb4+  10.Bd2  Bxd2  11.Qxd2  O-O  12.Rd1  transposes to  8...Bb4+  . }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Rd1
{ A rare move, only the 5th most popular in the position. The main lines are  11.Bc4  or  11.Be2  . I have seen it from Rapport first, but Kramnik and recently Giri also employed this variation.The main point of this move is to stay as flexible as possible. Black has a few different ways to put their pieces, and with this useful move we are basically saying to Black that first, they will show us what they want, and then we will react accordingly. We don't give up on the d5 idea, but we also don't give up on putting our bishop on d3 to play against the black king. }
