{ On move 11, the most popular move is Bc4, but here we can use the flexibility offered by playing Rd1 first in our favour. From e2, the bishop will support the d5 break much more effectively than from c4, since ...Na5 will not come with tempo! }
12... Qa5
{ Black goes for the endgame. Therefore, we don't castle; our king stays in the centre and will go to e3. }
13. Rc1 Rd8
{ Black is putting pressure on d4, so it is time to trade queens and force the knight away from attacking d4. }
14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Kd2
{ The king will be perfect on e3, protecting both central pawns. } 15... Bd7
16. Ke3 Rac8 17. h4
