{ This move was played only once, but it deserves attention because it is the recommendation of GM Ganguly in his fantastic course on the Semi-Tarrasch. }
12. h4
{ We are going on with the most flexible move! As it is excellently demonstrated by GM Ganguly, if  12.Bd3  , then White has problems with the defence of the d4-pawn after  12...Ba4!  13.Rb1  Nc6!  . If  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be2  , then Black first plays  12...Ba4!  13.Rb1  and only now  13...Bc6  , so White doesn't have d5 and has to lose a tempo with  14.Bd3  , which is far from ideal.   @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc4  doesn't give anything either, because after  12...Bc6!  if we want to play d5 and recapture there with a pawn, then we are opening the e-file for our king.Here comes the point of playing a useful waiting move like h4. If Black is going to attack e4, then we can play Bd3 right away; if they want to attack d4, our pawn is currently protected, since the bishop is not closing the queen's way to protect the pawn.It is also worth mentioning that h4 is even useful for White if we castle short. This move doesn't mean that we are going for an all-out attack with our king in the centre. }
12... Bc6 13. Bd3 { The bishop reaches its ideal square in 1 move! } 13... Ba4
{ This is Black's original idea against 12.Bd3, but now we have an extra h4-move in the position. }
14. Rb1 Nc6 15. Qe3 Qa5+ 16. Kf1
{ Without the pawn on h4 it would be somewhat strange to play like this, but now the rook has work on the h-file or on the 3rd rank. }
16... Rad8 17. Rh3
{ The rook is coming into play thanks to the extra h4 move! } 17... Kh8
{ Black has to prepare ...Qc3 with this move. If instead  17...Qc3?  , then Black is in trouble after  18.e5!  g6  19.h5!  and a long forced line works out in White's favour:  19...Nxd4  20.hxg6  fxg6  21.Rxb7  Qa1+  22.Ne1  Rd7  23.Rxd7  Bxd7  24.Qh6  Rf7  25.Bxg6  Bb5+  26.Bd3+-  and White has a big advantage. }
18. Rg3 Qc3
{ Now e5 wouldn't be an issue for Black, because Bxh7 is not a threat. } 19.
Rxb7 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Rxd4
{ Surprisingly, the best recapture, according to the computer, is  20...Qxd4!  forcing the queen trade.  21.Qxd4  Rxd4  22.Rxa7  g6  23.Ke2  Even though the position is closer to equal than an edge for White here, according to the machine, in a practical game Black will have a difficult task to prove it since White has a solid extra pawn. }
21. Kg1
{ Bringing the king into safety. White has threats like taking on a7 or playing Rc7, decoying the queen and then taking on d4 with a double attack.  21.Rxa7??  would have been a big blunder:  21...Bb5!  and Black is winning. }
