3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6 4. cxd5
{ We take on d5 now, as we are aiming for the Carlsbad structure. In case of  4.Bg5  , we would give Black the possibility to play with  4...dxc4!  and then the game would take a completely different direction. }
4... Nxd5
{ The Semi-Tarrasch, an absolutely sound alternative to the much more regular and popular  4...exd5  . This move is only played in 10% of the games, compared to the 90% ofthe Tarrasch 4...exd5. It is quite shocking, but I believe the reason is that the Semi-Tarrasch is really an opening for the highest level and for professional chess.Even though Black doesn't have too many winning chances in general, the position is very solid and a good weapon to neutralise the dangerous, attacking 1.d4 players. }
5. e4
{ Of course, there is no reason not to push e4 if we can do it without any downside. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ We have a nice pawn centre so, obviously, the most logical and best move for Black is to challenge it immediately. The alternatives are much worse. }
6... c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black is developing with a tempo and finally trades this bishop. Instead,  8...Nc6  9.Be2  Bb4+  10.Bd2  Bxd2  11.Qxd2  O-O  12.Rd1  transposes to  8...Bb4+  . }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Rd1
{ A rare move, only the 5th most popular in the position. The main lines are  11.Bc4  or  11.Be2  . I have seen it from Rapport first, but Kramnik and recently Giri also employed this variation.The main point of this move is to stay as flexible as possible. Black has a few different ways to put their pieces, and with this useful move we are basically saying to Black that first, they will show us what they want, and then we will react accordingly. We don't give up on the d5 idea, but we also don't give up on putting our bishop on d3 to play against the black king. }
11... Bd7
{ This move was played only once, but it deserves attention because it is the recommendation of GM Ganguly in his fantastic course on the Semi-Tarrasch. }
12. h4
{ We are going on with the most flexible move! As it is excellently demonstrated by GM Ganguly, if  12.Bd3  , then White has problems with the defence of the d4-pawn after  12...Ba4!  13.Rb1  Nc6!  . If  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be2  , then Black first plays  12...Ba4!  13.Rb1  and only now  13...Bc6  , so White doesn't have d5 and has to lose a tempo with  14.Bd3  , which is far from ideal.   @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/4p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P2Q1PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc4  doesn't give anything either, because after  12...Bc6!  if we want to play d5 and recapture there with a pawn, then we are opening the e-file for our king.Here comes the point of playing a useful waiting move like h4. If Black is going to attack e4, then we can play Bd3 right away; if they want to attack d4, our pawn is currently protected, since the bishop is not closing the queen's way to protect the pawn.It is also worth mentioning that h4 is even useful for White if we castle short. This move doesn't mean that we are going for an all-out attack with our king in the centre. }
12... Ba4 { Playing this move is one of the main ideas behind 11...Bd7. } 13.
Rb1 Bc6 14. Bd3 f5
{ GM Ganguly mentions this move as an interesting option in a similar position, just without h4. }
15. Ng5 fxe4 16. Bc4 Bd5 17. Nxe6 e3 18. fxe3
{ The pawn on h4 makes the difference here: if Black could play ...Qh4+, their position would be completely fine. }
