[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...dxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black is giving up their central control. This move only makes sense if Black is going to protect this pawn in the next move. }
4. e3 Be6
{ Looks ugly, but still, it is one of the possible ways to protect the pawn. }
5. Nbd2
{ Let's not join the group of players who lost the game at move 5 by playing  5.Ng5??  and blunder this knight to  5...Qa5+  . }
5... b5
{ 5...Qa5  will most likely transpose to 5...b5, since at one point that will be the only move to protect the pawn.  6.Be2  Nf6  7.O-O  Now the pawn is hanging again on b5, so  7...b5  8.a4  and we have transposed to the 5... b5 line.     6...c3  will allow Black to keep the extra pawn, but with zero developed minor pieces.  7.bxc3  Qxc3  8.Rb1  Bc8  is the best in order not to create weaknesses.  9.O-O  with a huge lead in the development. The computer is already evaluating this position as +3.  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2pppp/2p1b3/q7/2pP4/4PN2/PP1NBPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  is the other possible deviation:  7.O-O  Nb6  8.Ne4!±  with Nc5 coming on the next move guarantees White a big advantage. }
6. a4 { Our threat is axb5 and then b3. } 6... a6 7. Ng5 Bd5
{ If the bishop goes backwards,  7...Bd7  for example, then  8.axb5  cxb5  9.Qf3!  this double attack is very unpleasant. }
8. e4 h6 9. Ngf3 Be6 10. axb5 cxb5 11. b3
{ We are undermining Black's queenside. } 11... c3 12. Bxb5+ axb5 13. Rxa8
cxd2+ 14. Bxd2 { We are going to win material very soon. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...dxc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black is giving up their central control. This move only makes sense if Black is going to protect this pawn in the next move. }
4. e3 Be6
{ Looks ugly, but still, it is one of the possible ways to protect the pawn. }
5. Nbd2
{ Let's not join the group of players who lost the game at move 5 by playing  5.Ng5??  and blunder this knight to  5...Qa5+  . }
5... b5
{ 5...Qa5  will most likely transpose to 5...b5, since at one point that will be the only move to protect the pawn.  6.Be2  Nf6  7.O-O  Now the pawn is hanging again on b5, so  7...b5  8.a4  and we have transposed to the 5... b5 line.     6...c3  will allow Black to keep the extra pawn, but with zero developed minor pieces.  7.bxc3  Qxc3  8.Rb1  Bc8  is the best in order not to create weaknesses.  9.O-O  with a huge lead in the development. The computer is already evaluating this position as +3.  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2pppp/2p1b3/q7/2pP4/4PN2/PP1NBPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  is the other possible deviation:  7.O-O  Nb6  8.Ne4!±  with Nc5 coming on the next move guarantees White a big advantage. }
6. a4 { Our threat is axb5 and then b3. } 6... Qa5
{ If instead  6...Nd7  , then  7.Ng5!  is already very strong.  7...Bd5  8.e4  h6  9.exd5  hxg5  10.dxc6  and Black's position is collapsing. }
7. Be2
{ We want to castle quickly, and then see what we can do on the queenside. }
7... Nf6 8. O-O g6
{ Black is trying to finish the development. Instead,  8...Nbd7  is not really good. One possible line is  9.Ng5!  attacking the bishop:  9...Bf5  10.e4  Bg6  11.e5  Everything is coming with tempo.  11...h6  12.Ngf3  Nd5  13.Nh4!  Bh7  14.e6!  and Black is collapsing on the light squares. }
9. Ng5 { Not giving Black the time to play ...Bg7 and ...O-O. } 9... Bd7
{ Instead,  9...Bd5  is even worse and makes our task very easy:  10.e4  h6  11.exd5  hxg5  12.dxc6  and Black's queenside pawn chain is falling. }
10. Nde4
{ The easiest way to have a nice advantage.  10.b4!  is already winning according to the engine, but it's not so easy to figure it out if you don't remember the lines. We have to sacrifice a piece against some moves there, and yes, it is indeed the best line, but I believe in such a rare variation we don't really have to remember lines with a piece sacrifice up to move 20. }
10... Bg7
{ Instead,  10...Nxe4  doesn't change much:  11.Nxe4  Bg7  12.Nc5±  with a clear edge for White. Our next move is Bf3. }
11. Nc5 { We have a very strong positional compensation for the pawn. } 11...
O-O 12. Bd2 Qb6 13. Bf3
{ With axb5 to follow, Black can't keep their pawn chain compact anymore. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...dxc4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black is giving up their central control. This move only makes sense if Black is going to protect this pawn in the next move. }
4. e3 b5 5. a4
{ We are immediately starting to undermine Black's queenside pawns. } 5... a6
{ It is very easy to win back the pawn against this move. } 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3
{ This is our typical idea in the 4...b5 line: take on b5 and then push b3. }
7... cxb3
{ 7...Be6?  is not really good. Black will lose the c4-pawn anyway, but at least also slows down their own development.  8.bxc4  bxc4  9.Nc3  Nf6  10.e4+-  with d5 and e5 coming, this position is already lost for Black. }
8. Bxb5+ { Using the pin on the a-file, we are taking back one pawn. } 8... Bd7
9. Bc4 e6 10. O-O Nf6 11. Qxb3
{ If we can reach this structure, it is always a clear advantage for us. We have a strong centre and no weaknesses, while Black will have to defend the weak a-pawn, which is not easy. }
*

