1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black is giving up their central control. This move only makes sense if Black is going to protect this pawn in the next move. }
4. e3 b5 5. a4
{ We are immediately starting to undermine Black's queenside pawns. } 5... Bb7
6. b3 { After this move Black already can't keep their extra pawn. } 6... cxb3
7. axb5 cxb5
{ Instead,  7...e6  8.Qxb3  is just a clear advantage for White. If Black can finish the development without major issues, they will still be left with a weak a-pawn. }
8. Bxb5+ Bc6 9. Ne5
{ We are better in different ways, but this is a pretty nice way! } 9... Bxb5
10. Qxb3 e6 11. Qxb5+ Nd7 12. Nd2
{ With Ndc4 and O-O coming, it is unlikely that Black can finish their development without losing material. }
