{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black is giving up their central control. This move only makes sense if Black is going to protect this pawn in the next move. }
4. e3 b5 5. a4
{ We are immediately starting to undermine Black's queenside pawns. } 5... e6
6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 Bb4+
{ This is the most interesting concept for Black in this variation. They are giving back the pawn, but want to have connected passers on the queenside! }
8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 a5
{ 9...c3?  is not working:  10.Bxb5+  Bd7  11.Bxd7  Nxd7  12.Nc4+-  and we will soon collect the pawn on c3. }
10. bxc4 b4
{ Here we are. Black has managed to create two passed pawns on the queenside, but in return for it, White has a very strong centre. }
11. Ne5 { Introducing the Qf3 threat into the position. } 11... Nf6 12. Be2 O-O
{ Instead,  12...Bb7?  is pretty much losing:  13.Qa4+!  Nbd7  14.c5  O-O  15.c6  Nb6  16.cxb7  Nxa4  17.bxa8Q  Qxa8  18.Rxa4  Qxg2  19.Bf3  Qh3  20.Rxa5+-  We have a lot of material for the queen. }
13. Bf3 Ra6
{ The main line for Black. It will be much easier to play for ...Nbd7 when the rook is not standing in the Nc6 tempo. }
14. O-O Qc7 15. Nd3 Nbd7 16. Ra4
{ With the idea of Qa1. We are blockading and also attacking the pawns.  16...Nb6  is not very disturbing: we just play  17.Ra2  with Qa1 and the Nxb4 threat to follow. }
