[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...e6 4.Nbd2 f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 e6
{ Black is playing the Triangle System but, contrary to theTriangle Chapter @@StartBracket@@when our knight is on c3 in this identical situation@@EndBracket@@, we are not taking on d5 now. That's because the f3-knight is not working well together with our main idea in those Carlsbad structures, stopping @@StartBracket@@or at least preparing to meet@@EndBracket@@ the development of the c8-bishop. }
4. Nbd2
{ We are protecting the c4-pawn, and getting ready to fianchetto our f1-bishop in case Black is going for the Stonewall. }
4... f5 { 4...Nf6  5.Qc2  is discussed viathe 3...Nf6 move order. } 5. g3
{ Of course, we put our bishop on g2, and we are not developing with e3 because we don't want to close the c1-bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O
{ After the natural developing moves, we have to figure out which setup we want to play. }
8. Ne1
{ I like this manoeuvre the most! The idea is not rare, but the move is, at least in the current position. We want to play Nd3-Nf3-Bf4 and control the central dark squares.  8.Ne5  is very similar to my chosen move, but I didn't like it for one concrete reason: I want my other knight on e5! Let's see what line I'm referring to:  8.Ne5  b6  9.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd5  10.Ndc4  Bc7  11.Bf4  and here our knight on c4 is hanging on the air a little bit. We'll see how it'll work out if we start with Ne1! }
8... b6 9. cxd5
{ Again, we are not waiting for Black to play ...Bb7-...Nbd7 and ...c5, but closing the diagonal. }
9... cxd5
{ 9...exd5  10.Nd3  with Bf4 to follow is very pleasant. Black would have a fine position with the pawn on b7, but the pawn is already on b6, meaning that the c6-square is a big issue. }
10. Nc4 Bc7 11. Ne5
{ And now, instead of having a knight on c4, we will have the perfect setup with N1d3 and Bf4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...e6 4.Nbd2 f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 e6
{ Black is playing the Triangle System but, contrary to theTriangle Chapter @@StartBracket@@when our knight is on c3 in this identical situation@@EndBracket@@, we are not taking on d5 now. That's because the f3-knight is not working well together with our main idea in those Carlsbad structures, stopping @@StartBracket@@or at least preparing to meet@@EndBracket@@ the development of the c8-bishop. }
4. Nbd2
{ We are protecting the c4-pawn, and getting ready to fianchetto our f1-bishop in case Black is going for the Stonewall. }
4... f5 { 4...Nf6  5.Qc2  is discussed viathe 3...Nf6 move order. } 5. g3
{ Of course, we put our bishop on g2, and we are not developing with e3 because we don't want to close the c1-bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O
{ After the natural developing moves, we have to figure out which setup we want to play. }
8. Ne1
{ I like this manoeuvre the most! The idea is not rare, but the move is, at least in the current position. We want to play Nd3-Nf3-Bf4 and control the central dark squares.  8.Ne5  is very similar to my chosen move, but I didn't like it for one concrete reason: I want my other knight on e5! Let's see what line I'm referring to:  8.Ne5  b6  9.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd5  10.Ndc4  Bc7  11.Bf4  and here our knight on c4 is hanging on the air a little bit. We'll see how it'll work out if we start with Ne1! }
8... Nbd7 9. Nd3 Qe7
{ Black is improving their position a little bit, and also waiting for us to protect on c4 somehow. Then, they will decide whether to go for the ...b6-plan, or rather to go with ...Ne4. }
10. Qc2 { Protecting on c4, so Nf3 and Bf4 can come. } 10... b6
{ This is probably the first time in a Stonewall structure when our opponent plays ...b6 and we don't take. They simply chose a smart move order, forcing us to commit the queen to c2, and we need that half tempo very much, since our queen is better on a4, applying pressure on Black's queenside. }
11. b4 { I still don't want to wait for Black to play ...Bb7-...c5! } 11...
Bxb4
{ Taking the pawn is extremely risky, but the only test of the b4 idea. After  11...Bb7  12.c5!  we managed to play c5 instead of Black, making their b7-bishop very passive.  12...Bc7  13.Nf3⩲  . Our next move is Bf4 and then we can continue to put pressure on the queenside. }
12. Nxb4 Qxb4 13. a4
{ With Ba3 coming in the next move, White has a huge compensation for the pawn. According to the engine, it is even a clear edge. Let's see a couple of sample continuations:   13...Qd6  14.Ba3  c5  15.cxd5!  exd5  16.Nb3!  We are taking back the missing pawn.  16...Ba6  17.dxc5  bxc5  18.Nxc5  Nxc5  19.Bxc5  Rfc8  20.Rfc1±  Black's structure is weak, and we also have the bishop pair advantage.   13...Re8  14.Ba3  Qa5  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Nc4  Qa6  17.Nd6  Rd8  18.Qc7  Rf8  19.Nb5  Re8  20.Qd6  and Nc7 is unstoppable in the next move, so we are winning an exchange. }
*

