10. Qc2 { Preparing Nf3 and Bf4. } 10... Qe7
{ Instead, if  10...Ndf6  , then  11.c5!?  looks good, gaining space on the queenside. After  11...Bc7  we can just play  12.Nf3  with Bf4 to follow, since the knight on f6 is not allowing Black to prevent it with ...g5. }
11. Nf3 b6 12. cxd5
{ We can return to our standard ways since Black gave back the tempo we lost for Qc2 in the form of ...Ne4, which is absolutely not useful in this structure. Quite the contrary rather, since if Black can play ...Ba6 and ...Bxd3 at some point, then exd3 would be a tempo on the e4-knight. }
12... cxd5 13. Bf4 { Exchanging one defender of the e5-square. } 13... Ba6 14.
Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qa4
{ With a slight advantage for White because of the e5-square and pressure on the queenside. }
