{ After the natural developing moves, we have to figure out which setup we want to play. }
8. Ne1
{ I like this manoeuvre the most! The idea is not rare, but the move is, at least in the current position. We want to play Nd3-Nf3-Bf4 and control the central dark squares.  8.Ne5  is very similar to my chosen move, but I didn't like it for one concrete reason: I want my other knight on e5! Let's see what line I'm referring to:  8.Ne5  b6  9.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd5  10.Ndc4  Bc7  11.Bf4  and here our knight on c4 is hanging on the air a little bit. We'll see how it'll work out if we start with Ne1! }
8... Nbd7 9. Nd3 Ne4
{ If instead  9...b6  , then  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Nf3⩲  with Bf4, Qa4, Rfc1 to follow and pressure on the queenside. }
10. Qc2 { Preparing Nf3 and Bf4. } 10... Qf6
{ The most aggressive move from Black, controlling the e5-square and also the g5-square multiple times. }
11. Nf3 g5
{ Stopping the Bf4 move, so we have to look for some new square for our bishop. }
12. b3
{ Preparing a positional pawn sacrifice. This position was reached via a different move order inKunte-Lahiri and Black played  12...f4  . }
12... g4 13. Nfe5
{ We are giving up the d4-pawn, but in return will get a very strong dark-squared bishop, and full control over the long diagonal. }
13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bb2
{ Now it is White's turn to attack. Black's kingisde is overextended. } 16...
d4 17. f4
{ Opening up the position, since if Black's queen retreats, then we just take back the pawn on e4. On  17...Qc5  we of course play  18.Qd3  first and then take on d4 or e4. }
17... gxf3 18. exf3 Nc3
{ Black would be happy to give back the pawn immediately, but we have a lot of time to win it back. }
19. Rae1 Qf6 20. f4
{ White has a clear advantage: Black's c8 bishop is awful. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Bg4
{ Because of the e2-pawn, this is not a pin. Therefore, this move makes a strange impression, inviting the aggressive Ne5. }
4. Ne5
{ Black will have to waste another tempo on the bishop, so their position is already suspicious. }
4... Bh5 { Not a good move, going in the bad direction with the bishop. } 5.
Qb3 { With a double attack on b7 and d5. } 5... Qb6
{ Instead,  5...Nd7  is just giving up the pawn without a fight:  6.Qxb7  Nxe5  7.dxe5+- }
6. Qh3
{ A very nice and rare double attack. Black is losing a lot of material. } 6...
Nf6 7. Qc8+ Qd8 8. Qxb7
{ White is already up a pawn, but there is more to come. } *

