[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Bg4
{ Because of the e2-pawn, this is not a pin. Therefore, this move makes a strange impression, inviting the aggressive Ne5. }
4. Ne5
{ Black will have to waste another tempo on the bishop, so their position is already suspicious. }
4... Nf6
{ Black is giving up the pair of bishops and even allowing White to gain a lot of space in the centre. }
5. Nxg4 Nxg4 6. e4 { The knight has to move again. } 6... Nf6 7. e5
{ Securing our space advantage in the centre. } 7... Nfd7 8. Nc3 e6 9. Be3
{ Strengthening the centre and preparing against future ...c5-breaks from Black. }
9... Bb4 10. Qg4
{ Forcing some weaknesses on the kingside, as Black can't castle due to the Bh6 threat. }
