[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Bg4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Bg4
{ Because of the e2-pawn, this is not a pin. Therefore, this move makes a strange impression, inviting the aggressive Ne5. }
4. Ne5
{ Black will have to waste another tempo on the bishop, so their position is already suspicious. }
4... Bf5
{ Instead,  4...Be6  looks very awkward.  5.cxd5  cxd5  6.Nc3  f6  7.Qa4+  Nd7  8.Nd3±  with Nf4 and e4 to follow give White a very nice advantage. }
5. cxd5 cxd5 6. e4 { White is already winning. } 6... dxe4 7. Bc4
{ The idea is to force ...e6 first, and then give a check on the a4-e8 diagonal, closing out the f5-bishop so it can't help defend. }
7... Be6
{ Instead,  7...e6  8.Qa4+!  is decisive.  8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Qxc6+  Ke7  11.Bg5+  @@StartBracket@@forcing a black piece to f6, so the king will not be able to run away via f6@@EndBracket@@  11...f6  12.Qb7+  and since the king can't go away, the queen has to block the check, leaving the rook on a8 hanging:  12...Qd7  13.Qxa8  fxg5  14.O-O+-  . }
8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Qh5+ { White is winning a lot of material. } 9... g6 10. Nxg6
Nf6 11. Qb5+ { The h8-rook is dropping. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Bf5
{ Too early to play this move. As we have already seen many times before, the refutation of this move is connected with Qb3. }
4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3 { It is absolutely not trivial to protect the b7-pawn! }
5... Qc7
{ The second most common move in the position is also losing for Black.  5...Qd7?  This move is also asking for trouble, walking straight into the Ne5 tempo and also into the a4-e8 diagonal.  6.e4!  opening the way for our bishop with a tempo.  6...Bxe4  7.Ne5  A huge tempo on the queen, which has to keep guarding the b7-pawn.  7...Qc8  8.Nc3  Now Nxe4 followed by Qxf7 is the threat.  8...e6  9.Nxe4!  dxe4  10.d5+-  With Bb5+ or dxe6 coming in the next move, Black's position is just losing. }
6. Nc3 { Covering the c1-bishop and attacking the d5-pawn twice. } 6... e6
{ Instead, on  6...Nf6  , we can simply take the extra pawn.  7.Nxd5  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  e6  9.Qb3±  with a healthy extra pawn. Black has no compensation whatsoever. }
7. Bf4
{ Using the fact that the queen has to protect the b7-pawn.  7...Qxf4??  8.Qxb7  is resignable for Black. }
7... Qb6 8. Nb5 { The next threat Black has to address is Nc7+. } 8... Na6 9.
Rc1
{ Occupying the c-file looks like the most natural move in the position, but we are allowing ...Bb4+! }
9... Bb4+ 10. Kd1
{ And even though it will be Black who will take a piece first, eventually they will end up down a piece. }
10... Qxb5 11. e4 { We are taking back the piece immediately. } 11... Qb6 12.
exf5
{ The material is equal, but Black has huge problems with their piece coordination. }
12... Nf6 13. Bxa6 { Winning a piece by force! } 13... bxa6 14. Bc7
{ We will force the queen to an unprotected square, and then pin the bishop on b4. }
14... Qb5 15. a4 Qb7 16. Ba5
{ The game is over, since on  16...Rb8  we will take everything on b4, and then pick up the rook on h8. }
*

