{ The threat is e5 when Black's f6-knight has no square to go to, so taking on e4 is forced. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ By far the best move.  7...Be7  is very passive:  8.Nxf6+  Nxf6  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Bd2!  where we can castle long in the next move and prepare for a kingside attack with g4-g5.   7...Bb4+  is also inaccurate because we can cover the check with  8.Nc3!  O-O  9.Be2  and we keep our slight edge thanks to our space advantage in the centre. }
8. Qxe4
{ It is worth comparing this position with a better-known variation where we are getting the same structure: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e3  e6  5.Nf3  Nbd7  6.Qc2  Bd6  and here, even though not the main move, a perfectly playable sideline for White is to play  7.e4  dxe4  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Qxe4  . In this variation, White played e4 in 2 moves, and Black used that extra tempo for the very useful developing move ...Bd6. We have an improved version here, as we could play e4 in one go thanks to Nbd2 protecting the c4-pawn. @@StartBracket@@We didn't have to protect it with e3.@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Bb4+ { This is the most logical move. Black is developing with tempo. } 9.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 O-O
{ Instead,  10...Nf6  is illogical, as the knight is leaving the square where it could support both the ...c5 and ...e5 breaks, and those moves are crucial for the activity of their light-squared bishop.  11.Qe3  O-O  12.Be2  b6  13.O-O⩲  White is better. We enjoy some space advantage and Black still hasn't solved the problem of their c8-bishop. }
11. O-O-O c5
{ Black is challenging our centre, which is definitely the way to go, but at the same time, we are getting closer to an endgame, where our queenside majority can be a big asset. }
12. Nf3 cxd4
{ The gameLaznicka-Andriasian features  12...Qa5  @@StartBracket@@13...Qa5 there.@@EndBracket@@ }
13. Bd3 { Developing with tempo. } 13... Nf6 14. Qxd4
{ Black is facing a tough decision here. The endgame is definitely at least slightly worse for them, but if they keep the queens on the board, it is rather the black king who can be attacked. }
14... Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. Rhe1
{ It's much easier to push our majority on the queenside than Black's on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... g6
{ Playing in the Schlechter style is quite possible here. Even though we didn't close our c1-bishop with e3 yet, we are very far from achieving our ideal setup @@StartBracket@@knight on c3, bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@ when the Schlechter is considered dubious. }
5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4
{ Black is developing their bishop, but this move is basically offering us the bishop pair advantage. Instead,  7...Bf5  is also possible, but we just keep on gaining space on the queenside and the bishop will have to watch out for Nh4 ideas.  8.b4  Nbd7  9.a4  and White has a clear play on the queenside. }
8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 e6
{ Black's setup is extremely solid, and they managed to get rid of their bad bishop. However, it is tough to play these waiting type of positions. Basically, they have no active ideas: if they go for some pawn push, it will favour our bishops. }
10. b4 Nbd7 11. a4
{ Gaining space on the queenside. We will eventually play b5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... g6
{ Playing in the Schlechter style is quite possible here. Even though we didn't close our c1-bishop with e3 yet, we are very far from achieving our ideal setup @@StartBracket@@knight on c3, bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@ when the Schlechter is considered dubious. }
5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. b4
{ Now we are not taking on d5, which is our usual approach in such positions  @@StartBracket@@seethe Grünfeld Chapter@@EndBracket@@ since our knight on d2 is also misplaced for such a structure. Instead, we are gaining space on the queenside. }
8... a5
{ Black is going for this active idea before we have the chance to push a4. This way Black can push ...a4 themselves as well, but it will not pose big problems for us. }
9. b5 c5
{ Black is creating maximum tension in the centre.  9...dxc4  10.bxc6  bxc6  11.Nxc4  is better for White. It will not be that easy for Black to get rid of the c6-pawn, since  11...c5  12.Ba3!  and if  12...cxd4  , then after  13.Nxd4  our pieces are much more active, Nc6 is a threat, and Bf3 is coming too.  9...cxb5  10.cxb5  a4  when Black is isolating the pawns on the queenside @@StartBracket@@also for themselves@@EndBracket@@, but it doesn't affect our development.  11.Ba3⩲  and that is a perfect place for the bishop. }
10. Bb2 b6
{ In the gamePetrosyan-Gholami Black released central tension first with  10...cxd4  11.Bxd4  b6  . }
11. cxd5
{ Vacating the c4-square for the knight, which was our worst piece in the position. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nc4
{ And it suddenly becomes a good piece, attacking on b6 and also helping the Nfe5 idea. }
12... Bb7 13. Rc1
{ White has some nice pressure. We will play Qd2 and Rfd1, and it is pretty hard to improve Black's position. It would be good to play ...e6-...Qe7, but it allows Nd6. }
