[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... a6
{ Against our setup the Chebanenko Slav is not very effective, because in general it has two main points:1@@EndBracket@@ Play ...b5 and ask White what to do with the c4-pawn.2@@EndBracket@@ As a useful waiting move, help the development of the c8-bishop, since the critical move after ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 is most often Qb3 and, after a6, Black can protect the pawn with ...Ra7 or ...b5.Playing ...b5 is not really advisable, since we can still put our bishop on the long diagonal and, once it opens up, Black has just created a weakness on c6. On the other hand, Black didn't need any preparation for bringing the bishop out: ...Bf5 was already possible. }
5. g3 { Anticipating ...b5, we are developing the bishop on g2. } 5... b5
{ We are very happy to see this, since it is weakening the long diagonal. } 6.
b3 Bf5 7. Bg2 e6
{ Instead, Black can try  7...h6  to secure the h7-square for their bishop, but it will lead to some issues with the development of their other bishop.  8.Ba3!  Nbd7  9.O-O  e6  10.Bxf8  Kxf8  11.Ne5  and White has the initiative. Black will have to waste a lot of time to put their king into safety. }
8. Nh4
{ Taking Black's light-squared bishop, after which it will be much easier to play for e4. }
8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bb2
{ O-O and e4 are coming. The position is clearly better for White: Black has lost a lot of their solidity by playing ...b5 and weakening the c6-square. }
*

