1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bg4 { This move is still bad, just invites Ne5 with tempo. } 5. Ne5 Bf5 6.
cxd5 cxd5 7. e4
{ In contrast withthe 3...Bg4 line, now we have knights on d2 and f6. This should rather favour Black, but it is not changing the evaluation of the position: Black is much worse/losing. }
7... dxe4
{ 7...Nxe4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bc4!  we have already seen this trick, forcing ...e6 so the bishop can't help blocking the future check on the a4-e8 diagonal.  9...e6  10.Bb5+  Nc6  11.Nxc6  Qd5  12.Qb3!  a6  13.Ba4  Qxb3  14.axb3+-  and White keeps their extra piece because  14...b5?  is not possible, as after  15.Bxb5  the rook is hanging on a8. }
8. Qb3 { With a double attack on b7 and f7. } 8... Be6 9. Qxb7 Nbd7 10. Nc6
{ Collecting some material, and entering a very promising endgame. } 10... Qc8
11. Qxc8+ Rxc8 12. Nxa7
{ We are up a pawn but, more importantly, our queenside pawns are extremely dangerous. }
