[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Bg6
{ This move is still kind of okay, but it gives up the pair of bishops without any compensation for it.  5...Bg4  is similarly giving up the bishop without a fight:  6.h3!  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Nxg6  hxg6  9.Bg2⩲ }
6. Qb3 Qc7
{ Black has to play this move and go for a solid but passive position.   Instead,  6...Qb6?  is already bad though.  7.Qh3!  One of the main tricks of the Nbd2 system is that, by leaving the 3rd rank open, the queen can create double threats using the h3-square.  Nbd7  8.Nxg6  fxg6  9.e3±  With a clearly better position for White. Not only do we have the bishop pair, but also a much better structure. }
7. Nxg6 { Securing the bishop pair advantage. } 7... hxg6 8. g3
{ We will play for e4 so, of course, our bishop's natural square is g2. We are also protecting the h2-pawn along the way. }
8... e6 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O Be7 11. e4
{ There is no reason to delay this move. The knight will have to go from d2 anyway, so our c1-bishop can develop. }
11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nf6 14. Bf3
{ We have a small but long-lasting edge here, because of the bishop pair and the space advantage in the centre. We will have 2 potential ideas to break Black's position. Once they castle, we can consider the plan Kg2-h4-Rh1 and starting active operations on the kingside, but we can also play for b4-b5 to weaken the long diagonal and make our bishop on f3 even stronger. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Be6
{ This may look ugly at first sight, but Black wants to develop with ...g6 after this move, and the bishop on e6 and our knight on h4 are kind of in the same category, far from ideally placed. }
6. e3 g6 7. b3
{ I believe it is worth playing this move now. If we choose another move order, for example,  7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.b3  , then Black can use this moment to play  9...c5!  and take advantage because our bishop is not on b2 yet. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb2
{ We don't have to be afraid of ...c5 anymore, since our bishop is controlling the long diagonal after dxc5. }
8... O-O 9. Nhf3
{ We bring our knight back to a normal square, but we also give up the control of the f5-square, so Black can do the same with their bishop. }
9... Bf5
{ We still achieved something though. Ideally, Black would combine ...Bf5 with ...h6 and retreat the bishop to h7. Instead, they can't go backwards on this diagonal anymore, because we kind of forced them to develop with ...g6. }
10. Be2 a5
{ This is always an idea when our knight is not on c3 but on d2, as now playing ...a4 is a real possibility. }
11. O-O a4
{ However, this is not good in this particular position!   If Black tries to get the knight to b4, we don't allow it!:  11...Na6  12.a3  Ne4  13.cxd5!  Going for an Exchange Slav structure is very effective here, since we can get rid of our only misplaced piece, the d2-knight. Black, on their part, created a weakness by playing ...a5, and they can't be too proud of their g7-bishop and a6-knight either.  13...cxd5  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Ne5⩲  with pressure on the queenside, with Qd2 and Bc3 to follow. }
12. bxa4 { Somewhat ugly, but very effective! } 12... Qa5 13. cxd5 cxd5
{ Black has to take like this.  13...Nxd5??  allows  14.e4+-  . } 14. Bb5
{ And we are proudly keeping our extra pawn on the a-file! } *

