{ 10...Nbd7  11.O-O  Ne4  12.Nxe4  will lead to the same position. } 11. O-O
Nd7 12. Nxe4 { We will gain the pair of bishops! } 12... Bxe4
{ Instead,  12...dxe4  would just create an extra weakness for Black.  13.Nd2  h5  14.Qc2  Nf6  15.a4⩲  with a pleasant pressure on the queenside. If Black plays ...h4 at some point, then we can reply with h3, but before that, we don't need to do anything on the kingside. }
13. Ng5
{ Now we can see why it is very good for us that there is a pawn on g6: the bishop can only retreat to f5. }
13... Bf5
{ 13...Nf6  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qc2⩲  with a small but definite advantage because of the pair of bishops and clear play on the queenside with b4-a4. }
14. g4 e5
{ Counterattacking the knight on  g5  . Instead,  14...h6  would lead to an even worse position for Black:  15.gxf5  hxg5  16.fxg6  f5  .  This was Black's idea to keep their structure healthy, but they are not in time:  17.Bd3!  threatening  Qh5  17...g4  18.f3!  is opening up the kingside and Black's position is just losing. }
15. Nxh7 { Key move, but not very difficult to find. } 15... Kxh7 16. gxf5 gxf5
17. Kh1 { Our structure is better and Black's king is pretty weak. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 Bf5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Be4
{ Black is forcing f3 before retreating to g6, so we have to close the 3rd rank. Then the Qh3 idea is not working anymore. }
6. Qb3 Qc7
{ A solid move, but we can already take, since including Qb3-Qc7 is an improvement for us. Our queen is attacking, while Black's queen is defending. }
7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Nf3
{ The knight was not doing anything on h4 anymore, so it was time to return. ...Qa5+ was also a threat. }
8... e6 9. Nd2 { Exchanging Black's most active piece. } 9... Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Nd7
11. e3
{ Bd3-O-O-Qc2 and then we will start pushing our queenside pawns, but we can also consider playing with e4 if Black allows us @@StartBracket@@that is, doesn't play ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 Bf5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Be4
{ Black is forcing f3 before retreating to g6, so we have to close the 3rd rank. Then the Qh3 idea is not working anymore. }
6. Qb3 Qb6 7. f3
{ Instead,  7.Qh3?  would be a mistake here, since it is not a double but rather a fake double threat.  7...Nbd7  8.f3  Bc2!  and we are never taking on g6, but managed to completely misplace our pieces instead. }
7... Qxb3 8. Nxb3 Bc2 9. g4
{ With the idea of pushing g5 at some point and we will have the g2-square for the knight, so we can't blunder ...g5 anymore. As a side note, this is also a very nice positional trick. }
9... e6
{ Taking on c4 looks good, but it is pretty dangerous for Black:  9...dxc4  10.Na5  b5  Of course, if we can take on c4 or b7 for free, then we are simply better. This move is the only question.  11.Bd2!  Not the usual refutation. :@@EndBracket@@ We are preventing any ...Bb4+ ideas from Black, and preparing to play Rc1-b3 and undermine their queenside, where there will be a lot of weaknesses available once the c4-pawn is exchanged.  e6  12.Rc1  Bg6  13.e4±  With the g6-bishop and f6-knight completely restricted because of our central pawns, and b3 coming in the next move, White has a clear advantage. }
10. Bd2 { Preparing to meet  10...dxc4  with  11.Na5! } 10... Be7 11. Ng2
{ We are also not blundering the ...Nxg4 trick. } 11... dxc4
{ This move is still not working, but this is the only way to challenge our slightly better position.  11...h6  12.e3  O-O  13.Kf2⩲  is simply better for White because we have more space, and our next moves are h4-Nf4 hinting at g5 ideas. Na5 is also a possibility. }
12. Na5 b5 13. Rc1 Bg6 14. h4 { And Black has problems with their g6-bishop. }
14... h5
{ 14...h6  15.Nf4  Bh7  16.e4±  with strong pressure on Black's position and b3 or g5 coming in the next move. }
15. g5 Nd5 16. e4 { Occupying the centre and closing the bishop with a tempo. }
16... Nb4 17. a3 N4a6 18. Nf4
{ Bh3 is coming in the next move and Black will have a hard time preventing Nxg6 and the loss of the e6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
