[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Slav Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Slav: 3...Nf6 4.Nbd2 Bf5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav Defence is one of the most solid choices available for Black against 1.d4. This is a very sound and stable opening, very popular in all levels. Black is supporting the d5-pawn by playing ...c6 and, contrary to the QGD variations, they are not closing their bishop on c8, so it is ready to develop to f5 or g4. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2
{ Only the 7th most popular move in the position, so we can call it a sideline and we'll have a good chance to surprise our opponent with this. The main idea of the move @@StartBracket@@besides avoiding all the heavily analysed main lines@@EndBracket@@ is to challenge the development of the c8-bishop. }
4... Bf5
{ By far the most common move. There is no reason for Black to delay the development of their bishop. }
5. Nh4
{ The key move of the 4.Nbd2 variation. If we wait for Black to play ...h6 and keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, then we have no advantage whatsoever. Black would have easily solved the issue of their problematic piece and we just put our knight on a less than ideal square on d2. }
5... Be4
{ Black is forcing f3 before retreating to g6, so we have to close the 3rd rank. Then the Qh3 idea is not working anymore. }
6. Qb3 Qb6 7. f3
{ Instead,  7.Qh3?  would be a mistake here, since it is not a double but rather a fake double threat.  7...Nbd7  8.f3  Bc2!  and we are never taking on g6, but managed to completely misplace our pieces instead. }
7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 { Securing the double bishop advantage. } 8... hxg6 9. cxd5
{ The most direct way of playing. We want to clarify the situation on the queenside and then play accordingly. }
9... Qxb3
{ This move is inaccurate: it is improving our knight and will give us the initiative. }
10. Nxb3 cxd5 11. Bd2
{ Preparing to bring the rook to the open file. It is better to keep the bishop on d2 than to put it on the seemingly more active f4-square, because after  11.Bf4  Nc6  12.e3  Nh5!  is an annoying idea. }
11... e6 12. e3 Nc6 13. Bb5 Rc8 14. Rc1
{ Na5 is coming. Black is under pressure. } *

