[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Delayed Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Delayed Queen's Gambit Accepted 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... dxc4
{ Black is taking on c4 one move later than in the Classical QGA, which gives us the option to play e4 without entering heavily analysed theoretical lines. As Black is already committed to play with ...e6, these much sharper options are not available anymore:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  b5!?   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  e5 }
4. e4 Nf6
{ Instead,  4...Bb4  has no independent value, since after  5.Bxc4  Black will play ...Nf6 anyway.   Same goes for  4...Nc6  , when after  5.Nf3  Black again has nothing better than to play with ...Nf6. }
5. Bxc4
{ If here Black plays  5...c5  , by far the best move, then we are transposing tothe 4...c5 5.d5 Nf6 6.Bxc4 variation. All the other possible moves are too slow and give us a chance to trade our edge in the centre for a dangerous initiative. }
5... Be7
{ Putting exactly zero pressure on our centre. This is not even solid, because the g7-square will be an issue for Black. }
6. e5 Nd5 7. Qg4 g6 { Instead,  7...O-O  drops an exchange to  8.Bh6+-  . } 8.
Bh6 { With Nf3 and O-O to follow, the black king has serious issues. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Delayed Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Delayed Queen's Gambit Accepted 4...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... dxc4
{ Black is taking on c4 one move later than in the Classical QGA, which gives us the option to play e4 without entering heavily analysed theoretical lines. As Black is already committed to play with ...e6, these much sharper options are not available anymore:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  b5!?   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  e5 }
4. e4 Nf6
{ Instead,  4...Bb4  has no independent value, since after  5.Bxc4  Black will play ...Nf6 anyway.   Same goes for  4...Nc6  , when after  5.Nf3  Black again has nothing better than to play with ...Nf6. }
5. Bxc4
{ If here Black plays  5...c5  , by far the best move, then we are transposing tothe 4...c5 5.d5 Nf6 6.Bxc4 variation. All the other possible moves are too slow and give us a chance to trade our edge in the centre for a dangerous initiative. }
5... Nc6
{ Putting the knight before the c-pawn looks unnatural and, as usual, it is bad again. Having said that, this position has been reached many times OTB and thousands of times in online games. }
6. Nf3 Bb4 7. Bd3
{ Among many good options for us, I like this the most. We are preventing short castle, besides protecting the pawn on e4. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Nxd4??  is a little bit too greedy:  8.Nxd4  Qxd4  9.Bb5+  and Black lost their queen. }
8. e5 Nd5 9. Bxh7+ { The Greek gift is working very well here! } 9... Kxh7 10.
Ng5+ Kg8
{ 10...Kg6  doesn't make our task very difficult.  11.h4!  We want to force the king to h6, give a discovered check with the knight and win the queen.  11...Nxc3  12.h5  Kh6  13.bxc3  Bxc3  14.Kf1+-  with Nxe6/Nf7 or Qd3-Qh7 coming. }
11. Qh5 Qxg5
{ Only move. After  11...Re8  the standard mate is coming:  12.Qxf7+  Kh8  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Qh7+  Kf8  15.Qh8+  Ke7  16.Qxg7  1-0 }
12. Bxg5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxc3+ 14. Ke2 Bxd4 15. Bf6
{ A very nice move. Black can't escape from the mating attack. } 15... gxf6 16.
Qg4+ Kh7 17. Qh4+ Kg6 18. Qxf6+ Kh7 19. Qh4+ Kg7 20. Qg4+ Kh7 21. Rhd1
{ The rook is coming to deliver checkmate. } *

