{ Black is taking on c4 one move later than in the Classical QGA, which gives us the option to play e4 without entering heavily analysed theoretical lines. As Black is already committed to play with ...e6, these much sharper options are not available anymore:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  b5!?   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  e5 }
4. e4 c5
{ Immediately challenging our centre is a must for Black if they want to get a decent position in this line. }
5. d5
{ Once the e6-pawn is exchanged, the d5-square is going to be an excellent outpost for our pieces. }
5... Nf6 6. Bxc4 exd5 7. Nxd5
{ 7.exd5  is also possible but, as I said earlier, I would like to use this square with the minor pieces. }
7... Nxd5
{ Instead,  7...Nxe4??  is losing a piece because of  8.Qe2  Bf5  and  9.f3+-  . }
8. Bxd5 Be7
{ 8...Nc6?!  is inviting us to enter a better endgame, which I believe we should accept.  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.Bf4⩲  Black has no compensation for their worse structure. }
9. Ne2
{ Now the Qh5-Nf3 attacking plan was not so effective anymore, since the bishop from e7 is nicely controlling the g5-square. Therefore, our knight goes to e2, since from that square it is 2 moves away from d5, while from f3 it would be 4! }
9... O-O 10. O-O Nd7 { Black wants to challenge or even trade our d5-bishop. }
11. Nc3 Nb6
{ Better than  11...Nf6  , because it leaves the f6-square for the bishop. The knight's task is the same anyway: put some pressure on the d5-square. }
12. Bf4 Bf6 13. Rc1
{ Bringing the rook into the game, and anticipating both ...Bd4 and ...Nxd5. }
13... Bd4 14. b4 { Undermining the strong bishop on d4. } 14... Nxd5 15. exd5
Bxc3 16. Rxc3 cxb4 17. Rg3
{ Black has won a pawn, but the main factor with opposite-coloured bishops is king safety. We basically have an extra attacking piece on the dark squares and our goal is to use it and attack Black! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Queen's Gambit Stonewall"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Stonewall: 6...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... f5
{ The signature move of the Stonewall setup. Black is putting their pawns on light squares, therefore controlling all the light squares in the centre very well. That will make it difficult for White to break there, for example with the e2-e4 move. Hence the name of the opening.On the other hand, this setup will logically create weaknesses on the dark squares and also seriously restrict the c8-bishop, which the Black players originally tried to active via the d7-e8-h5 route. A more modern approach is to play with ...b6, put the bishop on b7, and then later play ...c5. }
4. Bf4
{ A very important move, which in my opinion makes the Stonewall a very questionable choice against our repertoire. Let me show you another move order when Black is building the Stonewall.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  and here, if instead of entering very sharp lines with  4.Nf3  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  Qxd4  , White plays  4.e3  and Black replies with  4...f5  , in that case, the Stonewall is a much more respectable opening. The reason is that the c1-bishop is stuck within the pawn chain and will not be able to fight and occupy the weakened dark squares. }
4... c6
{ Black completes the Stonewall formation, and indeed their control of the light squares is impressive. }
5. e3 Nf6 6. Nf3
{ The most natural square for our knight, immediately eyeing the weak e5-square, which can't be controlled by black pawns anymore. }
6... Bd6
{ This move is less challenging than  6...Be7  . We are completely okay with the exchange of the dark-squared bishops and, once it happens, the e5-square will be even weaker for Black. }
7. Bd3
{ We can simply continue the development. We don't have to make a decision yet with the f4-bishop since, as we will see, taking on f4 is rather good for us and not for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Bxf4
{ With this move Black decides to change the structure. However, what I like for White here is that, once we kick the black knight from e4, not only the e5-square will be very weak, but we can also attack the e6-pawn in the semi-open file.Additionally, the main attacking option for Black is to play with ...g5 at some moment, and our f4-pawn can slow down or even make that plan impossible in many cases. }
9. exf4 Ne4 10. Qc2
{ A natural improving move, which very often makes the ...b6 ideas for Black much more difficult to execute, since White can reply to those with cxd5 and the queen is ready to do damage on the c-file. }
10... Nd7 11. Ne2
{ A very typical move for the whole Stonewall variation. This move has usually three main ideas: to transfer the knight to f4 @@StartBracket@@in the present position this idea is out of the picture@@EndBracket@@ and then maybe later via d3 to e5, to open the c-file for the queen @@StartBracket@@therefore making ...b6 more difficult or impossible to play@@EndBracket@@, and, when we are ready to push f3 and kick the knight from e4, that knight can get into danger if it can't take on c3 anymore. }
11... Rf6
{ Black is trying to create something on the kingside, but it will be very difficult. One, if not the most important demand of a successful attack in general, is to have the superiority of forces, which is very hard for Black to achieve here around the white king.   Instead  11...b6?  would perfectly illustrate the point of White's two previous moves:  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.Qc6!  and the double attack on the rook and on the e6-pawn is winning material for White.   11...Ndf6  was also played in a few games. Here we can simply occupy the weak square by playing  12.Ne5  , and if for instance Black is playing  12...Bd7  , then after  13.c5  @@StartBracket@@taking away the d6-square@@EndBracket@@ if our opponent is not careful, we will trap the e4-knight with f3 in the next move! }
12. g3
{ An interesting idea. We can build a stonewall around our king, so the f3-knight will not be on defensive duties anymore and can go to e5. }
12... Rh6 13. c5
{ Gaining space advantage on the queenside. We are ready to push there with b4-a4-b5 and later, with the knight joining from e5, put big pressure on the c6-pawn. }
13... Qe8 14. h4
{ With this move we completely stop all possible threats from Black. } 14...
Qh5 15. Kg2 Ndf6 16. Ne5
{ Black's position is strategically lost. Basically, they have no attack, and White can start putting pressure on the queenside. We can also play for f3, but in that case always watch out for sacrifices. }
*

