4. Bf4
{ A very important move, which in my opinion makes the Stonewall a very questionable choice against our repertoire. Let me show you another move order when Black is building the Stonewall.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  and here, if instead of entering very sharp lines with  4.Nf3  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  Qxd4  , White plays  4.e3  and Black replies with  4...f5  , in that case, the Stonewall is a much more respectable opening. The reason is that the c1-bishop is stuck within the pawn chain and will not be able to fight and occupy the weakened dark squares. }
4... c6
{ Black completes the Stonewall formation, and indeed their control of the light squares is impressive. }
5. e3 Nf6 6. Nf3
{ The most natural square for our knight, immediately eyeing the weak e5-square, which can't be controlled by black pawns anymore. }
6... Be7
{ The idea of this move is that after ...Ne4 Black is ready to go with ...g5 immediately with some actual threats! That was not the case inthe 6...Bd6 line, when anytime ...g5 would come, White could always just exchange the bishop on d6. }
7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2
{ I like this move order better than starting with  8.O-O  . There may not be any big differences, but it is good to inform Black that we are ready for the ...b6-plan. Also, Black can't play ...g5 so confidently until we castle. }
8... Ne4 9. h3
{ Very important to prepare a square for the bishop in case of ...g5. We also slow down Black's play with ...g4 a lot, since after hxg4-fxg4 the support of the e4-knight is going to be much weaker. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O g5 11. Bh2 Rf7
{ With the idea of playing ...Rg7 and supporting the attack from there. } 12.
Ne2 { The knight is controlling very important squares from e2. } 12... h5
{ Finally we can see some attack from Black! Fortunately, it is not so difficult to defend against it. }
13. Ne5
{ Introducing the f3 idea into the position, and also not allowing ...g4 to come with a tempo. }
13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bd6 15. Bxe4
{ Exchanging all the active black pieces, with a clear positional idea in mind! }
15... dxe4
{ Instead  15...fxe4  may look more logical, but Black's position is falling apart after the very strong  16.f3! }
16. h4 { A very nice idea, gaining the f4-square for the knight. } 16... gxh4
17. Nf4
{ Black's attack is stopped and we have our usual play on the queenside. If now someone wants to play on the kingside, it is actually White, after playing Kh2-Rg1 and g3. }
