[Black "Austrian Defence: 3...Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5
{ This is the so-called Austrian or Symmetrical Defence. Black immediately wants to solve their opening problems by copying White and exchanging all the pawns in the centre. The main downside of Black's play is how to finish development or not to get too far behind, since their queen coming immediately into play offers White chances to gain some tempi. }
3. cxd5
{ The most logical move, inviting the black queen into the game to speed our development at its expense. }
3... Nf6
{ Black rather develops first, planning to take back the pawn on d5 with the knight. In case we take on c5, our opponent has ...Qa5+ ideas. }
4. e4
{ An important move to remember! Instead of the queen, now it's the knight's turn to go on an early journey and make a few moves in a row. That will give us a lead in development. }
4... Nxe4 { A must. Otherwise, Black is just down a pawn. } 5. dxc5
{ We continue asking questions: how does Black want to regain the missing pawn? }
5... Nxc5 6. Be3 { Developing with a tempo is rarely bad! } 6... e6 7. Nc3 exd5
{ Black is successfully executing the idea of this opening, getting rid of the central pawns, but White keeps a stable advantage thanks to the better development and piece coordination. }
8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. Nxd5 Ne6 { Already the 4th move with this knight! } 10. Nf3 Nc6
11. Bc4
{ We will castle next, and place the rooks on the c- and d-files, with very unpleasant pressure on our opponent. }
