[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Austrian / Symmetrical Defence"]
[Black "Austrian Defence: 3...Qxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5
{ This is the so-called Austrian or Symmetrical Defence. Black immediately wants to solve their opening problems by copying White and exchanging all the pawns in the centre. The main downside of Black's play is how to finish development or not to get too far behind, since their queen coming immediately into play offers White chances to gain some tempi. }
3. cxd5
{ The most logical move, inviting the black queen into the game to speed our development at its expense. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3
{ The most natural development move. We are ready to harass Black's queen. }
4... cxd4 5. Nc3
{ We are exploiting Black's main problem: the early involvement of their queen. }
5... Qd8
{ Too passive, and still gives White a chance to gain a tempo on the queen. }
6. Qxd4
{ Exchanging the piece that is covering the c7-square, a nice target for our knights. This also comes with tempo, since Black can't really allow Qxd8+. }
6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 e5
{ Instead,  7...a6  looks logical to cover the b5-square, but Black is simply losing after  8.Nd5! }
8. Ndb5 Na6
{ The only normal way for Black to protect the c7-square, but it is a sad necessity. Now they can't kick our knight with ...a6. }
9. g3 Bd7 10. Bg2
{ Our bishop is fantastic on the long diagonal. We will castle next, and then f4 or a3-b4 could be our short-term idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Austrian / Symmetrical Defence"]
[Black "Austrian Defence: 3...Qxd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5
{ This is the so-called Austrian or Symmetrical Defence. Black immediately wants to solve their opening problems by copying White and exchanging all the pawns in the centre. The main downside of Black's play is how to finish development or not to get too far behind, since their queen coming immediately into play offers White chances to gain some tempi. }
3. cxd5
{ The most logical move, inviting the black queen into the game to speed our development at its expense. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3
{ The most natural development move. We are ready to harass Black's queen. }
4... cxd4 5. Nc3
{ We are exploiting Black's main problem: the early involvement of their queen. }
5... Qa5 6. Nxd4
{ We obviously take with the knight. Our queen has nothing to do on d4 now. It would just walk into some ...Nc6 move. }
6... e5 7. Nb3
{ Somehow, there is no good square for the queen in this opening. } 7... Qc7 8.
Nb5 Bb4+
{ It is logical to finally develop a minor piece before moving the queen again. If instead  8...Qe7  , then we can even continue with  9.Bg5!  and keep Black's queen busy.   8...Qc6  fails to solve Black's problems: the queen is very awkward on c6. After  9.e3  a6  @@StartBracket@@critical@@EndBracket@@  10.Qd5!  White has many threats. You can find some deeper analysis in the gameGoganov-Bezgodov, where Black played the strange  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/2q5/1N2p3/8/1N2P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qd7?  . }
9. Bd2 Qe7 10. Nc7+
{ Gaining the bishop pair advantage and making castling pretty difficult for Black. }
10... Qxc7 11. Bxb4
{ White has a pleasant advantage with the bishop pair. It is a very nice bonus that Black has serious issues with development and the dark squares. }
