[Black "Austrian Defence: 3...Qxd5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5
{ This is the so-called Austrian or Symmetrical Defence. Black immediately wants to solve their opening problems by copying White and exchanging all the pawns in the centre. The main downside of Black's play is how to finish development or not to get too far behind, since their queen coming immediately into play offers White chances to gain some tempi. }
3. cxd5
{ The most logical move, inviting the black queen into the game to speed our development at its expense. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3
{ The most natural development move. We are ready to harass Black's queen. }
4... cxd4 5. Nc3
{ We are exploiting Black's main problem: the early involvement of their queen. }
5... Qa5 6. Nxd4
{ We obviously take with the knight. Our queen has nothing to do on d4 now. It would just walk into some ...Nc6 move. }
6... Nf6 7. g3
{ The long diagonal will be very nice for the bishop: there are no pawns on c6 or d5 to restrict it. }
7... e5
{ Black is opening the diagonal for the f8-bishop and also gaining a tempo by attacking the knight on d4. As we can see, the downside of this move is that the d5-square is going to be chronically weak in the future, as the pawn can't go back to e6. }
8. Nb3 { Very important tempo on the queen. } 8... Qc7 9. Bg2 Bb4
{ The most natural move, pinning the knight and planning to take it and ruin White's structure. In any case, when our knight is exchanged, the weakness of the d5-square will be less relevant. }
10. Bd2
{ We want to recapture with the bishop on c3 and keep our perfect structure. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ Black has two natural developing moves available at this moment, but thankfully we can react the same way to both! }
11... Nc6 12. Qc1 { Protecting the knight and preparing to play Bg5. } 12...
Bg4
{ Black is also developing pretty fast in the last couple of moves, but they are just not in time to get an equal position. }
13. h3
{ A useful forcing move, asking Black whether they want to take on e2 or completely abandon the idea of targeting that pawn. }
13... Bh5 14. g4 { Now the e2-pawn is safe. } 14... Bg6 15. Nb5
{ Still forcing matters, not waiting for the black rooks to join the game. }
15... Qe7 16. Bxb4 Qxb4 17. Qc5
{ A very nice move. After the exchange, our knight can occupy the c5-square. Black has big issues on the long diagonal, and their bishop is also out of play on g6. }
