{ This is the Baltic Defence, a pretty rare opening which has the strange idea of fighting for the centre by taking a knight on b1! }
3. cxd5 Qxd5
{ This is just very bad, and completely not in the spirit of the opening. } 4.
Nc3 { Now the queen has to go and the bishop is doing nothing on f5. } 4... Qa5
{ Giving some Scandinavian flavour to the position, but White has an e-pawn instead of the c-pawn on the board, which is not really in Black's favour. }
5. Bd2 { Breaking the pin and getting ready to push e4. } 5... c6 6. e4 Bg6 7.
f4
{ White has occupied the centre and is ready to continue with Nf3 and Bc4 or even push their pawns, like g4 and f5. }
