[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Baltic Defence"]
[Black "Baltic Defence: 3...Bxb1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5
{ This is the Baltic Defence, a pretty rare opening which has the strange idea of fighting for the centre by taking a knight on b1! }
3. cxd5 Bxb1
{ The main point of this opening. Now after ...Qxd5 the queen can stay in the centre for a while, and Black wants to continue the game with ...Nc6 and put some pressure on the centre. }
4. Rxb1 { 4.Qa4+  is by far the main line, but  4.Rxb1  seems simpler to me. }
4... Qxd5 { There is no Nc3 now, and Black is also attacking a2. } 5. a3
{ The computer would give up this pawn but I'd rather keep it. :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... Qe4
{ This strange-looking move has never been played in a classical game. Even though the position is unusual, I decided to look at it anyway. }
6. Be3
{ This is not the natural square for the bishop, but for a while it will do a good job there, protecting the d4-pawn. }
6... Nc6 7. Nf3 O-O-O 8. g3
{ The light-squared bishop will be extremely strong on the long diagonal. }
8... e5 { Looks somewhat tricky, but White can handle these complications. } 9.
Bh3+
{ Developing with a tempo but, more importantly, preparing a nice tactical trick. }
9... Kb8
{ If instead  9...f5  , then  10.Qd3  and we can force a clearly better endgame.  10...Qxd3  11.exd3  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  exd4  13.Bxf5+  and Black's queenside majority is not really going anywhere, while White's on the kingside will be pretty dangerous. }
10. Bg2 exd4 11. Nxd4
{ This was the point of first giving the check and then playing Bg2. Now the rook on d8 is not protected by the king, and Nxc6 will come with a check too. }
11... Qxg2 12. Nxc6+
{ White is winning a lot of material. Taking the knight is forced and after  12...bxc6  13.Qxd8  with Qd4 coming, Black lacks material and development. }
*

