{ If Black doesn't want to accept the pawn, but tries  7...e5  , it will be even worse for them after  8.e4  , where the key line is  8...Nxd4  9.exd5  Nxc2  10.Kd1  and if  10...Nd4  11.Nxe5  Black can't protect the f7-square, while after  11...Rxd5  12.Nxf7+-  White is just winning a lot of material since the knight on d4 doesn't have a good discovered check.Black can also try to go back with the queen,  8...Qd6  but then simply  9.d5  Nd4  10.Nxd4  exd4  11.g3  gives White a clear advantage. }
8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. g3
{ The bishop is going to g2 and suddenly Black's king is not so safe. } 9...
Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Allowing this move for free makes Black's position extremely difficult to play. }
10... e6
{ Maybe the safest move for Black is  10...Kb8  but it still doesn't solve the issues of the position.  11.O-O  e6  12.Be3  Developing with tempo.  12...Qd7  13.b4  White's play is very simple: if Black does nothing, we just push our queenside pawns and attack the king.  13...Nd5  14.Bd4  f5  Black is trying to build an outpost on d5 for the knight.  15.e4!  Breaking Black's structure.  15...fxe4  16.Qxe4±  It is just a matter of time for White to regain the e6-pawn after playing Rfe1, while the attack on the queenside continues. }
11. Be3 Qd6
{ Or  11...Qe5  12.O-O  Kb8  13.b4  Nd5  14.Rfd1  Bd6  15.Bd4  Qh5  16.e4+-  and g7 drops. Of course not  @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/4q3/8/P3B1P1/1PQ1PPBP/1R2K2R w K - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxa7??  Qa5+!-+  picking up the bishop.   @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3q4/P3B1P1/1PQ1PPBP/1R2K2R b K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd7?  gives back the pawn.  12.Bxa7+-  and the bishop can't be trapped with  12...b6??  because of the pin on the c-file:  13.Bxb6!  . }
12. O-O Kb8 13. Rbc1 Rc8 14. Rfd1 Nd5 15. Qa4 a6 16. Rd3
{ Ideas like Bf4 and Rb3 are in the air. Even though White is down a pawn, the computer already evaluates this position as +5, which says a lot about Black's prospects. }
