[White "13) Baltic Defence"]
[Black "Baltic Defence: 3...Bxb1 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5
{ This is the Baltic Defence, a pretty rare opening which has the strange idea of fighting for the centre by taking a knight on b1! }
3. cxd5 Bxb1
{ The main point of this opening. Now after ...Qxd5 the queen can stay in the centre for a while, and Black wants to continue the game with ...Nc6 and put some pressure on the centre. }
4. Rxb1 { 4.Qa4+  is by far the main line, but  4.Rxb1  seems simpler to me. }
4... Qxd5 { There is no Nc3 now, and Black is also attacking a2. } 5. a3
{ The computer would give up this pawn but I'd rather keep it. :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... Nc6
{ The main move and the best. The knight is attacking the d4-pawn and also helping with the ...e5 break. Instead, if immediately  5...e5?  we just play  6.dxe5  Qxd1+   @@StartBracket@@in case of  6...Qxe5  , Black is just allowing White to develop with tempo with  7.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@  7.Kxd1  Nc6  8.Nf3±  and Black is not taking back the pawn.Finally, in case of  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/3P4/P7/1P2PPPP/1RBQKBNR b Kkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , Black is not challenging our centre at all, so we can keep a clear advantage by simple means:  6.Nf3  e6  7.g3  c6  . Black is playing as in a Slav Defence but with the queen on d5 instead of a pawn :@@EndBracket@@  8.Bg2  Be7  9.O-O  and White is clearly better thanks to the space advantage in the centre and the pair of bishops. }
6. Nf3 O-O-O 7. Qc2
{ A pawn sacrifice, but in return Black's king will lose its main defender and is going to face a very strong attack. }
7... Nxd4
{ If Black doesn't want to accept the pawn, but tries  7...e5  , it will be even worse for them after  8.e4  , where the key line is  8...Nxd4  9.exd5  Nxc2  10.Kd1  and after  10...Nd4  11.Nxe5  Black can't protect the f7-square, while after  11...Rxd5  12.Nxf7+-  White is just winning a lot of material since the knight on d4 doesn't have a good discovered check. Black can also try to go back with the queen,  8...Qd6  but then simply  9.d5  Nd4  10.Nxd4  exd4  11.g3  gives White a clear advantage. }
8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. g3
{ The bishop is going to g2 and suddenly Black's king is not so safe. } 9... e6
10. b4
{ 10.Bg2  is also a good move, but I would like to avoid the queen dance happening after  10...Qc5  11.Qa4  Qd4  , as then we have to play  12.b4  allowing  12...Qc3+  . This is still good for us, but I find it unnecessary. }
10... Qd5 { 10...Qg4  was played inSvensson-Pallett } 11. e4
{ Similarly tothe previous trainable, we are meeting this idea with this pawn push. }
11... Qh5 12. Be2 { One more tempo on the queen. } 12... Qh3 13. Bf4
{ Now one on the king. :@@EndBracket@@ } 13... Bd6 14. e5
{ And finally on the bishop. :@@EndBracket@@ } 14... Qg2 15. Rf1 Be7 16. Rc1
{ With Qa4 coming next, Black's position is almost hopeless. } *

