[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. cxd5 c6
{ A very dubious gambit if White knows what to do. } 4. dxc6
{ The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 4... Nxc6 5. Nf3
{  } 5... Bg4 { Looks logical, but actually rather helps White. } 6. e3 e5 7.
Be2 e4
{ 7...exd4  doesn't get the pawn back:  8.Nxd4!  Bxe2  9.Qxe2!±  Black has no compensation for the pawn, but  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/8/3N2b1/4P3/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxd4  9.exd4±  is just a clear extra pawn for White.   A different try to take back the pawn is  7...Bb4+  8.Nc3  Bxf3  but this fails, too.  9.Bxf3  exd4  10.Bxc6+  or  10.exd4  even better according to the engine:  10...Nxd4  11.Bxb7  Rb8  12.Be3!±  Finishing the development and keeping the extra pawn, or  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pB3ppp/5n2/8/1b1n4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qe7+  12.Be3  Qxb7  13.Qxd4±  And White keeps the extra material because taking on g2 is just losing:  13...Qxg2??  14.O-O-O!+-  Black's position is falling apart here. }
8. Nfd2 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Nb4
{ Looks like a dangerous double threat, but actually it is nothing. } 10. Qb5+
Nd7
{ Trading queens doesn't help Black.  10...Qd7  11.Qxd7+  Kxd7  12.Kd1  Covering the c2-square and preparing to play Nc3.  12...Nd3  13.Ke2+-  Black is just lost in this endgame. }
11. Na3
{ White is winning.  11...Nd3  is just one check which basically achieves nothing. }
