[White "14) Marshall Defence"]
[Black "Marshall Defence:  3...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. cxd5 c6
{ A very dubious gambit if White knows what to do. } 4. dxc6
{ The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 4... Nxc6 5. Nf3
{ 5...Bf5?  With the idea of playing ...Nb4, but this is simply not working here.  6.Nc3  Nb4?  fails to  7.Qa4++-  and White is just winning. Therefore, Black has to waste some time:  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/5b2/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.e3  Nb4  This is still very bad.  8.Bb5+  Nd7  9.Ne5+-  White will end up with a lot of extra material. }
5... e5 6. Nxe5 { Going for a favourable endgame. } 6... Nxe5
{ The most common, but the rare  6...Bb4+  is no worse.  7.Nd2!  Qxd4  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e3  Qh4  10.Be2  Developing and preparing against the ...Ng4 idea.  10...Ng4  11.Bxg4  Qxg4  This is objectively the best recapture and Black has decent chances to fight for a draw.  12.Qxg4  Bxg4  13.O-O⩲  . Instead,  11...Bxg4  doesn't really work well:  12.Qa4!  Bd7  13.O-O±  Black has no compensation for the missing pawn. }
7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Ng4 9. Ke1 Bc5
{ 9...Nxe5?!  allows White an easy development.  10.Bd2  The bishop will be very solid on c3.  10...Be6  11.e3  Rc8  12.Bc3±  Nd2 and Bb5 are coming and Black has no counterplay at all. }
10. e3 Nxe5 11. Bd2 Bf5
{ Intending ...Nd3+ to get the pair of bishops, but there is obviously not enough compensation for a pawn. }
12. Bc3 { Inviting the black knight to d3. } 12... Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 Bxd3 14. Nd2
{ Completing development. White has a clean extra pawn. } 14... f6 15. Nb3 Be7
{ 15...Bb6?  is very bad because it allows White to gain a lot of tempi.  16.Bd4!  Bc7  17.Nc5+-  . }
16. f3 { Kf2 is coming and Black will suffer here with no winning chances. } *

