1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. cxd5 { Trainable. } 3... g6
{ Not as bad as it should be. :@@EndBracket@@ } 4. Nf3
{ I believe it is more precise than  4.Qa4+  At the very least, it gives Black fewer options. For example  4...Bd7  will not work at all with the 4.Nf3 move order.  5.Qb3  c6  6.Qxb7  cxd5!  This is Black's point, and the position is not easy at all.  7.Qxa8  Qb6  8.Bf4  e5!  Black is getting the upper hand!  9.Bxe5  Bb4+  10.Nc3  O-O∓  Next is ...Bc6, and White is worse. }
4... Bg7 { 4...Nxd5  5.e4  transposes back tomain lines. } 5. Qa4+ c6
{ Now  5...Bd7?  is just bad.  6.Qb3  c6  7.Qxb7  cxd5  8.Ne5!  This is the big difference, compared to the 4.Qa4+ line above.  8...Nc6  According to the engine, this is Black's best move, and leads to a pawn down endgame.  9.Nxc6  Qc8  10.Qxc8+  Rxc8  11.Nc3  Rxc6  12.e3±  With a clear extra pawn for White. Protecting b7 allows White to do the same with the d5-pawn and after  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pppbppbp/5np1/3P4/3P4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.e4+-  Black is losing.   Also  5...Qd7?  is very bad. Black is not in time to win back the pawn on d5.  6.Qxd7+  Nbxd7  7.Nc3  Nb6  8.e4+-  White has a winning position.   Finally, White can keep the extra material after  5...Nbd7?  as well:  6.Nc3  O-O  7.e4  Nb6  8.Qc2+-  With Be2 and O-O coming next, Black doesn't really have any compensation. }
6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3 Bf5
{ Black can also start with  7...O-O  but after  8.e3  Bf5  it is just a transposition to the main line. }
8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 a6
{ All of the 22 OTB games which have reached this position continued like this.  9...e5  looks like a try, but White has easy moves.  10.dxe5  Nd5  11.O-O  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Nxe5  13.Ba3  Re8  14.Rfd1±  Again Black has not much for the missing pawn. }
10. O-O b5 11. Qd1 Rc8 12. Nh4 e5
{ This has never been played before but is definitely the most challenging continuation. Instead,  12...Be6  was played in 3 OTB games which reached this position, but here White has an easy task.  13.Bd2  Qd6  14.a3±  Intending to play f4 and then Nf3, keeping the solid extra pawn. Black doesn't have active counterplay.   12...Bd7  is an attempt to play ...e5 on the next move. The best is to stop it completely.  13.f4±  . }
13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. a4
{ The top choice of the engine is  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Qb3  but the line just goes on with some really unclear lines:  15...Ne4  16.Rd1  Qh4  17.Nxe4  fxe4  18.Bd2  Rc6  and so on, and I don't really like it for White. }
14... exd4
{ White is getting a very strong centre after  14...b4?!  15.Bxa6!  bxc3  16.Bxc8  Qxc8  17.bxc3±  White's king is safe and we have a rook+3 pawns for 2 knights, which should be pretty good. }
15. exd4 Nxd4 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Ne4 18. Bd3
{ Black is still pretty active but even if they manage to take back the b2-pawn the kingside structure will remain weak. }
