[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Marshall Defence"]
[Black "Marshall Defence: 4...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ The Marshall Defence, a dubious opening where Black is not supporting the pawn on d5 with another pawn. Instead, the knight goes to d5, somewhat similarly to the Grünfeld Defence. As we will see, there is a major difference which will give White a clear advantage. }
3. cxd5
{ Of course, this is the best reply. We are not waiting for Black to correct their mistake and play 3...c6 or 3...e6 in the next move. }
3... Nxd5
{ No gambits. The other recapture,  3...Qxd5  , would be very bad. White can just play  4.Nc3  developing with tempo, and the queen has to look for a new square immediately. }
4. Nf3
{ Our main idea is to occupy the centre with e4. Since Black can't really prevent it, we can even afford one developing move before moving our e-pawn. Once we play e4, Black has to attack our centre, and the f3-knight is doing a great job of protecting and controlling the d4 and e5 squares. }
4... Bf5
{ Black is controlling the e4-square for the moment, but this defensive strategy will lead them to a very passive position. }
5. Nbd2
{ Now they really have to stop e4 again, as this time it is coming with a fork. }
5... Nf6 6. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop is much more logical than developing with  6.e3  since our ultimate goal is still e4 and the bishop can support this push from g2. }
6... Nc6
{ Black is looking for counterplay before White can finish development. } 7.
Bg2 { We can completely ignore the threat on our d4-pawn. } 7... e6
{ Instead,  7...Nxd4  8.Qa4!+  Nc6  9.Ne5  is just horrible for Black: c6 is falling apart. }
8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5 { And Black has huge problems on the long diagonal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Marshall Defence"]
[Black "Marshall Defence: 4...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ The Marshall Defence, a dubious opening where Black is not supporting the pawn on d5 with another pawn. Instead, the knight goes to d5, somewhat similarly to the Grünfeld Defence. As we will see, there is a major difference which will give White a clear advantage. }
3. cxd5
{ Of course, this is the best reply. We are not waiting for Black to correct their mistake and play 3...c6 or 3...e6 in the next move. }
3... Nxd5
{ No gambits. The other recapture,  3...Qxd5  , would be very bad. White can just play  4.Nc3  developing with tempo, and the queen has to look for a new square immediately. }
4. Nf3
{ Our main idea is to occupy the centre with e4. Since Black can't really prevent it, we can even afford one developing move before moving our e-pawn. Once we play e4, Black has to attack our centre, and the f3-knight is doing a great job of protecting and controlling the d4 and e5 squares. }
4... g6
{ This is Black's Grünfeld type of play, so now we will be able to see the major downside of the Marshall Defence. }
5. e4
{ Our knight is not on c3, but on b1! Normally it shouldn't sound like a big improvement for White, but in the Grünfeld Black can take that knight and immediately start their central counterplay by playing ...c5! Here it is not possible: the knight has to go away, and we can even play one more prophylactic move after that. }
5... Nb6 6. h3
{ A very nice move. Black's ideas here are to play for an ...e5 or ...c5-break, and the light-squared bishop could help a lot with that if it could pin our f3-knight. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3
{ Firm grip on the two squares that Black could potentially use to challenge our central dominance. }
8... Nc6 9. Bb5
{ Not necessarily to take on c6: even though that is a very legit idea, we just don't have to rush with it. This bishop is also fighting for the centre now: it is bothering the knight that is attacking the d4-pawn and supporting the ...e5 break. }
9... Bd7 10. O-O a6 11. Be2
{ We can just go back now: once we don't ruin Black's structure with Bxc6 bxc6, it doesn't really make much sense to give up the bishop pair. }
11... e5
{ Black has to do something in the centre. Otherwise, we are just improving our position with Rc1, Qd2 and Rfd1. Such moves are not available for Black because of their lack of central control and space. }
12. d5
{ White is clearly better. Our next move is likely going to be d6, and Black is not ready for an open fight with such bad minor pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Marshall Defence"]
[Black "Marshall Defence: 4...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ The Marshall Defence, a dubious opening where Black is not supporting the pawn on d5 with another pawn. Instead, the knight goes to d5, somewhat similarly to the Grünfeld Defence. As we will see, there is a major difference which will give White a clear advantage. }
3. cxd5
{ Of course, this is the best reply. We are not waiting for Black to correct their mistake and play 3...c6 or 3...e6 in the next move. }
3... Nxd5
{ No gambits. The other recapture,  3...Qxd5  , would be very bad. White can just play  4.Nc3  developing with tempo, and the queen has to look for a new square immediately. }
4. Nf3
{ Our main idea is to occupy the centre with e4. Since Black can't really prevent it, we can even afford one developing move before moving our e-pawn. Once we play e4, Black has to attack our centre, and the f3-knight is doing a great job of protecting and controlling the d4 and e5 squares. }
4... Bg4
{ This move is pretty often played, even though it doesn't make much sense: since White has a pawn on e2, it is not even a pin. }
5. Ne5 Bh5 6. Qb3
{ A typical motif when Black's light-squared bishop is developed early. Then Qb3 always comes with some extra power. }
6... Nb6 7. Qh3
{ This very nice and unexpected idea leads Black to a strategically lost position. }
7... Bg6 { If instead  7...g6  8.g4  Qxd4  9.f4  White wins a piece. } 8. Nxg6
fxg6 9. e3
{ Black's structure is horrible, and the light squares in their camp are not very strong either. }
*

