1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ The Marshall Defence, a dubious opening where Black is not supporting the pawn on d5 with another pawn. Instead, the knight goes to d5, somewhat similarly to the Grünfeld Defence. As we will see, there is a major difference which will give White a clear advantage. }
3. cxd5
{ Of course, this is the best reply. We are not waiting for Black to correct their mistake and play 3...c6 or 3...e6 in the next move. }
3... Nxd5
{ No gambits. The other recapture,  3...Qxd5  , would be very bad. White can just play  4.Nc3  developing with tempo, and the queen has to look for a new square immediately. }
4. Nf3
{ Our main idea is to occupy the centre with e4. Since Black can't really prevent it, we can even afford one developing move before moving our e-pawn. Once we play e4, Black has to attack our centre, and the f3-knight is doing a great job of protecting and controlling the d4 and e5 squares. }
4... e6 5. e4
{ Once again, we can compare this position with another opening: in the Semi-Tarrasch, Black can take on c3 in a similar position, then play ...c5 and have an immediate presence in the centre. Unfortunately for Black, our knight is still standing on b1. }
5... Nb6
{ The knight stands really badly here. At least inthe 4...g6 line, we could say that it makes sense to go to b6 because then the knight is not blocking the bishop's diagonal on f6. }
6. Nc3 c5 { Logical, but too late. } 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Space advantage in the centre, perfect development, and soon some serious pressure on the queenside. }
8... Be7 9. Ndb5
{ With huge pressure on Black. For example,  9...O-O  is already losing material because of  10.Qxd8  Bxd8  @@StartBracket@@Black has to stop Nc7@@EndBracket@@  11.Bc5  Re8  12.Nd6+-  . }
