[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Chigorin Defence"]
[Black "Chigorin Defence: 7...e4?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The starting position of the Chigorin Defence. This opening doesn't have a very good reputation, but it has served well to creative, dynamic players, since it offers active piece play in many variations. The most famous player who used this opening frequently on the highest level is Alexander Morozevich, while later it was also one of Richard Rapport's main weapons. }
3. cxd5
{ This is one of the main options, besides  3.Nf3  and  3.Nc3  . I chose this move because I believe it offers Black the smallest number of ways to deviate from our main line, where White will get a solid and slight edge without many complications. That is not something Chigorin players are looking for. }
3... Qxd5 4. e3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn and getting ready to kick the queen from d5 with playing Nc3. }
4... e5
{ Pretty much the only move for Black. They have to fight for the centre, and they can only do so by pinning the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Again, no real alternatives for Black. Against any queen move, we just push d5 and seize control over the centre. }
6. Bd2
{ Breaking the pin. The situation is very similar to the previous move: if the queen has to move, then simply d5 and White has a comfortable advantage. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ 7.bxc3  is also possible and interesting, but leads to completely different types of positions. Our threat now is to take on e5 and win a pawn. Black still doesn't have much of a choice, but they still can go wrong. }
7... e4
{ If you look at this move from the general perspective, Black could say something like this: 'My opponent has the pair of bishops; therefore, it is in my interest to keep the position closed.' And it is true.The problem is just that there are many other factors in the position, and Black can only keep the position closed for a very limited amount of time. }
8. Ne2
{ The knight is heading to f4 to kick the queen. Then we can push d5 and open the long diagonal for our bishop. }
8... Nf6
{ 8...g5  to physically stop Nf4 is very bad, as we can just reply with  9.h4!  and Black's structure and position are falling apart. }
9. Nf4 { The queen has to go. } 9... Qd6 10. d5
{ Our bishop is fantastic again. Black simply couldn't keep the position closed by playing ...e4. }
10... Ne5 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Bb5
{ Black is close to losing here and very likely dropping at least a pawn, since ...O-O is not possible because of Bb4, and on ...O-O-O our opponent has issues with the a7-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Chigorin Defence"]
[Black "Chigorin Defence: 7...exd4 8.Ne2 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The starting position of the Chigorin Defence. This opening doesn't have a very good reputation, but it has served well to creative, dynamic players, since it offers active piece play in many variations. The most famous player who used this opening frequently on the highest level is Alexander Morozevich, while later it was also one of Richard Rapport's main weapons. }
3. cxd5
{ This is one of the main options, besides  3.Nf3  and  3.Nc3  . I chose this move because I believe it offers Black the smallest number of ways to deviate from our main line, where White will get a solid and slight edge without many complications. That is not something Chigorin players are looking for. }
3... Qxd5 4. e3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn and getting ready to kick the queen from d5 with playing Nc3. }
4... e5
{ Pretty much the only move for Black. They have to fight for the centre, and they can only do so by pinning the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Again, no real alternatives for Black. Against any queen move, we just push d5 and seize control over the centre. }
6. Bd2
{ Breaking the pin. The situation is very similar to the previous move: if the queen has to move, then simply d5 and White has a comfortable advantage. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ 7.bxc3  is also possible and interesting, but leads to completely different types of positions. Our threat now is to take on e5 and win a pawn. Black still doesn't have much of a choice, but they still can go wrong. }
7... exd4 8. Ne2
{ The point of our previous play. Without this move, Black would simply have a better position. Please note that  8.Nf3?  wouldn't be the same, as then Black could play  8...Bg4!  with a better position. }
8... Bg4
{ This is the only moment when Black can create sharp play in this variation. It is indeed not easy here, but the position starts from +1 for us, so I'm willing to enter this mess. }
9. f3
{ We have no other option. Otherwise, we are just down a pawn in a bad position. }
9... O-O-O
{ Black is defending the queen on d5, so now our bishop on c3 is hanging.  9...Be6  10.Nxd4  O-O-O  11.Qa4  Nge7  and  9...Nf6  10.Nxd4  O-O-O  are discussed under 9...O-O-O here and in the following trainable lines. }
10. Nxd4
{ Now the bishop is hanging on g4, and it is really hanging. Nevertheless, the most common move in this position is10...Nf6. :@@EndBracket@@ }
10... Nf6
{ Instead.  10...Nxd4??  is just losing on the spot, because after  11.Qxd4  Qxd4  12.Bxd4+-  both the bishop and the g7-pawn are hanging. }
11. fxg4
{ We accept the piece since Black's sacrifice is objectively unsound. } 11...
Rhe8 12. Nc2
{ The computer gives both  12.Nf5  and  12.Qe2  as winning, but this move seems to be the easiest and most stable to me. }
12... Qe4
{ On  12...Qg5  we can continue with  13.Qf3  Nxg4  and the key is to play  14.Qg3!  with Be2 to follow and Black has no compensation for the piece whatsoever. }
13. Qe2 Nxg4
{ If instead  13...Ne5  , then  14.Kf2!  and the king goes to safety.  14...Nexg4+  15.Kg1  and Black has no attack. }
14. Qf3
{ Nice finesse! Now it's not a problem that the c2-knight is hanging, since the g4 one is hanging also, even with check! }
14... Qg6 15. Be2 Nce5 16. Qg3
{ Black has nothing to compensate our extra piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
