[Round "?"]
[White "15) Chigorin Defence"]
[Black "Chigorin Defence: 7...exd4 8.Ne2 Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The starting position of the Chigorin Defence. This opening doesn't have a very good reputation, but it has served well to creative, dynamic players, since it offers active piece play in many variations. The most famous player who used this opening frequently on the highest level is Alexander Morozevich, while later it was also one of Richard Rapport's main weapons. }
3. cxd5
{ This is one of the main options, besides  3.Nf3  and  3.Nc3  . I chose this move because I believe it offers Black the smallest number of ways to deviate from our main line, where White will get a solid and slight edge without many complications. That is not something Chigorin players are looking for. }
3... Qxd5 4. e3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn and getting ready to kick the queen from d5 with playing Nc3. }
4... e5
{ Pretty much the only move for Black. They have to fight for the centre, and they can only do so by pinning the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Again, no real alternatives for Black. Against any queen move, we just push d5 and seize control over the centre. }
6. Bd2
{ Breaking the pin. The situation is very similar to the previous move: if the queen has to move, then simply d5 and White has a comfortable advantage. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ 7.bxc3  is also possible and interesting, but leads to completely different types of positions. Our threat now is to take on e5 and win a pawn. Black still doesn't have much of a choice, but they still can go wrong. }
7... exd4 8. Ne2
{ The point of our previous play. Without this move, Black would simply have a better position. Please note that  8.Nf3?  wouldn't be the same, as then Black could play  8...Bg4!  with a better position. }
8... Bg4
{ This is the only moment when Black can create sharp play in this variation. It is indeed not easy here, but the position starts from +1 for us, so I'm willing to enter this mess. }
9. f3
{ We have no other option. Otherwise, we are just down a pawn in a bad position. }
9... O-O-O
{ Black is defending the queen on d5, so now our bishop on c3 is hanging.  9...Nf6  10.Nxd4  O-O-O  was discussed under 9...O-O-O inthe previous trainable and  9...Be6  10.Nxd4  O-O-O  11.Qa4  Nge7  will be covered here and in the following trainable. }
10. Nxd4
{ Now the bishop is hanging on g4, and it is really hanging. Nevertheless, the most common move in this position is10...Nf6. :@@EndBracket@@ }
10... Be6
{ Objectively the best move for Black, but this retreat also means that our king will be in complete safety. }
11. Qa4 { Going out from the pin and threatening to take on c6. } 11... Nge7
{ Developing and protecting the c6-knight. Instead,  11...Nxd4  could lead to a lost endgame quite quickly.  12.Bxd4  a6  and here  13.Bxa6!  is very strong, with the idea of exchanging queens and then Bxg7 will work.  13...bxa6  14.Qxa6+  Qb7  15.Qxb7+  Kxb7  16.Bxg7  Ne7  17.Bxh8  Rxh8  18.Kf2±  White has a rook and 3 pawns for the 2 minor pieces, which is already a big advantage, but we can even create passed pawns on both sides of the board. It will be even more difficult for the minor pieces to stop them. }
12. Kf2
{ The king will be perfect on f2. Even better than on g1, because here it is protecting the e3-pawn, so after taking on e6, ...Qxe6 will not come with a tempo. We keep our bishop flexible on f1 for the moment. }
12... Rhe8 13. Nxe6 { We can gain the pair of bishops. } 13... Qxe6 14. Bc4 Qg6
15. Rhd1 { Our bishops are dominating the knights in this open position. } *

