[White "15) Chigorin Defence"]
[Black "Chigorin Defence: 7...exd4 8.Ne2 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The starting position of the Chigorin Defence. This opening doesn't have a very good reputation, but it has served well to creative, dynamic players, since it offers active piece play in many variations. The most famous player who used this opening frequently on the highest level is Alexander Morozevich, while later it was also one of Richard Rapport's main weapons. }
3. cxd5
{ This is one of the main options, besides  3.Nf3  and  3.Nc3  . I chose this move because I believe it offers Black the smallest number of ways to deviate from our main line, where White will get a solid and slight edge without many complications. That is not something Chigorin players are looking for. }
3... Qxd5 4. e3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn and getting ready to kick the queen from d5 with playing Nc3. }
4... e5
{ Pretty much the only move for Black. They have to fight for the centre, and they can only do so by pinning the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Again, no real alternatives for Black. Against any queen move, we just push d5 and seize control over the centre. }
6. Bd2
{ Breaking the pin. The situation is very similar to the previous move: if the queen has to move, then simply d5 and White has a comfortable advantage. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ 7.bxc3  is also possible and interesting, but leads to completely different types of positions. Our threat now is to take on e5 and win a pawn. Black still doesn't have much of a choice, but they still can go wrong. }
7... exd4 8. Ne2
{ The point of our previous play. Without this move, Black would simply have a better position. Please note that  8.Nf3?  wouldn't be the same, as then Black could play  8...Bg4!  with a better position. }
8... Nf6
{ A much more solid, but also a much easier variation to handle, compared to  8...Bg4  . }
9. Nxd4 O-O
{ Instead,  9...Ne4?  is an attempt to equalise the position immediately by taking the c3-bishop. It fails quite badly, though, because we have  10.Nb5!  and Black can't protect c7 normally.  10...Qxd1+  11.Rxd1  O-O  12.Nxc7  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Bg4  14.Nxa8  Bxd1  15.Kxd1  Rxa8  16.Kc2+-  and we are a clear pawn up. }
10. Rc1
{ With the idea of taking on c6 and playing Bb4. This move is very rare, played only 5 times OTB. The main line  10.Nb5  was played 167 times and can lead to big complications after  10...Qg5  . We don't want that. }
10... Nxd4
{ If instead  10...Re8  , we could just play  11.Nxc6  Qxc6  12.Bd4  . Now the queen has to guard the knight on f6:  12...Qd6  13.Be2  b6  and after  14.Bc3⩲  we have a slightly better endgame. }
11. Qxd4 Be6
{ 11...Qxa2??  is not advisable. Black is losing the queen after  12.Bc4  , since on  12...Qa4  we have  13.Bxf7+  .   11...c5  doesn't look so good either, since after  12.Qh4  there is strong pressure on Black's position. Then, after the most logical reply  12...Ne4  we can enter a forced line which is very favourable for us.  13.Rd1!  Qc6  14.Bd3  Bf5  15.f3!  Nxc3  16.Bxf5  g6  17.bxc3  gxf5  18.O-O±  with a clear advantage for White thanks to our much safer king. }
12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 { We are not giving up the pair of bishops! } 13... c6
14. a3
{ The position is close to equal, according to the computer, but very unpleasant for Black in my opinion. Black doesn't have a clear way to play, while White can just improve the position and eventually push the kingside majority. The main thing is to be patient and avoid minor piece exchanges! }
*

