[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 3...dxc4?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 dxc4
{ This is not the Albin anymore. At least, the point of the opening is not to enter a worse endgame straight out from the opening. }
4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Be6 7. Ng5
{ A very strong move, suggested by the engine. We will trade the e5-pawn for the c4-pawn, but will get the bishop pair and the central control along the way. }
7... Nxe5 8. f4 Nc6 9. e4
{ With Nxe6 and Bxc4 to follow, White will have a clear advantage in the endgame.   9...Nb4?  is met by  10.f5!  and has the same problems as 9...Nd4.  9...Nd4?  10.f5!  After this move Black is losing material.  10...Nc2+  11.Kd1  Nxa1  12.fxe6  Nh6  13.Nxf7+  Nxf7  14.exf7+-  White will pick up the c4-pawn and later the a1-knight with an easily winning endgame. Finally, counterattacking with  @@StartFEN@@r2k1bnr/ppp2ppp/4b3/5PN1/2pnP3/2N5/PP4PP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...h6  doesn't help Black either:  11.fxe6  hxg5  12.Bxg5+  f6  13.O-O-O!  fxg5  14.Rxd4++-  and White is completely winning here. }
