[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 4...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 d4
{ This is the signature move of the Albin Countergambit. Black wants to have some space advantage in the centre, thanks to the d4-pawn. Then, their idea is either to develop quickly, castle long and attack our king, or play with ...Nge7-...Ng6 and take back the pawn on e5. }
4. Nf3 c5
{ If our opponent has played 3...d4, it means they know a thing or two about this opening, so I wouldn't really expect  4...c5  here, even though it was played in a surprisingly big amount of games. }
5. e3
{ Since there is no ...Bb4+ anymore, we can simply start undermining the d4-pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bd3
{ Now the e5-pawn is as weak or as strong as the one on d4, so basically we are a pawn up for nothing. Black shouldn't try to hurry and get it back. For example: }
7... Bg4 8. O-O Nxe5 9. Qe1
{ This is one possible way to win quickly in case Black wants to take back on e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 5...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 d4
{ This is the signature move of the Albin Countergambit. Black wants to have some space advantage in the centre, thanks to the d4-pawn. Then, their idea is either to develop quickly, castle long and attack our king, or play with ...Nge7-...Ng6 and take back the pawn on e5. }
4. Nf3 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and challenging the d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ Quick development is the key to the Albin Countergambit. This is the logical follow-up to 3...d4. We havejust seen that the surprisingly popular  4...c5  doesn't work well. }
5. g3
{ As we saw, e3 is not a good idea as long as ...Bb4+ is available for our opponent, so we need to find another way to continue development.Our bishop will be very nice on g2, since ...O-O-O is a usual plan for Black and in that case, the b7-square will be already under some X-ray attack we can potentially use. }
5... Bg4
{ Quick development. Black wants to play ...Qd7, ...O-O-O and attack on the kingside. Also, after this move we sometimes need to look out for some tactical tricks with the ...d3-push, as then our queen can get into a pin. }
6. Bg2 Qd7 7. O-O Bh3
{ Black wants to exchange the bishops right away, which makes sense since, as we will see, it will be pretty difficult after they castle long. }
8. e6
{ One of our must-know ideas in the Albin! In this case, we are giving back the pawn in order to gain time and use our advantage in the development. }
8... Bxe6 { The only way.  8...Qxe6??  was losing to  9.Ng5!+- } 9. Qb3 Rb8
{ Instead,  9...O-O-O  is pretty much losing. We have  10.Ne5!  followed by Nxc6 and Qa4, and Black's position is in ruins. }
10. e3
{ Opening the position, as Black's king is stuck in the centre! We already have a big advantage here: for instance  10...Na5  11.Qc2  d3  12.Qc3  Nc6  13.Rd1  and Black will soon lose the d3-pawn. }
