[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 5...Be6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 d4
{ This is the signature move of the Albin Countergambit. Black wants to have some space advantage in the centre, thanks to the d4-pawn. Then, their idea is either to develop quickly, castle long and attack our king, or play with ...Nge7-...Ng6 and take back the pawn on e5. }
4. Nf3 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and challenging the d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ Quick development is the key to the Albin Countergambit. This is the logical follow-up to 3...d4. We havejust seen that the surprisingly popular  4...c5  doesn't work well. }
5. g3
{ As we saw, e3 is not a good idea as long as ...Bb4+ is available for our opponent, so we need to find another way to continue development.Our bishop will be very nice on g2, since ...O-O-O is a usual plan for Black and in that case, the b7-square will be already under some X-ray attack we can potentially use. }
5... Be6
{ Developing with a tempo and still keeping the ...Qd7-...Bh3 idea on the table. }
6. Nbd2 Qd7 7. a3
{ The idea of this move is to wait before playing Bg2 since, if Black wants to trade that bishop, they have to play ...Bh3. Then we can take there immediately instead of losing a tempo with Bg2.Of course, a3 is not just a waiting and useful move @@StartBracket@@preventing any potential ...Bb4@@EndBracket@@ but it also prepares a b4-b5 push combined with Bb2, which can pose big problems to the d4-pawn. }
7... a5
{ Stopping b4, but at the same time making long castle almost impossible, since Black's king will not be safe on that side of the board with a pawn on a5. We can pretty much play b4 at any moment and the king will already be under attack. }
8. Bg2
{ With that pawn on a5, I'm willing to take any opposite side castling position. }
8... Bh3 9. O-O h5 10. Bxh3 { We can speed up our development with this move! }
10... Qxh3 11. Ng5 Qd7
{ Black is behind on development, so there's no time to go after the e5-pawn:  11...Qf5  12.Ndf3  Nxe5?  fails to  13.Nxe5  Qxe5  14.Qb3  with ideas like Qf3 or Bf4 after Black protects the b7-pawn. }
12. Ndf3
{ It is not clear what Black's king will do, and where is Black's compensation for the missing pawn. }
*

