{ The idea of this move is to wait before playing Bg2 since, if Black wants to trade that bishop, they have to play ...Bh3. Then we can take there immediately instead of losing a tempo with Bg2.Of course, a3 is not just a waiting and useful move @@StartBracket@@preventing any potential ...Bb4@@EndBracket@@ but it also prepares a b4-b5 push combined with Bb2, which can pose big problems to the d4-pawn. }
7... Nge7 8. b4 Ng6 9. Bb2
{ Black will take back the pawn, but their position will be very shaky, our pieces will be much more active, and Black's attack is nowhere. }
9... Ngxe5 10. Bg2 Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3
{ Once Black takes the pawn back, we have to play energetically and place our pieces on active squares. Otherwise, Black could be just completely okay. }
11... Bxc4 12. O-O
{ For the time being, Black even has an extra pawn, but they can't give it back without landing on a much worse position with equal material. }
12... O-O-O
{ 12...Be7  looks a safer choice but after  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Qxd4  Qxd4  15.Bxd4  both the g7 and the b7-pawn are hanging, so Black can't keep the material equality. }
13. Rc1 Bd5 14. b5 Na5 15. Qa4
{ The difference between the kings' safety is the main factor in this position. }
15... b6 16. Nxd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2
{ Our next goal is to take, or chase away, the a5-knight, and then put our knight on c6. }
