[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 5...Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 d4
{ This is the signature move of the Albin Countergambit. Black wants to have some space advantage in the centre, thanks to the d4-pawn. Then, their idea is either to develop quickly, castle long and attack our king, or play with ...Nge7-...Ng6 and take back the pawn on e5. }
4. Nf3 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and challenging the d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ Quick development is the key to the Albin Countergambit. This is the logical follow-up to 3...d4. We havejust seen that the surprisingly popular  4...c5  doesn't work well. }
5. g3
{ As we saw, e3 is not a good idea as long as ...Bb4+ is available for our opponent, so we need to find another way to continue development.Our bishop will be very nice on g2, since ...O-O-O is a usual plan for Black and in that case, the b7-square will be already under some X-ray attack we can potentially use. }
5... Nge7
{ The most solid continuation from Black. They don't want to enter shaky and objectively bad positions by playing for ...O-O-O and an attack. Instead, their aim is rather to take back on e5 as soon as possible. }
6. Bg2 Ng6 7. O-O
{ We are giving back the pawn and will try to use our development lead to gain some other, non-material advantage. }
7... Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ Black is still 2 moves away from castling. We need to use this time to create some threats against the d4-pawn. The c4-pawn is not currently hanging because we have the Qa4+ trick. }
9. Na3
{ We want to play Nb5 next, targeting the d4-pawn. If we can follow up with Bf4, the c7-pawn can be in danger too. Another good point is that if Black takes some time to stop Nb5, we can still go Nc2 and attack the pawn. }
9... Bxa3 { It would be great if White had to recapture with the b-pawn... }
10. Qa4+ { We can also recapture with the queen. } 10... c6 11. Qxa3 Nxc4
{ Black is temporarily up a pawn, but we'll have some very dangerous compensation. }
12. Qc5 Be6 13. b3 Nb6 14. Ba3
{ We'll take back the pawn on d4 with a clear advantage because of the pair of bishops and the shaky black king. }
*

