[White "16) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: 5...Nge7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, a pretty risky opening with a dubious reputation. The only player who is using it relatively frequently on the top is Alexander Morozevich, though mainly in rapid or blitz games. }
3. dxe5 d4
{ This is the signature move of the Albin Countergambit. Black wants to have some space advantage in the centre, thanks to the d4-pawn. Then, their idea is either to develop quickly, castle long and attack our king, or play with ...Nge7-...Ng6 and take back the pawn on e5. }
4. Nf3 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and challenging the d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ Quick development is the key to the Albin Countergambit. If our opponent has played 3...d4, it means they know a thing or two about this opening, so I wouldn't really expect  4...c5  here, even though it was played in a surprisingly big amount of games.We'd play  5.e3!  , as there is no Bb4+ anymore. We can simply start undermining the d4-pawn.  5...Nc6  6.exd4  cxd4  7.Bd3  and now the e5-pawn is as weak or as strong as the one on d4, so basically we are a pawn up for nothing.  7...Bg4  8.O-O  Nxe5  9.Qe1+-  is one possible way to win quickly in case Black wants to take back on e5. }
5. g3
{ As we saw, e3 is not a good idea as long as ...Bb4+ is available for our opponent, so we need to find another way to continue development.Our bishop will be very nice on g2, since ...O-O-O is a usual plan for Black and in that case, the b7-square will be already under some X-ray attack we can potentially use. }
5... Nge7
{ The most solid continuation from Black. They don't want to enter shaky and objectively bad positions by playing for ...O-O-O and an attack. Instead, their aim is rather to take back on e5 as soon as possible. }
6. Bg2 Ng6 7. O-O
{ We are giving back the pawn and will try to use our development lead to gain some other, non-material advantage. }
7... Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ Black is still 2 moves away from castling. We need to use this time to create some threats against the d4-pawn. The c4-pawn is not currently hanging because we have the Qa4+ trick. }
9. Na3
{ We want to play Nb5 next, targeting the d4-pawn. If we can follow up with Bf4, the c7-pawn can be in danger too. Another good point is that if Black takes some time to stop Nb5, we can still go Nc2 and attack the pawn. }
9... Be7
{ Instead,  9...Bc5?  is much worse, because it walks into  10.b4!  Of course, Black can't take because of Qa4+, so the game can continue  10...Be7  11.Bb2  O-O  12.Qxd4  Qxd4  13.Bxd4  with an extra pawn for us, since  13...Bxb4  is not possible due to  14.Nc2  and Black is losing more material. }
10. Nb5 O-O 11. Nxd4
{ 11.Bf4  is an interesting alternative to my choice, but it can lead to big complications and requires a lot of memorisation after  11...Bf6  12.Nxd4  Nxc4  13.Nb5  c5  14.Nc7  g5!  Therefore, I'd rather go with the simplest way, which gives us a small advantage. }
11... Nxc4 12. Qd3 { Using the c4-knight to speed up our development. } 12...
Ne5 13. Qe4 Bf6 14. Rd1
{ And we have a nice advantage here, with a more mobile pawn majority and also more active pieces. It is not clear, for example, where that c8-bishop should go to. You can check the gameSalzmann-Jones in the Model Games section to see how play can continue. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara: 5...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Instead of playing  4...exd5  and entering theTarrasch Defence,  Black plays the so-called Hennig-Schara Gambit. This variation had a pretty dubious reputation for a long-long time but, mainly thanks to the effort of GM Alexander Grischuk, it came somewhat back to fashion and was even played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the recent Wijk aan Zee tournament against Shankland. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the precise way to play. Instead,  5.Qxd4  would allow Black to develop with a tempo,  5...Nc6  . }
5... b5 { This is the alternative to  5...Bd7  , but it is not a good line. }
6. Nxb5 Bd7 { Black is threatening ...a6. } 7. e4 a6
{ Protecting the knight, so the queen is ready to escape the pin. Inserting  7...exd5  8.exd5  a6  doesn't improve matters. Play continues as in the main line:  9.d6  axb5  10.Qxa8  Bxd6  Now the same plan of Bd2-Rc1 cannot be played because against  10.Bd2  Black has  10...Qe7+!   However, exchanging pawns on d5 has freed the e4-square and allowed @@StartFEN@@Qn1qk1nr/3b1ppp/3b4/1p6/3p4/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR w KQk - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe4!  followed by 11.Qxd4. }
8. d6 { Nc7+ is a huge threat, so Black's only option is to take the knight. }
8... axb5 9. Qxa8 Bxd6 10. Bd2
{ White is just a clean exchange up here. There is no way that our queen can be trapped in such a position. }
10... Nf6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Nf3
{ Developing and gaining a tempo, because of the e5-threat. } 12... e5 13. Bd3
{ We will castle, our queen will return to safety and then we can start converting our advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara: 5...Nd7?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Nd7
{ A bad move. However, even this contains a little trick, so it is worth checking a little bit. }
6. Qxd4 { Same as inthe 5...Bd7 lines. } 6... exd5
{ 6...e5  7.Qd1  Bb4  Black is hoping to be able to get back the pawn with quick development, but it is not going to happen.  8.e4  Ngf6  9.Bd3  Developing and protecting the pawn.  9...Nc5  Black is increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn.  10.Nge2!  We can ignore the threat on e4 for the time being!  10...O-O  11.O-O±  The c3-knight is not pinned anymore and White comfortably keeps the extra pawn. Note that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/5n2/2nPp3/1b2P3/2NB4/PP2NPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nfxe4??  is just losing for Black:  11.Bxe4  Nxe4  12.Qa4++-  and the bishop drops. This is the point behind 10.Nge2. }
7. Nxd5 Ne7
{ The only move that could pose us some problems. Black couldn't develop with the f8-bishop because of the weakness of the g7-square and if  7...Ngf6  we would just trade and enter an endgame with an extra pawn with  8.Nxf6  . }
8. Nf3
{ We continue the development without helping Black by taking on e7. Instead,  8.Nxe7  Bxe7=∞  and Black has a pretty nice compensation here for the missing pawn.  9.Qxg7?  This move is even losing right away due to  9...Bb4+-+ }
8... Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nc6
{ Black is gaining some time with forcing moves, but we are not much behind in the development and also have no particular weaknesses, so we don't have to worry much here. }
10. Qd1
{ The most natural move, guarding the c2-square after an eventual ...Nb4. According to the computer,  10.Qf4  works well, too. }
10... Nde5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Qd5
{ The queen returns to the centre making it more difficult for Black to harmoniously finish their development. }
12... Qe7 13. e3 Be6 14. Qe4
{ With Be2 or Bc4 to follow, White keeps a healthy extra pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara: 5...Bd7 with 8...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Instead of playing  4...exd5  and entering theTarrasch Defence,  Black plays the so-called Hennig-Schara Gambit. This variation had a pretty dubious reputation for a long-long time but, mainly thanks to the effort of GM Alexander Grischuk, it came somewhat back to fashion and was even played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the recent Wijk aan Zee tournament against Shankland. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the precise way to play. Instead,  5.Qxd4  would allow Black to develop with a tempo,  5...Nc6  . }
5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5
{ This is the starting position of the Gambit. Here,  7...Nc6  used to be the main move by far, but Grischuk started to play  7...Nf6  . In our case it will not make much of a difference, since our reaction is going to be the same, so transpositions are very likely. On  7...Nc6  we answer with  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  and we have already transposed to  7...Nf6  . }
7... Nf6 8. Qd1
{ The main move and, in my opinion, the best choice. The queen could get under attack much more easily on any other square. }
8... Bc5
{ Van Foreest and then later Grischuk and Tabatabaei used this move order when they played this position. }
9. Nf3
{ The most natural. We are not committing to e3 yet, since Bg5 is a move we really want to play in some variations, especially when Black plays with ...O-O-O. }
9... O-O 10. a3
{ The point is that  10.Bg5  is not really good, because Black has  10...Qb6!  attacking f2 and b2 with a good position. After Black takes on b2, it is very important to control the b4-square, and that's why a3 is a very nice move to play. }
10... Nc6 11. Bg5 { And now this move already works very nicely! } 11... Qb6
12. e3
{ Of course we can't give the f2-pawn, and now our threat is taking on f6 and just protecting b2. }
12... Qxb2 { The only critical test to our setup. } 13. Bxf6
{ Instead,  13.Na4  looks very strong, pretty much trapping the queen, but Black has the surprisingly strong resource  13...Bb4+  14.axb4  Qxb4  with strong compensation! If we try  15.Qd2  , then  15...Ne4!  16.Qxb4  Nxb4  and Black is even better, because we can't really deal with the Nc2 threat. }
13... gxf6 14. Na4
{ The queen is still trapped, but now that ...Ne4 counterplay doesn't exist anymore. }
14... Bb4+ 15. axb4 Qxb4+ 16. Qd2
{ White is just up a piece with a clearly winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara: 5...Bd7 with 8...Bc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Instead of playing  4...exd5  and entering theTarrasch Defence,  Black plays the so-called Hennig-Schara Gambit. This variation had a pretty dubious reputation for a long-long time but, mainly thanks to the effort of GM Alexander Grischuk, it came somewhat back to fashion and was even played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the recent Wijk aan Zee tournament against Shankland. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the precise way to play. Instead,  5.Qxd4  would allow Black to develop with a tempo,  5...Nc6  . }
5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5
{ This is the starting position of the Gambit. Here,  7...Nc6  used to be the main move by far, but Grischuk started to play  7...Nf6  . In our case it will not make much of a difference, since our reaction is going to be the same, so transpositions are very likely. On  7...Nc6  we answer with  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  and we have already transposed to  7...Nf6  . }
7... Nf6 8. Qd1
{ The main move and, in my opinion, the best choice. The queen could get under attack much more easily on any other square. }
8... Bc5
{ Van Foreest and then later Grischuk and Tabatabaei used this move order when they played this position. }
9. Nf3
{ The most natural. We are not committing to e3 yet, since Bg5 is a move we really want to play in some variations, especially when Black plays with ...O-O-O. }
9... O-O 10. a3
{ The point is that  10.Bg5  is not really good, because Black has  10...Qb6!  attacking f2 and b2 with a good position. After Black takes on b2, it is very important to control the b4-square, and that's why a3 is a very nice move to play. }
10... Nc6 11. Bg5 { And now this move already works very nicely! } 11... Qb6
12. e3
{ Of course we can't give the f2-pawn, and now our threat is taking on f6 and just protecting b2. }
12... Qxb2 { The only critical test to our setup. } 13. Bxf6
{ Instead,  13.Na4  looks very strong, pretty much trapping the queen, but Black has the surprisingly strong resource  13...Bb4+  14.axb4  Qxb4  with strong compensation! If we try  15.Qd2  , then  15...Ne4!  16.Qxb4  Nxb4  and Black is even better, because we can't really deal with the Nc2 threat. }
13... Nd4 { This spectacular move is the best according to the engine. } 14.
Bxd4 { Forced. } 14... Bxd4 15. Qxd4
{ 15.exd4  or  15.Nxd4  could make things more complicated since our king would have to stay in the centre. We don't have to be greedy, but give back some material and enter a technically winning endgame. }
15... Qxa1+ 16. Nd1
{ Black is forced to trade now because of the hanging bishop on d7. } 16...
Qxd4 17. Nxd4 Rac8 18. Kd2
{ The king is controlling all possible entry squares on the c-file. } 18... Rc5
19. Nc3 Rfc8
{ 19...Ra5  20.Nb1  Rc8  21.Bd3+-  With Rc1 coming in the next move or, if Black stops it with  21...Rac5  , then it will come after  22.Nb3  . }
20. Bb5
{ This nice move completely solves all the slight issues White had to complete the development. }
20... Bxb5 21. Ncxb5 a6 22. Nd6
{ With the rook joining on the next move, Black is completely lost. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara: 5...Bd7 with 8...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Instead of playing  4...exd5  and entering theTarrasch Defence,  Black plays the so-called Hennig-Schara Gambit. This variation had a pretty dubious reputation for a long-long time but, mainly thanks to the effort of GM Alexander Grischuk, it came somewhat back to fashion and was even played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the recent Wijk aan Zee tournament against Shankland. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the precise way to play. Instead,  5.Qxd4  would allow Black to develop with a tempo,  5...Nc6  . }
5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5
{ This is the starting position of the Gambit. Here,  7...Nc6  used to be the main move by far, but Grischuk started to play  7...Nf6  . In our case it will not make much of a difference, since our reaction is going to be the same, so transpositions are very likely. On  7...Nc6  we answer with  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  and we have already transposed to  7...Nf6  . }
7... Nf6 8. Qd1
{ The main move and, in my opinion, the best choice. The queen could get under attack much more easily on any other square. }
8... Nc6
{ With this move order Black keeps the possibility of castling long, which is traditionally the main concept of this variation. }
9. Nf3 Bb4 { Black wants to put pressure on our c3-knight by using the pin. }
10. Bd2 { Breaking the pin! } 10... O-O 11. e3
{ We continue with our kingside development. } 11... Qe7 12. Be2 Rfd8 13. Qc2
{ Not even allowing ...Bf5. We will castle in the next move with a healthy pawn up. }
