1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Instead of playing  4...exd5  and entering theTarrasch Defence,  Black plays the so-called Hennig-Schara Gambit. This variation had a pretty dubious reputation for a long-long time but, mainly thanks to the effort of GM Alexander Grischuk, it came somewhat back to fashion and was even played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the recent Wijk aan Zee tournament against Shankland. }
5. Qa4+
{ This is the precise way to play. Instead,  5.Qxd4  would allow Black to develop with a tempo,  5...Nc6  . }
5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5
{ This is the starting position of the Gambit. Here,  7...Nc6  used to be the main move by far, but Grischuk started to play  7...Nf6  . In our case it will not make much of a difference, since our reaction is going to be the same, so transpositions are very likely. On  7...Nc6  we answer with  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  and we have already transposed to  7...Nf6  . }
7... Nf6 8. Qd1
{ The main move and, in my opinion, the best choice. The queen could get under attack much more easily on any other square. }
8... Nc6
{ With this move order Black keeps the possibility of castling long, which is traditionally the main concept of this variation. }
9. Nf3 Bc5 10. a3
{ A very-very promising new line, instead of the much more popular and heavily analysed main line  10.e3  . The idea is to control the b4-square and therefore make Bg5 possible.  10.Bg5?!  is not yet possible due to  10...Qb6!  11.e3  Qxb2  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Nd5  Bf5  and Black has a good position. }
10... Qe7
{ Instead,  10...O-O  11.Bg5  transposes and is discussed under the 8...Bc5 move order. }
11. Bg5 { So now our bishop is out and we are ready to continue with e3. }
11... h6
{ It's a rarer but also more challenging continuation than  11...O-O-O  . The point is that our standard idea with  12.Nd5?!  is not working here, because of  12...Bxf2+!  13.Kxf2  Qc5+  and Black is taking back the material with a better position. }
12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e3
{ It's a huge improvement for White to exchange the passive c1-bishop for that knight, compared to the main line. Therefore, Black has to prove their compensation here very quickly, but neither me nor, more importantly, Houdini, can see how. }
13... O-O-O 14. Be2
{ Again, we are not afraid of discovered attacks on our queen, but now we have to know or see a few tactical ideas. }
14... Bh3 { This looks very unpleasant! } 15. Qa4
{ But with this move we tricked Black! } 15... Bxg2 16. Qg4+
{ The bishop drops. } *

