{ Instead,  10...O-O  11.Bg5  transposes and is discussed under the 8...Bc5 move order. }
11. Bg5 { So now our bishop is out and we are ready to continue with e3. }
11... h6
{ It's a rarer but also more challenging continuation than  11...O-O-O  . The point is that our standard idea with  12.Nd5?!  is not working here, because of  12...Bxf2+!  13.Kxf2  Qc5+  and Black is taking back the material with a better position. }
12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e3
{ It's a huge improvement for White to exchange the passive c1-bishop for that knight, compared to the main line. Therefore, Black has to prove their compensation here very quickly, but neither me nor, more importantly, Houdini, can see how. }
13... O-O-O 14. Be2
{ Again, we are not afraid of discovered attacks on our queen, but now we have to know or see a few tactical ideas. }
14... g5 { The classical way to attack, with a pawn storm. } 15. O-O Bf5
{ Probably the most critical variation in the whole chapter. Here we have to remember a very nice tactical idea! }
16. Qa4 g4 17. Nh4
{ 17.Ne1  would be too passive, but this brilliant move keeps the advantage for White. }
17... Qxh4 18. Qb5 { And we will take one of the bishops! } 18... Qe7 19. Na4
Rd2
{ This is an interesting try, since it looks like Black can keep the extra material. If instead  19...Rd5  , then  20.b4  and even though Black has the very spectacular  20...Qxe3  they are much worse after  21.Nxc5  Qe7  22.Rac1  , with a very dangerous attack to follow. }
20. Nxc5 Rxe2 21. Rac1 Rc2
{ Black has to play this move. On  21...Rd2  22.Nxb7  Qxb7  23.Rxc6  Kb8  24.Qe5  is just crushing. }
22. Nxb7 { A discovered attack on the f5-bishop! } 22... Be4
{ Only move! Black needs to cover c6. For example,  22...Bg6  23.Rxc2  and Black loses even more material. }
23. Rxc2 Qxb7 24. Qe5 Bxc2 25. Qxh8+
{ And White is much better, since Black's king is weak and it will be very hard to coordinate the minor pieces without outposts. This is a pretty long line in a relatively new and unexplored territory but, since the play is pretty logical up to 17.Nh4!!, I figured it's good to go a little bit deeper and see how play can develop. }
*

