[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Nimzo-Indian"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... Nc6
{ Protecting the bishop on b4 and attacking d4 at the same time, since after ...Nxd4, Qxb4 is not an option: we lose the queen to ...Nc2+. }
5. e3
{ Maybe the most important move to remember of the whole 4...Nc6 variation!  5.Nf3  would be inaccurate because of  5...Ne4!  and Black will take on c3 with the bishop doubling our pawns, and then support their knight with ...f5.By playing e3, we keep the option to kick out the knight from e4 with f3. }
5... d5
{ Black is playing in the style I don't like, combining ...Nc6 with a d5-e6 structure. It looks much more normal to play with ...d6-...e5 if your knight is already on c6. }
6. Nf3
{ We have to be precise and continue our development before playing a3! The immediate  6.a3  would allow Black to open the position and exploit their better development.  6...Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  e5!  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Qd3  Nc5  and Black has very good counterchances. }
6... Ne4 { This move is not an issue at all anymore. } 7. Bd3
{ Previously I said that it is best to kick out this knight with f3, but since ...d5 kind of forced our knight to f3 to stop ...e5, that idea is not possible anymore. On the other hand, after playing ...d5 it is much harder for Black to support the knight with ...f5 as well, since it would create a weak square on e5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ We went out of the pin, so Black has to protect their knight somehow. } 8...
Bxc3 9. bxc3
{ Black has managed to create double pawns, but here we see another reason why I don't like ...d5 for Black. If that pawn were on d7 or d6, then we could struggle a little bit with our structural problems; thanks to the d5-pawn, however, we will just take on d5 and play c4 and have a perfect structure. }
9... b6
{ Black wants to develop with ...Ba6. Instead,  9...Na5  does nothing, since after  10.Qc2  Black can't take on c4 because the knight on e4 would fall.   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1pn1p3/3p4/2PPn3/1QPBPN2/P4PPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  9...dxc4  is just a small trap but after  10.Qxc4!  Black has just given up the centre for no reason. Instead,  10.Bxc4?  would be a mistake because  10...Na5!  more or less equalises for Black, by taking the bishop on c4. }
10. cxd5 { We are getting rid of our structural problems. } 10... exd5 11. c4
Ba6 12. Bxe4
{ Going for an opposite-coloured bishop position, where the b2-bishop will be extremely strong. }
12... dxe4 13. Nd2 Re8 14. Qc3 Na5 15. Bb2
{ We will soon open up the diagonal with d5, and then will also play f3 and launch a huge attack against Black's king. }
*

