[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... Nc6
{ Protecting the bishop on b4 and attacking d4 at the same time, since after ...Nxd4, Qxb4 is not an option: we lose the queen to ...Nc2+. }
5. e3
{ Maybe the most important move to remember of the whole 4...Nc6 variation!  5.Nf3  would be inaccurate because of  5...Ne4!  and Black will take on c3 with the bishop doubling our pawns, and then support their knight with ...f5.By playing e3, we keep the option to kick out the knight from e4 with f3. }
5... d5
{ Black is playing in the style I don't like, combining ...Nc6 with a d5-e6 structure. It looks much more normal to play with ...d6-...e5 if your knight is already on c6. }
6. Nf3
{ We have to be precise and continue our development before playing a3! The immediate  6.a3  would allow Black to open the position and exploit their better development.  6...Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  e5!  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Qd3  Nc5  and Black has very good counterchances. }
6... O-O 7. a3 { Asking the bishop to make a decision: take on c3 or go back. }
7... dxc4
{ With this intermediate move Black makes the ...Bd6 retreat possible, so the bishop can regroup to a normal square from where it will support the ...e5-push. }
8. Bxc4 Bd6
{ Both ...Na5 and ...e5 are coming, but obviously we can't give up our light-squared bishop, so the main priority is to meet ...Na5. }
9. Qc2
{ The queen is well placed on c2. We will not allow the bishop to develop to f5 after Black plays ...e5. }
9... e5 10. h3 { Preventing ...Bg4! } 10... exd4 11. exd4 Ne7
{ Black is preparing to blockade the isolated pawn on  d4  . Instead, a check, let's say  11...Re8+  , does nothing:  12.Be3  and Black's rook has just left the f7-square weaker. }
12. O-O h6 { Useful move, preventing Bg5. } 13. Ne5 c6 14. Bf4
{ We have finished our development and have some pressure to compensate for the isolated pawn. It is hard for Black to do anything else than to put a knight on d5. Then, the structure will eventually be symmetrical, but we will have more active pieces.   For example,  14...Ned5  15.Nxd5  Nxd5   @@StartBracket@@  15...cxd5  16.Bd3⩲  @@EndBracket@@  16.Bxd5  cxd5  17.Qb3⩲  , or  14...Nfd5  15.Nxd5  cxd5  16.Bd3  Be6  17.Rfe1⩲  . }
