6. Nf3
{ We have to be precise and continue our development before playing a3! The immediate  6.a3  would allow Black to open the position and exploit their better development.  6...Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  e5!  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Qd3  Nc5  and Black has very good counterchances. }
6... O-O 7. a3 { Asking the bishop to make a decision: take on c3 or go back. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3
{ Black is giving up the pair of bishops, but in return they want to have a strong knight on e4. }
8... Ne4 9. Qc2 a5
{ This ...a5 move is more serious than it was a move ago, since the main idea is stop b4-b5, therefore stabilising the knight on c6. This can be an important piece after ...f5, as the main defender of the e5-square. }
10. Bd3 f5 11. O-O Rf6
{ Black is trying to attack on the kingside, but they don't have enough pieces to scare us.   11...a4  is also possible, but will not really alter our plans:  12.Bd2  Rf6  13.Be1  @@StartBracket@@intending Ne5 and f3@@EndBracket@@  Rh6  14.Rc1  and our next move is probably h3, so after Ne5-Nxe5 dxe5-Qh4 the queen doesn't come with tempo. }
12. Bd2 Rh6 13. Be1
{ A nice idea. The point is that, after we play Ne5 and exchange knights on e5, we can play f3 and Black's knight will be in danger, since ...Nxd2 will not be available. }
13... g5 14. Ne5
{ The f3 move is a nice threat now, because Black's knight can't capture on d2. Also, the bishop is doing a great job on e1 by covering the h4-square, so it will be not easy for the black queen to join the 'attack'. }
