7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3
{ Black is giving up the pair of bishops, but in return they want to have a strong knight on e4. }
8... Ne4 9. Qc2 f5 10. b4
{ If Black allows it, we are fine with playing this move, with the idea of b5 and occupying the e5-square. }
10... a6
{ Slowing down our b5 idea. Instead,  10...Rf6  doesn't do much:  11.b5  Ne7  12.a4±  and we just gained a lot of space on the queenside and the e5-square is available for our knight.   10...Bd7  with the typical Stonewall idea, to bring the bishop around to e8-h5, is not very effective either:  11.Bd3  Be8  12.cxd5  exd5  13.b5  Ne7  14.a4±  With O-O, Ne5, f3 and Ba3 to follow, we have an easy play and a clear advantage. }
11. Be2
{ Instead,  11.b5  is not so clear:  11...Na5  and Black has counterplay against our c4 and b5-pawns. }
11... Rf6 12. O-O Rh6 13. g3
{ Basically putting an end to Black's attack. Our idea is to play Ne5 and f3, and before that we have prevented the queen from coming to h4. }
