{ Protecting the bishop on b4 and attacking d4 at the same time, since after ...Nxd4, Qxb4 is not an option: we lose the queen to ...Nc2+. }
5. e3
{ Maybe the most important move to remember of the whole 4...Nc6 variation!  5.Nf3  would be inaccurate because of  5...Ne4!  and Black will take on c3 with the bishop doubling our pawns, and then support their knight with ...f5.By playing e3, we keep the option to kick out the knight from e4 with f3. }
5... O-O
{ Instead,  5...Ne4?!  is exactly the move we prepared against! After  6.Bd3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  f5  8.Ne2±  we'll continue O-O, f3 and later e4. Without the knight on e4, Black's position will be very passive. }
6. a3 Bxc3+
{ Black can insist on keeping the bishop with  6...Ba5  , but after  7.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@with the threat of b4@@EndBracket@@ they will have to eventually take on c3. }
7. Qxc3 a5
{ A normal move for Black, but since it was not in our immediate plans to play with b4, it just gives us extra time to finish the development. }
8. Bd3 d6 9. Ne2
{ This is the setup we want, since it makes the f3-e4 plan possible. } 9... e5
10. f3
{ With O-O and e4 coming, we have a clear advantage, because we enjoy more space and the pair of bishops. Since this position has not been tested in practice yet, I decided to finish the trainable line here. Nevertheless, I would like to show you some ideas of how the game can develop.   10...exd4  doesn't make our task difficult:  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Qxd4⩲  We keep our edge with the pair of bishops.   10...Qe7  11.O-O  d5!?  This is an interesting try for Black   @@StartBracket@@  11...e4?  would be just very bad:  12.fxe4  Nxe4  13.Qc2  f5  14.Nf4±  and with that horrible knight on c6, Black's position is pretty loose.  @@EndBracket@@  12.Re1!⩲  putting more fire into the position. We have more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@Bd2 and then Rc1/Rd1@@EndBracket@@ and once the position will open up, it should favour our bishops.   10...Re8  11.e4  d5  Not an easy move to find, but the only one able to complicate the game somewhat:  12.cxd5  exd4  13.Qc4  Ne5  14.Qxd4  c6  15.d6  c5  16.Qe3  Qxd6  17.Bc2⩲  keeping the better position with the pair of bishops. }
*

