1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... Bxc3+
{ This move is obviously a mistake. There is no reason to give up the bishop pair without at least waiting for a3.   If we look at one of the main lines, @@StartFEN@@'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1'@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.Qc2  who would take here voluntarily on c3? This is what actually happens now. }
5. Qxc3 Ne4
{ The most common move for Black, immediately occupying the e4-square and then supporting the knight with ...f5 or ...d5. }
6. Qc2 f5
{ Instead,  6...d5  is much rarer, and after  7.Nf3  O-O  8.e3⩲  with Bd3 to follow, Black's compensation against our pair of bishops is not clear. }
7. Nf3
{ Natural developing move. We can't kick this knight quickly with  7.f3?  because of  7...Qh4+!  . }
7... b6
{ Black can also start with  7...O-O  . We play  8.g3  anyway and most likely transpose to the main line. }
8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O
{ Both sides have made their natural developing moves, but now Black is facing a problem: their b8-knight can't really develop well. The natural and good way would be to play ...d6-...Nd7-...Ndf6 but, as we will see, it is not possible. }
10... d6
{ Instead,  10...Nc6  is the other option for Black.  11.a3  @@StartBracket@@to prevent any ...Nb4 jumps, and with the threat of b4@@EndBracket@@  11...a5  12.Rd1±  with a clear advantage for White. The knight is misplaced on c6, b3-Bb2 and later d5 is our idea. }
11. Ng5
{ Because of the double attack on e4 and e6, White is winning material. } *

