1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... a5
{ This variation is quite similar to the one with the immediate capture on c3, since even though Black did wait for a3 and only then took on c3, the extra move was used in ...a5, not the most useful developing move, to say the least. }
5. a3 Bxc3+
{ Black has to take.  5...Be7?  is a serious mistake:  6.e4!  and White has complete control over the centre. }
6. Qxc3 b6 7. Bg5
{ I've said that we have to be careful about playing Bg5 before Black castles, because of ...h6-...g5 and then ...Ne4 ideas.Here, the a3-a5 inclusion works in our favour since, even though the black king can castle long, it will be not very safe there either because of our potential options to break with b4 and c5 on the queenside. }
7... Bb7 8. f3 c5
{ Black is counterattacking in the centre, but we can keep everything under control. }
9. e4
{ A typical motif from the Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. When we have the queen on c3 and the bishop on g5, after we play e4 we always have to watch out for the ...Nxe4 trick. }
9... Nxe4
{ Here the trick doesn't work and Black should go for something like  9...cxd4  10.Qxd4  Nc6  11.Qe3  h6  12.Bf4⩲  where we keep our advantage. Black couldn't achieve enough activity to compensate for the pair of bishops and lack of space in the centre. }
10. Bxd8 Nxc3 11. Bc7
{ This is the good square for the bishop! Instead,  11.Bxb6?  would be a big mistake:  11...Na4!  12.Bxc5  Nxc5  13.dxc5  and we are up a pawn temporarily, but after  13...a4!∓  with ...Na6-...Nxc5 to follow, Black has a clear positional advantage. }
11... Na4 12. b3 Na6
{ This intermediate move is not changing anything. Black's a4-knight will get trapped on c3 anyway. }
13. Bd6 Nc3 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Rc1 Na2 16. Rc2 { And the black knight is lost. }
