{ 15...g5??  would be a problem for the h4-bishop, but it is just losing instantly to  16.Nf5+-  Black's position is falling apart because of this double attack, and covering the f5-square with  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bpnqpp1/1p3n1p/p3p3/2P4B/P1QBP1N1/1P3PPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...g6  weakens many dark squares around the king:  16.Bc2!→  Intending to push f4 next. Black has a very risky position. Instead,  16.f4  doesn't work so well right away:  16...exf4  17.exf4  Qe3+!  That's why we have to start with 16.Bc2, to prevent this check.  18.Kh1  Ng4⇆  Black has decent counterplay. }
16. Bc2 Qe6
{ Stepping out of the pin, but now White can kick out the c5-knight. If instead  16...a4  Black would stabilize the knight but after  17.f4!→  with pressure on the f6-knight, White has a very promising position. }
