1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... Qe7
{ Maybe somewhat better than  4...a5  , but still, not the kind of development that would challenge the 4.Qb3 line. }
5. a3 { Gaining the pair of bishops! } 5... Bxc3+
{ 5...Ba5  is again just delaying the exchange for one more move. After  6.Qc2  Black has to take anyway because of the b4-threat. }
6. Qxc3 b6 7. Qg3
{ Not the only good move, but quite helpful. The queen supports the Bg5 move, and also in some cases frees the c3-square for the knight. }
7... Nc6
{ If instead  7...O-O  , then  8.Bg5  d6  9.e3⩲  , with the idea of finishing development by means of Bd3-Ne2-O-O-Nc3. Hard to see from where Black's counterplay is coming from.   @@StartFEN@@ rnb2rk1/p1ppqppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/P5Q1/1P2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qxc7?!  Nc6!  would give Black a lot of counterplay with ...Ba6 and ...Rc8 coming. }
8. Nf3 Nh5 { Black is not allowing the Bg5 pin. } 9. Qg5
{ Exchanging the queens with the pair of bishops is a very good idea in most cases. The knights can create active counterplay most effectively with the help of the queen.  9.Qxc7  was again not really good:  9...Ba6!  and ...Rc8 is even threatening to trap our queen. }
9... Qxg5 10. Bxg5 h6 11. Bd2 Nf6
{ Black is bringing their knight back into the game. } 12. b4
{ The space advantage on the queenside and the pair of bishops guarantee White a nice endgame. }
