[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... c5
{ This is by far the best move for Black, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre at the same time. Also, ...Nc6 will be a much more natural developing move once the knight is not blocking the c-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ The only try for the advantage. We keep Black busy with their bishop. } 5...
Na6
{ After this move we will most likely transpose to the 4.Qc2 variation of the Nimzo, and specifically into a variation considered to be dubious for Black. }
6. a3 { Forcing the bishop to make a decision. } 6... Qa5 7. Bd2
{ Preventing Black to triple our pawns on the c-file. } 7... Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Nxc5
9. Qd1
{ The key move of the variation, which gives White a clear advantage. It was quite easy to go wrong with  9.Qc2  , when  9...Qa4!  gives Black a good game because we have problems to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board. }
9... Qa4
{ Since this move is not coming with a tempo, we have the time to make a very useful developing move. }
10. f3 { With the idea of playing e4 and having a clear advantage. } 10... Qxc4
{ The only question, even though it will lead to a very bad position for Black. }
11. Rc1 { Threatening different discovered attacks on the queen. } 11... Qh4+
{ Instead,  11...Qb5  is also possible but doesn't help Black:  12.b4  Na6   @@StartBracket@@  12...Na4  is losing the knight after  13.Bxf6!  gxf6  14.e3+-  @@EndBracket@@  13.e4  We will improve our position winning tempi on each move.  13...Qb6  14.Bd4  Qd8  15.b5  Nb8  16.Bxf6  gxf6  17.Qd6!+-  and Black can hardly move, while we also have the Qc5 threat to win a piece. }
12. g3 Qg5
{ Black can also play  12...Qh5  , but after  13.b4  Na6  14.e4+-  it is hard to offer good advice: their pieces can't really move. }
13. b4 { Forcing the knight to the extremely passive a6-square. } 13... Na6 14.
f4 Qf5 15. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Instead,  15...Qxf6?  is just losing a piece to  16.b5+- } 16. Qd4
{ Black's minor pieces can't move, and we also have the g4 idea to decoy Black's queen and win a piece by means of b5. }
