[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... c5
{ This is by far the best move for Black, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre at the same time. Also, ...Nc6 will be a much more natural developing move once the knight is not blocking the c-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ The only try for the advantage. We keep Black busy with their bishop. } 5...
Na6
{ After this move we will most likely transpose to the 4.Qc2 variation of the Nimzo, and specifically into a variation considered to be dubious for Black. }
6. a3 { Forcing the bishop to make a decision. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 Nxc5
{ This is a direct transposition to the 4.Qc2 Nimzo. } 8. b4
{ Black has a few tricky options in this variation, but if we know what we are doing, then the line is very dubious/bad. }
8... Na4
{ This move is not really tricky. We will just have an extra pawn and not a particularly difficult task to finish our development. }
9. Qc2 b5
{ This pawn sacrifice is the point behind ...Na4. Black wants to open the c-file, and also have an extra pawn in the centre. Instead,  9...Nb6  is just moving the knight to a very passive square and allows White to develop as they want.  10.e4  d6  11.Nf3  O-O  12.e5!  dxe5  13.Nxe5  With Bb2 and Be2 to follow. White has a clear advantage thanks to the pair of bishops and the queenside majority. }
10. cxb5 Nb6 11. Nf3
{ We just have to finish the development with the most solid moves available, and then ask Black what they have for the pawn. }
11... Bb7 12. e3 Rc8 13. Qd1 O-O 14. Be2 Ne4
{ The first threat from Black, but we can easily prevent ...Nc3. } 15. Bb2
{ We will castle on the next move, and Black clearly doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn. }
