[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Nimzo-Indian"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4...c5 5.dxc5 Na6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... c5
{ This is by far the best move for Black, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre at the same time. Also, ...Nc6 will be a much more natural developing move once the knight is not blocking the c-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ The only try for the advantage. We keep Black busy with their bishop. } 5...
Na6
{ After this move we will most likely transpose to the 4.Qc2 variation of the Nimzo, and specifically into a variation considered to be dubious for Black. }
6. a3 { Forcing the bishop to make a decision. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 Nxc5
{ This is a direct transposition to the 4.Qc2 Nimzo. } 8. b4
{ Black has a few tricky options in this variation, but if we know what we are doing, then the line is very dubious/bad. }
8... Nce4 9. Qb2
{ 9.Qd4  is also possible and actually the most common move, but the queen is a little bit more exposed there to the trickery of Black's knights and central pawns. Therefore, I would rather play Qb2, also the preferred choice of the engine. }
9... d5
{ The most logical. Black is ahead in development, so they have to go for active play.  9...Nd6  is pretty weird and not very good.  10.c5  Nc4  11.Qc3  d5  12.e4!  This strong move opens the position and gives White a big advantage:  12...Nxe4  13.Qxg7  Qf6  14.Qxf6  Nxf6  15.Bg5±  . }
10. c5
{ We don't want to open the game when we are behind in the development. Additionally we are taking the d6-square away from the knight, so f3 is a big threat now. }
10... d4
{ Now. in case of f3, the knight could simply go to c3. Instead,  10...h6?  was played in a surprisingly big number of OTB games. That move is just very sad:  11.f3  Ng5  12.h4  Ngh7  13.Bf4+-  and we can conclude that Black didn't manage to get active play. }
11. e3
{ Undermining Black's centre and opening the diagonal for the f1-bishop. }
11... Ng4 { With the big threat of ...Nxf2. } 12. Nh3
{ Protecting the f2-square. } 12... dxe3
{ Instead,  12...e5?  is just bad. It was played in a high-level correspondence game, although quite a long time ago.  13.Bb5+!  Kf8   @@StartBracket@@if  13...Bd7  , then  14.Bxd7+  Qxd7  15.f3  is possible because the queen can't deliver a check on h4 anymore@@EndBracket@@  14.O-O+-  with a winning position for White: f3 is a threat and also Black's king is not ideally placed. }
13. Qxg7 { Important intermediate move! } 13... Ke7
{ Instead,  13...exf2+  leads to a horrible endgame for Black:  14.Nxf2  Qf6  15.Qxf6  Ngxf6  16.Bb2+-  the bishop pair will completely dominate the game. }
14. Ng5
{ A very strong move which reduces the mess in the position.  14.Qxg4?  would be a mistake because Black has the very strong  14...Qd4!  and they have very dangerous play.  14.f3  is winning according to the engine, but the line is very dodgy, which can't be said about Ng5. }
14... exf2+ 15. Ke2 Qd5
{ The queen frees the d8-square for the king and creats some counterthreats. }
16. Qxf7+ Kd8
{ Now Black has the ...Nc3# threat, so it's important to play accurately here. }
17. Qf3
{ The key move of the variation: everything is hanging for Black, and they can't avoid the exchange of queens. }
17... Nxg5 18. Qxd5+ exd5 19. Bxg5+ Kc7 20. h3
{ We are collecting the f2-pawn, entering a technically winning endgame. }
20... Re8+ 21. Kf3 Ne5+ 22. Kxf2
{ White is up a pawn and has the pair of bishops, so our chances to win this position are excellent. }
