{ We have to start with this move, since  7.Bg5  leads to a very good position for Black.  7...h6!  8.Bh4  g5!  9.Bg3  Ne4  and ...f5 is coming. We also have problems on c3, so better not to allow this and start with  7.a3  . }
7... Bxc5 8. Bg5 Nd4 { A motif already known from the Qc2 Nimzo. } 9. Nxd4 Bxd4
10. e3 Qa5
{ This is the point behind 8...Nd4. Black is forcing further exchanges and we will have problems with the development of the f1-bishop. }
11. exd4 Qxg5 12. Nb5
{ A very interesting concept, and I believe the only try to have an advantage.  12.g3  d5!  is just perfectly fine for Black. }
12... d5
{ Not allowing the knight to blockade Black's whole position from d6. } 13. c5
Ne4
{ With some counterthreat on d2. :@@EndBracket@@ Black obviously had many other possibilities as well, but I believe this is the closest way to equalise.  13...b6  14.Qg3!  Endgames are fantastic for us with the queenside majority.  14...Qh6  15.Nd6!⩲  and it is hard to play around that knight on d6.   13...Bd7  doesn't help much either:  14.Qe3!  and if Black doesn't want to exchange queens, they have to use less than ideal squares.  14...Qxe3  15.fxe3⩲  .   13...e5?!  looks like the most logical move, to open the centre against our king on e1, but it walks straight into  14.Qe3!  and we are forcing the exchange of the queens. }
14. Qe3 Qxe3+ 15. fxe3 b6
{ Black is undermining the very important c5-pawn.  15...a6?  would be a big mistake, because after  16.Nc3±  Black lost the option to play ...b6. }
16. cxb6 axb6 17. Bd3 Ba6 18. Bxe4 Bxb5 19. Bf3
{ I still slightly prefer White, since it is easier for us to create a passed pawn, but the position is very close to equal. }
