{ Important move, keeping Black under pressure! Instead,  13.Bh4?!  would allow  13...Nh5!  which would ease the pressure on Black's position. We could have problems on some dark squares like f4, for example. }
13... Nh5 { Interesting, but it doesn't work that well here. } 14. Bc1
{ The point is that if Black plays  14...Na5  we can simply react with  15.b3  because the a3-pawn will be protected. Instead, both  15.O-O  and  15.e5  are good, according to the machine. The lines are quite complicated and fun. You can investigate them but my move is just good enough for a slight advantage as well. }
14... Qc7 15. O-O Nf6
{ 15...Nf4?  leaves Black with a very passive position.  16.Nb5  Nxe2+  17.Qxe2  Qd8  Obviously, Black would prefer to go to b8, but the d7-pawn is hanging.  18.Bf4±  Black's position is very tough. }
16. h3
{ A useful prophylactic move preparing Be3. Now ...Ng4 will not be an issue. }
16... Rfd8
{ Instead,  16...Na5?  would be a serious mistake.  17.e5!  White is getting an overwhelming advantage here.  17...Ne8  18.Nb5+-  and Black can't defend a7 and d7 at the same time.   Black can cover the b5-square with  16...a6  but this weakens the b6-pawn, which is immediately targeted with  17.Be3  Na5?  Now the problem for Black is not the weakness of the b5-square, but a quick attack against the b6-pawn.  18.e5!  Ne8  19.Na4+-  and Black is falling apart on b6, but would be down a lot of material at the end of this forcing line:  @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/1bqpbpp1/pp2pn1p/n3P3/2P5/P1N1BN1P/1PQ1BPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Bxf3  19.exf6  Bxe2  20.fxe7  Bxf1  21.exf8=Q+  Rxf8  22.Rxf1+-  and White is winning. }
17. Rfe1 Na5
{ Trading the knights with  17...Ne5  is an option for Black, but the queen will not be so comfortable on e5: when it moves, White can push e5.  18.Nxe5  Qxe5  19.Bf1⩲  . }
18. e5
{ Gaining some space in the centre and forcing Black's knight to a more passive square. }
18... Ne8 19. Nb5 Qb8 20. b3
{ White keeps the better chances here with more space and more active pieces. }
