[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence, a popular opening at all levels. Maybe in this opening, as in the Ruy Lopez against 1.e4, it is easier to say who hasn't played it than who has.Black's idea with 3...Bb4 is very simple: stopping the e4 move and also developing a piece in the process. }
4. Qb3
{ This is the 9th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most popular move in the position, and called the Spielmann Variation. It fits well with our repertoire: it doesn't allow doubled pawns on c3, it avoids the sharpest lines which require a lot of memorisation, and also asks Black a question about their bishop on b4. There is only one good way to answer it. }
4... c5
{ This is by far the best move for Black, protecting the bishop and attacking our centre at the same time. Also, ...Nc6 will be a much more natural developing move once the knight is not blocking the c-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ The only try for the advantage. We keep Black busy with their bishop. } 5...
Nc6
{ The most natural developing move. Black is still keeping their options: they can play with ...Bxc5 later as well, but they don't give up on the ...Ne4 idea either.   The immediate  5...Bxc5  is possible, but it will transpose after  6.Nf3  with either  Nc6  7.Bg5  or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2b5/2P5/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  7.Bg5  when eventually Black will play ...Nc6. }
6. Nf3
{ Pretty much the only normal developing move we have. If  6.Bg5  , then  6...h6!  and Black is already taking over the initiative. Both  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Rc1  Bxc5  and  7.Bh4  g5!  8.Bg3  Ne4  are preferable for Black. }
6... Ne4
{ Since we don't want a horrible structure, we have to give Black the bishop pair after this move. }
7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2
{ The next moves can happen in all possible orders. Anyway, Black will play ...Bxc5, ...O-O and ...b6-...Bb7 to reach the main line, but there are some inferior possibilities as well. }
8... Bxc5 9. g3
{ Our bishop will be much more active on the long diagonal than it would be after e3-Be2. It is also worth mentioning that, with the bishop on c5, the ...f5-...f4 push is a very legit idea for Black and much more dangerous when we have a pawn on e3, and not on g3. }
9... b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O Na5
{ 11...Nd4  is clearly the worst option, because White will be able to gain a tempo on the knight later in the game.  12.Qd1  Bxg2  13.Kxg2  O-O  14.Nde4!  now b4 is a threat to win the d4-knight.  14...Nf5  15.Nxc5  bxc5  16.Qd3⩲  with both the c5 and d7-pawn as possible targets and, because of the misplaced knight on f5, White keeps a solid advantage. }
12. Qc2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 O-O 14. Rfd1
{ The position is obviously equal according to the computer, but since it is extremely hard to achieve ...d5 or ...b5 for Black, it will be never very drawish: the position is not symmetrical, and Black still has one problematic pawn on d7. }
14... Be7 15. Qd3 Qc7 16. b3 Rfd8 17. Nf3 Rac8 18. Rac1
{ Both sides are playing normal, useful moves. At the end of the day though, the situation is the same: a long fight is ahead, where Black is under some slight pressure and they have to play a waiting game, not everyone's cup of tea. }
