[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 2...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 a6
{ Black's aim with this move order is to play only one exact variation of the Benkő Gambit, after  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  b5  . }
3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ This is the problem with Black's move order. Black can't recapture this pawn in the most natural way, with Na6-Nxc5, because the pawn is already on a6. Besides this, the b6-square is also an issue for Black. }
4... e6 5. e4 { With the threat of e5! } 5... Nc6 6. f4
{ White is almost exclusively playing  6.Be3  in this position, and it is better for White, but it can get a little bit complicated after  6...Qa5  7.Qa4  Ng4! }
6... Bxc5 7. e5 Ng8 8. Ne4
{ White has a clear advantage. This again looks like a bad Sicilian for Black, when they allowed e5. }
8... Be7 9. Nf3
{ White is dominating the centre, and will play Bd3 and O-O in the next moves. }
