[Black "Benko Gambit: 2...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 a6
{ Black's aim with this move order is to play only one exact variation of the Benkő Gambit, after  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  b5  . }
3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ This is the problem with Black's move order. Black can't recapture this pawn in the most natural way, with Na6-Nxc5, because the pawn is already on a6. Besides this, the b6-square is also an issue for Black. }
4... e6 5. e4 { With the threat of e5! } 5... Qc7
{ Preventing e5 for the time being.  5...Bxc5?  6.e5  Ng8  7.Qg4  g6  8.Nf3±  is clearly better for White. Black is very weak on the dark squares.   5...Qa5?!  is also dubious. Black wants to use the pin to prepare against e5, but we will have a countertrick:  6.e5!  Ne4  7.Qa4!  forcing the exchange of queens and getting the pair of bishops along the way.  7...Qxa4  8.Nxa4  Bxc5   @@StartBracket@@  8...Nxc5  is losing to  9.Nb6!+-  @@EndBracket@@  9.Nxc5  Nxc5  10.Be3  with a clear advantage for White. }
6. f4 { Renewing the threat of e5. } 6... Bxc5 7. e5 Ng8
{ Black has to go backwards. The position looks like a Sicilian which went really bad for Black. }
8. a3 { Preparing to meet ...d6 with b4! } 8... d6 9. b4 Bxg1 10. Rxg1 dxe5 11.
Ne4
{ Black has won a pawn, but they are extremely weak on the dark squares and their king will remain in the centre. }
11... exf4 12. Bb2 Nf6 13. Nd6+
{ Not even taking back a pawn on f6, just keeping the initiative going. } 13...
Ke7 14. c5
{ Black's king is very weak, while White's minor pieces are fantastic. } *

