[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit 4.Qc2 Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Qa5+ { This check doesn't really disrupt our development. } 5. Nd2
{ In many cases the knight is even happy to go to d2 since the main goal is to reach the c4-square. }
5... e6
{ Very ambitious. Black is attacking our centre from all angles but it is not working very well because of concrete reasons. }
6. e4 exd5
{ After  6...bxc4  7.Bxc4  Developing and protecting d5.  7...Bb7  8.Ne2  exd5  9.exd5±  neither the knight nor the bishop can take on d5 because Qe4+ wins a piece. Therefore, we can conclude that Black's opening strategy has been a complete failure. They are behind in development and both the queen and the bishop are quite misplaced. White's knights have excellent squares on e4 and f5.  9...Bxd5??  10.Bxd5  Nxd5  11.Qe4++-  . }
7. e5
{ An important move! If we just recaptured on d5 Black could get a lot of extra time to finish development. }
7... Ng4
{ After  7...Ne4  8.cxd5!  the knight is hanging again and will move for the third time to take our knight, which moved only once and is pinned right now!  8...Nxd2  9.Bxd2±  Black lost the battle for the centre and at the same time he also forgot about piece development. :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. cxd5 { The g4-knight is in trouble! } 8... d6
{ Black has to include new pieces in the game.  8...Nxe5?  9.Qe4  d6  10.f4+-  is just a piece up for White. }
9. Nf3 { We do the same! } 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Be2
{ Black managed to save the knight but now our opponent has a new problem, being seriously behind in development. }
11... Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Ne4
{ Black can't keep the position together: the bishop and two pawns are hanging at the same time. }
13... Qd8 14. Bxb5
{ White regains the pawn with a clear positional advantage. } *

