{ Opening up our bishop with tempo!  10...Qb6?!  11.Be3!  Again with tempo!  11...d6  12.dxe6!  With all the pieces in play, it is very logical to force things and be aggressive!  12...fxe6  13.e5!±  Ruining Black's pawn structure, or  12...Bxe6  13.Bxe6  fxe6  14.Ng5!  Still forcing matters, not just waiting for the b8-knight and the rook to join the game.  14...Re8  15.e5!  Crushing Black's structure and position.  15...Nd5  16.exd6  Nxe3  17.fxe3  Qxd6  18.Rad1+-  All Black's light squares are weak, the c5-pawn is hanging, our queen can attack from e4 or c4... and Black hasn't even finished their development yet.   10...Qc7  11.d6!  Qxd6  12.e5+-  and after  @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p1qp1pbp/3Ppnp1/2p5/2B1P3/1N3N2/PPQ2PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  12.Be3  Bb7  13.Bd3±  White is going to take on c5 with an extra pawn and Black has no compensation for it. }
10... Qa4 11. e5 { Playing for structural advantage! } 11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 exd5
13. Qxc5 { We have a much better pawn structure and a nice d4 square. } *

