1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Qa5+ { This check doesn't really disrupt our development. } 5. Nd2
{ In many cases the knight is even happy to go to d2 since the main goal is to reach the c4-square. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 d6 7. Bxc4 g6 8. b3
{ One of the reasons why 4...Qa5+ is not causing us a big headache is that, although the bishop usually goes to the long diagonal via d2, playing b3+Bb2 is also perfectly fine. }
8... Bg7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Ne2
{ Since Black 'forced' the b1-knight to d2, now the other one is heading to c3. }
10... e6 11. O-O exd5 12. Bxd5
{ After  12.exd5  our bishop wouldn't be so strong. It makes sense to exchange it and free the c4-square for the knight. }
12... Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. exd5
{ Black's king is weak and the c8-bishop is not something to be proud of either. A very dangerous idea is Qb2+ with Nc4 or Ne4 to follow. }
