[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit 4.Qc2 Qa5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Qa5+ { This check doesn't really disrupt our development. } 5. Nd2
{ In many cases the knight is even happy to go to d2 since the main goal is to reach the c4-square. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 e6 7. Bxc4 exd5 8. exd5 d6 9. Ne2
{ An important move and concept! The position looks as if we achieved the e5-break and exchanged on d6. It doesn't matter that it was Black who did the job for us with ...e6. :@@EndBracket@@Our knight mainly goes to f3 to support that break. Once it is done, it would stay much better on e2 to reach the f5-square. Therefore, if the ...exd5 exd5 exchange actually happens with the knight still on g1, often e2 is the preferred square! }
9... Be7
{ With this move Black is in time to finish the development, but the e7-bishop is going to be horribly passive.  9...g6?  Black is lagging so much in development that there's no time for that bishop to reach its prefered square.  10.Nc3  Bg7  Black is one move away from getting a decent position.  11.Bb5+!  Bd7  12.Nc4  Everything is coming with tempo.  12...Qc7  13.Qe2+  And this move makes castling impossible.  13...Kf8  14.O-O+-  The king's weakness, combined with the weak pawn on d6, is fatal for Black. }
10. O-O O-O 11. b3
{ Our bishop on b2 will have no opposition on the diagonal. } 11... Nbd7 12.
Bb2
{ With Rae1 and Ng3 to follow. We will put our focus on the kingside and the centre. }
