1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Qa5+ { This check doesn't really disrupt our development. } 5. Nd2
{ In many cases the knight is even happy to go to d2 since the main goal is to reach the c4-square. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 Ba6 7. Bxc4 Bxc4 8. Qxc4
{ This can be a slight benefit of an early ...Qa5+. Now the direct knight recapture is not possible, but in the future we can remove our queen any time, and Nc4 will come with tempo. }
8... d6 9. Nf3 Nbd7
{ 9...Qa6  Threatening to exchange queens and take our e4-paw!  10.b3!  We want to take back with the pawn and use the b-file!  10...Qxc4  11.bxc4  g6  12.Rb1±  Black is worse both on the centre and the queenside. }
10. O-O g6 11. b3 Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qd3
{ Vacating the c4-square for the knight!  13.Qc2  is also a good move, but it would offer Black the possibility to play  13...Nb6  . }
13... Qc7
{ 13...Nb6??  Black is preventing Nc4, but trapping his own queen!  14.Bc3!  Qa3  The only square for the queen.  15.Qb5!  The queen is trapped!  15...c4  16.Bb4  Qb2  17.Rfb1  Qc2  18.Ne1+-  . Black can go for  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/p3ppbp/1n1p1np1/1QpP4/4P3/qPB2N2/P2N1PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nfxd5  16.Bxg7  Nc7  17.Qc6  Kxg7  18.Qxc7+-  and save their queen, but at the price of a minor piece. }
14. Rfe1
{ With a pleasant edge for White. We have a couple of useful preparatory moves before going for the e5-break. }
