[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... d6 5. e4 g6
{ If  5...bxc4  instead, then we reach a position which is analysed viathe 4...bxc4 5.e4 d6 move order. }
6. cxb5
{ So, you could ask, why are we accepting the pawn here? Well, there is a crucial difference compared to the original 4.cxb5: our b5-pawn is not hanging! It means that, once Black is playing ...a6, we are not forced to deal with it, but can just calmly continue the development. }
6... a6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. a4
{ Building a nice outpost on b5, essentially blocking Black's counterplay on the queenside, and still delaying our bishop's development, since in some cases we can go immediately to b5. }
9... axb5 10. Bxb5 { Here we go! } 10... Na6 11. O-O Nb4 12. Qe2 Bg4
{ Anytime Bg4 happens, h3 looks like an automatic reaction but, as long as there is no Ne5 threat in the position, we can do more useful things with our position. }
13. Rb1
{ Prophylaxis! In case of  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Nc2  , Black's knight reaches c2 with a tempo and then can jump further to d4. }
13... Nd7
{ 13...Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Nc2  illustrates the point of 13.Rb1: this knight jump is not coming with a tempo and we can easily control the d4-square before the knight can go there.  15.Ne2±  Now ...Nd4 is prevented and we are getting ready to kick out the c2-knight by means of Bd2 and Rfc1. }
14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ White enjoys a nice advantage here. One thing to note is that I would leave the e2-square vacant for a while. This way, in case Nc2 comes, we can always meet it with Ne2.Also, I believe that this is an instructive position to examine a little bit. White is clearly better, having an extra pawn, having the pair of bishops and having no weaknesses, whereas Black has no visible counterplay.On the other hand, there is no clear-cut plan for White to execute. But... Chess is played by 2 players! We have many useful moves to make, will improve our position to the maximum, and then we'll see new possibilities. Very often our opponent is helping us as well, by creating new weaknesses. For example, if you don't see a clear plan for White here... how miserable this position is for Black, who doesn't have any play and is down a pawn? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... d6 5. e4 g6
{ If  5...bxc4  instead, then we reach a position which is analysed viathe 4...bxc4 5.e4 d6 move order. }
6. cxb5
{ So, you could ask, why are we accepting the pawn here? Well, there is a crucial difference compared to the original 4.cxb5: our b5-pawn is not hanging! It means that, once Black is playing ...a6, we are not forced to deal with it, but can just calmly continue the development. }
6... a6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. a4
{ Building a nice outpost on b5, essentially blocking Black's counterplay on the queenside, and still delaying our bishop's development, since in some cases we can go immediately to b5. }
9... axb5 10. Bxb5 { Here we go! } 10... Ba6
{ Black is trying to play in the spirit of the Benkő. } 11. O-O Bxb5 12. Nxb5
Na6 13. Bd2 { Developing and stopping the opponent's threat at the same time! }
13... Qb6
{ Black can try to get rid of our minor pieces on b5 and to put pressure on the b-file by means of  13...Nc7  , and it looks like finally succeeds :@@StartBracket@@ However, after  14.Nxc7  Qxc7  15.b4!  instead of putting pressure on the queenside, their momentarily unprotected queen forces on Black the unpleasant task to stop our connected passers.  Nd7  16.Ra2+-  and White's position is just winning here: extra pawn and Black is without counterchances. Even pushing the pawn till c3 makes no difference. It can't go any further. }
14. Bc3
{ Controlling the long diagonal and the b4 square, and vacating the d2-square for the knight! }
14... Rfc8 { Trying to push c4 and then Nc5. } 15. Nd2 c4
{ 15...Nb4  Here, taking this knight would be an instructive mistake. That's all the rook on c8, the knight on f6 and the bishop on g7 are waiting! After cxb4-Nd7-Nc5, Black would suddenly get counterplay.  16.Qb3!+-  Black's knight on b4 is not particularly dangerous. We will just improve further our position without giving Black any counterchances. We will place our knight on c4, with h3 we are going to open the back rack and at the same time stop any Ng4 actions, and then bring both rooks to the centre and prepare the decisive e5-break. }
16. Na3
{ Simple chess, just taking another pawn and winning. Black simply has no way to protect this pawn 'physically'. The only try could be  16...Nb4  but then White can just play  17.Qd1  and, even though now the a6-square is available for the queen to protect the pawn, then the knight on b4 is hanging. }
