1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... g6
{ More often than not, this move will transpose to either4...d6  or4...bxc4 lines. }
5. e4 Bg7 6. cxb5 O-O 7. Nc3 e6
{ Black is trying to open the e-file before White can finish their kingside development. If instead of this move Black played  7...d6  , then after  8.Nf3  a6  9.a4!  we reach a position which isanalysed under the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  g6  6.cxb5  a6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.a4  move order. }
8. dxe6
{ Thanks to this capture the e-file will be not opened in the near future. }
8... fxe6
{ The correct recapture. Black's only hope is playing d5 and creating some tension in the centre. Instead,  8...dxe6?  is just very bad. Black can't hope for any counterplay in the centre after this move, since no more pawn breaks are available anymore. We just play  9.Nf3  with our next moves being Be2, O-O, h3, Be3, and our opponent is just down a pawn without any counterplay. }
9. Nf3 d5 10. Be2
{ With this calm developing move, we ignore Black's play in the centre. We will only start active and direct operations once our king is in safety! }
10... Bb7 11. O-O
{ Still not reacting in the centre, since  11...dxe4  12.Ng5  looks awful for Black: not only do they have many pawn islands in that position, but all of them are going to be weak at the same time! }
11... d4 12. e5
{ 12.Ng5  is also strong according to the machine, but I find my suggestion easier to play. }
12... dxc3 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. Bg5 { Developing with a tempo is rarely bad! }
14... Qf5 15. Qxf5 Rxf5 16. bxc3
{ Black's position is full of weak pawns and squares, so even after taking on c3, we will retain a very nice and stable advantage. Our position has zero problems and we can activate our pieces just by targeting Black's weaknesses! }
