[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... g6
{ More often than not, this move will transpose to either4...d6  or4...bxc4 lines. }
5. e4 Bg7 6. cxb5 O-O 7. Nc3 e6
{ Black is trying to open the e-file before White can finish their kingside development. If instead of this move Black played  7...d6  , then after  8.Nf3  a6  9.a4!  we reach a position which isanalysed under the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  g6  6.cxb5  a6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.a4  move order. }
8. dxe6
{ Thanks to this capture the e-file will be not opened in the near future. }
8... fxe6
{ The correct recapture. Black's only hope is playing d5 and creating some tension in the centre. Instead,  8...dxe6?  is just very bad. Black can't hope for any counterplay in the centre after this move, since no more pawn breaks are available anymore. We just play  9.Nf3  with our next moves being Be2, O-O, h3, Be3, and our opponent is just down a pawn without any counterplay. }
9. Nf3 d5 10. Be2
{ With this calm developing move, we ignore Black's play in the centre. We will only start active and direct operations once our king is in safety! }
10... a6 { Fighting for the initiative! } 11. Bg5
{ An indirect way to fight against the centre! Sometimes we can't or don't need to control the centre by physical means. For example, in this situation we want to put pressure on the d5-pawn and ease the pressure on our e4-pawn. Here, the dark-squared bishop is doing exactly that, although this piece has absolutely nothing to do on the light squares. :@@EndBracket@@ However, it can pin and, in this sense, neutralise Black's most important piece: the f6-knight which is attacking the e4-pawn and protecting the d5-square. }
11... d4
{ The most natural move. Black needs to gain some time to stop our threats. Obviously,  11...axb5??  would be a great move if not for  12.e5+-  winning a piece for us. :@@EndBracket@@ }
12. Na4
{ If Black plays slowly here, then White can just occupy the weak squares or take the weak pawns. :@@EndBracket@@ }
12... c4
{ Looks like a desperate try, but if Black is doing nothing, we will just take that pawn on c5. :@@EndBracket@@ For example, after  12...axb5  13.Nxc5+-  the crucial squares are under control, we have an extra pawn, and it is even Black who has to address a few threats, like e5 winning a piece. }
13. b6
{ Preventing Black's queenside pieces from being active and taking part in the fight. Even if this pawn is going to be lost in the future, it allows White to win a lot of time, keeping the queenside closed for the time being. }
13... d3 14. Qxc4 dxe2 15. e5
{ The tactical justification of 13.b6! Of course, our intention was not just to play a piece down. :@@EndBracket@@ }
15... Nbd7 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxe2
{ White is up two pawns. Most probably, Black will take one back, but the remaining extra pawn still should provide a clear advantage. }
