[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... e6
{ Black is trying to undermine our centre in a Blumenfeld Gambit style. } 5. e4
{ We don't take anywhere! We just stick with our main goal, to keep the initiative and control the centre. }
5... exd5
{ If instead  5...bxc4  , then after  6.Nc3  we reacha position which is annotated via the 4...bxc4 5.e4 e6 6.Nc3 move order. }
6. cxd5 Qe7
{ Black continues playing in a counterattacking style!   Another try is  6...Qb6  but we get perfectly on time!  7.a4!  stops  7...a6  , Black's most desirable move here, positionally speaking. That would keep their pawns flexible and maintain control over the c4-square. Unfortunately for them, that move is simply not protecting the b5-pawn, because of the undefended rook on a8, so after  8.axb5  White is just winning a pawn for free.Therefore, Black is forced to go for  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/p2p1ppp/1q3n2/1ppP4/P3P3/8/1PQ2PPP/RNB1KBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  7...b4  8.Bc4±  Now, if we take a closer look, the structure really resembles the one we can get from the Benoni Defence. There, one of the most important, if not the most important square to control, is c4. White is already occupying that square and Black lacks the main Benoni-type counterplay with a6-b5 to kick our minor piece from there. This already gives us a great advantage, and if we combine that with quick development and aim for e5, our advantage can be even larger in the near future. }
7. Bxb5
{ Now we take this pawn, since we didn't really have a comfortable way of protecting the e4-pawn and the d5-pawn was hanging too because of the pin. This is not a big 'sacrifice' from our side since, besides taking a pawn, we also developed our bishop. }
7... Qxe4+ 8. Qxe4+ Nxe4 9. Nc3
{ Usually we only give 'mathematical value' to pieces, since the concept 'time' is very hard to translate into numbers in chess. However, if a piece makes three moves and takes a piece which only made one, we have definitely won something. Of course, it would be silly to say that we won a pawn now, but just for the sake of debate, I would say that with this exchange White won half a pawn. ;@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Nf3 Ba6
{ Black is desperately trying to catch up with development, but our nice space advantage in the centre, provided by the d5-pawn, makes it very difficult for them. The b8-knight doesn't have access to its most natural square c6 and, if Black plays d6, that will further restrict the e7-bishop and will create an additional target for our pieces. }
12. Rb1 Bxb5 13. Rxb5
{ A much better endgame for us. We will stabilise the centre with c4, and not having castled yet really comes in handy, as our king can walk to d3 and protect the c4-pawn. The bishop will most probably go to f4 with pressure on the diagonal or, if Black plays d6, on the pawn. }
