{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... e6
{ Black is trying to undermine our centre in a Blumenfeld Gambit style. } 5. e4
{ We don't take anywhere! We just stick with our main goal, to keep the initiative and control the centre. }
5... exd5
{ If instead  5...bxc4  , then after  6.Nc3  we reacha position which is annotated via the 4...bxc4 5.e4 e6 6.Nc3 move order. }
6. cxd5 c4 7. Nf3
{ 7.a4?!  looks like the most natural move, to immediately break Black's structure, but unfortunately it doesn't quite work here:  7...Na6!  8.axb5  Nb4  9.Qxc4  Bb7  and Black has a very strong initiative in this position. }
