1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... b4
{ Our opponent is not giving us the opportunity to take on b5 anymore, but with this move Black's potential counterplay on the queenside, the main idea of the Benkő Gambit, is gone. On the positive side for Black, we have to note that the very nice c3-square is not available for our knight anymore. }
5. e4 d6 { Black has to stop e5 ideas. } 6. a3
{ This move would achieve absolutely nothing if Black could react with a5 and take back on b4 with the flank pawn. However, this is not possible thanks to the undefended rook on a8, so Black will have to make some concession. }
6... a5 7. axb4 cxb4
{ Black can only take like this, so we have an extra pawn in the centre. } 8.
c5
{ I like this idea which offers a lot of positional compensation and a long-term initiative for White, plus taking the c5-square away from the black knights. }
8... dxc5 9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. Nf3 e6
{ This is the best way for Black to stop the e5-e6 threat, but it creates a weak pawn on e6 and many weak squares as well. }
11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Nbd2 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. Qc4
{ White has huge play for the small price of a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 b4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... b4
{ Our opponent is not giving us the opportunity to take on b5 anymore, but with this move Black's potential counterplay on the queenside, the main idea of the Benkő Gambit, is gone. On the positive side for Black, we have to note that the very nice c3-square is not available for our knight anymore. }
5. e4 d6 { Black has to stop e5 ideas. } 6. a3
{ This move would achieve absolutely nothing if Black could react with a5 and take back on b4 with the flank pawn. However, this is not possible thanks to the undefended rook on a8, so Black will have to make some concession. }
6... a5 7. axb4 cxb4
{ Black can only take like this, so we have an extra pawn in the centre. } 8.
c5
{ I like this idea which offers a lot of positional compensation and a long-term initiative for White, plus taking the c5-square away from the black knights. }
8... dxc5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bc4
{ The point of including the check on b5! Now the bishop on d7 is in the way of the b8-knight and also it can't go to a6 to immediately challenge the strong bishop on c4. Let's speak a little bit more generally about the position and about the structure at this point.White's main compensation for the missing pawn is our central dominance. We have one extra pawn there on d5, and we already have very serious threats such as pushing e5!Another very important factor of White's concept is to have firm control over the c4-square. Since Black has already played b4, our minor pieces can use this square with great effect. For now the bishop is excellent there, but in case it is exchanged, the b1-knight wouldn't be unhappy on that square either.The third and deepest point of White's pawn sacrifice is its long-term nature. While in some gambits if the side with extra material can finish the development or can exchange some pieces they will be immediately much better, here it's not the case at all. That means that we don't have to win the game in the next ten moves: we can just continue playing 'normal' moves, since our advantage in the centre is going to be there. Also, if we look at the side where Black has 3 pawns against our single 'b'-pawn, I believe it is not so easy to see how those pawns are going to promote in the near future. }
10... e6
{ Immediately challenging the centre and stopping e5 is very logical.   Another plan is  10...g6  11.Nf3  Bg7  12.O-O  Just normal development. As I said, we don't have anything to 'prove' right away, if we understand the nature of our compensation.  12...O-O  13.Bf4  Bg4  14.Nbd2  Nbd7  Black is also developing and will even have the opportunity to exchange a pair of minor pieces?!  15.h3  Fine with me.  15...Bxf3  16.Nxf3=∞  After a series of very natural developing moves, White retains a strong compensation for the missing pawn, mainly thanks to our very strong central control and to the pair of bishops. You can see that in the last few moves we just improved our position, doing nothing special, but our central dominance remained the same. Also, Black didn't manage to promote any of their queenside pawns. :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Bf4 Qb6
{ After exchanging on d5, this move helps to develop the f8-bishop to d6. } 12.
Nd2 exd5 13. exd5 Bd6 14. Bg5
{ Exchanging on d6 and making Black's development easier is not in our interest! }
14... Bc7 15. Ne4
{ Black has some concrete problems to solve here. We are threatening to damage their structure on f6, and combining it with a correctly timed d6-push we can pose huge problems for Black. }
