1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... b4
{ Our opponent is not giving us the opportunity to take on b5 anymore, but with this move Black's potential counterplay on the queenside, the main idea of the Benkő Gambit, is gone. On the positive side for Black, we have to note that the very nice c3-square is not available for our knight anymore. }
5. e4 d6 { Black has to stop e5 ideas. } 6. a3
{ This move would achieve absolutely nothing if Black could react with a5 and take back on b4 with the flank pawn. However, this is not possible thanks to the undefended rook on a8, so Black will have to make some concession. }
6... Na6
{ With this move, Black is sort of preventing axb4. On the other hand, the knight is not doing much on a6 besides waiting for the exchange on b4. }
7. Nf3 g6 8. e5
{ This breakthrough may seem a little bit surprising, since most of our pieces are still on the back rank. However, concrete reasons like the knight not guarding the c6 square anymore and the weakness of the a4-e8 diagonal make it possible and strong! }
8... Nd7 { Is basically losing right away. } 9. e6 fxe6 10. dxe6
{ That pawn on e6 is a little bit strong. :@@EndBracket@@ } 10... Nb6
{ Black has to cover the check. } 11. Ng5
{ The knight had to go to b6 to stop Qa4+, but it is now really missing from f6, and Black's position is just collapsing. }
11... Qc7 12. Bd3 { Bxg6+ is a huge threat now. } 12... Rg8 13. a4
{ We have a difficult position with White. It's not easy to decide whether to win on the queenside, the centre or on the kingside. :@@EndBracket@@ }
