[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 b4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... b4
{ Our opponent is not giving us the opportunity to take on b5 anymore, but with this move Black's potential counterplay on the queenside, the main idea of the Benkő Gambit, is gone. On the positive side for Black, we have to note that the very nice c3-square is not available for our knight anymore. }
5. e4 d6 { Black has to stop e5 ideas. } 6. a3
{ This move would achieve absolutely nothing if Black could react with a5 and take back on b4 with the flank pawn. However, this is not possible thanks to the undefended rook on a8, so Black will have to make some concession. }
6... bxa3 7. Rxa3
{ White has the better structure after this exchange, and the c3-square is again available for the knight. }
7... g6
{ The most obvious move, which is also setting up a nice tactical trick! } 8.
Nf3 { And... we are of course falling for it! } 8... Bg7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be2 Na6
{ The only way to use the advantage of the bxa3, Rxa3 exchange is to bring the knight to b4. }
11. O-O Nb4 12. Qd1 Bg4
{ It looks logical to exchange this bishop, since White's next move would have been h3 and the bishop would have been just an 'extra' bad piece for Black.   After  12...e6  13.dxe6  Bxe6  14.Bf4±  the position is quite equal... if we don't count Black's two weak pawns. :@@EndBracket@@ We'll first line up our pieces against the d6-pawn, and it is also good to insert the prophylactic move h3, so in case of Nh5 our bishop can safely retreat to h2 and continue putting pressure on d6. }
13. Bf4 { The most natural square for our bishop, helping a future e5 break. }
13... a6 14. h3
{ Model gameRios-Avila Pavas features  14.Qd2  Ne8  15.h3  but is not a big difference. }
14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd7 16. Be2
{ Black is very solid here, mainly thanks to the knight on b4. On the other hand, the position is also extremely passive for our opponent, basically without any counterplay.Therefore, we can take the time to improve our position further and our main ideas are still to play e5 at some moment, or exchange the knight on b4 and attack the a6 pawn. }
