[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 Na6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Na6 5. a3 { Restricting the knight! } 5... Qa5+
{ Black insists on playing Nb4! } 6. Bd2
{ Normally both Nd2 and Bd2 are available and good for us to block this check. The main point of the bishop's move is to develop with a tempo and ask the black queen some questions. On the other hand, if later Black takes on c4  @@StartBracket@@which happens in the majority of the cases@@EndBracket@@ then it makes a lot of sense to block with the knight since that is the piece we want on c4.   However, in this particular case there is a significant difference between the two options. After  6.Nd2?!  bxc4  7.e4  , Black can play the very strong  7...Nb4!  using the fact that our rook is not protected in the corner and exchanging this very bad piece which was completely restricted by the a3-pawn.  8.Qb1  Nd3+  9.Bxd3  cxd3⩱  and with the bishop coming to a6, even Black's position is preferable here. }
6... Nb4
{ It's very confusing what Black is doing, but it involves a trick, so we have to know what we are doing here. }
7. Qc1 bxc4 8. Nc3
{ Developing and avoiding all tricky options!  8.Qxc4  would be a mistake here, since after  8...Qa4!  9.b3  Qa6  Black is forcing the exchange of queens, planning to continue with Nc7 and Rb8 to attack our pawns on d5 and b3. }
8... Na6
{ This sad retreat is necessary, since our a1-rook is already protected so axb4 was a threat, and  8...Nbxd5  9.Nxd5  with a discovered attack on the queen was also not a very tempting alternative for Black. }
9. e4 d6 10. Bxc4
{ Black wasted a lot of time with the knight+queen trickery, and now has to be very careful not to be completely lost after a quick b4 or e5 break. }
*

