1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Na6 5. a3 { Restricting the knight! } 5... bxc4
{ If instead Black tries the other pawn move  5...b4  , then after  6.e4  d6  we transpose intoa position which is analysed via the 4...b4 5.e4 d6 6.a3 Na6 move order. }
6. e4
{ Of course! We don't want to recapture on c4 with the queen but rather with a minor piece! }
6... g6 7. Bxc4 Nc7
{ It makes sense to bring this knight to c7 as soon as possible: for example,  7...d6  is met by the quite unpleasant  8.Qa4+  . }
8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O d6 10. Nc3 O-O
{ Both sides have completed the development, and the knight on c7 is rather a problem for Black than an advantage compared to the more normal square d7. Aiming for the d4 square via b5 looks impossible, because White can stop it anytime by playing a4, so the only active option for Black is e6. }
11. Bg5
{ Making e6 much more difficult and much less appealing, because of the unpleasant pin on the black queen. }
11... h6 12. Bf4
{ If instead, we played  12.Bh4  here, or in any similar situation after Black played h6, we have to make sure that  12...Nh5!  is not really working for Black. If we have to give up this bishop after g5 on g3, then Black will have a lot of compensation for the weakened squares on the kingside thanks to the very strong dark-squared bishop. }
12... Rb8
{ In case of  12...Nh5  13.Be3  we can easily save our important bishop, and the knight is just misplaced on h5. }
13. h3
{ Typical prophylactic move. In case of Nh5, our bishop doesn't even have to leave the h2-b8 diagonal anymore. }
13... e6 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. b3
{ This way we get rid of the somewhat weak b2-pawn and keep a firm control over the d5-square, which means we keep Black's backward pawn on d6 and can attack it with Rad1 in the next move. }
