1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... Na6 5. a3 { Restricting the knight! } 5... bxc4
{ If instead Black tries the other pawn move  5...b4  , then after  6.e4  d6  we transpose intoa position which is analysed via the 4...b4 5.e4 d6 6.a3 Na6 move order. }
6. e4
{ Of course! We don't want to recapture on c4 with the queen but rather with a minor piece! }
6... e6 7. Bxc4 exd5
{ 7...Nc7  8.Nc3  exd5  9.exd5  d6  is another way to reach our main line after  7...exd5  . }
8. exd5 Nc7
{ 8...g6??  Black doesn't have the time for the usual development of this bishop.  9.Qe2+  Qe7  because our queen is also pinned, we are not winning the piece immediately.  10.Be3!  Now it is hanging again!  10...Nb8  11.d6  Qe5  12.Nf3+-  Black is losing their queen or getting checkmated after our bishop moves away from e3 with a discovered check. }
9. Nc3 d6 10. b4
{ An interesting aggressive idea. The main point is either to create a passed pawn on d5 or, in case of the exchange on b4, White can take control over the very important d4 square. }
10... Be7 11. bxc5 dxc5
{ Now we have a passed pawn which is protected by tactical ideas. Or we can even give it up for gaining a strong initiative. }
12. Nf3 Ncxd5
{ The critical test in this variation. Instead,  12...O-O  13.O-O  Bd6  14.Bg5±  If Black is not trying to take or attack our pawn, then it just leads to a passive position where the d5-pawn is very strong and the c7-knight is very bad. Rfe1 or Ne4 is our next move to increase the pressure in Black's position. }
13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. O-O O-O 15. Bb2
{ White has a very strong initiative here. This is a very open position where our bishops are already working perfectly, the knight is ready to jump to e5 or sometimes to g5, and the rooks are coming to the centre immediately creating huge threats. Black has to play very well to avoid being much worse.   For instance,  15...Be6  16.Rad1  Qd6  17.Be5  Qc6  18.Bd3!  Forcing some weakening move on the kingside and setting up the Nd4 idea!  18...h6  19.Nd4  Qd7  20.Nxe6  fxe6   @@StartBracket@@  20...Qxe6  is losing to  21.Rfe1+-  where Black will lose material@@EndBracket@@  21.g3  and White has great compensation here. The light squares in Black's camp are horribly weak, Qe2-e4 already looks like a very dangerous idea against the king, but even if we just play positionally with Rfe1 and put pressure on e6, it will be very hard for Black to protect both e6 and c5-pawns.     If Black tries @@StartFEN@@ 'r2q1rk1/p3bppp/4b3/2pn4/2B5/P4N2/1BQ2PPP/3R1RK1 b - - 5 16' @@EndFEN@@  16...Qd7?  this is already losing material:  17.Rxd5!  Bxd5  18.Rd1  Using the pin once more!  18...Be4  19.Rxd7  Bxc2  20.Rxe7±  and even though materially speaking the position is almost okay for Black, the activity of the pieces is also a factor. :@@EndBracket@@ }
