1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... e6 6. Nc3 Bb7
{ Black is just misplacing the bishop here. We can protect d5 with the move we wanted to play anyway. }
7. Bxc4 exd5 8. exd5 d6
{ The bishop is not only completely blocked on b7, but it is also missing from the defence of the f5-square. }
9. Nge2
{ This allows the knight to go towards g3 and, more important, then to e4 or f5. Putting the knight to f3 here wouldn't make much sense here, since there is no e5 break to support. }
9... g6 { Very risky approach. } 10. Bg5 Bg7 11. Bb5+ Kf8
{ Of course, this move already shows that Black is in big trouble. If instead  11...Nbd7?  , then after  12.Ne4+-  Black will lose material because of the pins. }
12. O-O
{ With the king stuck in the centre, it's hard to see any realistic ambition for Black, other than not losing under 20 moves. }
