{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ The sharpest and most tactical line of the whole 4.Qc2 variation. } 7... d4
{ Counterattacking the knight is not a good idea here. } 8. exf6 d5
{ It has to be said that Black built an impressive centre! Other options are just losing right away. If  8...d3  , then  9.Qa4  Qxf6  10.Qxc4+-  Black's centre has collapsed. White is easily winning with the extra piece.   If  8...dxc3??  , then  9.Qe4+  is pretty unpleasant:  9...Be7  and here many lines are winning. Let me just suggest one which offers our opponent zero counterchances:  10.fxg7  Rg8  11.bxc3  Rxg7  12.Qxa8  Nc6  13.g3  with Ne2, Bg2 and O-O to follow. We can simply win the game with the extra rook. }
9. Bxc4 { Okay... not for long. :@@EndBracket@@ } 9... dxc4
{ If instead  9...dxc3  , then  10.Bb5!+  Bd7  11.Qe2+-  is winning a lot of material. }
10. Qe4+ Be6 11. Qxa8 dxc3 12. Ne2
{ White is just winning with an extra exchange. } *

