[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 bxc4 5.e4 e6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ The sharpest and most tactical line of the whole 4.Qc2 variation. } 7... Bb7
{ The best move, giving up a piece but keeping interesting counterchances with a flexible centre. }
8. exf6 Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7
{ Alternatively, Black can play  9...Na6  10.Bg5  Nb4  11.Qd2  Qf5  12.Qe3+  Qe6  13.O-O-O±  . The position is full of tension, but it's Black who has to make concessions first in order to finish development. For instance, after  13...f6  14.Bf4  d4  15.Qxe6+  dxe6  16.Nb5  e5  17.Bg3  White has managed to create targets for the minor pieces, which is the key for this position, and therefore keeps a clear advantage. }
10. Bg5 Qe6+ 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O d4 13. Rae1
{ Bringing a new piece into the game! } 13... f6
{ If instead  13...dxc3  then after  14.Bd1!  White will keep the extra piece, but Black's strong centre is disappearing. }
14. Qa4
{ Giving up the piece for a much calmer position, where White will have a clear edge. }
14... Bc6 15. Bxc4 Bxa4 16. Bxe6+ dxe6 17. Nxa4 fxg5 18. Rxe6
{ White is currently down a pawn, but we'll take it back very soon and our knights are going to have fantastic squares on c4 and d3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 bxc4 5.e4 e6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ The sharpest and most tactical line of the whole 4.Qc2 variation. } 7... Bb7
{ The best move, giving up a piece but keeping interesting counterchances with a flexible centre. }
8. exf6 Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7
{ Alternatively, Black can play  9...Na6  10.Bg5  Nb4  11.Qd2  Qf5  12.Qe3+  Qe6  13.O-O-O±  . The position is full of tension, but it's Black who has to make concessions first in order to finish development. For instance, after  13...f6  14.Bf4  d4  15.Qxe6+  dxe6  16.Nb5  e5  17.Bg3  White has managed to create targets for the minor pieces, which is the key for this position, and therefore keeps a clear advantage. }
10. Bg5 Qe6+ 11. Be2 d4 12. O-O d3
{ Leads to some concrete, forced lines, but if White knows what they are doing, this move is not enough to equalise. }
13. Bxd3 cxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O 15. Rfe1 Qd6
{ The point of Black's idea. In this way they can avoid losing a piece... again. }
16. Qb5 Bxf3 17. Bxe7 Qg6
{ It's extremely tough to reach this position as Black without being super-well prepared. }
18. Qf1 Re8
{ Instead,  18...Rc8  is also not good enough to reach equality:  19.Re3  Nc6  20.Bxc5  d6  21.Bxa7  Bxg2  22.Qxg2  Rxa7  23.Rd1±  and because of the connected pawns on the queenside, every endgame is basically winning for White. }
19. Bxc5 Nc6 20. Kh1
{ Slight advantage for us, as the d-pawn is weak and it is not clear what the light-squared bishop will do, since it can't stay on the long diagonal. }
*

