{ I find this the smartest move order. We are not afraid of Bg4 and Ng4 is not yet a move for Black, so we can delay h3. Depending on Black's reaction, we can also choose between d2 and c3 squares for our knight. }
9... Nfd7
{ 9...Bg4  illustrates the advantage of having started with Re1 and not Nc3, since we can easily replace the knight on f3.  10.Nbd2!  Nbd7  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Nxf3±  In general, we don't mind exchanging Black's light-squared bishop for one of our knights, rather the opposite is true actually! Therefore, I would delay playing h3 as long as possible and allow Black to go for Bg4. After the exchange, the typical Benkő breaks with e6 and f5 are much riskier because of the weakness of the light squares. Also, if Black is trying some a5 on the queenside, we can easily stop it with a4 and our bishop can have a very nice outpost on b5.   9...Ng4?!  doesn't make so much sense here, since Black can't recapture on e5 with the other knight.  10.h3  Ne5  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  The bishop is doing nothing here.  12.Bh6  Re8  13.Nd2±  Black has just wasted a lot of time and White's initiative is going to be very strong in the centre. }
10. Nc3
{ We don't have to wait anymore with this move since Black is not playing for Ne5. }
10... a5
{ 10...Ba6  11.Nb5!±  Again, Black can hardly play without taking on b5, but that will seriously limit their counterchances.   10...Nb6  11.Bf1  Ba6  12.Nb5±  when we'll support our knight on b5 and complete our development, with a comfortable position, or  11...Na6  12.Bf4⩲  with Rad1 and e5 to follow. }
11. Bf4 Ba6 12. Be2 { The exchange is fine, but in our terms! } 12... Bxe2 13.
Qxe2 a4 { Black wants to play a3 and make the g7-bishop really powerful. } 14.
e5 { Closing the diagonal! } 14... dxe5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Qxe5
{ White managed to break through and Black's position is in ruins. Our opponent is left with three pawn weaknesses and zero developed pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit: 4.Qc2 bxc4 5.e4 d6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ This is the starting position of the Benkő Gambit. Alternatively,  3...a6  is a tricky move. Black wants to tempt us into some  4.Nc3  b5  Benkő.   In case of  4.Qc2  they can even go for the Benoni with ...e6 and then we don't want our queen on c2.   The best approach is to play  4.a4  and stop ...b5 completely, and the game will most likely transpose into some kind of Benoni, depending on Black's next move. }
4. Qc2
{ We don't give Black the possibility to have the initiative after 10 moves or so. Therefore, we decline the gambit, and at the same time we get ready to push e4 and occupy the centre! }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ Of course, we want to take back on c4 with the bishop and not with the queen. }
5... d6
{ 5...g6  doesn't really have independent value. Either  6.Bxc4  d6  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  will transpose or after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppp1p/5np1/2pP4/2B1P3/8/PPQ2PPP/RNB1K1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.O-O  Black will eventually play d6, so we'll just transpose again. }
6. Bxc4 g6
{ Instead,  6...Nbd7  doesn't change much, since Black will have to play g6 eventually. After  7.Nf3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.Re1  we transpose back to 6...g6. }
7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ I find this the smartest move order. We are not afraid of Bg4 and Ng4 is not yet a move for Black, so we can delay h3. Depending on Black's reaction, we can also choose between d2 and c3 squares for our knight. }
9... Nbd7 10. h3
{ Once the knight lands on d7, we have to watch out for the Ng4-Ne5 idea, which is typical for this opening and can potentially give our opponent some decent counterplay! For example,  10.Nc3  Ng4!  would give Black chances to create some play! }
10... Nb6
{ In case of  10...Rb8  a useful waiting move is  11.a4!  still keeping the options for the b1-knight. Black can try  11...Nh5  announcing their next move is Ne5. Then we can play one more useful move and after the knight trade on e5 it's enough to play Nd2:  12.Ra3  @@StartBracket@@Getting out of the diagonal and controlling the third rank!@@EndBracket@@  12...Ne5  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Nd2±  The knight belongs to c4 or f3 and definitely not to c3 in this case.   Another option for Black is  10...Ne8  11.Nc3  Nc7  12.Bf4  Nb6  13.Bf1  Ba6  and with these knight manoeuvres, Black prevented White from meeting Ba6 with Nb5.  14.Bxa6  Nxa6  15.Rad1  It's not a big deal: in the meantime, White optimally placed all their pieces  15...Nc7  16.b3±  With an e5 break to follow. }
11. Bf1 { Of course we don't give up our bishop for a knight! } 11... a5
{ Black would like to push a4 and gain some space, plus having an occasional a3 threat on the queenside. }
12. a4 { We are not allowing it, but creating a strong outpost on b5! } 12...
e6 { Black is looking for counterplay in the centre now. } 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14.
Nc3 d5 15. e5 Nfd7 16. Nb5
{ Black's position doesn't look so bad at first sight, but their main problem is that White can play around the strong central pawns. Another problem is that, if either d4 or c4 happens, it just creates nice squares for White's minor pieces. }
*

