7. h3
{ A routine move in this variation. We don't want to give up this bishop after ...Nh5, so we prepare a retreat square on h2. Also, ...Bg4 is a move Black wants to play, so h3 is a multi-purpose move. }
7... Qa5
{ With the idea of using the pin, and playing ...Ne4 in the next move.   7...Qb6  is met by  8.Qb3  Qxb3  If instead, Black moves their c8-bishop, we push c5! and because of the unprotected b7-pawn Black will be forced to take on b3, giving us a better endgame.  9.axb3  Na6  Black's usual positional idea after taking on b3: to use the weakness of the b4-square and install a knight there. However, it will not work in this particular situation. First, we secure the space advantage on the queenside.  10.c5!  Nb4  11.Ra4  a5  12.Bc7±  And the supporter of the b4-knight is falling in the next move. }
8. Bd3
{ Instead,  8.Nd2  is also possible, but if we can continue the development, then why not?! }
8... dxc4
{ Black is taking on c4 because we just developed our bishop, so we are kind of losing a half tempo. }
9. Bxc4 Nd5
{ Attacking the bishop on f4 and the knight on c3. Instead,  9...b5  is not doing much. After  10.Bb3  it is still not clear how will Black compensate for giving up the centre and creating some weaknesses. }
10. Bxd5
{ We have to give up the bishop pair, but we don't mind it so much, since we will get the Exchange Slav structure with the passive bishop on g7. }
10... cxd5 11. Qb3 e6 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nb5
{ With Rfc1 and Nd6 coming, we already exert some serious pressure on Black's queenside. }
