5. e3 Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O
{ If we consider this position from the Slav viewpoint, which we should do, since now it is rather a Slav Defence than a Grünfeld, then Black already made an inaccuracy and entered an inferior line of the Schlechter variation: @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  or  @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e3  g6  5.Nf3  Bg7  and this is the starting position of the Schlechter.As you can see, there is a huge difference if we compare that position with what we have on the board: our bishop is on f4 instead of the passive c1! And that is the reason why after  @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Black has many good choices here  @@StartBracket@@  4...a6  ,  4...e6  ,  4...dxc4  @@EndBracket@@  but  4...g6  is considered to be dubious because White can play  5.Bf4!  That is exactly what we have now in our line. }
7. h3
{ A routine move in this variation. We don't want to give up this bishop after ...Nh5, so we prepare a retreat square on h2. Also, ...Bg4 is a move Black wants to play, so h3 is a multi-purpose move. }
7... Bf5
{ Looks normal, but White can quickly gain the initiative against this move. }
8. Qb3 Qb6 9. g4
{ And now Black is either giving up the pair of bishops or retreating to a very passive square. }
9... Be6
{ Instead,  9...Be4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Bd3⩲  provides a nice edge for White because of the pair of bishops. Also, Black is stuck with the bishop that is not really going to take part in the fight on the queenside. }
10. c5
{ Because of the weakness of the b7-pawn we are forcing the queen exchange, gaining serious space advantage on the queenside, and also opening the a-file for the rook. }
10... Qxb3 11. axb3 Nbd7 12. Bd3
{ Black's minor pieces are stuck. Our next move will be b4, with the positional threat of playing b5 and creating a weakness on the queenside, and if Black stops it by playing ...a6, then Nd2-b3-a5 is our next idea to attack the b7-pawn! }
*

