[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... c6
{ This move is possible, but it is absolutely not in the spirit of the Grünfeld Defence @@StartBracket@@rather the Slav!@@EndBracket@@. Black wants to create lively piece play in this opening. For that to happen, playing ...c5 at some moment is almost a must. }
5. e3 Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O
{ If we consider this position from the Slav viewpoint, which we should do, since now it is rather a Slav Defence than a Grünfeld, then Black already made an inaccuracy and entered an inferior line of the Schlechter variation: @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  or  @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e3  g6  5.Nf3  Bg7  and this is the starting position of the Schlechter.As you can see, there is a huge difference if we compare that position with what we have on the board: our bishop is on f4 instead of the passive c1! And that is the reason why after  @@StartFEN@@ 'rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1' @@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Black has many good choices here  @@StartBracket@@  4...a6  ,  4...e6  ,  4...dxc4  @@EndBracket@@  but  4...g6  is considered to be dubious because White can play  5.Bf4!  That is exactly what we have now in our line. }
7. h3
{ A routine move in this variation. We don't want to give up this bishop after ...Nh5, so we prepare a retreat square on h2. Also, ...Bg4 is a move Black wants to play, so h3 is a multi-purpose move. }
7... Nbd7
{ The most common move in the position, and a very serious inaccuracy! } 8.
cxd5
{ After this exchange on d5, Black's knight is misplaced on d7. It should be ready to go to c6 instead! }
8... Nxd5
{ At least after this capture the d7-knight can go to  f6  .  8...cxd5?  is even worse, because after  9.Qb3!  we can force the knight to a very awkward square:  9...Nb6  10.Be2±  with O-O, Rfc1 and a4! to follow. Black has 2 minor pieces which are really unfortunate, the b6-knight and the g7-bishop. }
9. Nxd5
{ We want the Exchange Slav structure, since basically we'll have an extra piece on the queenside because the g7-bishop is side-lined. }
9... cxd5 10. Be2 Nf6 11. O-O
{ Qb3 and then Rfc1 is coming, Black's minor pieces are on the wrong side of the board, where nothing is happening. }
