[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Grünfeld Defence"]
[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 dxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... dxc4
{ This move is better now than a move ago. Since Black's bishop is on g7 already, Black has some extra possibilities in case of  6.e4  . For example,  6...c5  7.d5  b5!  with counterchances against our centre. }
6. e3 { We are ready to recover the pawn on c4. } 6... Be6
{ Holding on to the extra pawn. Black would like to keep the c4-pawn by protecting it with their queen, but that fails.  6...Nd5  Using the tempo on our bishop.  7.Nxd5  Qxd5  8.Rc1  We are taking back the pawn anyway.  8...b5?  The only way to protect c4, but Black is creating a lot of weaknesses.  9.b3±  Black's position is falling apart. }
7. Ng5 { In most cases this is the critical response against ...Be6. } 7... Bd5
8. e4 h6
{ Instead,  8...Bc6  9.Bxc4  is much worse for Black: they have completely lost the fight for the centre, and their bishop is very strange on c6. }
9. Nxd5
{ The position is very sharp. Only this move provides an advantage for White.  9.exd5  hxg5  10.Bxg5  Nxd5  is quite okay for Black. }
9... hxg5
{ Black is entering the complications, but with precise play, we'll keep a big advantage.   White's point was that the natural  9...Nxd5  fails to the very important intermezzo  10.Nxf7!  Without this, Black would simply be better.  Kxf7  11.Bxc4  We are winning back the piece and our king will be much safer at the end of the variation.  11...e6  12.exd5  exd5  13.Bd3→  Black's king is very weak, as is especially the g6-pawn. White has a clear advantage. }
10. Nxc7+ Kf8 11. Bg3 Nc6 12. d5
{ Only move!  12.Nxa8?  Nxe4!  would be already clearly better for Black because of the huge activity of their pieces. Even being down a rook doesn't matter! }
12... Nd4 13. Qxd4 Nh5 14. Be5 Qxc7
{ Black is taking back the piece, but that will not solve all their problems. }
15. Bxg7+ Nxg7 16. Bxc4 Rxh2
{ If Black includes  16...Rc8  , then after  17.Be2  Rxh2  White has only one move to be better, the very funny  18.O-O!  and once we play g3 in the next move, we will keep a clear advantage because of our central pawns and Black's very bad knight on g7. }
17. Rxh2 Qxh2 18. O-O-O
{ Our centre is very strong and we are going to play g3 in the next move. It is important to note that  18...Qxg2  is pretty much losing to  19.d6!  exd6  20.Qf6  with a mating attack. }
*

