[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 dxc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... dxc4
{ This move is better now than a move ago. Since Black's bishop is on g7 already, Black has some extra possibilities in case of  6.e4  . For example,  6...c5  7.d5  b5!  with counterchances against our centre. }
6. e3 { We are ready to recover the pawn on c4. } 6... c5
{ Instead,  6...O-O  would lead to the same position, since after  7.Bxc4  Black doesn't have any better move than  7...c5  and  8.O-O  just transposes to 6...c5. }
7. Bxc4 O-O { 7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  O-O  9.O-O  leads to the same thing. } 8. O-O
cxd4
{ 9...Nc6  provokes  10.d5  , but since it is a good move, we will play it.  10...Na5  10.Be2  Nh5  The only way to justify Black's play. If we could play e4 and keep the dark-squared bishop, then it would be just a much better position for White.  11.Be5!  Before giving up this bishop, we first force Black to close the long diagonal for a while and to weaken some light squares.  11...f6  12.Bg3  Nxg3  13.hxg3⩲  Rc1-a3-b4 is coming. Black's position is very strange with that ...f6 move. }
9. Nxd4
{ The pawn structure is symmetrical, so we can't count on any strategical advantage here. However, it is an open position, and thanks to our better development we can still hope for a slight advantage. }
9... a6
{ Black wants to develop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. They can try many other moves, but none provides equality.  9...Nh5?  doesn't make much sense, because  10.Bg5  keeps the bishop and Black just misplaced the knight.   9...Nc6  is a serious positional error:  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Rc1⩲  with a clear advantage for us because of the better structure.   9...Nbd7  with the threat of ...e5 is interesting but after  10.Bg3  it is not easy to see Black's follow-up, because on  10...Nh5  we can still keep the bishop with  11.Bh4⩲  . }
10. Be2 { Going away from the ...b5-tempo, which now we can even meet by Bf3! }
10... Nbd7 11. Nb3
{ Black still has to solve the issue of their light-squared bishop, which will not be an easy task. }
