{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... c5
{ In this position,  5...c5  is much more logical than a move before because the bishop is already on g7. It was played in 729 OTB games according to my database, even by very strong Grandmasters. However, it is still a mistake! }
6. dxc5 { With the threat of taking on d5 as well. } 6... Ne4
{ This move was tried by Fabiano Caruana. } 7. cxd5
{ But I don't see a good continuation for Black after this exchange sacrifice. }
7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bxc3+ 9. Bd2 Bxa1 10. Qxa1
{ We have a bishop+pawn for the rook, and a huge central dominance. } 10... O-O
11. e4
{ The position is just winning according to the computer, and it is hard to argue. For instance,  11...Nd7  12.Qc3  Qc7  13.Be3!  We are not in a rush to play Bh6 and take back the rook, as Black can hardly move because of our strong centre.  13...Nf6  14.Bd3  with a +3 score according to my engine. }
