13. e3
{ Planning to meet  13...Nc6  with  14.Bb5!   Instead,  13.Qxa8?!  is very risky and not good:  13...Nc6  14.Qb7  Rb8  15.Qc7  Rc8  With ...Nxb4 to follow in the next move, our position is very suspicious. }
13... Nd7 { Black wants to play ...Rab8 and take on b4. } 14. a3
{ We are stabilising our queenside. } 14... Rfd8 15. Qa6
{ Bringing back our queen into the game by offering the trade. } 15... Qc2 16.
Qd3
{ Doing the same again! Here the best move for Black is to take on d3 and enter a pretty sad endgame.  16...Qb2?  fails to  17.Qd4!  and we can develop with a tempo after  17...Qc2  18.Bd3!  Qa4  19.Qc3  With castle in the next move, White is completely winning. }
16... Qa4 17. Qc3
{ Going out from the d-file and opening the way for the bishop to c4. } 17...
a5
{ Black has to be very fast, since if we castle with 2 extra pawns, then the game is over. }
18. Rc1 axb4 19. axb4 Nf6 { Now we have to defend against ...Nd5. } 20. Bc4
Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Nd5 22. c6
{ And we keep one extra pawn, with excellent winning chances. For example,  22...Nxb4  23.c7  Rdc8  24.O-O+-   Or  23...Nd3+  24.Kf1  Qa5  25.cxd8Q+  Rxd8  26.Ke2  Nxc1+  27.Qxc1+-  . }
*

