[White "20) Grünfeld Defence"]
[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Rc1 dxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 dxc4
{ Black is allowing us to occupy the centre, and they will build their counterplay on playing ...Bg4 and putting pressure on the centre. }
7. e4 c5
{ A perfectly playable move. Black is not far from equality in this variation. }
8. dxc5 Qa5 9. Nd2 { Breaking the pin and preparing Nxc4 ideas. } 9... Be6 10.
Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Nxc4 Qxc5 12. b3
{ The pawn structure is symmetrical and Black has no weaknesses, so we can't hope for a big advantage in this position. On the other hand, our pawn on e4 gives us more control over the centre, so we can look forward to a slightly better endgame. }
12... Nc6 13. Be3 Qh5 { The only square for the queen! } 14. Qxh5 Nxh5 15. g4
{ We can also gain some space on the kingside with tempo. } 15... Nf6 16. f3
{ In this symmetrical position the game is going to be decided on the queenside, and White's pieces are better positioned for that fight. Black's position is OK and there is a lot to play, but White has the better chances. }
*

