{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 dxc4
{ Black is allowing us to occupy the centre, and they will build their counterplay on playing ...Bg4 and putting pressure on the centre. }
7. e4 b5
{ Black is protecting the pawn on c4, and wouldn't mind the exchange of the b5 and e4-pawns. }
8. Nxb5 { We have to take. Otherwise, Black is just a solid pawn up. } 8...
Nxe4 9. Bxc4
{ Our pieces are very active and we have the threat of Nxc7.  9.Nxc7?  was not working because of  9...e5!  and Black is better. }
9... c6 { Sending back our knight. } 10. Nc3
{ 10.Nc7  was still not working because of  10...e5!  and, even though we will be briefly up an exchange after  11.Nxa8  exf4  , our knight can't escape from a8. }
10... Nd6
{ Gaining a tempo on the c4-bishop and rerouting the knight towards f5, so it can attack the d-pawn. Black was obviously not interested in taking on c3:  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  just makes our centre stronger, since the d4-pawn is not isolated anymore. }
11. Be2 Nf5 12. Be5
{ Protecting the d4-pawn and offering the bishop trade, which would be highly beneficial for us: without the g7-bishop, the pressure on our centre is much lighter. }
12... Bh6
{ Attacking the rook and gaining a tempo for ...Nd7 to eliminate our strong bishop from e5 with the knight. }
13. g4
{ Only played once, this move is the only test to Black's previous play. If we played  13.Rb1  , then after  13...Nd7  Black has a perfectly fine position. }
13... Bxc1
{ The logical continuation, but it is not a surprise that the only game to reach this position went with  13...Nd6  , since indeed it looks very risky to give up this bishop and let White attack on the kingside. However, after  14.g5  Bg7  15.Bxg7  Kxg7  16.h4!  with Qd2-Qf4 and h5 to follow, we still have a very dangerous attack and not even an exchange down! }
14. Qxc1 Nd6
{ Instead,  14...f6  is very bad:  15.gxf5  fxe5  16.fxg6  Bf5  17.Qh6  Bxg6  18.Rg1+-  and Black can't survive this attack. }
15. h4 { We need the h1-rook for the attack! } 15... f6
{ Black has problems on the dark squares, so attacking and restricting this bishop, seemingly with a tempo, makes perfect sense.  15...Bxg4  16.h5  Bxh5  17.Rxh5  is crushing. }
16. h5
{ The open h-file is much more important than a piece! Black is facing a very dangerous attack. One possible line for example is  16...g5!  Black has to keep the h-file closed; otherwise, they can get quickly checkmated.  17.Nxg5!  fxe5  18.dxe5  We are down a full rook, but the attack is very strong.  18...Nf7  19.e6!  Nxg5  20.Qxg5+  Kh8  21.Qe5+  Kg8  22.Bc4!  intending h6, and on ...Rf6 we can sacrifice the queen on f6, as e6-e7 is coming with a discovered check. }
*

