{ The main move. Black is challenging our central dominance. Even though it will most likely lead to an endgame, Black is hoping the control over the f4-square will offer enough compensation for White's pair of bishops. }
11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. O-O
{ Our goal in this endgame is to play f4. If we can do that, then we are clearly better with the 2 bishops. If not, then Black is probably fine. }
13... Nd7 { Black is keeping the c6-square available for their pawn. } 14. b4
{ The pawn will not hang anymore on b2, and it is much better on b4 than on b3, because it leaves the b3-square free for our bishop.   14.Nd5  wouldn't make any sense now, since Black can immediately reply  14...c6  and they have no problems because the knight is well placed on d7.   14.Ne2  is the most common move, with the idea of f4, but now  14...Bxb2!  is working very well for Black:  15.Rb1  Ne5!  the key intermezzo  16.Rxb2  Nxc4  17.Rxb7  Nxe3  18.fxe3  Rd2  with an equal endgame. }
14... Nb6 15. Bb3 Nf4 16. Rc2
{ With the idea of Ne2 and then eventually f4, we have a nice advantage in this endgame. }
