{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 Be6
{ This weird-looking move is probably mathematically Black's best option against the line I recommend you to play against the Grünfeld. This is a move order finesse: now  7.Ng5  begs to be played against this bishop, but Black will reply  7...c5!  and after  8.dxc5  they have  8...d4!  9.Nb5  Nc6  and this is a very good line for Black.   Black can't transpose to this with a reversed move order, since  6...c5  7.dxc5  Be6  gives White the option to play  8.Nd4!  attacking the bishop, while physically stopping ...d4 at the same time. }
7. e3 dxc4
{ The logical follow-up after ...Be6. What else is the bishop doing on e6, besides protecting this pawn? }
8. Ng5 Bd5 9. e4 h6
{ Only move for Black.  9...Bc6?  is unplayable:  10.Bxc4  with a clear advantage for White because of the centre, and if Black forces the issue, then we'll win quite some material after  10...h6  11.Nxf7  Rxf7  12.Qb3  Be8  13.Bxf7+  Bxf7  14.Qxb7  Nbd7  15.Bxc7+- }
10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5 12. Bxc4 Nb6
{ Again, only move for Black.  12...Nxc3?  will eventually make the game more open for our bishops:  13.bxc3  c5  @@StartBracket@@otherwise, ...Nxc3 has no point@@EndBracket@@  14.O-O  cxd4  15.cxd4  Qxd4  16.Bxe7  Qxd1  17.Rfxd1  Re8  18.Bg5±  The bishop pair is completely dominating in such an open position. }
13. Bb3 Qxd4 { This move is also possible, and very-very close to equality. }
14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5 Bxb2 16. Rc2
{ In order to take with the knight on c7, and gain the pair of bishops. } 16...
Be5 17. Nxc7 Bxc7 18. Rxc7 Nc6 19. Rxb7
{ Because of the bishop pair, we have some winning chances in this endgame, but objectively it should be a draw, since the material is very limited and the black knights can have nice squares in the centre @@StartBracket@@d4, d5@@EndBracket@@. }
