{ Again, only move for Black.  12...Nxc3?  will eventually make the game more open for our bishops:  13.bxc3  c5  @@StartBracket@@otherwise, ...Nxc3 has no point@@EndBracket@@  14.O-O  cxd4  15.cxd4  Qxd4  16.Bxe7  Qxd1  17.Rfxd1  Re8  18.Bg5±  The bishop pair is completely dominating in such an open position. }
13. Bb3 Nc6 14. d5 Nd4
{ Black is going to take our bishop, so we will lose the bishop pair advantage. }
15. O-O Nxb3 16. axb3
{ Played only in 1 OTB game, so should be much trickier to face for Black than the normal  16.Qxb3  , where after  16...Bxc3  17.Rxc3  Qxd5  18.Bxe7  Rfe8  the position is very drawish. See the conclusion of the trainable. }
16... Bxc3
{ This move, which works excellently after 16.Qxb3, is a big mistake now. } 17.
Rxc3 Qxd5 { 17...Nxd5  18.Rh3!  with a dangerous attack. } 18. Bxe7 Rfe8 19.
Rxc7
{ If we had played 16.Qxb3, now Black could trade queens on b3 followed by ...Nd5! winning material. That's not possible here because after  19...Qxd1  20.Rxd1  the rook will also control the d5-square. }
