[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Grünfeld Defence"]
[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Rc1 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 c6
{ Black opts for the Slav structure again. Compared to 4...c6, this is slightly better, because instead of the best move 7.h3, here we just played a good, useful move with Rc1. }
7. e3 Qa5
{ Now this plan is less effective than inthe 4...c6 variation because the rook is already protecting the c3-knight. }
8. Be2 Ne4 9. O-O
{ We can sacrifice a2, because not only Black's queen, but their whole position will be stuck after it. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxa2 11. Ra1
{ Not allowing the queen back to safety via a5. } 11... Qb2 12. c5
{ With a clear advantage for White. Black has problems with their queen and also it is not easy to find active squares for their minor pieces. For instance,  12...Qxc3  is immediately losing to  13.Qb1!  with the threat of Rc1 and if  13...Bf5  then just  14.Qxb7+-  .   12...Na6  is a better try, but after  13.Bxa6  bxa6  14.h3±  both Black bishops are extremely passive, and the b-file is open only for us, because the f4-bishop prevents our opponent from using it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Grünfeld Defence"]
[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Rc1 c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 c6
{ Black opts for the Slav structure again. Compared to 4...c6, this is slightly better, because instead of the best move 7.h3, here we just played a good, useful move with Rc1. }
7. e3 Bg4
{ Making use of the absence of the h3 move.  7...Nh5?!  could fail very spectacularly:  8.Be5  and here the logical follow-up from Black is  8...f6?  in order to take the bishop, but they are just losing after  9.Bxb8!  Rxb8  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Nxd5!  and they can't recapture on d5 because Bc4 is winning the queen and the game.   7...Nbd7?!  This move is exactly as bad asin the case of 4...c6:  8.cxd5!  cxd5  9.h3⩲  The knight should be on c6 and not on d7, and the g7-bishop should be on e7. }
8. Qb3
{ Typical reaction to ...Bg4, going out from the pin and attacking the unprotected b7-pawn. }
8... Qb6 9. Qxb6
{ Here we can just take and play for the weakness of the b6-pawn. } 9... axb6
10. cxd5
{ An extremely important move and idea! If we don't do this after Qxb6 basically in any other similar situation, then we just improved Black's structure and opened the a-file for their rook.   Let's say a lazy move like  10.a3  or  10.Be2  would lead to a completely fine position for Black after  10...dxc4  . The point is that we can't isolate the b6-pawn anymore. }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. a3
{ With a small but long-lasting advantage, because of the weak b6-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Grünfeld Defence"]
[Black "Grünfeld Defence: 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Rc1 c6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence, a very popular and very good opening. It offers dynamic, aggressive, tricky play for the Black player in many of the variations, so it shouldn't be a surprise that it was one of the main weapons of Garry Kasparov. Nowadays, its main experts are Svidler, Nepomniachtchi and MVL. }
4. Bf4
{ Basically, White has to make a decision at move 4: either they want to play  4.cxd5  and then e4 and build a big centre with e4-d4-c3 pawns, which Black will attack by playing ...c5-...Bg7-...Nc6-...Qa5-...Rd8-...Bg4 etc., or play any other variation where Black's play will depend on the concrete line White has chosen. This is one of the downsides of the Grünfeld Defence, that Black has to be ready for a lot of different setups and variations from White, which requires a lot of memorisation.My choice is  4.Bf4  , a solid variation. We are developing and preparing the c1-square for the rook so it can quickly step out of the g7-bishop's scope. Many times, Black is building their counterplay around the c3-knight @@StartBracket@@...c5-...Ne4-...Qa5@@EndBracket@@. In this case, the rook will offer the knight some extra protection. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Continuing the development. Of course, the other moves we want to play later, such as  5.Rc1  or  5.e3  , are also possible. Since this opening is very concrete, or move by move, those moves would offer Black some extra options, or lead to different positions altogether. }
5... O-O 6. Rc1 c6
{ Black opts for the Slav structure again. Compared to 4...c6, this is slightly better, because instead of the best move 7.h3, here we just played a good, useful move with Rc1. }
7. e3 Bg4
{ Making use of the absence of the h3 move.  7...Nh5?!  could fail very spectacularly:  8.Be5  and here the logical follow-up from Black is  8...f6?  in order to take the bishop, but they are just losing after  9.Bxb8!  Rxb8  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Nxd5!  and they can't recapture on d5 because Bc4 is winning the queen and the game.   7...Nbd7?!  This move is exactly as bad asin the case of 4...c6:  8.cxd5!  cxd5  9.h3⩲  The knight should be on c6 and not on d7, and the g7-bishop should be on e7. }
8. Qb3
{ Typical reaction to ...Bg4, going out from the pin and attacking the unprotected b7-pawn. }
8... Bxf3
{ Black is making our structure somewhat worse for now, but it is really not a big deal, and later we can even use it to our advantage. }
9. gxf3 Qb6
{ This move allows an endgame very favourable for us, as we can isolate the b6-pawn. Instead,  9...b6  is pretty weakening:  10.cxd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  cxd5  and for example  12.h4!?  leads to a nice position for White. We want to play h5, and if Black stops it by playing ...h5 themselves, then we can play Bd3-Ke2-Rhg1. Besides being better on the queenside, here we also have an initiative on the kingside.   The least weakening way to defend the pawn is  9...Qd7  , but now Black's development becomes pretty problematic because the queen is occupying the knight's natural square on d7. After  10.Be5  dxc4  11.Bxc4  b5  12.Bf1⩲  we will put the bishop on g2, play O-O and then f4 with a nice advantage. Black's position is pretty loose. }
10. Qxb6 axb6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. a3
{ It will be very difficult for Black to get a draw from such a position. } *

