[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "KID Black sidelines: 4...O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O
{ Black can also start with this move order, but it doesn't really affect us, since we just play our normal Be2. }
5. Be2 c5 6. d5 e6
{ 6...d6  7.Bg5  In most systems played against the KID, White should adjust its setup against the early ...c5 move, but fortunately we are just back to Averbakh territory. }
7. e5
{ We have to go for this! If instead, we play  7.Bg5  , then Black plays  7...h6  8.Be3  exd5  9.exd5  d6  and Black tricked us into a position we are not playing, as against the early ...h6 system we play with dxe6. }
7... Ne8 8. Nf3
{ 8.h4  is also good and leads to a dangerous attack, but I found that Nf3 is much easier and it's better not to memorise too much in such a rare line. }
8... exd5 9. Bg5
{ We don't have to rush to recapture on d5. It's better to develop first with a tempo. }
9... f6
{ Instead,  9...Qa5  is not better.  10.cxd5!  Our centre is stable and ...Be7 is a threat. }
10. Qxd5+ Kh8 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Qxc5 { A free pawn for White. } *

