{ 6...d6  7.Bg5  In most systems played against the KID, White should adjust its setup against the early ...c5 move, but fortunately we are just back to Averbakh territory. }
7. e5
{ We have to go for this! If instead, we play  7.Bg5  , then Black plays  7...h6  8.Be3  exd5  9.exd5  d6  and Black tricked us into a position we are not playing, as against the early ...h6 system we play with dxe6. }
7... Ne8 8. Nf3
{ 8.h4  is also good and leads to a dangerous attack, but I found that Nf3 is much easier and it's better not to memorise too much in such a rare line. }
8... d6 9. O-O
{ Keeping the tension in the centre, since Black can't release it in an advantageous way. }
9... dxe5
{ 9...exd5  is met by  10.Bg5!  Qd7  @@StartBracket@@The queen has to cover e7@@EndBracket@@  11.Qxd5  dxe5  12.Qxc5  Nc6  13.Rad1⩲  Every developing move comes with a tempo. Black is already in a very dangerous situation because of their lack of development. }
10. dxe6 Qxd1 11. exf7+
{ This intermediate check is the key point of our previous play. } 11... Rxf7
12. Bxd1
{ Instead,  12.Rxd1  is also fine, but at least after  12...Nc6  13.Ng5  Rd7  Black can get rid of that awkward rook. }
12... Nc6 13. Ng5 Rf8 14. Bf3 Nf6 15. Bxc6
{ We make our structural advantage even bigger with this move. } 15... bxc6 16.
Nge4
{ It will be hard for Black to hold this endgame with such an awful pawn structure. }
