[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "KID Black sidelines: 5...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 e5
{ A tricky move order from Black. They want to avoid some systems against the KID, and one of them is the Averbakh!  6.d5  O-O  and we were tricked.   After  5...O-O  6.Bg5  Black has to make some preparation to play e5, and here they could do it right away. }
6. dxe5
{ We are forced to make this move, but fortunately this line is very promising for White! }
6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. f4
{ Just like this! We have to play very aggressively because Black's king is in the centre and also because, given our structure and weak square on d4, our long-term chances are not so good. }
8... Be6
{ Nobody has played  8...exf4?!  so far, since it is just helping White's development:  9.Bxf4  Be6  10.O-O-O+  Kc8  11.Nf3  With the idea of playing Nd5 and Ng5 to put Black under maximum pressure.  Nh5  12.Be3  Nd7  13.Rhf1↑  Nd5 and Ng5 are very annoying and Black's king is awkward on c8.     8...Nfd7  is too passive and Black is playing a move with an already developed piece.  9.Nf3  c6  Opening the way for the king to c7.  10.f5!  If we can play a timely f5 in this variation, then we can even switch to positional play because we will have a big space advantage on the kingside. The d4-square is irrelevant, Black can't reach it with their knights.  a5  11.Be3  Na6  12.O-O-O  f6  13.g4±  Black's pieces are very passive. }
9. Nf3 Nbd7 10. O-O c6 11. f5
{ This is not even a pawn sacrifice. We are just getting a better structure. }
11... gxf5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nxe5 Bg6 14. Bf4
{ Black's king is in a very dangerous situation, even without queens on the board. }
