[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "KID Black sidelines: 5...e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 e5
{ A tricky move order from Black. They want to avoid some systems against the KID, and one of them is the Averbakh!  6.d5  O-O  and we were tricked.   After  5...O-O  6.Bg5  Black has to make some preparation to play e5, and here they could do it right away. }
6. dxe5
{ We are forced to make this move, but fortunately this line is very promising for White! }
6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. f4
{ Just like this! We have to play very aggressively because Black's king is in the centre and also because, given our structure and weak square on d4, our long-term chances are not so good. }
8... Nc6
{ The most natural move for Black, protecting the e5-pawn and also hinting at the Nd4 idea. }
9. Nf3 Be6
{ 9...Nd4??  is a big mistake:  10.fxe5  Nc2+  11.Kd1  Nxa1  12.Bg5  h6  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.exf6+-  and we will catch the knight in the corner.  9...exf4?!  still helps our development:  10.Bxf4  Be6  11.O-O-O+  Kc8  12.Nd5  Nh5  13.Be3  b6  14.Ng5  Kb7  15.Rhf1  Ne5  16.Kb1!  Rhe8   @@StartBracket@@  16...c6?  is not working because  17.g4!  cxd5  18.gxh5  is just winning for White@@EndBracket@@  17.Bd4  h6  18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Ne3± }
10. O-O
{ With the threat of f5! White has a strong initiative here. Since there are only 8 OTB games for this position, and most of those didn't happen recently, I'll finish the trainable line here. I will show you quite a few examples illustrating how our initiative can develop or what are our ideas in these positions.   A@@EndBracket@@  10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Nd7  12.Rad1  Kc8  13.Nd5  Nce5  14.Ng5  c6  15.Bg3!  Rf8  16.Ne7+  Kd8   @@StartBracket@@  16...Kc7  17.Nf5!  @@EndBracket@@  17.Bxe5  Bxe5  18.Nxc6  bxc6  19.Nxe6++-   @@StartFEN@@ r1k4r/pp1n1pbp/2p1b1p1/3Nn1N1/2P1P3/6B1/PP2B1PP/3R1RK1 b - - 1 15 @@EndFEN@@  15...cxd5  16.cxd5  Bg4  17.Bxg4  Nxg4  18.Nxf7+-   Or @@StartFEN@@r2k3r/ppp2pbp/2n1bnp1/8/2P1PB2/2N2N2/PP2B1PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 11 @@EndFEN@@  11...Kc8  12.Nd5  Ne8  13.Ng5  Bxb2  14.Rad1  b6  15.Be3  Ne5  16.c5  Kb7  17.Rb1+-   B@@EndBracket@@  10...Kc8  11.f5!  gxf5  12.exf5  Bxf5  13.Nxe5  Nd4  14.Bd3  Bxd3  15.Nxd3±   @@StartFEN@@ r1k4r/ppp2pbp/2n1bnp1/4pP2/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2B1PP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bd7  12.Ng5  Rf8  13.Nd5  Nd4  14.Bd3±   C@@EndBracket@@ and the most complicated line:  10...Nd4  11.Nxd4  exd4  12.f5!  Bd7  13.Nd5  Nxe4  14.fxg6  fxg6  15.Bf3  Nc5  16.Bg5+  Kc8  17.Rae1  d3  18.b4  Ne6  19.Bf6  Bxf6  20.Nxf6±   @@StartFEN@@ r2k3r/pppb1pbp/5np1/3N1P2/2PpP3/8/PP2B1PP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 13 @@EndFEN@@  13...Nxd5  14.cxd5  gxf5  15.exf5  Bf6  16.Bh5  Bb5  17.Bxf7  Bxf1  18.Kxf1  Ke7  19.Be6  Kd6  20.Ke2  c6  21.Kd3  cxd5  22.b3±   @@StartFEN@@ r2k3r/ppp2pbp/4bnp1/5P2/2PpP3/2N5/PP2B1PP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 12 @@EndFEN@@  12...dxc3  13.fxe6  Nxe4  14.exf7!  Ke7   @@StartBracket@@  14...Bd4+  15.Kh1  Nf2+  16.Rxf2  Bxf2  17.Bg5  Kd7  18.bxc3  Rhf8  19.Bg4+  Kc6  20.Bf3+  Kb6  21.Rf1+-  @@EndBracket@@   15.bxc3  Bxc3  16.Ba3+  c5  17.Rad1  Rad8  18.Bf3  Rxd1  19.Rxd1  Nf6  20.Bxc5+  Kxf7  21.Bxb7+- }
