[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 6...e5?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... e5
{ The trademark move of the KID is already a serious mistake here! Black is exposing the queen, and later the rook, to a lethal pin. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nd5
{ The rook is pinned, and Black is facing the unsolvable problem of defending the c7- and f6-squares with one move. }
9... Nxd5
{ Relatively the best. Black is sacrificing an exchange instead of a pawn. If  9...Nbd7  we are just taking the free pawn.  10.Nxc7  Rb8  11.f3  Preparing against ...h6. With the e4-pawn protected, now we don't have to part ways with our dark-squared bishop. This is a very important piece for us, since our only weakness is the d4-square and this bishop can perfectly control it.  h6  12.Be3  Coming back with a tempo even!  b6  13.O-O-O+-  Simply a pawn up and a winning position for White. Black doesn't even have the hint of a counterplay. }
10. Bxd8 Nb4
{ Instead,  10...Nf4  is also possible, but we can keep the full exchange anyway:  11.Bf1  c5  12.Ba5  Nc6  13.Bd2  Nd4  14.O-O-O± }
11. O-O-O { Developing and stopping the fork on c2, at once. } 11... N8a6
{ If  11...Nxa2+  12.Kb1  Nb4  13.Bxc7  we again managed to keep our extra material. }
12. Kb1
{ Our opponent protected the c7-pawn, but it gave us the necessary time to do the same with the a2-pawn. }
12... Be6 13. Bg5
{ Bringing back the bishop to its perfect place, the e3-square. } 13... Nc5 14.
f3
{ White has a straightforward way of finishing development: bishop back to e3, the knight goes to f2, and then doubling on the d-file. But in order to execute this plan, Black first has to stop the idea of Rd8+, since we know the side with an extra exchange is interested in trading rooks. }
