[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 6...Nc6?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Nc6
{ Black is trying to change the move order. Now they are ready to play ...e5, since the knight is protecting the d8-square too. }
7. d5 { Not giving the possibility to play ...e5. } 7... Ne5 8. Nf3
{ Just developing normally. Instead,  8.f4?!  Ned7  would have given Black some counterchances, like attacking the e4-pawn with ....Nc5, or playing ...c6 and trying to exploit the weakness of the g1-a7 diagonal. }
8... h6
{ 8...Nxf3+  shows the b8-knight's journey was not successful. After moving 3 times, it took a knight that moved only once.  9.Bxf3  c6  Black has to try to do something about their lack of central presence.  10.O-O  Nd7  Opening the long diagonal and looking for a more active place for the knight.  11.Qd2  a5  12.b3⩲  We have the typical queenside play here, with a3-b4, but probably the best strategy is just to keep playing solid, strengthening moves like Rfe1, Be2, Bf1 and see what Black is doing. We don't have to hurry with anything: our space advantage in the centre is not going to disappear or even be challenged anytime soon. }
9. Be3 { We are not giving up this bishop! } 9... Nfg4 10. Bd2
{ The bishop is not perfect here, but eventually it will find their way back to e3 or c3. }
10... e6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. O-O
{ White managed to finish the development and keeps a nice edge thanks to the space advantage in the centre. }
12... exd5 13. cxd5
{ Now Black has a backward pawn on c7, which is a potential target for us. }
13... f5
{ Black has to challenge our centre, otherwise they can't activate their pieces. }
14. exf5
{ Pushing the pawn to f4 was a dangerous positional threat, creating a fantastic outpost for the knight on e5. We obviously want nothing of that. }
14... Bxf5 15. Nb5
{ Keeping Black busy by attacking the c7-pawn and getting closer to the weak e6-square. }
15... c5 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Nd4 Bd7 18. Bc3
{ Our advantage has been transformed: no more backward pawn or weak square on e6. Instead, Black has an extra pawn island, and the c6-d6 hanging pawns are going to be a problem for them later in the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 6...c6!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c6
{ This is a very subtle move! It doesn't happen very often that, with one little pawn move, Black is preparing three different types of ideas to challenge our centre. The most obvious one is ...d5, but there is also the idea of attacking our centre from the flank, with ...a6 and ...b5, exchanging one of our pillars, the c4-pawn. Last but not least, since this move is covering the d5-square, it makes ...e5 possible, because our refutation of that move @@StartBracket@@dxe5, exchanging queens and playing Nd5@@EndBracket@@ doesn't exist anymore! }
7. h4
{ Maybe a very surprising move at first sight, but I figured that this move works best against the different options of Black. White has two different moves besides h4.   7.Nf3  looks like the most natural alternative and it indeed works well against all the breaks but after  7...h6!  8.Be3  e5  9.d5  Ng4  leads to positions where I like Black's chances in general, and it has nothing in common with the positions I would like to achieve with the Averbakh variation.   Instead of @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppb1/2pp1npp/6B1/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3  we can try  8.Bf4  too, to avoid Ng4 and 'stop' e5, but Black nevertheless plays the nice  8...e5!  and has a great position after  9.dxe5  Nh5!  10.Be3  dxe5  .     The other alternative is  7.Qd2  but after  7...a6  8.Nf3  b5  , here besides ...bxc4, ...b4 is a threat too, so we have to take the time to play  9.a3  and then  bxc4  10.Bxc4  d5  11.exd5  cxd5  12.Bxf6  exf6  13.Bxd5  Re8+  14.Kd1  Ra7  leads to a very complex position, which I definitely want to avoid with my king on d1.   So, the move left was  7.h4  , which is also a developing move. Not only does it make the h1-rook more active, but developing also means helping our strategy, and one of our strategic goals in the Averbakh is to make Black's play on the kingside more difficult by pushing the pawns there ourselves! }
7... a6
{ Black is going for the ...b5-break, but it looks pretty slow and ineffective now. }
8. h5
{ It's not really a mating attack, it is rather 'the best defence is attack' phrase, but of course, creating a few weaknesses along the way in Black's camp doesn't hurt either. }
8... b5 9. hxg6 fxg6
{ If Black plays  9...hxg6?!  , then they are playing with fire. After  10.Qc1!  suddenly that 'improbable' checkmate looks realistic. }
10. a3 { Simple way of stopping Black's threat. } 10... Nbd7 11. Nf3
{ Black's position is very loose here. White has obvious moves to take advantage of the opponent's weaknesses, such as Qb3 threatening on the diagonal or Rc1 to put also some pressure on the c-file. }
*

