{ This is a very subtle move! It doesn't happen very often that, with one little pawn move, Black is preparing three different types of ideas to challenge our centre. The most obvious one is ...d5, but there is also the idea of attacking our centre from the flank, with ...a6 and ...b5, exchanging one of our pillars, the c4-pawn. Last but not least, since this move is covering the d5-square, it makes ...e5 possible, because our refutation of that move @@StartBracket@@dxe5, exchanging queens and playing Nd5@@EndBracket@@ doesn't exist anymore! }
7. h4
{ Maybe a very surprising move at first sight, but I figured that this move works best against the different options of Black. White has two different moves besides h4.   7.Nf3  looks like the most natural alternative and it indeed works well against all the breaks, but after  7...h6!  8.Be3  e5  9.d5  Ng4  leads to positions where I like Black's chances in general, and it has nothing in common with the positions I would like to achieve with the Averbakh variation.   Instead of  8.Be3  we can try  8.Bf4  too, to avoid Ng4 and 'stop' e5, but Black nevertheless plays the nice  8...e5!  and has a great position after  9.dxe5  Nh5!  10.Be3  d5  .     The other alternative is  7.Qd2  but after  7...a6  8.Nf3  b5  , here besides ...bxc4, ...b4 is a threat too, so we have to take the time to play  9.a3  and then  bxc4  10.Bxc4  d5  11.exd5  cxd5  12.Bxf6  exf6  13.Bxd5  Re8+  14.Kd1  Ra7  leads to a very complex position, which I definitely want to avoid with my king on d1.   So, the move left was  7.h4  , which is also a developing move. Not only does it make the h1-rook more active, but developing also means helping our strategy, and one of our strategic goals in the Averbakh is to make Black's play on the kingside more difficult by pushing the pawns there ourselves! }
7... e5 8. d5
{ Obviously,  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  doesn't make any sense, since we can't play 10.Nd5.   8.Nf3  would be also inaccurate:  8...exd4  9.Nxd4  h6  and with ...Re8 to follow Black achieves decent counterplay against the e4-pawn. }
8... h6 9. Be3 cxd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. g4
{ Again, the idea is not to attack, but to stop Black's play before it even started, if possible close the kingside, and then win the game on the queenside. }
11... Nc5 12. f3 a5 13. h5 g5 14. Nh3
{ Is a strategically winning position for White. Black has no play on the kingside, and eventually will run into problems on the queenside. }
*

