[Black "Averbakh system: 6...Nbd7 7.Qd2 c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Nbd7 { Supporting the ...e5 move. } 7. Qd2 c5 8. Nf3
{ The situation is the same as inthe  ...Na6  line. The knight on d7 is also not suitable for a Maróczy Bind, so we don't have to rush to push d5 at all.Moreover, on  8.d5  there is  8...b5!  and after  9.cxb5  a6  , we don't have my favourite a4 anymore to take back with the pawn on b5, so Black could achieve a very decent version of the Benkő Gambit. }
8... cxd4
{ Black goes for the Maróczy Bind, but instead of the normal c6-square, their knight is on d7. }
9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. f3 Ne6
{ This move is by far the most common, and I have to say the best in the position, but with this, it's very easy to understand that, instead of ...Nc6-d4, Black had to play ...Nd7-c5-e6-d4 to exchange our d4-knight. That's 2 extra tempi! }
11. Be3
{ To be fair with Black, our bishop on g5 was also under attack, so actually our opponent is just losing one tempo. }
11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Be6 13. O-O Nd7
{ As a general rule, if we decide to exchange the bishops, then we should play on the kingside and centre, while if we decide to keep the bishops on the board, then it's better to play on the queenside. }
14. Bxg7
{ I like this approach better! Of course, it makes a lot of sense to pose some threats against the king which has just lost its main defender. }
14... Kxg7 15. f4 f6 16. Kh1 { The bishop needed some space. } 16... a5 17. b3
{ And we will start regrouping our forces towards the kingside. } *

