6... Nbd7 { Supporting the ...e5 move. } 7. Qd2 e5 8. d5 Nc5
{ Instead,  8...a5  is possible but after  9.h4  Nc5  10.f3  we transpose back to 8...Nc5. }
9. f3 a5 10. h4
{ This is my recommended move order, but I invite you to check the annotated gameTratar-Kotz that went  10.g4  h6  11.Be3  Ne8?  12.h4  to see what happens if White manages to close the kingside. }
10... h5 11. Nh3
{ The knight will stay well on f2 and in some cases can go to d3, to exchange the c5-knight. We also remain flexible, keeping the options of castling short or long. }
11... c6 12. Nf2 a4 13. O-O Qa5 14. Nd3 Nfd7
{ If the knight jumps to h7, we can go for the d6-pawn.  14...Nh7  15.Be7  Re8  16.Bxd6  Nxd3  17.Bxd3  cxd5  18.exd5+-  since if Black gives a check,  18...Qb6+  we can simply play  19.c5  with a winning position. }
15. b4
{ Now it was not so advisable to go after the d6-pawn:  15.Be7  Re8  16.Bxd6  Nxd3  17.Bxd3  cxd5  and we can see the difference compared to the 14...Nh7 line. Now we can't really recapture well on d5, because the d7-knight is controlling the c5-square when the queen checks from b6. }
15... axb3 16. axb3 Qxa1 17. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 18. Kh2
{ There is no coordination among the black pieces. The queen is stronger in this position. }
