5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Nbd7 { Supporting the ...e5 move. } 7. Qd2 e5 8. d5 Nc5
{ Instead,  8...a5  is possible but after  9.h4  Nc5  10.f3  we transpose back to 8...Nc5. }
9. f3 h6 10. Be3 Nh5 { Black wants to play with f5 or sometimes with Nf4. } 11.
O-O-O
{ Now the pawn is finally hanging for free on h6.   If instead  11.Bxh6  , then  Qh4+  12.Kd1  Qf2  and our position is collapsing on g2. }
11... Kh7 12. g3
{ The move is absolutely logical, stopping Nf4, but there is a very deep idea behind it as well! }
12... Qe7 13. Re1 Bd7 14. Bd1
{ Transferring the bishop to c2, and vacating the e2-square for the knight. }
14... c6 15. Bc2 Rfb8
{ Black is moving their forces towards the queenside, but we are ready to face the b5-break. }
16. Nge2 b5 17. dxc6
{ With this move we secure the d5-square for later. Also, Black will have a backward d6-pawn. }
17... Bxc6 18. cxb5 Bxb5 19. Nxb5 Rxb5 20. Nc3
{ White keeps the advantage because of the weak pawn on d6. The knight has a nice outpost on d5 too. }
