Nh7
{ Black can also try something on the queenside:  12...Bd7  13.Nh3  a4  14.Ng5  a3  15.b3↑  The queenside is still not completely closed. First White should play Rhg1 and g4 and then keep the tension there, while also keeping an eye on the queenside, since that a3-pawn can become a target anytime. }
13. Nh3 f5 14. exf5
{ White doesn't want to let Black decide whether to push on f4 or take e4. }
14... gxf5
{ The vast majority of King's Indian players would take this way, since now the e4-square is under firm control. If  14...Bxf5  15.Nf2  Nf6  we execute a light-square strategy:  16.Bxc5!  dxc5  17.g4  Bd7  18.gxh5  Nxh5  19.Rdg1±  and the black king's position is in ruins. }
15. Rdg1
{ Preparing the kingside breakthrough with g4! That move is positionally very good too, as it will help to fight for the e4-square. }
15... a4 16. g4 hxg4 17. fxg4 f4 { Black has to keep the g-file closed. } 18.
Bxc5 dxc5 19. a3
{ Black has strategically lost the game. In the next moves White will occupy all the nice blockading squares with minor pieces, and then will start pushing the kingside pawns. }
