[Black "Averbakh system: 6...Na6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Na6
{ This move was recently played by Kasparov himself, so we have to take it very seriously. The idea of the move is to make ...e5 possible for Black, since after exchanging on e5 and then d8 our Nd5 move is not a double attack anymore because the knight is defending the c7-square. }
7. Qd2 c5
{ This is much rarer than playing with e5. On d5, Black wants to reply Nc7 and then play for the b5-break. Eventually we'll play d5, but I believe we can improve that line a little bit. }
8. Nf3
{ In the vast majority of cases on both ...c5 and ... e5 we react with d5, but here it is not necessary, since Black already misplaced the knight if the game transposes to a Maróczy Bind structure. }
8... Bg4
{ Black is putting a lot of pressure on the d4-pawn, so we have to react now. I feel that we improved a little bit compared to the immediate d5, since Black sometimes wants to use their bishop on d7, and we eliminated that possibility.   If  8...cxd4  , then  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.f3  , and we reach a position which is analysed via the  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/6B1/2PPP3/2N5/PP2BPPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nbd7  7.Qd2  c5  8.Nf3  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.f3  move order. }
9. d5 Nc7 { Black is starting the standard plan. } 10. O-O a6 11. a4
{ We stop b5! } 11... Rb8 { Black insists on playing it. } 12. a5
{ We only allow it if our opponent has to ruin the structure a little bit to get it.  12...b5  13.axb6  Rxb6  14.e5!  Black's c7-knight is horrible, so it makes sense to start active operations right now.   A@@EndBracket@@  14...Bxf3  Even though this intermezzo looks unpleasant, White keeps everything under control.  15.Bxf3  dxe5  16.Na4!  This double attack is the tactical justification for playing e5.  16...Rb4  17.b3!  We don't want to give up the c-pawn, but rather the b-pawn, so we can keep our strong centre, and will also gain a tempo if the rook takes on b3.  17...Qd6   @@StartBracket@@  17...Rxb3  18.Nxc5  Rb6  19.Rac1⩲  White is down a pawn, but with such strong pieces it rather feels like we are up on material. Once we can start pushing our central pawns, Black's position can collapse very quickly. @@EndBracket@@  It looks like that by playing Nd7 next Black can protect everything and will have a nice position. Our opponent is just missing one tempo.  18.Nxc5!  This cool tactical idea provides White a nice edge.  18...Qxc5  19.Be3  Qd6  20.c5  We are taking back the material.  20...Qd7  21.Qxb4  e4!  If not for this resource, White would be just completely winning.  22.Bxe4  Nxe4  23.Qxe4  Bxa1  24.Rxa1  Nxd5  25.Bh6  After the position calmed down, with a strong passer on the c-file and some threats against the Black king, White keeps a nice and stable edge.  25...Rc8  26.h3⩲  .   B@@EndBracket@@  14...Nfe8  15.exd6!  A concrete approach: we take quickly so Black can't yet recapture with a pawn, and then the c5-pawn will be very weak.  15...Nxd6  16.Be3  Bxf3  17.gxf3⩲  Unfortunately, Black could spoil our structure a little bit, but there are no pieces around our king, and we are going to take a very important pawn in the next move. }
