[White "21) King's Indian Averbakh System - Black Sidelines"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 6...Na6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Na6
{ This move was recently played by Kasparov himself, so we have to take it very seriously. The idea of the move is to make ...e5 possible for Black, since after exchanging on e5 and then d8 our Nd5 move is not a double attack anymore because the knight is defending the c7-square. }
7. Qd2 e5
{ Instead, Black can start with  7...Qe8  too, but after  8.f3  e5  9.d5  Nh5  10.Bd1  we still reach a position which is discussed after 7...e5. }
8. d5 c6 9. h4 { Our usual idea, clarifying things first on the kingside. }
9... cxd5 10. cxd5 Nc5 11. f3
{ Protecting e4 is necessary in most cases when the knight lands on c5. } 11...
Bd7
{ Trying to get some activity on the queenside, but as usual, it shouldn't bother us too much. }
12. g4
{ Here  12.h5  looks like the most obvious move, but Black has a very nice and surprising response:  12...h6!  13.Bxh6  Nxh5  and the position is rather opening for Black on the kingside. Their next move could be Nf4, for example, and our strategy to keep the kingside closed or under control has failed. }
12... a5 13. h5
{ Now the pawn is protected, so we don't have to look out for h6 at all. }
13... a4
{ 13...b5  According to the engine, we could take this pawn, but I don't see why to bother. We'll have the time to win the game later on the queenside. For now let's just clarify the situation on the kingside:  14.h6!  Bh8  15.Nh3⩲  . }
14. Nh3 Qa5 15. Nf2 b5 16. h6
{ Again this useful move to close the kingside first and then start operations on the queenside. }
16... Bh8 17. Ncd1 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2
{ Our plan is to get rid of the c5-knight and then Black's position can collapse really quickly on the queenside. }
