1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... Na6
{ This move was recently played by Kasparov himself, so we have to take it very seriously. The idea of the move is to make ...e5 possible for Black, since after exchanging on e5 and then d8 our Nd5 move is not a double attack anymore because the knight is defending the c7-square. }
7. Qd2 e5
{ Instead, Black can start with  7...Qe8  too, but after  8.f3  e5  9.d5  Nh5  10.Bd1  we still reach a position which is discussed after 7...e5. }
8. d5 Qe8
{ Instead,  8...Nc5  is also possible:  9.f3  a5  and  10.h4  leads to the same position what we have analysed via the  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/6B1/2PPP3/2N5/PP2BPPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nbd7  7.Qd2  e5  8.d5  Nc5  9.f3  a5  10.h4  move order. }
9. f3
{ The smartest move order, in my opinion. Most players are starting with  9.Bd1  instead, but since Black can play  9...Nh5  anyway @@StartBracket@@because taking on h5 doesn't bring us anything@@EndBracket@@, it's not particularly useful for us to keep the d1-h5 diagonal open. On the other hand, Black can also reply with  9...c6  , and then they have very quick b5 ideas. In this scenario, we'll miss our bishop from e2. }
9... Nh5
{ Now Black gives up on the queenside play, so we can calmly continue our development. }
10. Bd1
{ The bishop could also go to d3, but since the target square for our bishop is c2, it's better to leave the d3-square empty now as that could be a very useful place for our knight. }
10... f5 11. Nge2 Bd7
{ Black can immediately close the kingside, but it'll not bring them much:  11...f4  12.Nc1!  Bf6  It is certainly a positional achievement for Black to exchange that passive bishop, but it's not going to challenge our strategical dominance on the queenside.  13.Bxf6  Nxf6  14.Nd3⩲  We'll play b4, Ba4 and O-O-O, then probably Kb2 and slowly start pushing forward on the queenside. }
12. a3 { Preparing b4. } 12... fxe4
{ This was Kasparov's choice, since I guess he didn't like the possibility of closing the kingside and then defending passively on the queenside. }
13. Nxe4 { The e4-square is a very nice outpost for the knight. } 13... Nf4 14.
O-O Nc5
{ Exchanging the strong knight on e4.  14...h6?  15.Nxf4  We are giving up our dark-squared bishop for total dominance over the light squares.  15...hxg5  16.Nd3  Bf5  17.Ndf2±  The queenside attack is about to start @@StartBracket@@with Rc1-b4-c5@@EndBracket@@ and we can pick up g5 when we want to. }
15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. Nc3
{ It's bad luck for Black that we have another knight for that square. :@@EndBracket@@ }
