1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... h6
{ This is quite a popular move, but after Black plays later c5 or e5 and their knight lands on c5, it will just transpose to one of those lines in most cases. }
7. Be3 e5
{ Instead,  7...c5  8.d5  is already a transposition tothe 6...c5 7.d5 h6 8.Be3 line. }
8. d5 c6
{ If Black doesn't want to transpose anywhere, this looks like the move to try. }
9. Qd2 cxd5 10. cxd5
{ If Black is going for this early exchange on d5, that usually means that they have some a6-b5 idea in mind. In general, as I stated many times already, I'm not afraid of such plans, since White should always be the favourite if the main battle is going to take place on the queenside. }
10... h5 { A rare moment, where Black plays h5 without our pawn being on h4. }
11. h3
{ We can try to take advantage of it, and change our plans a bit, since h5 in itself makes f5 more difficult and more weakening for Black on account of the g6-pawn and the g5-square having been weakened by this move. }
11... Na6 12. Nf3 Nc5 13. Qc2
{ Instead of f3, we protect the pawn like this and are ready to kick that knight back very soon. }
13... Qc7 { Renewing the Ncxe4 threat. } 14. Rc1 Bd7 15. O-O
{ We are threatening b4 now. } 15... a5 16. Nd2
{ With the idea of playing Qb1, b3, a3 and then b4 with a nice initiative on the queenside.   Note that  16.a3?!  would have been inaccurate and a positional mistake, because of  16...a4!  . }
