{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c5
{ Since,as we saw, 6...e5 is not available for Black, this move is the most popular choice, challenging the centre from the other side. }
7. d5
{ We have to react in the centre.  7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Bd2  Qxc5  can be an interesting alternative, but it leads to something which doesn't really fit well with all the other lines I give in this opening.   7.Nf3  'fails' to  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  and we have a normal Maróczy structure where our bishop on g5 is misplaced and we'll have eventually lose a tempo by bringing it back to e3. }
7... a6
{ Black wants to have an improved version of 7...b5. If we play for example  8.Nf3  here, after  8...b5  we can't use the outpost strategy on b5 because our pawn is on a2 and not on a4.   7...Qa5  has no independent value: at some point, Black will have to play ...e6, and we are going to transpose to those so-called 'half-Benoni' structures.  @@StartBracket@@exd5-exd5@@EndBracket@@  8.Bd2  e6  9.Nf3  exd5  10.exd5  Bg4  11.O-O⩲  and we reach a familiar position. }
8. a4
{ Okay, this shouldn't be unexpected by now :@@EndBracket@@ We don't allow any unnecessary counterplay! }
8... Qa5 9. Bd2
{ Just breaking the pin. 7...a6 shouldn't have any independent value, since Black can insert this move anytime in the 7...h6 or 7...e6 variations, so even if the position doesn't transpose anywhere precisely, the character of the game definitely does. }
9... e6 10. Nf3 exd5 11. exd5
{ We are still saying no to cxd5 and to play a proper Benoni. } 11... Bg4 12.
O-O Qc7 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nbd7 15. Qc2
{ Just normal development from both sides. } 15... Ne8 16. Rae1 Be5
{ I decided to cover this variation because Nakamura played like this once, and our reaction is pretty instructive. }
17. Bd1 Ng7 18. g4
{ Black can't activate their knight, and I wanted to show that even with queens on the board this move is possible for us, since our king is just very safe, and passive pieces are yet to deliver mate in the history of the game. }
18... f5 19. Kg2
{ It is even White who can think about some active operations on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) King's Indian Averbakh System 6...c5"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 7...b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c5
{ Since,as we saw, 6...e5 is not available for Black, this move is the most popular choice, challenging the centre from the other side. }
7. d5
{ We have to react in the centre.  7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Bd2  Qxc5  can be an interesting alternative, but it leads to something which doesn't really fit well with all the other lines I give in this opening.   7.Nf3  'fails' to  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  and we have a normal Maróczy structure where our bishop on g5 is misplaced and we'll have eventually lose a tempo by bringing it back to e3. }
7... b5 { Playing in the style of the Benkő Gambit. } 8. cxb5 a6 9. a4
{ There is a big difference though, compared to a regular Benkő. White's knight is already developed to c3, which means that the a1-rook is protected. Therefore, after an eventual axb5-axb5 exchange our passed pawn will block Black's counterplay on the queenside! }
9... axb5 10. axb5 Rxa1 11. Qxa1 { White is just up a very strong b5-pawn. }
11... Nbd7 12. Nf3 Bb7 13. O-O
{ Next task for White is to coordinate pieces and play strengthening moves. Rd1 is very good both against a potential e6-break from Black and also to protect the d5-pawn when White is ready to push e5.The move h3 is always useful to stop Ng4-Nge5 ideas, and also the bishop can drop back to f4 and h2 to support the e5 break from there. When all these things are done, we can go for typical manoeuvres like Nd2-c4 as well. }
