14. Bxh6
{ If we insist on keeping this bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal by playing  14.Bf4  , then after  14...Qxb2  15.Rc1  unfortunately not everything is the same as alongthe 13...Qxb2 line, because now there is  15...Qf6!  and then Black has a better position, as their bishop can retreat to f5 without trading queens. }
14... Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Qxb2 16. O-O
{ Finishing the development and protecting the a1-rook. } 16... Bc2
{ Black's pieces do make a strange impression, but do a great job of looking back on the diagonals. }
17. Rac1
{ This is a tricky move, because the threat is not Qd2 @@StartBracket@@as Black has a counterattack with Qf6, so they are not going to lose a piece@@EndBracket@@, but the idea is to pin this bishop with Rf2! }
17... Nd7
{ Already two very strong grandmasters, Van Foreest and Amin, played this instantly losing move. }
18. Rf2 { The threat is Bf1 or Bd1, to win the bishop. } 18... Ba4 19. Bd1
{ Black is able to save the bishop, but their defenders from the diagonal are disappearing. }
19... Qa3 20. Bxa4 Qxa4 21. f4 { And Black is helpless against our attack. }
21... Nf6 22. Nf5 gxf5 23. Qg5+ Kh7 24. Rf3 { The checkmate is coming. } *

