{ This is a tricky move, because the threat is not Qd2 @@StartBracket@@as Black has a counterattack with Qf6, so they are not going to lose a piece@@EndBracket@@, but the idea is to pin this bishop with Rf2! }
17... Ba4
{ This move is not good either, since White doesn't have to react on it. } 18.
f4 Qxe2
{ Black should go for  18...Qg7  when exchanging is not an option for us, since we are attacking! After  19.Qg5  Nd7  20.f5  Rae8  21.Rf2→  we are bringing all pieces our into the kingside and Black is facing a dangerous attack. }
19. Nf5 gxf5 { 19...Qb2  would allow a nice mate:  20.Ne7#  1-0 } 20. Rf3 Re8
21. Rg3+ Qg4 22. Rxg4+ fxg4
{ For a moment Black is up on material, but the attack continues. } 23. f5 Nd7
24. f6 Nxf6 25. Qxf6
{ Now already White is up on material, and the attack still continues. :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) King's Indian Averbakh System 6...c5"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 7...e6 8.Qd2 exd5 9.exd5 Qb6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c5
{ Since,as we saw, 6...e5 is not available for Black, this move is the most popular choice, challenging the centre from the other side. }
7. d5
{ We have to react in the centre.  7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Bd2  Qxc5  can be an interesting alternative, but it leads to something which doesn't really fit well with all the other lines I give in this opening.   7.Nf3  'fails' to  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  and we have a normal Maróczy structure where our bishop on g5 is misplaced and we'll have eventually lose a tempo by bringing it back to e3. }
7... e6
{ As we will see, this leads to either a very passive position for Black where they are playing for two results @@StartBracket@@a win is none of them@@EndBracket@@ or Black is very well prepared and goes for a very sharp line. }
8. Qd2
{ Because of this move, 7...e6 can be considered dubious, unless Black is extremely well prepared. Black can't play h6 anymore, and that bishop on g5 is an extremely unpleasant piece. }
8... exd5 9. exd5
{ Exactly like this! Absolutely coherent with our philosophy in this opening, we give Black as little counterplay as possible.   After  9.cxd5  there is  9...Re8  to attack e4 @@StartBracket@@counterplay Nr.1@@EndBracket@@ and on  10.f3  a6  , using the queenside majority. @@StartBracket@@counterplay Nr.2@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Qb6
{ Black has to know a lot here, but if they do, then half a point is deserved :@@EndBracket@@ The planned counterplay is connected with the b2-pawn. }
10. Nf3 Bf5 { With the idea of Ne4 and activating the g7 bishop. } 11. Nh4
{ The concrete fight begins! We can't just play  11.O-O  because after  11...Ne4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  , Black is just doing fine with the very strong bishops. }
11... Ne4
{ 11...Bg4?!  is a mistake: we won't allow Black to exchange pieces and achieve counterplay. Instead, we force the bishop back:  12.f3!  Bc8  13.g4!  Nice restricting and prophylactic move, and absolutely not a weakening one! After this, we can calmly castle short, since Black has zero pieces around our king.  13...Nbd7  14.O-O⩲  Now we can choose among different plans and can play on both sides of the board, but the simplest is probably to go for the b4-break. More importantly, no rush! Black has no active play, and little space, so we have all the time to prepare for the break. }
12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 h6
{ The first concrete move Black absolutely has to know in order to equalise. The idea is to force our queen away from d2, so Qxb2 can come with a tempo and returning via the long-diagonal the queen can protect the kingside very well. }
14. Bxh6
{ If we insist on keeping this bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal by playing  14.Bf4  , then after  14...Qxb2  15.Rc1  unfortunately not everything is the same as alongthe 13...Qxb2 line, because now there is  15...Qf6!  and then Black has a better position, as their bishop can retreat to f5 without trading queens. }
14... Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Qxb2 16. O-O
{ Finishing the development and protecting the a1-rook. } 16... Bc2
{ Black's pieces do make a strange impression, but do a great job of looking back on the diagonals. }
17. Rac1
{ This is a tricky move, because the threat is not Qd2 @@StartBracket@@as Black has a counterattack with Qf6, so they are not going to lose a piece@@EndBracket@@, but the idea is to pin this bishop with Rf2! }
17... Re8 { The only good move for Black! } 18. Rf2
{ This move was only played in 3 games, but I don't really like how the game goes after the more popular  18.Qd2  . Black plays  18...Qf6  counterattacking our knight, and after  19.g3  Ba4  20.f4  Nd7  21.Nf3  Qe7  I didn't find White's position particularly appealing. }
18... Ba4
{ Only move for Black. It's an absolute must to get out of the pin.  18...Qd4?  is losing to  19.Rxc2  Rxe2  20.Rcxe2  Qd1+  21.Rf1  Qxe2  22.Nxg6!+- }
19. Bd3 Qd4
{ This was played in the only game that has reached the position after 19.Bd3. }
20. Bxg6 { This strong 'sacrifice' was missed by White. } 20... fxg6 21. Qxg6+
Qg7
{ Instead,  21...Kf8??  is very bad:  22.Nf5  Qh8  23.Nxd6+-  and Black can hardly survive with such a weak king for a long time. }
22. Qxg7+
{ This is the point. Since the knight is coming to f5 with a check we can pick up one more pawn, so we'll have 3 pawns altogether for the piece. Therefore, it's not a real sacrifice to take on g6. }
22... Kxg7 23. Nf5+ Kf8 24. Nxd6 Re7 25. g4
{ White has a very easy plan here, just push the pawns on the kingside with the support of all pieces, and Black lacks active counterplay despite the extra piece. }
*

