9. dxe6
{ I decided to go for this move and try a different structure since, as I said,  9.Qd2  exd5  10.exd5  Kh7  looks like a significant improvement for Black. }
9... Bxe6 10. Qd2 Qa5
{ The recommendation of GM Gawain Jones in his excellent KID course. On the one hand, this move sets up the same threat as 10...Qb6, coveredhere, so the Qb4 idea is annoying, but we can't reply in the same way as in that line, with Rc1, because then ...a6-b5 is coming. }
11. Bxh6
{ This is the critical test to the variation. Black has to know a lot in order to be fine. }
11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Nxe4
{ This is also a point behind ...Qa5: Black is winning back the pawn because of the pin. }
13. Rc1 Nxc3
{ This is more common than the suggestion of GM Jones, but it leads to a dangerous position for Black. }
14. Rxc3 Qxa2 15. Qc1
{ Unfortunately, the queen has to retreat to protect the b2-pawn, but nevertheless pushing the h-pawn will be very dangerous for Black. }
15... Qa5 16. h4 Kg7
{ Black will have to play ...Rh8 at some point to avoid bigger problems. } 17.
h5 Nc6 18. hxg6 Rh8 { This was Black's defensive idea. } 19. Rxh8 Rxh8 20. gxf7
Bxf7 21. Nh3
{ The position is highly unusual, but I prefer White's chances, since it's clear that the black king is not very safe. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) King's Indian Averbakh System 6...c5"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 7...h6 8.Be3 e6 9.dxe6 dxe6 10.Qd2 Qa5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c5
{ Since,as we saw, 6...e5 is not available for Black, this move is the most popular choice, challenging the centre from the other side. }
7. d5
{ We have to react in the centre.  7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Bd2  Qxc5  can be an interesting alternative, but it leads to something which doesn't really fit well with all the other lines I give in this opening.   7.Nf3  'fails' to  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  and we have a normal Maróczy structure where our bishop on g5 is misplaced and we'll have eventually lose a tempo by bringing it back to e3. }
7... h6 8. Be3 e6
{ An improved version ofthe 7...e6 line. Now Black doesn't have to deal with that very unpleasant bishop on g5, and it's rather a problem for White where to put this bishop if the game went in a similar way. }
9. dxe6
{ I decided to go for this move and try a different structure since, as I said,  9.Qd2  exd5  10.exd5  Kh7  looks like a significant improvement for Black. }
9... Bxe6 10. Qd2 Qa5
{ The recommendation of GM Gawain Jones in his excellent KID course. On the one hand, this move sets up the same threat as 10...Qb6, coveredhere, so the Qb4 idea is annoying, but we can't reply in the same way as in that line, with Rc1, because then ...a6-b5 is coming. }
11. Bxh6
{ This is the critical test to the variation. Black has to know a lot in order to be fine. }
11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Nxe4
{ This is also a point behind ...Qa5: Black is winning back the pawn because of the pin. }
13. Rc1 Nc6 14. Nf3
{ The other tempting option is to play  14.h4  , but the analysis shown by GM Jones is very convincing. Black is doing well there in the complications. }
14... Nxc3
{ Instead,  14...Rfe8?!  is also inaccurate, and after  15.O-O  Nxc3  16.bxc3  Qd8  17.Ng5  , just transposes back to the text move. }
15. bxc3 { Keeping the c6-knight passive, and Ng5 is coming with initiative. }
15... Rfe8 16. Ng5 Qd8 17. O-O
{ Unfortunately, we can't deliver checkmate, but can keep the better chances. }
17... Qf6 18. f4 Qh8
{ Black manages to trade queens, but that doesn't mean full equality. } 19.
Qxh8+ Kxh8 20. Rcd1 Rad8 21. Rfe1 Na5 22. Bf1 Kg7 23. Nxe6+ Rxe6 24. Kf2
{ Neither side's pawn structure is perfect, but the pawns are on both sides of the board, which should favour the bishop. Also, White has a clear way to create a passed pawn on the h-file, while we can't say the same about Black. }
*

