11. Bxh6
{ This is the critical test to the variation. Black has to know a lot in order to be fine. }
11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Nxe4
{ This is also a point behind ...Qa5: Black is winning back the pawn because of the pin. }
13. Rc1 Nc6 14. Nf3
{ The other tempting option is to play  14.h4  , but the analysis shown by GM Jones is very convincing. Black is doing well there in the complications. }
14... Nd4
{ Not very illogical, but still, this is the only good move for Black. } 15.
Bd3 Nf5
{ This is Black's alternative to  15...Nxc3  , but it doesn't provide full equality even though the move is understandable. Black wants to kick the annoying queen out of h6. }
16. Qf4 Nxc3 17. bxc3
{ 17.Rxc3  also gives an advantage according to the engine, but the text move looks simpler. }
17... Rae8
{ Forcing short castle. Instead,  17...Qxa2??  is very bad. After  18.g4!  Ne7  19.O-O  Kg7  20.Ng5!+-  with threats like Ne4, or Nxe6 followed by Qxd6, White has a big advantage. }
18. O-O Kg7 { So the queen will not come back to h6 for sure. } 19. h3 Qd8
{ The most solid move.  19...Qxa2  was not losing anymore, but still pretty risky and after  20.g4  Ne7  21.Ng5  White has a dangerous initiative. }
20. Rcd1
{ White retains the better chances, although the position is still pretty complex. }
