{ This is my suggestion instead of  17.Ng5  , which is analysed by GM Jones as the main line. Black can still hold the draw with precise play, but it can be a very good surprise weapon against the owners of that course. :@@EndBracket@@ }
17... Qxa2
{ The most obvious move. It has to be said though, that Black has another way to make a draw, but it is a typical engine line.  17...b5  18.Bxg6  fxg6  19.Qxg6+  Kf8   @@StartBracket@@  19...Kh8??  would lose to  20.Ng5  Re7  21.Qf6+  Rg7  22.Nxe6  +-@@EndBracket@@  20.Re1  b4!  21.Rb3  Nxb3+  22.axb3  Bxc4!  again only move, but after this White has nothing better than a perpetual check. }
18. Rb1 { Protecting b2 is necessary. } 18... Nb3+ 19. Kc2 Bf5
{ Again the only move! The alternatives are losing pretty easily.  19...Na1+??  20.Rxa1  Qxa1  21.Ng5+-  and Bxg6 is unstoppable. Black is getting checkmated.   19...Nd4+??  20.Nxd4  cxd4  21.Ra3+-  and the queen is trapped!   19...d5  is also losing:  20.Bxg6  fxg6  21.Qxg6+  Kf8  22.Ne5  Ke7   @@StartBracket@@  22...Nd4+  23.Kd2  Nf5  24.Kc1+-  and White is winning with the double threat Ra3 and Qf6+@@EndBracket@@  23.Rxb3+-   @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pp6/4b1Q1/2pp4/2P5/1nR2N2/qPK2PPP/1R6 b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Kh8  22.Qh6+  Kg8  23.Qg5+  Kh8  24.Rxb3+- }
20. Bxf5 Re2+ 21. Kd1 Rae8
{ Instead,  21...Rxb2?  22.Rxb2  Qxb2  23.Bxg6  fxg6  24.Qxg6+  Kh8  25.Qf6  Kg8  26.Qe6+  Kh8  27.Re3+-  is winning for White. }
22. Re3 R2xe3 23. Bxg6 Re1+
{ After this move the game goes on. Black has another move after which the draw is very likely.  23...fxg6  24.Qxg6+  Kh8  25.fxe3  Rxe3  26.Qh6+  Kg8  27.Nd2  Nxd2  28.Qg6+  Kh8  29.Kxd2  Rb3!  and White has nothing better than a perpetual check. }
24. Nxe1 fxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kf8 26. Nf3 Re7 27. h4
{ With a very sharp position, but White should be doing fine with those kingside pawns. }
