[White "22) King's Indian Averbakh System 6...c5"]
[Black "Averbakh system: 7...h6 8.Be3 e6 9.dxe6 dxe6 10.Qd2 Kh7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ We are at the starting position of the King's Indian Defence, a very popular opening at all levels. This opening was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and, among current top players, Teimur Radjabov. Mainly, players with attacking and dynamic style are playing this opening, hoping to get a sharp, imbalanced game. }
5. Be2 O-O
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  e5  8.Qc2  then we find ourselves inthe Old Indian chapter. }
6. Bg5
{ My choice against the so-called 'KID' is the Averbakh system. This is one of the variations against the King's Indian where White is almost never going to face an attack against its own king @@StartBracket@@sometimes rather the opposite happens!@@EndBracket@@, so I feel like this is almost a small psychological victory against our opponent, who is mainly playing this opening to launch a dangerous attack against us.Another thing I like about this system is its flexibility. At this moment, we are two moves away from both short and long castling, hence making it quite difficult for Black to decide where to start their play. }
6... c5
{ Since,as we saw, 6...e5 is not available for Black, this move is the most popular choice, challenging the centre from the other side. }
7. d5
{ We have to react in the centre.  7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Bd2  Qxc5  can be an interesting alternative, but it leads to something which doesn't really fit well with all the other lines I give in this opening.   7.Nf3  'fails' to  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  and we have a normal Maróczy structure where our bishop on g5 is misplaced and we'll have eventually lose a tempo by bringing it back to e3. }
7... h6 8. Be3 e6
{ An improved version ofthe 7...e6 line. Now Black doesn't have to deal with that very unpleasant bishop on g5, and it's rather a problem for White where to put this bishop if the game went in a similar way. }
9. dxe6
{ I decided to go for this move and try a different structure since, as I said,  9.Qd2  exd5  10.exd5  Kh7  looks like a significant improvement for Black. }
9... Bxe6 10. Qd2 Kh7 11. h3 { Preparing Nf3. } 11... Nc6 12. Nf3 Qa5 13. O-O
{ Of course not  13.Qxd6??  since after  13...Nxe4  we are even losing right away. }
13... Rad8 14. Rfd1
{ Since the queen went to a5 instead of e7, we can use our a-rook on the queenside this time. }
14... Rfe8 15. Qc2
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and from now on Black has to be more concerned about the d6-pawn. Taking it with a queen was always risky because of potential tactical issues. }
15... Bc8 16. a3
{ With a better position for White. We can increase the pressure on d6 by playing Bf4, and also b4 is in the air, trying to advance and gain space on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 e5
{ Black is playing in theCzech Benoni way, but we need to be careful. If we play  3.c4  here, then after for example  3...d6  4.e4  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  Black has tricked us. For the knight is much better to stay on g8 here, not in the way of the ...f5 idea.   After  2...Nf6  we can safely play  3.c4  and Black can decide into which opening they want to transpose but we can't be tricked anymore. }
3. Nc3
{ The point of this move is to leave the c4-square empty for now, so the other knight can go there and attack the base of Black's pawn chain, the d6-pawn. Of course, we could have started with  3.e4  and then Nc3 as well, but I like that we seemingly offer Black the option to play ...f5 here. Why not give our opponent an extra chance to go wrong? }
3... d6
{ Instead,  3...f5  4.e4!  and the best Black has is to play  4...d6  and transpose to a bad version of the 3...d6 variation.  4...Nf6  is much worse:  5.exf5!  and we can simply keep our extra pawn.  5...d6  6.g4  h5  7.g5  Ng8  8.Bh3+-  . }
4. e4 f5
{ This move is still very bad. Black is overextending while ignoring their piece development.   4...a6  5.a4  @@StartBracket@@of course, we don't allow Black to gain space on the queenside!@@EndBracket@@  f5  is a somewhat improved version because we don't have Bb5+. Nevertheless, it is still very bad:  6.exf5!  Bxf5  7.Bd3!  Very logical. Black has a lot of weak light squares, so exchanging the main defender of those squares makes a lot of sense.  7...Bxd3  8.Qxd3±  One knight will go to e4, and the other's goal will be the e6-square. }
5. Bb5+ { There is no comfortable way to block this check. } 5... Bd7
{ Instead,  5...Nd7  makes it even easier for us to get a decisive advantage.  6.exf5!  a6  7.Qh5!+  g6  8.fxg6  Bg7  9.gxh7  Kf8  10.Bd3+-  Black is down a few pawns and has a weak king to compensate for it. :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. exf5 Nf6
{ Instead, taking on b5 doesn't help with anything:  6...Bxb5  7.Nxb5  a6  8.Nc3  and Qh5+ is a threat, Ne4 is coming, Nf3-g5-e6 is coming... Black's position is awful. }
7. Nf3 Bxb5 8. Nxb5 Qd7
{ With this double attack Black can take back the pawn, but that's pretty much all the good things we can say about our opponent's position. }
9. c4
{ Cementing the d5-pawn, which is very important if we want a knight on e6! And we do! }
9... a6 10. Nc3 Qxf5 11. Ng5
{ Black's position is on the verge of being completely lost. The knight on e6 will be too much to handle. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 e5
{ Black is playing in theCzech Benoni way, but we need to be careful. If we play  3.c4  here, then after for example  3...d6  4.e4  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  Black has tricked us. For the knight is much better to stay on g8 here, not in the way of the ...f5 idea.   After  2...Nf6  we can safely play  3.c4  and Black can decide into which opening they want to transpose but we can't be tricked anymore. }
3. Nc3
{ The point of this move is to leave the c4-square empty for now, so the other knight can go there and attack the base of Black's pawn chain, the d6-pawn. Of course, we could have started with  3.e4  and then Nc3 as well, but I like that we seemingly offer Black the option to play ...f5 here. Why not give our opponent an extra chance to go wrong? }
3... d6
{ Instead,  3...f5  4.e4!  and the best Black has is to play  4...d6  and transpose to a bad version of the 3...d6 variation.  4...Nf6  is much worse:  5.exf5!  and we can simply keep our extra pawn.  5...d6  6.g4  h5  7.g5  Ng8  8.Bh3+-  . }
4. e4 a6
{ This move is normally connected with the ...Be7-...Bg5 idea, so the main goal here is not to play ...b5 @@StartBracket@@although, if allowed, Black would of course do it@@EndBracket@@, but to prevent the knight from jumping to b5. It will not make a big difference for us, though, since my recommendation will be to play the same way against both  4...a6  and  4...Be7  . }
5. a4 { Of course, we don't allow Black to gain space on the queenside. } 5...
Be7
{ Black's idea is to play ...Bg5 and exchange their bad bishop, which is restricted by Black's central formation. }
6. Nf3
{ For the moment it is not possible: Black will have to exchange their good bishop to be able to do the same with their bad one. }
6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3
{ Eliminating one defender of the g5-square, therefore making ...Bg5 possible. }
8. Qxf3 Bg5 9. Bxg5 Qxg5 10. Qg4
{ I like this move. It forces a better endgame for White, since Black has no choice but to take the queen because of the threat on c8. }
10... Qxg4 11. hxg4
{ A very pleasant endgame. I would even say that we should be happy when Black plays 4...a6 and then we get this endgame, since now the b6-square and also the b7-pawn can be a weakness.Our idea is to transfer the knight to c4, then push a5, bring the rook to b3 and put some pressure on Black on both sides of the board. Once we have improved our pieces to the maximum, we can consider playing g3-f4 as well, to open some diagonals for our bishop. }
*

