{ This move is normally connected with the ...Be7-...Bg5 idea, so the main goal here is not to play ...b5 @@StartBracket@@although, if allowed, Black would, of course, do it@@EndBracket@@, but to prevent the knight from jumping to b5. It will not make a big difference for us, though, since my recommendation will be to play the same way against both  4...a6  and  4...Be7  . }
5. a4 { Of course we don't allow Black to gain space on the queenside. } 5...
g6 { An important move-order subtlety. } 6. Be2
{ We could play  6.h4  now but after  6...h5  we don't have Bb5+, so we have to play a little bit differently here.  6.Nf3  looks inaccurate because Black can stop the knight's way towards c4.  6...Bg4!  and the pin is annoying. }
6... Bg7
{ Black can trade their bad bishop with  6...Bh6  7.Bxh6!  It makes sense now to take right away because we can win a few tempi against the knight.  7...Nxh6  8.Qd2  Ng8  9.h4!  This is a very useful move again! Any time Black wants to play ... f5, they'll ideally recapture with the g-pawn.However, after having played ...h5 that will be very difficult.  9...h5  10.a5  Nf6  11.Nf3  Bg4  12.Nh2!  The position is closed, so of course, we are interested in keeping the knights on the board.  12...Bxe2  13.Qxe2±  The very promising c4-square is waiting for the h2-knight. Nf1-e3-c4 is our plan here. }
7. Nf3 f5
{ Playing this move before ...Nf6 looks logical, but Black can't afford it due to their lack of development. }
8. exf5 gxf5
{ 8...Bxf5  is rarely threatening. White keeps firm control over the light squares and Black will have no attack on the kingside.  9.Nd2  Nf6  10.g4!  Kicking back the bishop and securing control over the light squares.  10...Bc8  11.g5  Ng8  12.Nc4±  White has a very dominant position, with moves like a5, Ne4, or h4-h5 to follow. }
9. Ng5 { This is the problem! Bh5+ is coming with huge power. } 9... Nf6 10.
Bh5+ Ke7 11. Nf7 Qe8
{ This was Black's hope! And now it is a question of who tricked whom! } 12.
Bg5
{ This move secures the bishop on h5 and the knight is ready to unveil a discovered attack on the queen. After  12.Nxh8??  Nxh5-+  Black will collect the knight on h8 with a winning position. }
12... Kd7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxd6 { White is completely winning. } *

