2. d5 e5
{ Black is playing in theCzech Benoni way, but we need to be careful. If we play  3.c4  here, then after for example  3...d6  4.e4  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  Black has tricked us. For the knight is much better to stay on g8 here, not in the way of the ...f5 idea.   After  2...Nf6  we can safely play  3.c4  and Black can decide into which opening they want to transpose but we can't be tricked anymore. }
3. Nc3
{ The point of this move is to leave the c4-square empty for now, so the other knight can go there and attack the base of Black's pawn chain, the d6-pawn. Of course, we could have started with  3.e4  and then Nc3 as well, but I like that we seemingly offer Black the option to play ...f5 here. Why not give our opponent an extra chance to go wrong? }
3... d6
{ Instead,  3...f5  4.e4!  and the best Black has is to play  4...d6  and transpose to a bad version of the 3...d6 variation.  4...Nf6  is much worse:  5.exf5!  and we can simply keep our extra pawn.  5...d6  6.g4  h5  7.g5  Ng8  8.Bh3+-  . }
4. e4 g6 { Black has ...Bh6, but also simply ...Bg7-...Ne7-...O-O ideas. } 5.
h4 { I like this move against ...g6! } 5... h5
{ Black stops h5, but if they want to play with ...f5, now they will have to take into account the weaknesses of the g6 and g5 squares.   5...Bh6?  is too slow. We will be able to create structural problems.  6.Bxh6  Nxh6  7.Qd2  Gaining a tempo on the knight.  7...Ng8  8.h5  Nf6  9.hxg6  fxg6  10.Nf3±  Black has one less central pawn and, more importantly, only White can break the centre now, with the f4 push. Placing the knight on e6, supported by the bishop from c4, looks very tempting too.   If Black tries to prevent the b5-check with  5...a6  then  6.h5!  is more important now than to stop ...b5, and if Black goes for it we will have a good antidote anyways.  6...b5  7.hxg6  fxg6  We managed to open up our h1-rook, and have an extra pawn in the centre.  8.a4!  Black can't maintain the tension on the queenside. We will get the c4-square for our knight.  8...b4  9.Nb1±  With Nb1-d2-c4 coming, combined with a4-a5. Since the queenside is pretty much closed, we can consider castling there, and use the h-file for attacking purposes. }
6. Bb5+
{ A typical move in Benoni structures. Black doesn't really want to exchange their good bishop by playing ...Bd7, and after ...Nd7 their coordination will not be perfect. }
6... Nd7 7. a4
{ This move is almost always automatically played after any Bb5+! We have to anticipate Black's threat ...a6 followed by ...b5. }
7... Bh6 8. Nf3 Bxc1 9. Qxc1
{ Black has managed to exchange their bad bishop, but now we have a clear plan of bringing the knight to c4 and playing f4, attacking the d6 and e5-squares. }
*

