[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...e5 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 e5
{ Black is playing in theCzech Benoni way, but we need to be careful. If we play  3.c4  here, then after for example  3...d6  4.e4  g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  Black has tricked us. For the knight is much better to stay on g8 here, not in the way of the ...f5 idea.   After  2...Nf6  we can safely play  3.c4  and Black can decide into which opening they want to transpose but we can't be tricked anymore. }
3. Nc3
{ The point of this move is to leave the c4-square empty for now, so the other knight can go there and attack the base of Black's pawn chain, the d6-pawn. Of course, we could have started with  3.e4  and then Nc3 as well, but I like that we seemingly offer Black the option to play ...f5 here. Why not give our opponent an extra chance to go wrong? }
3... d6
{ Instead,  3...f5  4.e4!  and the best Black has is to play  4...d6  and transpose to a bad version of the 3...d6 variation.  4...Nf6  is much worse:  5.exf5!  and we can simply keep our extra pawn.  5...d6  6.g4  h5  7.g5  Ng8  8.Bh3+-  . }
4. e4 Be7 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Bg5 8. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ Everything is roughly the same as inthe 4...a6 line.   Here the overwhelming main line for White is  9.Nb5  . Although it leads to a better endgame, I find this far from convincing.  9...Qd8  10.Qg4  Kf8  11.Nxd6  Nf6  12.Qc8  Qxc8  13.Nxc8  Nxe4  14.Bd3  Nd7  15.Bxe4  Rxc8  happened in a lot of games, and Black is worse but very solid. }
9. Qg4
{ My recommendation is to play the same way and go for this endgame which offers more play than the one after  9.Nb5  . }
9... Qxg4 10. hxg4 h6
{ A useful move for Black. We had an annoying pressure on the h-file. Model gameMedvegy-Somlai features  10...f6?  . }
11. a4 { Typical move to gain some space on the queenside and stop ...b5. }
11... Nd7 12. Kd2 Ke7 13. Be2 Ngf6
{ The black knights are struggling in this position, without real good squares available. On the other hand, though, our knight has two great potential squares, c4 and f5. }
14. Rh3 Rhc8 15. a5
{ To bring the knight to f5 looks particularly unpleasant to me. Black can't really kick it out with ...g6 because of the weakness of the h6-pawn, and it will target both the d6- and the g7-pawn. }
