[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 f5
{ The Clarendon Court Defence. Frankly, I didn't know the name of this line before creating this repertoire. Black is mixing Benoni elements with the Dutch opening. }
3. e4
{ A very strong move, just before Black could play ...Nf6 and slow down this idea. We can compare this to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.e4  , already an interesting and very legit variation. If we add to that the pawn on d5, which gives us a space advantage and makes Black development more difficult, it already becomes a very good line. }
3... fxe4 4. Nc3
{ Of course, we will gladly take back the pawn in the next move if Black allows it. }
4... Nf6 5. Nge2 { With the idea of playing Ng3 to take on e4. } 5... g6 6. Ng3
Bg7
{ Black is also developing normally and they are ready to castle in the next move. }
7. h4
{ As we have seen many times before, this move can be extremely efficient against ...g6-...Bg7. Even more so in cases where Black doesn't have the f-pawn, since if they push their h-pawn now, then the g6-pawn will be horribly weak. }
7... d6
{ Castling is very risky:  7...O-O  8.h5  We first open the h-file, since we have time to recapture on e4.  8...d6  9.hxg6  hxg6  10.Ncxe4→  Black's king is in a very big danger. }
8. h5
{ We can still go on with our idea of pushing the h-pawn, without worrying about Black protecting their e4-pawn. }
8... Bf5 9. h6 { Caging the bishop! } 9... Bf8 10. Nxf5 gxf5 11. Be2
{ The position is lost for Black. We even have a really remarkable idea, Bh5-f7-e6 taking Black's central pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 e6 3. c4 exd5
{ If instead  3...d6  , then  4.dxe6  transposing tothe 2...d6 move order, and if  3...Nf6  , then after  4.Nc3  we transpose into some kind of normal Benoni, depending on which line Black wants to play. }
4. cxd5 d6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Black is delaying ...Nf6 but, since transposing back to the Modern Benoni with ...Nf6 is a possibility, we just have to make our usual moves. }
6. Nf3 Bg7 7. Bf4 Ne7
{ Instead of  7...Nf6  and playing the Modern Benoni, Black is developing their knight to e7, where it is not blocking the diagonal of the g7-bishop and sometimes gives the makes a quick ...f5 possible. On the other hand, the knight is much more passive on e7. }
8. Qd2 { Waiting for Black to castle. Then, we can start pushing our h-pawn. }
8... O-O
{ Instead,  8...Bg4  is not helping much. The knight is not pinned, so after  9.Ng5  we have Nge4 threats and can also kick back the bishop at any moment. }
9. h4 h5
{ Forced. A potential h5-hxg6 threat with an attack on the h-file would have been too dangerous for Black. }
10. e4
{ We can see now how bad the knight is on e7: it can't go anywhere, and even as a potential square only c8 comes into consideration, since playing ...f5 would extremely weaken the g5 and g6-squares. }
10... Re8
{ The knight is even blocking the e-file for the rook, so our centre is not under pressure. }
11. Be2 Bg4 12. O-O a6 13. Rae1
{ Our play in the centre will be so fast and strong that we don't even need to play a4 to stop ...b5. }
13... b5 14. Ng5 Bxe2 15. Rxe2
{ With Bg3 and f4-e5 coming, Black is in a very dangerous situation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...d6 & 3...g6 with 6...exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 d6
{ Black is still waiting with ...e6, but we can continue our normal development. }
3. c4 g6
{ Black first wants to put their bishop to g7, and only then move the e-pawn, therefore making our setup against the Benoni impossible. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ In order to keep the option of transposing into a Benoni, we should play  5.Nf3  or the strange-looking  5.Bf4  . But if Black's reply to those moves is  5...Nf6  and then ...O-O, then we can't transpose anyway and especially our bishop on f4 will do nothing. }
5... e6 6. Bd3
{ Of course, I don't want you to learn 2 different systems against the Benoni, so we will take back with the e-pawn no matter when Black takes on d5. In these positions, the bishop is already very useful on d3, since it will prevent the ...Bf5! idea. }
6... exd5 7. exd5
{ Just like this!  7.cxd5  Nf6  would lead to a huge theoretical variation we don't play. }
7... Nf6
{ With an early exchange on d5, placing the knight here is a serious inaccuracy! }
8. Qe2+
{ Black has to exchange queens, and will have a lot of problems to protect the d6-pawn. }
8... Qe7 9. Bf4 Qxe2+ 10. Ngxe2 Ke7 11. Kd2
{ Black is in huge trouble. It is hard to solve the issues with their king and d6-pawn. }
*

