{ In order to keep the option of transposing into a Benoni, we should play  5.Nf3  or the strange-looking  5.Bf4  . But if Black's reply to those moves is  5...Nf6  and then ...O-O, then we can't transpose anyway and especially our bishop on f4 will do nothing. }
5... e6 6. Bd3
{ Of course, I don't want you to learn 2 different systems against the Benoni, so we will take back with the e-pawn no matter when Black takes on d5. In these positions, the bishop is already very useful on d3, since it will prevent the ...Bf5! idea. }
6... Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O { If  7...exd5  , then obviously  8.exd5! } 8. O-O exd5
{ Black's best move. If Black delays this capture one more move, we can play h3! and the c8-bishop will have development problems. }
9. exd5 Bg4
{ 9...Re8?!  is very inaccurate:  10.h3!±  Black can't develop their c8-bishop. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3
{ The position is extremely similar to what we can get in the King's Indian Defence after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.Bg5  c5  7.d5  e6  8.Qd2  exd5  9.exd5  . I would say this present position is a slight improvement for Black, since in the Averbakh we have that very nice Qd2-Bg5 tandem which makes Black's play even more difficult. However, the overall assessment of the position is obviously the same: White has a small but clear advantage. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qd1 { The queen had nothing to do on f3 anyway. } 12... Re8
{ We will follow our main strategy against this move, first neutralising Black's active ideas, then start exchanging heavy pieces to go for the clearly better endgame. }
13. Bd2 a6 14. a4 { No ...b5! } 14... Nh5 15. g3
{ Controlling the f4-square and preparing the g2-square for the king. } 15...
Bd4 16. Kg2 { It was our plan anyway! } 16... Ne5 17. Be2
{ First this knight has to go back, and the other one will follow very soon after we push f4. }
17... Ng7 18. Qc2
{ With Rae1, f4 and then Bd3 to follow, White is getting ready to exchange heavy pieces on the e-file and go for a favourable endgame with only minor pieces on the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...d6 & 3...g6 Black delays ...exd5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 d6
{ Black is still waiting with ...e6, but we can continue our normal development. }
3. c4 g6
{ Black first wants to put their bishop to g7, and only then move the e-pawn, therefore making our setup against the Benoni impossible. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ In order to keep the option of transposing into a Benoni, we should play  5.Nf3  or the strange-looking  5.Bf4  . But if Black's reply to those moves is  5...Nf6  and then ...O-O, then we can't transpose anyway and especially our bishop on f4 will do nothing. }
5... e6 6. Bd3
{ Of course, I don't want you to learn 2 different systems against the Benoni, so we will take back with the e-pawn no matter when Black takes on d5. In these positions, the bishop is already very useful on d3, since it will prevent the ...Bf5! idea. }
6... Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O { If  7...exd5  , then obviously  8.exd5! } 8. O-O exd5
{ Black's best move. If Black delays this capture one more move, we can play h3! and the c8-bishop will have development problems. }
9. exd5 Bg4
{ 9...Re8?!  is very inaccurate:  10.h3!±  Black can't develop their c8-bishop. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3
{ The position is extremely similar to what we can get in the King's Indian Defence after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.Bg5  c5  7.d5  e6  8.Qd2  exd5  9.exd5  . I would say this present position is a slight improvement for Black, since in the Averbakh we have that very nice Qd2-Bg5 tandem which makes Black's play even more difficult. However, the overall assessment of the position is obviously the same: White has a small but clear advantage. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qd1 { The queen had nothing to do on f3 anyway. } 12... Nh5
{ Black's idea is to play ...Qh4, ...Be5 also probably ...f5 and look for counterplay on the kingside @@StartBracket@@This idea, for example, is not possible at all in the Averbakh, because of the pin on the queen@@EndBracket@@.   Black could also start with  12...a6  but, as usual, we reply with  13.a4!  and the position doesn't change much. }
13. Ne4 { And Black is not in time to make the desirable moves. } 13... Be5
{ Black wants to get control over the f4-square. Instead,  13...Ne5?  is also protecting the pawn, but it is much worse, since  14.Be2!  will force the knight back:  14...Nf6  15.Bg5!±  and Black's strategy has completely failed. }
14. f4 { Not allowing Black to place a piece on the f4-square. } 14... Bd4+
{ Morozevich went for  14...f5  against Topalov. You can check the gamehere. }
15. Kh2 Nhf6 16. Nc3
{ Our next goal is to eliminate the d4-bishop, and then our dark-squared bishop can be extremely powerful on the long diagonal, while Black's knights are without targets.   Instead,  16.Nxd6?!  would not be so obvious, since Black can play  16...a6!  blocking out the knight's way towards b5 and after  17.Ne4  Nxe4  18.Bxe4  b5!  their active pieces offer reasonable compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...d6 & 3...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 d6
{ Black is still waiting with ...e6, but we can continue our normal development. }
3. c4 e5
{ A tricky move order. Black wants to play Czech Benoni with the knight on g8 and with our pawn already on c4, so we can't play similarly tothe 2...e5 variation. }
4. dxe6
{ I find this move pretty interesting, and without going to some complex middlegame, where Black already slightly tricked us, we will have some very clear targets and play here. }
4... fxe6 5. Nh3
{ This is a novelty, and a really nice one! We want to put the knight on f4 to attack the e6-pawn and also prevent Black's d5 ideas. }
5... e5
{ Black is stopping our idea, but seriously weakening the light squares in the centre. Instead,  5...Nf6  allows  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nc3⩲  with a pleasant advantage for White. Our next move will be g3 and then Bg2 or Bh3. }
6. Ng5
{ It looks somewhat strange to move the knight again, but it is going to e4 and not for some weird journey. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. g3
{ Bg2-Nge4-O-O and we have a clear advantage because of the weak light squares and backward d6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...d6 & 3...e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 d6
{ Black is still waiting with ...e6, but we can continue our normal development. }
3. c4 e5
{ A tricky move order. Black wants to play Czech Benoni with the knight on g8 and with our pawn already on c4, so we can't play similarly tothe 2...e5 variation. }
4. dxe6
{ I find this move pretty interesting, and without going to some complex middlegame, where Black already slightly tricked us, we will have some very clear targets and play here. }
4... Bxe6 5. e4
{ Black has a structural problem here, the backward d6-pawn, and it is not easy to find enough activity to compensate that weakness. }
5... Nc6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bd3
{ Again we go for this setup. The e2-square is better than f3 for the knight. }
7... Be7
{ Keeping the d6-pawn protected, but the bishop will be very passive here. If instead  7...Ne5?!  then we can just play  8.f4!  since  8...Nxc4  9.f5!  is an extra piece for White. }
8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O a6 10. Nf4
{ Our next moves are b3 and Bb2, simply finishing development, and Black has no real compensation for their backward pawn on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Early Benoni (1.d4 c5 2.d5 Rare Lines)"]
[Black "Early Benoni: 2...d6 & 3...e5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Black would like to play some kind of Benoni. Keeping the knight on g8, they are not giving away which one yet. }
2. d5 d6
{ Black is still waiting with ...e6, but we can continue our normal development. }
3. c4 e5
{ A tricky move order. Black wants to play Czech Benoni with the knight on g8 and with our pawn already on c4, so we can't play similarly tothe 2...e5 variation. }
4. dxe6
{ I find this move pretty interesting, and without going to some complex middlegame, where Black already slightly tricked us, we will have some very clear targets and play here. }
4... Bxe6 5. e4
{ Black has a structural problem here, the backward d6-pawn, and it is not easy to find enough activity to compensate that weakness. }
5... g6
{ The bishop will be certainly more active on g7, but it also means that the pawn will be weaker on d6. }
6. Bd3 Bg7 7. Ne2 { On e2, our knight is closer to the d5-square than on f3. }
7... Nc6 8. Nbc3 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4
{ Both sides have finished the development. We will play Qd2 and Rad1 next and increase our pressure on the d6-pawn. }
