[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Old Indian Defence"]
[Black "Old Indian Defence: 3...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Bf5
{ This is the so-called Janowski variation. Black is stopping e4 for the moment, and wants to keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, but it will be not such a great diagonal when we finish our development and keep a strong pawn on e4. }
4. g3 e5
{ This will most probably transpose to  4...c6  , but there is one independent way for Black to play. }
5. Bg2 Nc6
{ 5...c6  is the most logical, to break the diagonal of the bishop. Indeed, it transposes to 4...c6, but now Black is protecting b7 and also attacking the d4-pawn, so at first sight, it looks tempting. }
6. d5
{ We can invite the knight to d4. We will be able to offer an exchange very quickly, and then this whole activity will lose its power. }
6... Nd4 7. e4 { The only move, but a very good way to prevent Nc2. } 7... Bg4
8. f3 Bd7 9. Nge2
{ And we are already challenging the knight and Black is not in time to cement it in the centre with c5. }
9... c5 10. dxc6
{ Of course! Now there is no time for ...bxc6 and c5, since the knight is hanging on d4. }
10... Nxc6 11. Be3
{ With a nice square on d5 and a weak backward pawn on d6, White is entering the middlegame with a clear advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Old Indian Defence"]
[Black "Old Indian Defence: 3...Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Bf5
{ This is the so-called Janowski variation. Black is stopping e4 for the moment, and wants to keep their bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, but it will be not such a great diagonal when we finish our development and keep a strong pawn on e4. }
4. g3 c6 5. Bg2
{ Since e4 is coming in the next move, Black has to decide now where they want their bishop, on g6 or h7.   After  5...h6  6.e4  Bh7  the bishop is safe on h7; whether it is doing a good job or not is another question.  7.Nge2  Nbd7  8.O-O  e5  Eventually, Black's idea would be to take on d4 and try to put a lot of pressure on our e4-pawn.  9.d5⩲  Next, we'll play f3 and Be3. It seems to me that the bishop on h7 is just out of the game, while we can slowly turn our attention to advancing on the queenside. }
5... e5 6. e4 Bg6
{ Instead,  6...Bg4  does not do so much. We just play  7.Nge2  Be7  8.Be3  with h3 coming very soon, and it is not clear what Black achieved by playing 3...Bf5, except walking into an e4-tempo. }
7. Nge2 Nbd7 8. O-O Be7 9. h3 O-O 10. Be3
{ In this case, when the bishop goes to g6, we don't need to hurry with d5. Since Black's bishop is exposed to f4-f5 ideas, our e4-pawn will never be in danger. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Old Indian Defence"]
[Black "Old Indian Defence: 3...e5 4.Nf3 exd4?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... e5
{ Black is playing the exact same moves as in the Philidor Defence. In an identical position where our pawn is on e4 instead of c4,I suggest you play dxe5-Qxd8 and enter a slightly better endgame.   Here, on the other hand,  4.dxe5  is a serious inaccuracy. After  4...dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  you can see that Black has some presence and advantage in the centre because of the e5-pawn. Later, they can continue with c6, and their pawns are in complete harmony. However, it would be a huge positional mistake for us to play e4 at any point: because our pawn can't go back to c3, we would just create a very weak square on d4. So I would say that in this case 4.dxe5 would even lead to a slightly better endgame for Black! }
4. Nf3
{ Continuing the development and putting pressure on the e5-pawn. Also, in case of exd4, now the knight can take back on d4 and we don't have to bring our queen into the centre so early. }
4... exd4
{ This move gives White a very pleasant game. We did nothing, but already have a nice space advantage in the centre and good squares for all our pieces. }
5. Nxd4 g6 6. g3
{ The bishop will be very strong on the long diagonal, and we don't even have to play e4 at all, since we already have perfect control over the e4-d5 squares. }
6... Bg7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. b3
{ Our other bishop is going to b2, and will neutralise the strong g7-bishop. }
9... Re8 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. Qc2
{ The only important thing to remember here is that we can, but don't have to play e4. I rather suggest not to play it. Look at Black's pieces! They are placed to attack e4, but there is nothing there! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Old Indian Defence"]
[Black "Old Indian Defence: 3...e5 4.Nf3 e4?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... e5
{ Black is playing the exact same moves as in the Philidor Defence. In an identical position where our pawn is on e4 instead of c4,I suggest you play dxe5-Qxd8 and enter a slightly better endgame.   Here, on the other hand,  4.dxe5  is a serious inaccuracy. After  4...dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  you can see that Black has some presence and advantage in the centre because of the e5-pawn. Later, they can continue with c6, and their pawns are in complete harmony. However, it would be a huge positional mistake for us to play e4 at any point: because our pawn can't go back to c3, we would just create a very weak square on d4. So I would say that in this case 4.dxe5 would even lead to a slightly better endgame for Black! }
4. Nf3
{ Continuing the development and putting pressure on the e5-pawn. Also, in case of exd4, now the knight can take back on d4 and we don't have to bring our queen into the centre so early. }
4... e4
{ This move is very ambitious and risky at the same time. Black is occupying more space in the centre, but it will be tough to provide enough backup to this e4-pawn.   Instead,  4...Nbd7  5.e4  would transpose tothe 4...Nbd7 main line, and  4...Nc6  5.d5  would transpose to theMexican defence! }
5. Nd2
{ The pawn is immediately under attack on e4, and its most natural protection d5 is not available. }
5... Qe7
{ This move looks weird, but actually, if the bishop goes to g7, it is completely fine from the development standpoint. }
6. g3
{ A rare move, but a very direct one. We are continuing the development and want to add another piece to attack the e4-pawn. }
6... e3 { This move is not working at all for Black. } 7. fxe3
{ We just play with an extra pawn if our opponent is not reacting very quickly here. }
7... Ng4 { 7...Qxe3  8.Nde4!  would be a nice way to trap the black queen! } 8.
Nf3 { And again we just keep the extra pawn. } 8... Nxe3
{ Since this move is losing even more material for Black. } 9. Bxe3 Qxe3 10.
Nd5 { The double attack on e3 and c7 is decisive. } *

