{ The bishop is not protecting b7 anymore, so we are trying to create some weaknesses on the queenside or the long diagonal. }
6... Nc6
{ Counterattacking on d4. Of course, that pawn is very important for us, so our next move is basically forced.   Instead,  6...Qc8  is not weakening the long diagonal, but the queen abandons the control over the d5-square. Therefore, even if Black plays c6, they can't follow up with d5.  7.g3  The simple Bg2 threat is very hard to face.  c5  8.d5  Be7  9.Bg2  e3  10.fxe3±  Relatively the best way for Black to give up the pawn, closing the diagonal of the g2-bishop as well as having the e5-square, but it is still not enough to have enough compensation for a full pawn. }
7. e3 Rb8 8. g3
{ With the knight on c6, Black doesn't have their standard c6-d5 plan. } 8...
Qd7 9. h3 { Nice prophylaxis. Black wanted to meet  9.Bg2  with  9...Bh3! }
9... h5 10. Bg2 { And Black is about to lose a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Old Indian Defence"]
[Black "Old Indian Defence: 3...Nbd7 & 8...exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Nbd7 4. e4
e5 5. Nf3
{ Developing to the most natural square. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 with the knight at any moment. }
5... g6 { Black chooses to play a King's Indian Defence with ...Nbd7. } 6. Be2
Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ After very natural developing moves, we are at a crossroads now. Many moves and variations are possible for White, of course. Some of them would transpose to big KID lines, which I don't want at all. I'll recommend one system that I believe is quite unpleasant for Black. }
8. Qc2
{ The Qc2-Rd1 setup is a nice way to continue the development. The queen will protect the e4-pawn, while the rook will come to oppose the black queen on the d-file and protect the d4-square. }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8
{ Black already has the Nxe4 threat, because our knight on d4 is hanging. } 10.
Rd1 { Completing our setup. We are defending our centre very nicely. } 10...
Nc5 { More pressure is coming for the e4-pawn. } 11. f3 c6
{ Black wants to stabilise their knight against b4 ideas, but  11...a5  runs into a typical positional concept:  12.Ndb5!  Now ...c6 will never be possible because of the d6-pawn, and otherwise Black's queen is stuck defending the pawn on c7.  12...Bd7  13.Be3  b6  If Black takes, we open the c-file and have the slow but effective plan of playing Rac1 and then b3-a3-b4. As the knight will have to leave c5, we can put pressure on the c-file.  14.b3⩲  .We have much more space, and can greatly improve our position before going for something concrete, whereas Black can only wait. After the text move, that annoying Ndb5 is not happening anymore. }
12. Be3
{ Our bishop is temporarily not protected, so in such cases we have to watch out for tactical tricks, for example ...d5. }
12... Qe7
{ It was easy to refute now  12...d5?  13.cxd5!  cxd5  14.Ndb5!  and both the knight on c5 and the pawn on d5 are hanging. }
13. Bf1
{ We could also play  13.Bf2  , but as long as d5 is basically losing, it is good to allow it. }
13... d5
{ Better is  13...a5  but after  14.Re1⩲  we have a very harmonious position with more space and Black has a weakness on d6. Our next moves are Rad1, Qd2 and then Bf2. }
14. cxd5 cxd5
{ 14...Nxd5  fails to  15.Nxc6!  bxc6  16.Nxd5  cxd5  17.Bxc5+-  and White is up material. }
15. Bg5
{ It is quite easy to blunder this move, and now Nd5 is coming with decisive power! }
