1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Nbd7 4. e4
e5 5. Nf3
{ Developing to the most natural square. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 with the knight at any moment. }
5... Be7
{ Black can insert ...c6 at any moment, but we will just play our usual moves, since sooner or later ...c6 will come and it is just a transposition. }
6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2
{ We play the same setup here as when the bishop goes to g7! We are not rushing with d5 here, since Black put their bishop on the much more passive square e7, but at least it is protecting the d6-pawn. }
8... Re8 9. Rd1 Qc7
{ If instead  9...Bf8  , then we can play  10.d5!  and soon start active operations on the queenside, since Black has wasted a lot of time in not particularly useful moves. }
10. h3 { Preparing Be3, so Ng4 will never be an idea. } 10... Nf8 11. Be3 Ng6
12. b4
{ Once we finished development, we are ready to go forward on the queenside, and have a pleasant game. Let me give you 2 sample lines on how the game can develop.   12...h6  13.d5!  cxd5  14.exd5!  and with a queenside pawn majority we have a very serious initiative on that side of the board. Nb5 and c5 are already coming.   12...a5  13.b5  exd4  14.Nxd4  Nd7  Black managed to get control over the c5-square, but there are other factors in the position.  15.Nf5!  Bf8  16.Qd2!  with strong pressure on the d6-pawn.  16...Re6  17.f4± }
