1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ This is the Old Indian Defence. Black first wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, and only then decide where to put their bishop, on g7 or e7 @@StartBracket@@when it goes to e7, technically that's the Old Indian; if to g7, that's rather a KID@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 { We are getting ready to occupy the centre with e4. } 3... Nbd7 4. e4
e5 5. Nf3
{ Developing to the most natural square. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 with the knight at any moment. }
5... Be7
{ Black can insert ...c6 at any moment, but we will just play our usual moves, since sooner or later ...c6 will come and it is just a transposition. }
6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2
{ We play the same setup here as when the bishop goes to g7! We are not rushing with d5 here, since Black put their bishop on the much more passive square e7, but at least it is protecting the d6-pawn. }
8... a6
{ Black wants to play with ...b5 and keep the position balanced on the queenside, instead of going for some hopeless 'attack' on the kingside.   Black can also start with  8...Qc7  , but then after  9.Rd1  it just depends on their next move.   We could transpose into either the  8...a6  or the  8...Re8  variation. }
9. Rd1 Qc7
{ Black's queen had to move away from the d-file, because dxe5 was already a threat. }
10. h3 { Preparing the development of the c1-bishop to e3. } 10... b5
{ Now ...b4 is a potential threat, so it is better to stop it right away. } 11.
a3 Bb7 12. Be3 Rac8 13. Rac1
{ Both sides are bringing their forces into play. } 13... Qb8
{ Against  13...Rfe8  we have different possibilities. We can play  14.b4  or  14.Qb1  to keep the tension, but I  suggest clarifying the central situation, which already promises us a nice advantage:  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.b4±  With Qb3 and a4 to follow, Black has a very unpleasant position here. Black has one opportunity to make the game sharper, but we have different good reactions to that.  15...c5  16.Qa2  cxb4  17.axb4  Bxb4   @@StartBracket@@If  17...bxc4  18.b5!  is super strong and after  18...a5  19.Na4  we just have a winning position@@EndBracket@@  18.cxb5  Bxc3  19.bxa6  Ba8  20.Ng5!  Rf8  21.Bd2  and we are eventually winning back the piece, with a winning position.   @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/1bqnbppp/p1pp1n2/1p2P3/2P1P3/P1N1BN1P/1PQ1BPP1/2RR2K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nxe5  is no better:  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Nb1!  The knight was restricted on c3 by the c6-pawn, and now it is heading to b3 to target the a5 and c5-squares.  c5  17.Nc3±  A nice trick: once the pawn is not on c6, the knight is actually very strong on c3! }
14. b4
{ With a pleasant edge for White because of the space advantage and the initiative.   For instance, if  14...Rfd8  , then we can play  15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  dxe5  17.c5±   If instead  14...bxc4?!  then we have the very strong  15.dxe5!  dxe5  16.Bxc4  c5  17.Qb3!  with Ng5 to follow and Black has serious problems on the f7-square.   Model gameFriedel-Tarjan features  14...Rfe8  . }
