[White "25) Czech Benoni"]
[Black "Czech Benoni: 5...g6?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... g6
{ Looks very logical at first, already supporting ...f5, but I actually consider this move a serious inaccuracy. }
6. Be2
{ We have the idea of h4-h5! which is very tough to meet without serious strategical concessions. }
6... h5
{ Again very logical. Black is trying to exchange their bad bishop, restricted by their own central pawns. }
7. f4
{ The position is closed, but still, Black played a little bit too slowly with ...g6 and ...h5, so this break works brilliantly for us. }
7... exf4 8. Bxf4
{ We have a nice target on d6. Even after an e5-break, we can have a very strong, protected passed pawn on d5. }
8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Ne8 11. Qd2
{ With h3 and doubling on the f-file to follow. Then, most probably, we will go for e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Czech Benoni"]
[Black "Czech Benoni: 5...g6?! #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... g6
{ Looks very logical at first, already supporting ...f5, but I actually consider this move a serious inaccuracy. }
6. Be2
{ We have the idea of h4-h5! which is very tough to meet without serious strategical concessions. }
6... Bg7 7. h4 h5
{ This move weakens the g5-square, and the other problem is the h5-pawn itself! Since Black would like to play ...f5 at some moment, and ideally take back on f5 with the g-pawn, we can see that it will be extremely difficult now with the weak h5-pawn.   However,  7...h6?!  wouldn't help either. After  8.h5!  , if Black wants to castle now, their next move is forced.  g5  9.g4±  This typical move closes the kingside like in a King's Indian Defence. Then we will play for two results on the other side of the board. Also, please note the difference between the f4 and f5-squares: while we can prepare to put a knight there, by playing Ng3 and Ne3, such options are not available for Black. }
8. Bg5 a6 9. Qd2
{ Normally I like to react to ...a6 with a4, but here the main and basically the only point of Black's position is that it is hard to break. So, if they voluntarily want to give up a pawn and open the queenside, we shouldn't stop that.Also note the difference: compared to the Benkő Gambit, the g7-bishop's diagonal is closed. }
9... Nbd7 10. f3 Nf8 { Black wants to get rid of the annoying bishop on g5. }
11. Nh3 N8h7 12. Be3
{ And we have the g4- and the b4-breaks in this position. Both are possible to play for. We don't rush with castle, since most probably we will not do that at all. Our rooks can help our break from g1 and b1 pretty well. An illustrative game isZaitsev-Shianovsky. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Czech Benoni"]
[Black "Czech Benoni: 6...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... Be7
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  , then we still play  6.Be2  and after  6...Be7  we transpose back to the main line. }
6. Be2
{ I like this move order. It keeps the h4-h5 option alive and also, once the f6-knight goes away, we have the Bg4 idea, exchanging our bad bishop. }
6... Nbd7 7. h4
{ As we have seen in earlier lines, keeping the king in the centre is not so unusual for this opening. Instead, we play h4, which gains some space on the kingside, stops ...Bg5 ideas from Black, and sometimes it can be followed up by g4-g5. }
7... h5
{ Or  7...Nf8  8.g3  Anticipating ...Ng6.  8...h5  9.Bg5±  We will finish the development in the next moves by playing f3-Nh3-Nf2, and then can start playing on the queenside with a3-b4.   We could also reply @@StartFEN@@r1bqkn1r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h5  , but that is rushing things a little bit. Black can play  8...h6  and then create some blockade on the g5-square. }
8. g3 g6 9. Nh3 Kf8 10. f3 Kg7 11. Nf2 a6 12. Be3
{ I believe this is a good moment to stop the trainable line. This setup is ideal for us, with chances to play for g4 or b4. Let me show you a few examples of how the game could continue.   12...Ne8  13.Kf1  Nc7  14.Kg2  b5   @@StartBracket@@ if instead  14...b6  15.Qd2  Rb8  and Black just waits, then we play  16.Rhb1  and b4 in the next move.@@EndBracket@@  15.cxb5  axb5  16.Nxb5  Nxb5  17.Bxb5  g5  18.hxg5  Bxg5  19.f4  exf4  20.gxf4  Bh4  21.a4±  with a pawn up and clearly better position for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Czech Benoni"]
[Black "Czech Benoni: 6...O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... Be7
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  , then we still play  6.Be2  and after  6...Be7  we transpose back to the main line. }
6. Be2
{ I like this move order. It keeps the h4-h5 option alive and also, once the f6-knight goes away, we have the Bg4 idea, exchanging our bad bishop. }
6... O-O 7. Be3
{ We could have started with h4 as well, but since Black can't prevent it anyway, I rather start by developing the bishop. }
7... a6 8. a4
{ We don't have to but, since Black's king is already committed to the kingside, I see our main chances there now. Therefore, closing the queenside makes sense. }
8... Nbd7 9. h4 Ne8 10. g4 { With similar play tothe 7...Nbd7 variation. } *

