[Black "Czech Benoni: 6...O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ The Czech Benoni. In the majority of cases, this opening will lead to some closed positions without any concrete theoretical lines. Therefore, it can be a choice for players who don't want to learn a lot of theory and prefer slower, manoeuvring games. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ Once we reach this central formation, it is clear that both sides have possible breaks with the f- and b-pawns. Of course, it requires a lot of preparation from both sides. Our advantage lies in the fact that the d5-pawn provides us with much more space for this preparation and manoeuvring. }
5... Be7
{ If instead  5...Nbd7  , then we still play  6.Be2  and after  6...Be7  we transpose back to the main line. }
6. Be2
{ I like this move order. It keeps the h4-h5 option alive and also, once the f6-knight goes away, we have the Bg4 idea, exchanging our bad bishop. }
6... O-O 7. Be3
{ We could have started with h4 as well, but since Black can't prevent it anyway, I rather start by developing the bishop. }
7... Ne8
{ With the idea of ...Bg5. Black is also controlling the h4-square with this move. }
8. h4
{ We play it anyway, with the idea of playing g4-g5 and gaining a lot of space on the kingside in case Black doesn't react. }
8... Bxh4 9. Bg4
{ Exchanging our bad bishop for the strong black bishop, and also opening the way for our queen towards the kingside. We don't really mind Black taking that h4-pawn, as we have an open file to use for the attack. }
9... Be7 10. Bxc8 Qxc8 11. Qh5 Nf6 12. Qh2
{ With f3 and g4 to follow. We have a very dangerous attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Snake Benoni"]
[Black "Snake Benoni: 7...Bc7?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 Bd6
{ This is the Snake Benoni, characterised by the strange, snake-like movement of the f8-bishop. It's not without poison @@StartBracket@@wow, what a joke:@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.Black wants to put pressure on our e4-pawn by bringing the bishop to a5. Then, this piece can work much better in combination with the f6-knight than in the Modern Benoni, when the bishop is on g7. }
6. g3
{ This is already a moment where problems are starting for Black. Nobody promised to play with e4... }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Bc7 { This move is very risky and objectively bad. } 8. d6
{ Greatly slowing down Black's development. } 8... Ba5 9. Nh3
{ The knight's dream square is d5, and the route is much faster via h3 than via f3. It is also a nice bonus that the knight is not blocking our e-and f-pawns, since we want to push them very soon. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O Bxc3
{ If the knight goes away from c3, the bishop has absolutely nothing to do on a5. }
11. bxc3 b6 12. e4 { A central pawn storm is coming. } 12... Ba6 13. Re1 Ne5
14. f4 Nd3 15. Re3 Nxc1 16. Rxc1
{ We have a completely winning position with such a centre. } *

