[Black "Snake Benoni: 7...Re8 8.Nf3 a6?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 Bd6
{ This is the Snake Benoni, characterised by the strange, snake-like movement of the f8-bishop. It's not without poison @@StartBracket@@wow, what a joke:@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.Black wants to put pressure on our e4-pawn by bringing the bishop to a5. Then, this piece can work much better in combination with the f6-knight than in the Modern Benoni, when the bishop is on g7. }
6. g3
{ This is already a moment where problems are starting for Black. Nobody promised to play with e4... }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. Nf3 a6
{ Black wants to play ...b5, but it is not really a threat. } 9. O-O b5
{ Instead, on  9...Bf8?!  we can already be very ambitious with  10.d6!  and, for instance, after  10...Re6  11.Bf4  Nh5  12.Ng5  Nxf4  13.gxf4  Rxd6  14.Bd5+-  White has a decisive advantage. }
10. Bg5 { The pin is very unpleasant. } 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. e4
{ Black solved the issue with the pin, but they are very seriously behind in development. }
12... Bc7
{ Instead,  12...b4?  is even worse:  13.Na4  with Nb6 ideas in the air, and Black is just lost. }
13. a4 { Making Black's structure looser before the decisive central break. }
13... b4 14. e5 Bxe5 15. Ne4 Qb6 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. a5
{ Another useful point of including 13.a4. } 17... Qc7 18. d6
{ Black's position is collapsing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Snake Benoni"]
[Black "Snake Benoni: 7...Re8 8.Nf3 Bf8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 Bd6
{ This is the Snake Benoni, characterised by the strange, snake-like movement of the f8-bishop. It's not without poison @@StartBracket@@wow, what a joke:@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.Black wants to put pressure on our e4-pawn by bringing the bishop to a5. Then, this piece can work much better in combination with the f6-knight than in the Modern Benoni, when the bishop is on g7. }
6. g3
{ This is already a moment where problems are starting for Black. Nobody promised to play with e4... }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. Nf3 Bf8
{ The rarest among the 3 main moves for Black, but I believe the best. Of course, the idea of ...Bd6 is not really to bring the bishop back to f8, so I can understand why this move is not so popular. }
9. O-O d6
{ We are basically in the g3 main line of a Modern Benoni, with the big difference that the bishop is on f8 and not on g7. Of course, it is much more passive in this case, but it also has some advantages, as protecting the d6-pawn. }
10. Re1
{ I found this to be the most precise move order. The clear main line is  10.Nd2  , but after  10...Na6  11.Nc4  Rb8  Black wants to play ...b5 and after  12.a4  Nb4  I don't really like the fact that we allowed that knight to b4. }
10... Nbd7 11. a4
{ It is even extremely important now! The knight can't go to b4 anymore, and if we had played  11.e4  , then  11...b5!  and Black has counterplay. }
11... a6 12. e4
{ And our knight will still go to c4, whereas the d7-knight is not going to be on b4, but in a much more passive situation. }
*

