[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Modern Benoni: 7...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The Modern Benoni, an asymmetrical opening. Black willingly takes less space in the centre, but they are building their hopes in active counterplay, which normally can come in 2 different ways: either from the queenside @@StartBracket@@playing for ...b5@@EndBracket@@ or from the centre @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ Instead, Black can also start with  6...a6  , but after  7.a4  g6  8.Bf4  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.e3  we are just transposing to  6...g6  . }
7. Bf4
{ My choice against the Benoni is the line with 7.Bf4. It has two main ideas. Most of the time we don't play e4 at all, therefore preventing one of Black's main sources of counterplay  @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and we are already eyeing the d6-pawn. This way, after the bishop leaves f8 and is not protecting the pawn on d6 anymore, we can do some havoc with Qa4+.Black is at crossroads here. They have two completely different ways to play against the Bf4 system. }
7... a6
{ This move is the most solid option. Black completely stops the Qa4 idea. On the other hand, they will not have the ...Na6-c7 idea, which could be very useful to support the ...b5-break. }
8. a4
{ Preventing ...b5 is a must for us. We can't give Black free play on the queenside. }
8... Bg7 9. h3
{ Since we want to play with e3, we need a retreat square for our bishop in case Black attacks it with a potential ...Nh5. }
9... O-O 10. e3
{ You can clearly see what we want in this variation: fighting against Black's active counterplay, and eventually bringing the knight to c4 to attack d6. There is no ...b5 now, and Black can't attack e4 since it is an empty square, so they have to look for some other kind of counterplay. }
10... Qe7
{ Looks more natural than  10...Ne8  , but eventually the knight will have to move from f6 if Black wants to play with ...Ne5. }
11. Be2 Nbd7 12. O-O Rb8 13. Re1
{ A very useful waiting move. It is clear that if Black is just waiting @@StartBracket@@like they did with ...Rb8@@EndBracket@@ then we will eventually play e4 at some moment. Just in the case that something happens in the centre, for example ...Nh5-...f5-...f4, will the rook be well placed on e1. }
13... Ne8
{ Black is preparing to play ...Ne5 or maybe ...Nc7 and ...b5 as well. } 14. e4
{ There is absolutely zero pressure on our centre, so we can go forward with e4. }
14... Ne5
{ Instead,  14...Nc7  is not really a good idea, since we can just continue with  15.Qd2  . If Black ever decides to go for ...b5, it will only help us, since we will have the open a-file. For example,  15...b5  16.axb5  Nxb5  17.Nxb5  axb5  18.Ra7  and White has a huge advantage. }
15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qd2
{ Our next move will be a5, and then our goal is to play for e5, with or without trading dark-squared bishops. In both cases we are completely fine. }
*

