{ Since we want to play with e3, we need a retreat square for our bishop in case Black attacks it with a potential ...Nh5. }
9... O-O 10. e3
{ You can clearly see what we want in this variation: fighting against Black's active counterplay, and eventually bringing the knight to c4 to attack d6. There is no ...b5 now, and Black can't attack e4 since it is an empty square, so they have to look for some other kind of counterplay. }
10... Ne8
{ Black is defending the d6-pawn with the knight. Therefore, a development with ...Nd7 and even ...Ne5 will be possible thanks to the e8-knight being a very good blockader of the potential passed pawn on d5. }
11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O Ne5
{ Black continues with their idea. This is Serbian GM Aleksandar Indjic's favourite plan. }
13. Bxe5 Bxe5
{ Instead,  13...dxe5  is also possible, but the bishop will not help much in the defence of Black's weakened queenside.  14.a5!  It is important to isolate the c5-pawn and free the a4-square for our knight.  14...Nd6  15.Nd2  f5  16.Nc4  with Na4 to follow. Black has some serious problems to solve. }
14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Ne4
{ Transferring the knight to c4, and attacking the c5-pawn along the way. }
15... b6 16. Nd2 Nd6 { Of course, not  16...Qxd5??  17.Bf3+-  . } 17. Qc2
{ With the positional threat of pushing a5. } 17... a5 18. e4
{ At some point, we will exchange the strong knight on d6 by playing Nc4. Our main break-through idea is to play f4, which can be supported by a rook lift to the kingside via the 3rd rank. }
*

