Ne4
{ So far in every OTB game  14.fxe3  was played, and it is good, but after  14...Qe7  Black can at least prevent our c3-knight from becoming very active.After this new move, however, Black is already facing very concrete problems with the d6-pawn. If the f- and e-files are opening up, that is certainly in our favour, since we are just much better developed, and completely ready for a fight.Since there were no games played from this moment on, let me show you a few possible lines.     @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p4bp/p2p2p1/2pP3n/P3N3/4pN1P/1P2BPPB/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...exf2+  15.Rxf2  Nf4  Black is protecting the d6-pawn, but the knight will be very unstable on f4.  16.Qd2  Bh6  17.Kh1!  The bishop is not protected on h6, so there are no jumps with the knight and our next moves are Raf1 and Nfg5. Black's position is lost according to the engine.   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p4bp/p2p2p1/2pP3n/P3N3/4pN1P/1P2BPPB/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bh6  is a little bit more tricky, but we still have many good options according to the machine.  15.fxe3  Bxe3  16.Kh1  Bf4  protecting the d6-pawn. Black looks safe for a while, but  17.Nfg5!  is extremely strong. The whole black queenside is just watching the game, and that simply has to tell. All the tactics are working out in our favour. For example,  17...Bxh2   @@StartBracket@@  17...Bxg5  18.Bxh5  gxh5  19.Rxf8+  Kxf8  20.Qxh5+-  and even though we are down a piece for the moment, the position is +13, which says quite a lot about Black's king safety@@EndBracket@@  18.Bxh5  Bf4  19.Bg4  Bxg5  20.Nxg5  Rxf1+  21.Qxf1  Qxg5  22.Bxc8  Kg7  23.Re1+- }
