10... Re8 { This move has the ...Ne4 idea behind! } 11. Nd2
{ Very precise! Instead,  11.Be2  would allow  11...Ne4!  12.Nxe4  Rxe4  and Black's rook can even come to b4 and create some counterchances. }
11... Nbd7 12. Be2 Ne5 13. O-O Nfd7
{ Black wants to play with ...f5 and then maybe later ...g5-...f4. } 14. Bg3
{ 14.Bh2  is the main move, but I think the bishop looks more active on g3. Since we don't have to be afraid of ...Nh5 anymore, why not just put it there. We have a nice threat as well: f4 trapping the knight! }
14... f5 15. Ra3
{ A very useful move. The rook steps out of the long diagonal, sometimes playing Rb3 with some pressure on the black queenside or just stopping ...b5. Most importantly, once we start our central play with f4 and then e4, the rook's control over the 3rd rank will really come in handy. }
15... b6 16. f4 Nf7 17. e4
{ With Bd3 and Kh1 to follow. We have a nice initiative here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Modern Benoni: 7...Bg7 8.Qa4+ Nbd7??"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The Modern Benoni, an asymmetrical opening. Black willingly takes less space in the centre, but they are building their hopes in active counterplay, which normally can come in 2 different ways: either from the queenside @@StartBracket@@playing for ...b5@@EndBracket@@ or from the centre @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ Instead, Black can also start with  6...a6  , but after  7.a4  g6  8.Bf4  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.e3  we are just transposing to  6...g6  . }
7. Bf4
{ My choice against the Benoni is the line with 7.Bf4. It has two main ideas. Most of the time we don't play e4 at all, therefore preventing one of Black's main sources of counterplay  @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and we are already eyeing the d6-pawn. This way, after the bishop leaves f8 and is not protecting the pawn on d6 anymore, we can do some havoc with Qa4+.Black is at crossroads here. They have two completely different ways to play against the Bf4 system. }
7... Bg7
{ The much more concrete approach. Black is allowing Qa4+, but here they really have to be booked up not to get into trouble very quickly. }
8. Qa4+ Nbd7
{ Sets up the famous Benoni-trick, but actually White can refute it pretty nicely.   8...Qd7?  is also bad.  9.Bxd6!  Qxa4  10.Nxa4  Ne4  Black was building on this move so they can create some pressure on the diagonal, but it is completely neutralised after our next move.  11.Be5±  and White keeps a healthy extra pawn. }
9. Bxd6 Qb6
{ Looks extremely good for Black. Even ...Qxb2 can come with a double attack. }
10. Qf4 { This move refutes the whole Black's idea. } 10... Qxb2 11. Qe3+ Ne4
{ Black has to sacrifice the knight in order to avoid checkmate. } 12. Qxe4+
Ne5 13. Nd1 Qxa1 14. Nxe5
{ Black is already down material, and will even lose more, but only if they can avoid a quick checkmate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Modern Benoni: 7...Bg7 8.Qa4+ Bd7 9.Qb3 b5! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The Modern Benoni, an asymmetrical opening. Black willingly takes less space in the centre, but they are building their hopes in active counterplay, which normally can come in 2 different ways: either from the queenside @@StartBracket@@playing for ...b5@@EndBracket@@ or from the centre @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ Instead, Black can also start with  6...a6  , but after  7.a4  g6  8.Bf4  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.e3  we are just transposing to  6...g6  . }
7. Bf4
{ My choice against the Benoni is the line with 7.Bf4. It has two main ideas. Most of the time we don't play e4 at all, therefore preventing one of Black's main sources of counterplay  @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and we are already eyeing the d6-pawn. This way, after the bishop leaves f8 and is not protecting the pawn on d6 anymore, we can do some havoc with Qa4+.Black is at crossroads here. They have two completely different ways to play against the Bf4 system. }
7... Bg7
{ The much more concrete approach. Black is allowing Qa4+, but here they really have to be booked up not to get into trouble very quickly. }
8. Qa4+ Bd7 { The only good way to meet this check. } 9. Qb3 b5
{ This is the best move, and according to current theory Black is standing quite well. }
10. Nxb5
{ Since we can't just allow Black to play ...b5 for free, we had two options: my choice, and  10.Bxd6  . The other option is nowadays considered to be White's main try, with many complex and long variations.   The reason I like  10.Nxb5  better is that basically we are forcing Black to make a lot of good/only moves in a row and, even if they do that, it's not that we have to agree to a draw. We can play on in an unbalanced position. }
10... Qa5+
{ This move is extremely tempting, but already wrong, in my opinion. Of course, since the position is extremely sharp, we have to know what we are doing. }
11. Nc3
{ Okay, the first move was easy, the knight was under attack. :@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Nxd5
{ The most common move in the position, but it has a straightforward refutation.   The second most popular move is  11...Ne4?  , but the refutation is still easy:  12.Bd2  just protecting c3 and, even though Black will take our bishop, we will keep our healthy extra pawn.  Nxd2  13.Nxd2  O-O  14.Nc4±  With e3-Be2 and short castle coming very soon, Black doesn't have much time to show any compensation for the missing pawn. }
12. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 13. Nd2 { This move gives us a huge advantage. } 13... Bxd2+
{ Instead,  13...Bxb2  14.Rb1  and Black is going to lose a lot of material. }
14. Bxd2 Qb6 15. Qe4+
{ The final finesse. Black can't block the check with the bishop, since after Qxa8 there will be no more ...Bc6 to trap our queen. }
15... Kd8 16. O-O-O
{ With such a king Black is in a completely lost position. } *

