[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The Modern Benoni, an asymmetrical opening. Black willingly takes less space in the centre, but they are building their hopes in active counterplay, which normally can come in 2 different ways: either from the queenside @@StartBracket@@playing for ...b5@@EndBracket@@ or from the centre @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ Instead, Black can also start with  6...a6  , but after  7.a4  g6  8.Bf4  Bg7  9.h3  O-O  10.e3  we are just transposing to  6...g6  . }
7. Bf4
{ My choice against the Benoni is the line with 7.Bf4. It has two main ideas. Most of the time we don't play e4 at all, therefore preventing one of Black's main sources of counterplay  @@StartBracket@@attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and we are already eyeing the d6-pawn. This way, after the bishop leaves f8 and is not protecting the pawn on d6 anymore, we can do some havoc with Qa4+.Black is at crossroads here. They have two completely different ways to play against the Bf4 system. }
7... Bg7
{ The much more concrete approach. Black is allowing Qa4+, but here they really have to be booked up not to get into trouble very quickly. }
8. Qa4+ Bd7 { The only good way to meet this check. } 9. Qb3 Qc7
{ This is by far the main move and, unless your opponent is up-to-date on current theory, this is the most likely move to face. However it doesn't provide equality for Black. Quite the contrary, they will stand worse in every line after this move. }
10. e4
{ Now we play with e4, since we want a quick Nd2-Nc4 and attack d6. We can't do the same with  10.e3  because of  10...Nh5!   If we play  10.h3  , then the variation with  10...O-O  11.e3  Na6  12.Nd2  Rab8  was not really convincing to me. }
10... O-O 11. Nd2 { Going to c4 to hit the d6-pawn. } 11... Nh5
{ By far the main and best for Black: the bishop was simply too strong on f4. Now Black even opens the way for the f-pawn in order to create some counterplay. }
12. Be3
{ That's why we played e4, to have this square available for the bishop. }
12... f5
{ Black has to hurry, since our next move would have been Be2, and then returning with the other bishop to f4. }
13. exf5 { We have to take: ...f4 was a big threat. } 13... Bxf5
{ This leads to calmer positions than  13...gxf5  and White can keep their advantage with relatively easy moves. }
14. Be2 Nf6 15. Nc4 { With the immediate threat of playing Nb5. } 15... Ne4
{ If instead  15...a6  , then  16.Qb6!  is extremely unpleasant. } 16. O-O Nxc3
17. bxc3 Nd7 18. Bf4
{ Our bishop was not doing much on e3, but now it returns to the 'correct' diagonal with tempo. }
18... Rf6 19. Bg3
{ Nice prophylaxis, so we will never blunder some ...Bc2 trick, which would be a very unfortunate trade of bishops for us. }
19... Nb6 20. Ne3
{ With a4-a5 next, and our knight returning to c4, keeping a nice advantage. You can check the gameChatalbashev-Cvitan in the Model Games section to see how play can go on. }
