[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Black "Accelerated QID: 3...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... e6
{ Surprisingly quite a common position, more often reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  b6  order, but just very bad, as Black is allowing us to occupy the centre. }
4. e4 Bb4
{ It's even worse for Black starting with this move instead of Bb7, since now the g7-square is going to be vulnerable. }
5. e5 Ne4 6. Qg4 Nxc3 7. a3 { The key move of the Qg4 idea! } 7... Bf8
{ Instead,  7...Na2  doesn't help either, since after  8.axb4  Nxc1  we still have the intermediate  9.Qxg7!  Rf8  10.Rxc1±  . }
8. Bg5 { And White is just winning a pawn. } 8... Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qxg7
{ This is the key move for White! } 10... Rf8 11. bxc3
{ White has an extra pawn for no compensation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Black "Accelerated QID: 3...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... e6
{ Surprisingly quite a common position, more often reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  b6  order, but just very bad, as Black is allowing us to occupy the centre. }
4. e4 Bb7 5. Bd3 Bb4 6. Qc2 c5
{ Black can slightly ruin our pawn structure with  6...Bxc3+  , but that does nothing about White's central dominance.  7.bxc3  d6  8.f4±  and White's central control offers us a clear advantage. }
7. d5 b5
{ Black has to challenge the centre and somehow activate the b7-bishop. } 8.
Ne2
{ Simply continuing the development. Because of tactical reasons, nothing is hanging in the centre. }
8... exd5 9. exd5 bxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O
{ Instead,  10...Bxd5??  just drops a piece because of  11.Bxd5  Nxd5  12.Qe4+   On  10...Nxd5  we have  11.Qb3!  Bxc3+  12.bxc3  and once the knight moves, we take on f7 with a much better position.  11.Qe4+  is not so good because Black has  11...Qe7!  and thanks to the X-ray they are not losing a piece. }
11. O-O d6 12. Bg5
{ White is clearly better here. We have seen similar positions in the Benkő Gambit. The pin on the h4-d8 diagonal is very unpleasant and we can develop a dangerous initiative by playing Ne4 and Ne2-g3-f5 and attack the d6-pawn, using the fact that the b4-bishop is completely out of the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Black "Accelerated QID: 3...Bb7 4.d5 e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... Bb7 4. d5
{ We close the b7-bishop, and don't allow Black to transpose into a Queen's Indian with moves such as  4.Nf3  . }
4... e5
{ This move looks very dubious to me. Black is absolutely not addressing the bad position of the b7-bishop, and this move guarantees White a space advantage for the rest of the game. }
5. a3
{ We stop Black's only idea when playing ...e5, to develop the bishop to b4. }
5... a5 6. Nf3 d6
{ Basically, we have a King's Indian type of position here, where Black has completely misplaced their bishop on b7. Also, instead of doing something on the kingside, they played a5 and b6, giving us hooks to speed up our queenside play. }
7. e4 g6 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5
{ A typical idea. The bishop is annoying for Black and, once they play h6, we go back to d2 and then play g3 at some point, preparing to meet Black's f5 push with Nh4. Thanks to having provoked the h6 push, the g6-square will be weak in those lines. }
10... h6 11. Bd2
{ Our next move is b4 and then we are preparing to play c5. If Black's knight moves away from f6, then we can always play g3 intending Nh4 in case Black is playing with ...f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Black "Accelerated QID: 3...Bb7 4.d5 c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... Bb7 4. d5
{ We close the b7-bishop, and don't allow Black to transpose into a Queen's Indian with moves such as  4.Nf3  . }
4... c6 { Black is trying to open the long diagonal for their bishop. } 5. e4
{ We really want to keep that pawn on d5! } 5... cxd5 6. cxd5 e6
{ Again attacking the d5-square but, more importantly, opening the way to b4 for the bishop. }
7. a3 { We stop the Bb4 idea, further solidifying our centre. } 7... exd5 8.
exd5 Bd6 9. g3
{ I like this move. The bishop will also help with the protection of the d5-pawn, and our knight will go to e2. Then, in case Black is playing Be5 at some point, we can simply replace our very important piece on c3. }
9... O-O 10. Bg2 Re8+
{ Doesn't really disturb our development, since the knight was going to e2 anyway. }
11. Nge2 Na6 12. Nb5 { Forcing the bishop to an awkward square. } 12... Bb8 13.
O-O
{ Black's bishops give a strange impression, and White keeps a nice advantage with the strong d5-pawn. }
