[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence"]
[Black "Accelerated QID: 3...Bb7 4.d5 e6 5.a3 exd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6
{ This is the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defence. Instead of playing the normal  2...e6  3.Nf3  b6  reaching the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence, Black is playing b6 already on the second move.   The idea of this move order is twofold. Firstly, Black wants to play a Queen's Indian without allowing White to decide whether they want to play a Nimzo-Indian Defence with  3.Nc3  , a Queen's Indian Defence with  3.Nf3  or a Catalan with  3.g3  .   Secondly, this move order is very provocative, so it is very tempting for White to punish it, let's say, by playing  3.f3  . Then, Black is aiming for tricky and non-standard positions. }
3. Nc3
{ For now, we play as if nothing happened. With my repertoire we want to play against the Nimzo, so obviously our choice is not going to be  3.Nf3  or  3.g3  . }
3... Bb7 4. d5
{ We close the b7-bishop, and don't allow Black to transpose into a Queen's Indian with moves such as  4.Nf3  . }
4... e6
{ The most logical move for Black, attacking the centre and opening up the f8-bishop.   4...g6?  fails to react to the central situation and just enters a very bad version of the King's Indian Defence.  5.e4  Bg7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Be2  We simply develop and keep our advantage. There is no reason to go into any kind of messy play by pushing e5 so early. Black would welcome any kind of small chaos on the board.  e6  8.O-O  exd5  9.exd5⩲  With a nice plus for White, because of the bad bishop on b7 and the space advantage. }
5. a3 { Of course! We don't want that bishop on b4 pinning our knight. } 5...
exd5 6. cxd5 Bd6
{ 6...Bc5?!  The bishop is completely misplaced here. We should just avoid playing e4 too quickly. That would weaken the g1-a7 diagonal, plus offer a target for the rook once it goes to e8.  7.g3!  O-O  8.Bg2  Re8  9.Nf3  a5  Preventing b4, but once again we don't mind the bishop staying on c5. It puts absolutely no pressure on our centre.  10.O-O±  We can play b3-Bb2, then probably Nh4 to target the f5-square, and later start pushing the e- and f-pawns. }
7. Nf3 { Not allowing the bishop to e5! } 7... O-O 8. g3 Na6
{ Bringing the knight to e4 will not provide equality for Black, since the bishop on b7 will still be very bad. }
9. Bg2
{ Instead,  9.b4  looks very logical, to prevent Nc5. The problem is that we are behind in development and Black can already start active counterplay with  9...c5! }
9... Nc5 10. O-O Re8 11. b4 Nce4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bb2
{ The contrast between the bishops and the Nh4-f5 idea give White a pleasant position. }
*

