[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Budapest Gambit"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit: 3...Ne4 4.a3 Qh4?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ne4
{ This is the Fajarowicz variation. As we'll see, it's dubious but tricky. TheBudapest main lines occur after  3...Ng4  , a much better square for the knight, where it immediately attacks the e5-pawn. }
4. a3
{ A very useful move, we take away the most threatening move which is in conjunction with the knight on e4. }
4... Qh4
{ Black is not joking; our opponent wants to finish the game as early as move 5! }
5. g3 { Preventing the mate with a tempo! } 5... Qh5 6. Bg2
{ Second developing move with a tempo! } 6... Qxe5 7. Nf3
{ And the third one! } 7... Qa5+ 8. Nbd2
{ Black managed to take back the pawn. However, it's not very principled to make 4 queen moves out of the first 7. With very simple moves to follow, White will have a huge lead in the development and a nice initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Budapest Gambit"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit: 3...Ne4 4.a3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ne4
{ This is the Fajarowicz variation. As we'll see, it's dubious but tricky. TheBudapest main lines occur after  3...Ng4  , a much better square for the knight, where it immediately attacks the e5-pawn. }
4. a3
{ A very useful move, we take away the most threatening move which is in conjunction with the knight on e4. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 d6
{ Since it was clear that Black can't take back the pawn on e5 anymore because White has many other moves to protect it, like Bf4 or Qd5, Black decides to go for quick development, trying to compensate the missing pawn that way. }
6. Qc2
{ The main problem of the Fajarowicz variation is again on display: Black's e4-knight is not stable, and it's not easy to protect. }
6... Bf5 { Black is developing and creating threats! } 7. Nc3
{ We can ignore all those threats, since the bishop on f5 is also unprotected. }
7... Ng3
{ Now the bishop is protected and the rook is attacked by knight at the same time, so it looks good for Black, but White has a very strong response. }
8. e4 { Now Black has 2 pieces hanging at the same time. } 8... Nxh1 9. exf5
{ Usual problems for Black: the knight is not coming back from h1. } 9... dxe5
10. Be3 Nd4 { Model gameMeister-Roth features  10...Be7  . } 11. Qe4
{ Black's position is falling apart. } *

