6. Qc2
{ The main problem of the Fajarowicz variation is again on display: Black's e4-knight is not stable, and it's not easy to protect. }
6... Nc5
{ If you are playing a gambit and you have to go backwards very quickly, usually that is not a very encouraging sign. }
7. b4 Ne6 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Bb2
{ For now we have a healthy extra pawn. Black has only one potential chance of counterplay left, and that is the a5 move. }
9... O-O 10. e3 a5 11. c5
{ I like this active approach here! Of course,  11.b5  Nb8  12.Be2  is also better for White, but after  12...Nd7  (Black can at least claim some sort of compensation because of their very strong grip on the c5-square.) }
11... Be7 12. b5 Nb8 13. Nc3
{ We are giving back the material, but in return we get a nice square on c4 for our bishop, and we also gain the initiative. }
13... Nxc5 14. Rd1 Nbd7 15. h4
{ With Bc4 next and Ng5 is going to be a huge threat very soon. } *

