[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ne4
{ This is the Fajarowicz variation. As we'll see, it's dubious but tricky. TheBudapest main lines occur after  3...Ng4  , a much better square for the knight, where it immediately attacks the e5-pawn. }
4. a3
{ A very useful move, we take away the most threatening move which is in conjunction with the knight on e4. }
4... b6 { This is the so-called Fajarowicz trick. } 5. g3
{ The easiest way to neutralise the potential pressure on the long diagonal if we also fianchetto our bishop. }
5... Bb7 6. Nf3
{ Precisely! There is one more trick to avoid:  6.Bg2  would lose the game on the spot to  6...Nc3!  attacking the queen and subsequently winning the bishop on g2 and the rook on h1. }
6... Bc5 7. e3 a5
{ Black has to play a5 pretty quickly. Otherwise, the bishop can be kicked by b4. }
8. Bg2 Qe7 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nfd2
{ The g2 bishop will very nicely control the long diagonal now. } 10... Nxd2
11. Bxd2 Qxe5 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Nd5
{ Bc3 is coming next and then we can slowly start pushing our central pawns but, if Black is not careful, b4 will be an option too. }
*

