5. Qc2 { First we are kicking that knight away from the centre. } 5... d5
{ 5...Bf5  is working as badly as inthe 4...Nc6 lines.  6.Nc3!  Ng3  7.e4!  Our typical reaction when the bishop is defended!  Bxe4  8.Nxe4  Nxh1  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nf3+-  White will finish the development and then take the knight with a dominating position and extra material. }
6. Nf3 Bf5 { Instead,  6...Nc6  7.e3  is transposing to 4...Nc6. } 7. cxd5 Qxd5
8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. Qxc3
{ The queen is out from any potential discovered attacks, and is also protecting e5. }
9... Nc6 10. Bf4 O-O-O 11. e3 Be7
{ Black's idea is to decoy our minor pieces and to take with the knight on e5, but we can stop it. }
12. Rc1
{ The knight has to cover c7. Bc4 and O-O are coming next for White, with a clear advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Budapest Gambit"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit: 3...Ne4 4.a3 d6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ne4
{ This is the Fajarowicz variation. As we'll see, it's dubious but tricky. TheBudapest main lines occur after  3...Ng4  , a much better square for the knight, where it immediately attacks the e5-pawn. }
4. a3
{ A very useful move, we take away the most threatening move which is in conjunction with the knight on e4. }
4... d6
{ In some of the lines the play will be very similar to the one we could see after  4...Nc6  , but Black can also play without that move, so d6 has some independent significance. }
5. Qc2 { First we are kicking that knight away from the centre. } 5... Nc5 6.
exd6 Bxd6
{ Here one of the main, and I believe the most dangerous idea for Black, is to play Qf6 and Bf5. Hence my next move. }
7. Nc3
{ Besides this move, I analysed both  7.b4  and  7.Nf3  too, and I have to say that objectively speaking both lead to an advantage for White, but some precision is needed: the arising positions are mainly only clear for the computer. The point of my choice is to meet the Qf6-Bf5 idea with e4. }
7... Qf6 8. e4 Nc6
{ Very logical. The problem with the  e4  move is that it weakens the d4-square.  8...O-O  will transpose back to the current line after  9.Be3  Nc6  . }
9. Be3
{ We cover it with the bishop, since  9.Nf3  Bg4  could have been unpleasant. }
9... Nd4 10. Bxd4 Qxd4
{ It may seem like that the weakness of our dark squares, combined with the exchange of the e3-bishop, may provide some compensation for Black. While this could be positionally true, White is coming now with the initiative, which will completely change the character of the position. }
11. Rd1 Qf6 12. b4 { We are pushing our opponent back move by move. } 12... Ne6
13. c5 Be5 14. Nd5 { Every move we go forward and with a tempo! } 14... Qg6 15.
Nf3 Bf6 16. Be2
{ Our position has improved significantly in the last few moves, while Black was just going backwards. Therefore, it's not a surprise that the position works out in White's favour even after giving back the pawn. }
16... Qxg2 17. Rg1 Qh3 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Qc1
{ With Rg3 and Rd5 threatening to trap the queen, the game is over. } *

