3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ne4
{ This is the Fajarowicz variation. As we'll see, it's dubious but tricky. TheBudapest main lines occur after  3...Ng4  , a much better square for the knight, where it immediately attacks the e5-pawn. }
4. a3
{ A very useful move, we take away the most threatening move which is in conjunction with the knight on e4. }
4... d6
{ In some of the lines the play will be very similar to the one we could see after  4...Nc6  , but Black can also play without that move, so d6 has some independent significance. }
5. Qc2 { First we are kicking that knight away from the centre. } 5... Nc5 6.
exd6 Bxd6
