[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is reinforcing the idea of ...Nxe5, but this move is already a serious inaccuracy, since Black is doing this before closing the c1-h6 diagonal for our bishop. }
5. Bg5
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop before it could be closed by ...Bc5 @@StartBracket@@we should reply with e3 to that@@EndBracket@@ is already a nice achievement. Here it comes with the bonus that after the exchange on e7 we will be able to play Nc3-d5 with a tempo. }
5... Be7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Nc3
{ With the idea of Nd5, and Black is already in serious trouble. } 7... Ncxe5
{ Black is freeing the way for the c-pawn, planning to meet  8.Nd5  with  8...Qd6  and then ...c6, so now we wait for a move. Once Black plays ...d6, then we are going for Nd5. }
8. Qd4
{ The queen is not only nicely centralised here, but also helping with the  8...--  9.Nd5  Qd6  10.c5!  idea. }
8... d6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. h3
{ Forcing ...Nxf3 and the opening of the g-file, since if Black is not taking, they are just losing a pawn on e5. }
10... Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 Nf6 12. Rg1
{ Black is in great trouble. Probably their best move is ...Kf8, but that means we are doing very well. }
