[Black "Budapest Gambit: 3...Ng4 4.Nf3 sidelines #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Bb4+ { A pretty bad move. Black is just helping our development. } 5. Bd2
Qe7
{ Instead,  5...Bxd2+  is worse:  6.Qxd2  Nc6  7.Nc3  Ngxe5  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Qe3!  Qe7  10.Nd5+-   Or, if  6.Qxd2  Qe7  , then  7.Nc3  Nxe5  8.Nd5!  Nxf3+  9.gxf3  Qd8  10.Rg1+-  . }
6. Nc3 { The knight is going towards d5. } 6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5
{ This is an important move. Even though we are not afraid of Nxf3+ because of gxf3,  7.Nd5??  Nd3#  would be unpleasant! }
7... Qxe5 8. a3
{ The computer already points a huge advantage for White: the bishop simply doesn't have a good square to retreat to. }
8... Bc5
{ 8...Bd6  Looks very strange, and indeed White has different ways to achieve a big advantage. For example,  9.e4!  Nc6  10.Bd3  O-O  11.f4  Qd4  12.Qe2+-  with O-O-O and e5 to follow. White is much better and Black's pieces are very badly placed. }
9. Nd5
{ With the idea of playing Bc3 or Bf4 in the next move and targeting the weak c7-square. }
9... O-O 10. Bc3 Qf5
{ Black is protecting c7 by creating a counterthreat on f2. } 11. e3 Bd6
{ An awkward move, but it was not easy to defend on c7. } 12. Bd3
{ Developing with a tempo and the black king is already in danger since it doesn't really have defenders, while White's minor pieces are very active. }
12... Qe6 13. Nf6+ { A nice idea and White is winning a lot of material. }
13... gxf6 14. Qh5 Re8
{ Black is preparing the way for their king to run, but the point of Nf6+ is coming now. }
15. Qh6
{ The king can't go anywhere, and the threat of Bxh7+ and then Bf5 discovered check winning the queen is unstoppable. }
