{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... d6
{ Black is trying to play in a gambit style, but it is simply not working. I was very surprised to see the popularity of this move in online blitz and rapid games. }
