[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Bc5
{ By far the best move for Black, forcing e3 and with that closing the diagonal for our c1-bishop. }
5. e3 { Again, Black has to do something: h3 is a threat. } 5... Nc6
{ This natural developing move is the main line. Black is ready to recapture on e5. }
6. Nc3
{ The second most popular move in the position, the first one being  6.Be2  . My recommendation involves a small trick which is very easy to fall into. }
6... Ngxe5
{ The most common and most logical move in the position. Black was ready to take on e5, so why wait? Here comes the point of starting with 6.Nc3 instead of 6.Be2: placing the bishop on the more active square d3 makes a pretty big difference! }
7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. f4
{ Preparing the d3-square for the bishop, but it is also very important that the knight can only go to g6 or c6. When we are building the centre with pawns on e4 and f4, Black's knight would be much better placed on c5 or f6, attacking our e4-pawn. Our opponent would have that chance if we waited for them to play ...d6 and then retreat to d7. }
8... Nc6 9. Bd3 d6
{ Black had to be careful:  9...O-O  10.Qh5!  is a double attack on the bishop and on the h7-pawn!  10...f5  11.Bxf5  g6  12.Bxg6  hxg6  13.Qxg6+  Kh8  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Qxc5+-  . }
10. O-O O-O 11. a3
{ A very useful move. We are threatening to gain space on the queenside, stopping Nb4 ideas. Also, if later in the game we attack the c7-pawn with the knight, Bb6 will not be possible, since Black can't recapture with the a-pawn in that case. }
11... a5 12. Kh1 { White is ready to push e4 at any moment now. } 12... Re8
{ Model gameJambrich-Gray features  12...Bd7  . } 13. Qh5
{ The queen is going to f3, but before that it is creating some weak squares around the black king. }
13... g6 14. Qf3
{ Our next moves are Bd2 and Rae1, and eventually we want to play e4. However, we are not in a hurry, since it is not clear what Black should do with their c6-knight and c8-bishop or, in general, with their position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Budapest Gambit"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit: 4...Bc5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Bc5
{ By far the best move for Black, forcing e3 and with that closing the diagonal for our c1-bishop. }
5. e3 { Again, Black has to do something: h3 is a threat. } 5... Nc6
{ This natural developing move is the main line. Black is ready to recapture on e5. }
6. Nc3
{ The second most popular move in the position, the first one being  6.Be2  . My recommendation involves a small trick which is very easy to fall into. }
6... Ngxe5
{ The most common and most logical move in the position. Black was ready to take on e5, so why wait? Here comes the point of starting with 6.Nc3 instead of 6.Be2: placing the bishop on the more active square d3 makes a pretty big difference! }
7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. f4
{ Preparing the d3-square for the bishop, but it is also very important that the knight can only go to g6 or c6. When we are building the centre with pawns on e4 and f4, Black's knight would be much better placed on c5 or f6, attacking our e4-pawn. Our opponent would have that chance if we waited for them to play ...d6 and then retreat to d7. }
8... Ng6
{ This square is more passive than c6. On the other hand, at least the knight will not allow us to force weakening moves around the king. }
9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O d6 11. Kh1
{ It is always useful to step out of the diagonal. } 11... f5
{ With this move Black is saying that they are not going to allow e4 for free. However, even after a central exchange, our pieces will be much more active. }
12. Bd2 a6
{ Black doesn't really have any active ideas, so the best they can do is to make some useful waiting moves. }
13. Qc2 { Eyeing the f5-pawn, and thus keeping the rook passive on f8. } 13...
Bd7 14. Rae1 Kh8 15. e4
{ White has mobilised its forces, so now we go for e4. This guarantees a nice initiative which can lead very quickly to an attack against the black king. }
