[Black "Budapest Gambit: 4...Bc5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The starting position of the Budapest Gambit. Black is sacrificing a pawn temporarily, but aims for quick piece development. Eventually, Black wants to take back the pawn on e5 or continue playing down a pawn but create immediate and dangerous threats. Of course, this will also depend on White's approach: some of the lines are just not giving Black chances to do much trickery. }
3. dxe5 { The only test of a gambit is if we accept it right away. } 3... Ng4
{ Black is immediately attacking the e5-pawn and the knight is in a much better place here than on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing and protecting the pawn on e5, while also introducing the h3-threat to the position, since Black's knight obviously doesn't want to go back to h6.   The other main move in the position is  4.Bf4  , the so-called Rubinstein variation, which is also a good line for White but it gives Black chances to continue in gambit style with  4...g5!?  or  4...f6  5.exf6  Qxf6  attacking both f4 and b2. }
4... Bc5
{ By far the best move for Black, forcing e3 and with that closing the diagonal for our c1-bishop. }
5. e3 { Again, Black has to do something: h3 is a threat. } 5... Nc6
{ This natural developing move is the main line. Black is ready to recapture on e5. }
6. Nc3
{ The second most popular move in the position, the first one being  6.Be2  . My recommendation involves a small trick which is very easy to fall into. }
6... O-O
{ Waiting with the recapture on e5 is the best in my opinion.   If we now play  7.Be2  @@StartBracket@@which is the main move here as well@@EndBracket@@ then Black has managed to avoid those immediate f4-Bd3 ideas. }
7. a3
{ On the one hand, the idea of the move is very obvious: we want to play b4 and Bb2 while also forcing Black's bishop to a more passive square. The other point of the move, though, is connected with a very rare idea, where stopping ...Bb4+ is crucial. }
7... Ngxe5 8. b4 Be7
{ Obviously, it is not a great development for Black to be forced to go back with their bishop to a passive square. }
9. Bb2 d6 10. Be2 Re8
{ Black is waiting with the decision to take on f3 or not.   Instead,  10...Nxf3?!  11.gxf3±  would give White a strong attack on the g-file.   In case of  10...Be6  11.Nd2!±  Black's minor pieces are stuck and we will just play with O-O next. We'd have a clearly better position with a space advantage. }
11. Nd2
{ A very strong move! We don't want to make Black's task easier by playing  11.O-O  and allowing  11...Nxf3+  , since now obviously taking back with the g-pawn is not so appealing. Otherwise, Black has managed to exchange a pair of minor pieces, which is always some achievement for the side with much less space. }
11... Bf8 12. O-O
{ The knights are in each other's way, and the f8-bishop is also very passive. }
12... a5 13. b5 Ne7 14. e4
{ With f4-Kh1 coming, White has a clear advantage thanks to our large space superiority. }
