Ba3 { One more pin is coming into the position! } 11... Qe7
{ Even though this square is obviously not comfortable for the queen, at least it offers some tactical counterchances: once the bishop moves from a7, playing for a Nc2+ idea and taking the bishop on a3 would greatly improve Black's position. }
12. Be2
{ Continuing the development and preparing for short castle, so the previously mentioned knight jump will not come with check. }
12... Bb8
{ Looks very strange, but the bishop is not pinned anymore on the a-file. If Black could play ...c5 next, getting rid of the pin on the queen as well, then their position would be quite acceptable.   12...Bb6  simply leads to a much better position for White after  13.O-O  Rxa3  14.Rxa3  and Black's b4-knight  doesn't have any good jump:  14...Nxe5  15.Ra8!+-   12...Bxe3  leads to some tactical fight where we'll end up with an extra piece after  13.fxe3  Nxe3  14.Qb3  Nbc2+  15.Kd2  Rxa3  16.Rxa3  Nxc4+  17.Qxc4  Nxa3  18.Qxc7+-  . }
13. Bxb4 { A very surprising move, taking the pinned knight. } 13... Qxb4+ 14.
Nfd2
{ The point of the previous move. We take advantage of Black's very poor coordination. }
14... Rxa1 15. Qxa1
{ The knight is hanging on g4 and with Qxa1 we have just protected the e5-pawn. }
15... f5 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Qa8 { The b8-bishop drops! } *

