[White "30) Owen's Defence (Hippo)"]
[Black "Owen's Defence (Hippo) #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b6
{ The Owen's Defence will not be an independent opening to study for us, since it will either transpose tothe Classical Dutch orthe Accelerated Queen's Indian. }
2. c4 Bb7 3. Nc3 g6
{ The only way Black can lead us into unfamiliar territory is by playing g6 and going for some type of Hippopotamus Defence.   Instead,  3...f5  4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.a3  is one way to reachthe Classical Dutch chapter and  3...e6  4.a3  Nf6  5.d5  transposes tothe Accelerated Queen's Indian chapter. }
4. e4 { Our centre is very impressive. } 4... Bg7 5. Be3
{ Of course, it is a matter of taste which setup you like the most here. We have at least 10 different ways to put our pieces. I like the Be3-Qd2-O-O-O setup the most. }
5... d6 6. Qd2 Nd7 7. f3
{ We are building a Saemisch setup, which is a very good variation against the KID. }
7... e5 8. Nge2 Bh6
{ Thanks to this trick, Black can exchange their dark-squared bishop. However, they will have enough bad pieces left for us to win the game. :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. O-O-O Bxe3 10. Qxe3
{ A potential plan for White in this position is Kb1 followed by h4-h5. } *

