[White "31) Dutch Defence"]
[Black "Dutch Defence: 2...d5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... d5
{ One of the main lines. Black stops the e4-break, but on the other hand, they are creating a weakness on e5. }
3. Bf4
{ A very natural developing move, which immediately controls the weakened e5-square and introduces the Nb5 idea. This can be a very annoying move for Black if they want to play a plan with ...c5, since they will have to react to Nb5 with ...Na6 to cover the c7-square, but then they can't kick out the knight with ...a6. }
3... Nf6
{ The most common move in this position, but with a smart move we can force Black to enter Stonewall territory and take the ...a6+...c5 plan away from them.  3...c6  has no independent value, since Black is already about to adopt the Stonewall formation there.  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  6.Bd3  just transposes to  3...Nf6  .   3...e6  would most likely also transpose at some point, unless Black goes for a serious mistake.  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  c5?  @@StartBracket@@here 5...a6 would transpose tothe 3...a6 line@@EndBracket@@  6.Nb5!  this knight is super strong on b5  6...Na6  and for example  7.Be2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.c4±  and opening the position for the more active pieces leads to a huge advantage for White.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp3pp/4pn2/3p1p2/3P1B2/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nb5  is an interesting alternative, but Black can reply  5...Bd6  6.Nxd6+  cxd6  with a quite unusual pawn structure. Because Black has no weak squares anymore, I would like to avoid this scenario. }
4. Nb5 { Forcing ...Na6! } 4... Na6 5. e3
{ Instead,  5.c4  would be strategically ideal, so our knight could return behind to the pawn, but  5...c6  6.Nc3  dxc4  7.e3  Be6  leads to some messy positions which we'd better avoid. }
5... e6
{ Black can also play like this but, if they are waiting too much with ...c6, White will be able to play c4 and put the knight behind the pawn on c3. That would solve the issue of the only misplaced white piece in the position. }
6. Nf3 Be7
{ Instead, Black should play  6...c6  and just transpose tothe 5...c6 line.   6...Ne4  stops our c4 idea because of ...Bb4+, but we can react with  6.Ne5!  and have the annoying Qh5+ threat! }
7. c4
{ And we have an excellent version of the Stonewall. We have the ideal setup and Black's knight is misplaced on a6. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3
{ White's knight is no longer misplaced, while Black's is. We have a better position. }
