[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Dutch Defence"]
[Black "Dutch Defence: 2...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg5 { Anticipating both  3...e6  and  3...g6  . } 3... e6 4. e4
{ Because of that early ...f5 move, the black king is not very safe here. }
4... fxe4
{ By far the main move, but let's look at two alternatives here.  4...Be7  is breaking the pin but is a pretty slow move.  5.exf5  exf5  6.Bc4!  stopping short castle  6...c6  7.Qe2!  and Black can't do anything against the Bxf6 threat:  7...d5  8.Bxf6!  gxf6  9.Bd3  with a clearly better position because of the weak black king, and a much better pawn structure.   4...h6  is the other way to address the pin:  5.Bxf6  Qxf6  6.exf5  exf5  7.Qe2+!  very annoying check  7...Qe7  8.O-O-O  Qxe2  9.Ngxe2  and even without queens White's development lead guarantees a clear edge.  9...c6  10.d5±  . }
5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. c3
{ We have many options here. I like  7.c3  the most because it is always good to protect the pawn on d4: it prepares Bd3-Bc2-Qd3 ideas and, since we didn't develop the knight to f3 yet, we still keep the Qh5 possibility. }
7... O-O
{ Black put their king into relative safety, so now we have to watch out for central actions from them. For example, on  8.Bd3  they can play  8...e5  and it is pretty complicated. }
8. Nf3 { Controlling the e5-square! } 8... d5
{ This move makes our task pretty simple. We will have a clear positional edge and we don't even have to go for O-O-O, because our pawn is still on h2. }
9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Bd3 Nd7
{ Black is not allowing us to use the d3-bishop in the fight for the e5-square.   If instead  10...c5  we play  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Bb5±  with total control over the e5-square.   On  10...Nc6  simply  11.Qe2±  with O-O, Qe3, Rae1 to follow. }
11. Bc2 { With the X-ray on the d5-pawn, Black still can't play ...e5. } 11...
c6 12. Qd3 Qh6 13. O-O
{ Black is positionally lost here, with the bad bishop on c8 and the weak square on e5. }
