2... Nf6 3. Bg5 { Anticipating both  3...e6  and  3...g6  . } 3... g6 4. h4
{ This move is again very effective against ...g6. } 4... Bg7
{ Instead,  4...h6?  would stop our h5 idea, but it would also horribly weaken the g6-square.  5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Nh3!  intending to target the g6-pawn, and in case Black plays  6...g5  7.e4!  already offers White a decisive advantage, because of the Qh5+ idea. }
5. h5 Nxh5
{ 5...d5  is no better, as  6.h6!  is forcing the bishop back to f8.  6...Bf8  7.f3±  and Black can hardly move, while we will play Qd2 and O-O-O, preparing e4. }
6. e4 fxe4 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Bc4
{ Of course,  8.Qxh5  is also good, but the computer just sees a winning line already. }
8... d6 9. Qxh5+ Kd7 10. Bh6 Bxh6
{ If instead  10...Bf6  then just  11.Nxe4  with Qf7 or O-O-O to follow and we are completely winning. }
11. Qf5+ { And we are giving a forced mate. } 11... Ke8 12. Bf7+ Kf8 13. Be6+
Kg7 14. Qf7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Dutch Defence"]
[Black "Dutch Defence: 2...Nf6 3.Bg5 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg5 { Anticipating both  3...e6  and  3...g6  . } 3... d5 4. f3
{ We want to play e4 in the next move and play a dynamic opening.   The main move is  4.Bxf6  but after  4...exf6  Black found a good setup with ...Nc6-...Be6-...Qd7 and ...O-O-O. Even though, of course, that is also a playable line for White, that character of the game is very different and not necessarily something which I really like for White. }
4... c5
{ Very logical. Black is attacking the d4-square, which is often our weak square when we put a pawn on f3 instead of a knight. }
5. e4
{ There is a huge tension in the centre, with many captures possible, so it is already a critical part of the game. }
5... cxd4
{ This move is not good, as it just invites the white queen into the game. } 6.
Qxd4 Nc6 7. Bb5 { Developing and keeping the queen on d4. } 7... fxe4 8. fxe4
dxe4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. O-O-O+
{ With a clearly better position for White, thanks to the shaky black king and also our much better pawn structure. }
*

