[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence, a very interesting, fighting opening. Black is immediately breaking the symmetry, and depending on our reply  2.Nf3  or  2.g3  , they can go for the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...g6@@EndBracket@@ or for the Classical Dutch  @@StartBracket@@playing ...Nf6 and ...e6@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nc3
{ With this move we are announcing that we want to play neither the Leningrad nor the Classical Dutch. Compared to the main lines which start with  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  and lead to complex, strategical battles, our move is much more direct and aggressive, we want to play e4 on the next move, and highlight the fact that with ...f5 being played, Black's king is a little bit open. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg5 { Anticipating both  3...e6  and  3...g6  . } 3... d5 4. f3
{ We want to play e4 in the next move and play a dynamic opening.   The main move is  4.Bxf6  but after  4...exf6  Black found a good setup with ...Nc6-...Be6-...Qd7 and ...O-O-O. Even though, of course, that is also a playable line for White, that character of the game is very different and not necessarily something which I really like for White. }
4... Nc6
{ Similarly to  4...c5  , Black is taking advantage of the fact that our knight can't go to f3 anymore, so our opponent can try to exploit it by attacking the d4 and e5 squares. }
5. Qd2 { Preparing for long castle, and basically stopping ...e5. } 5... e6
{ 5...e5?  is not working for Black:  6.dxe5  Nxe5  7.O-O-O  attacking the pawn on d5  7...Bb4  and here comes the key move of the line:  8.Qe3!  going out from the pin and attacking e5.  8...Bxc3  9.Qxc3  Qd6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.e4±  and Black is in a lot of trouble. }
6. O-O-O Be7
{ Another option is  6...Bb4  7.Nh3  O-O  8.e3  Bd7  9.Rg1⩲  The knight goes to d3 and we are playing for g4 to have some initiative on the kingside. }
7. e3
{ The main line here is  7.e4  , but after mass exchanges on e4, Black seems to be doing fine in that variation, while after the slower  7.e3  the bishop would of course rather be on b4. }
7... O-O 8. h4 { Nh3-Rg1-g4 and play on the kingside is our plan. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Classical Dutch"]
[Black "Classical Dutch: 4...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ Black has to play this move order to reach the Classical Dutch against us, since on  1...f5  we answer  2.Nc3! }
2. c4 f5 3. a3
{ A very rare move. The majority of the games feature  3.g3  or  3.Nf3  . Our idea is to play with Nc3 and not to allow the bishop to come to b4. }
3... Nf6
{ 3...d5  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Bg5  is analysed viathe 3...Nf6 move order.   The same can be said about  3...b6  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  , which is foundhere. }
4. Nc3 Be7
{ Black is keeping the option to play with ...b6, or not to play that move at all, depending on our next move. }
5. Bf4
{ Our bishop is going to be very well placed on the h2-b8 diagonal. It is attacking c7, and in case ...c6-...d5 comes, it is perfectly placed against the Stonewall setup.Also, if Black plays with ...d6-...e5, we will have a French type of structure where our bishop is going to put pressure on the opponent's centre instead of passively sitting on c1. }
5... O-O 6. e3 d6
{ Black is trying to build a wall against the f4-bishop. Even if it happens, the bishop will be still perfectly fine on g3.   If instead  6...b6  , then we can play  7.Bg3  Bb7  8.Nh3  and transpose to the line which starts with 4...b6. }
7. Be2
{ Very precise! Instead,  7.Nf3?!  would be inaccurate because of  7...Nh5!  and Black can take our bishop without committing with their other knight to d7. }
7... Qe8
{ With the idea of playing Bd8 and e5.   It is pretty weird to play  7...b6  now if Black didn't do it before:  8.Bf3  c6  9.h4⩲  With Bg3 and Nh3-f4 ideas to follow, we can say that Black's structure in the centre is flexible. I believe it is rather true, in the sense that any of their central pawns can get even weaker. :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Bg3
{ A typical move for this system @@StartBracket@@at least regarding my analysis, since, as I said, not many games have been played so far with this concept@@EndBracket@@. It is a slow, improving move, getting out from the e5-tempo and also vacating the square for the knight, in case it wants to go h3-f4. Sometimes Black is trying to play with ...Ne4 and ...g5, so we also put the bishop into safety against that plan. }
8... Bd8 9. b4
{ We can improve our position on the queenside and wait for Black to play ...e5 since, if that happens, our knight can come to f3 with tempo. }
9... e5 10. dxe5
{ Exchanging the d6-pawn, so the diagonal for the bishop will be much more open. }
10... dxe5 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. c5
{ We have a nice position, with a stable advantage thanks to the queenside initiative and Black's awkward piece coordination. }
*

