{ Black is trying to build a wall against the f4-bishop. Even if it happens, the bishop will be still perfectly fine on g3.   If instead  6...b6  , then we can play  7.Bg3  Bb7  8.Nh3  and transpose to the line which starts with 4...b6. }
7. Be2
{ Very precise! Instead,  7.Nf3?!  would be inaccurate because of  7...Nh5!  and Black can take our bishop without committing with their other knight to d7. }
7... Nc6 { Black's idea is e5. } 8. Bg3
{ A very nice prophylactic move!  8.Nf3  would allow  8...Ne4!  improving greatly Black's position. The point is that  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Nd2?  is not possible because of  10...Nxd4!  . }
8... e5 9. Nf3
{ Attacking the e5-pawn and forcing Black to make a decision in the centre. }
9... e4 10. Nd2
{ Now the position really looks like a reversed French Defence, with the huge difference that our bishop is strong on g3, instead of doing nothing on c1. }
10... Qe8 11. b4
{ With c5 coming very soon, putting pressure on Black's c7-d6 chain and making the bishop on g3 much more powerful. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Classical Dutch"]
[Black "Classical Dutch: 4...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ Black has to play this move order to reach the Classical Dutch against us, since on  1...f5  we answer  2.Nc3! }
2. c4 f5 3. a3
{ A very rare move. The majority of the games feature  3.g3  or  3.Nf3  . Our idea is to play with Nc3 and not to allow the bishop to come to b4. }
3... Nf6
{ 3...d5  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Bg5  just transposes to our line.   3...b6  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  is analysedhere. }
4. Nc3 d5
{ Black is going for a Stonewall setup. However, I would say that, in general, if we haven't played e3 and can develop the bishop to f4 or g5, we welcome such ideas from our opponent. }
5. Bg5
{ In theStonewall Chapter I suggest playing with Bf4, which would be again good of course, but since we played a3, which can be considered a waste of time, I'll show you some other solution, so we will not feel that we were tricked into a slightly inferior version of our usual setup against the Stonewall. }
5... c6 6. e3 Be7
{ Instead,  6...Bd6  would lead to a very similar position, but with Black keeping their dark-squared bishop on the board, which is not necessarily an achievement, as the position has a closed character.  7.f4!  Nbd7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.c5!  Another downside of the bishop on d6 is that this space gaining move is coming with a tempo.  9...Bc7  10.b4  h6  11.Bxf6  Nxf6  12.Be2⩲  with pressure on the queenside to follow. }
7. f4
{ This is a nice positional idea to know, I have seen it first in a game of Karpov. The point is that we take a similar central formation to our opponent, but we will have always some advantage, thanks to the c4-c6 pair of pawns, which will provide more space on the queenside for us. }
7... O-O
{ If instead  7...b6  , as we learned, this is normally our moment to take on d5, and it doesn't change here.  8.cxd5!  cxd5  9.Nf3  O-O  10.Rc1⩲  with a very pleasant edge for White in this Exchange Slav type of position. }
8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Be2 Ne4
{ Black doesn't really have any other active move in the position. } 10. Bxe7
Qxe7 11. O-O { We will play on the queenside, where we have more space! } *

