[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...b6?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... b6 { Not a good move. We can gain the bishop pair for free. } 4. a3 Bxd2+
{ Of course, retreating the bishop is too passive:  4...Be7?  5.e4!  and White has the dream pawn centre. }
5. Bxd2 Bb7 6. Qc2
{ 6.f3?  would be very logical but, unfortunately, it fails to  6...Qh4+  . }
6... Nf6
{ Black can also play  6...f5  7.e3  Nf6  8.f3!  This pawn is doing an amazing job restricting the b7-bishop and the f6-knight.  8...O-O  9.Bd3  d6  10.Ne2±  We will castle and then play for d5 @@StartBracket@@targeting the weakness of the f5-pawn@@EndBracket@@ or will just go for our usual queenside play. }
7. f3
{ Now there is no problem with f3 anymore, and e4 is coming in the next move unless Black reacts in the centre. }
7... c5 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. e3
{ Obviously not  9.e4?  because Black's ...c5 is supporting the ...Nc6-...d4 idea. }
9... O-O 10. Nh3
{ If Black does nothing, Nf2-Be2-O-O-Rfd1 are coming with a clear edge. } 10...
d5 11. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Taking with the queen is the only way; otherwise the c5-pawn is hanging. }
12. Bc4
{ Next is short castle, and White has a clear advantage because of the bishop pair and the weak black pawns on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence 3...b6?! #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... b6 { Not a good move. We can gain the bishop pair for free. } 4. a3 Bxd2+
{ Of course, retreating the bishop is too passive:  4...Be7?  5.e4!  and White has the dream pawn centre. }
5. Bxd2 Bb7 6. Qc2
{ 6.f3?  would be very logical but, unfortunately, it fails to  6...Qh4+  . }
6... Nf6
{ Black can also play  6...f5  7.e3  Nf6  8.f3!  This pawn is doing an amazing job restricting the b7-bishop and the f6-knight.  8...O-O  9.Bd3  d6  10.Ne2±  We will castle and then play for d5 @@StartBracket@@targeting the weakness of the f5-pawn@@EndBracket@@ or will just go for our usual queenside play. }
7. f3
{ Now there is no problem with f3 anymore, and e4 is coming in the next move unless Black reacts in the centre. }
7... d5 8. Rc1
{ It is probably better to start with this move since, to my surprise, after  8.cxd5  exd5  whether White plays  9.Rc1  or  9.b4  Black can throw us ...c5 at some point. Even though the engine likes those positions for White, I think it is unnecessary to enter any complications here. }
8... c6
{ Black has to waste time on this move. Against  8...O-O  we can take on d5 and on c7 as well!  9.cxd5!  Qxd5  10.Qxc7  Ba6  11.Qc3±  The next move is e4 and White has a clear advantage. }
9. e3 O-O 10. Nh3
{ White is planning to continue with simple development like Bd3-O-O-Nf2 and we welcome any try from Black to open the position since that will favour us with the bishop pair. }
10... Nbd7 11. cxd5
{ We can release the tension in the centre and achieve a nice structure or an endgame with the bishop pair. }
11... cxd5
{ If  11...exd5  12.Bd3  c5  13.Qa4±  Preparing the b1-square for the bishop. We will play O-O and then Nf4 with a very nice position. Black's minor pieces are very passive. }
12. Qc7
{ Trading queens limits the chances for counterplay for the side with knights. }
12... Qxc7 13. Rxc7 Rab8 14. Nf4 Rfc8 15. Rc3
{ With a clear edge in the endgame because of the bishop pair and the potential expansion on the kingside. }
*

