[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...d5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... d5 4. Qa4+
{ I believe this move makes 3...d5 quite dubious. The knight going to c6 with the e6-d5 structure is a good sign for us. }
4... Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. a3
{ It is good to ask the bishop whether it wants to take on d2 or go back to e7. }
7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Ne4
{ Black will not allow us to keep the bishop pair advantage for long. On the other hand, the issue with the knight on c6 is still not solved. }
9. Qc2 a5 { With the idea of playing ...a4 blockading our queenside. } 10. Bd3
f5 11. O-O a4 12. Bb4
{ It is not so easy to take the bishop anymore, because then the a4-pawn will become very weak. }
12... Rf6 13. Ne5
{ Our next move is f3, kicking back Black's most active piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...d5?! #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... d5 4. Qa4+
{ I believe this move makes 3...d5 quite dubious. The knight going to c6 with the e6-d5 structure is a good sign for us. }
4... Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. a3
{ It is good to ask the bishop whether it wants to take on d2 or go back to e7. }
7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Ne4
{ Black will not allow us to keep the bishop pair advantage for long. On the other hand, the issue with the knight on c6 is still not solved. }
9. Qc2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qe7
{ Black wants to take on c4 and play for ...e5.   Instead,  10...b6  leads to a quite simple position with a clear edge for White:  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Bd3⩲  and we have a very nice version of a QGD Carlsbad. }
11. Qc3 { Controlling the e5-square. } 11... Re8 12. Be2
{ 12.Be2  and  12.Bd3  look very similar, but sometimes there can be a significant difference. If we put the bishop on e2, then maybe we can do something else after dxc4, since the bishop will be not hanging with tempo.  @@StartBracket@@I'm not saying that is the case here, just a general observation.@@EndBracket@@ }
12... dxc4 13. O-O e5 14. d5
{ Of course, we are not interested in trading everything on e5 and playing an equal endgame. }
14... Nb8 15. Bxc4 { We have nice play on the semi-open c-file. } *

