[Black "Keres Defence: 3...d5?! #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... d5 4. Qa4+
{ I believe this move makes 3...d5 quite dubious. The knight going to c6 with the e6-d5 structure is a good sign for us. }
4... Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. a3
{ It is good to ask the bishop whether it wants to take on d2 or go back to e7. }
7... Be7 8. Qc2
{ The queen had served its purpose on a4, hence it was time to bring it back to a natural square. }
8... a5
{ The ...a4 push is a small positional threat we should prevent if we can. } 9.
b3 Nb8
{ Yes, the knight was that bad on c6! Now it opens some possibilities to play with ...b6 and ...c5. }
10. Bb2 b6 11. Bd3
{ With normal development. Thanks to the ...Nc6 and then ...Nb8 back manoeuvre, we can easily keep a better position. }
11... Bb7 12. O-O Nbd7
{ 12...c5  doesn't quite work yet because after  13.cxd5  exd5  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Rac1±  both the h7 and the c5-pawns are hanging. }
13. e4
{ We are the first to push in the centre, not waiting for Black's equaliser idea ...c5. }
13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4
{ We will centralise our rooks, and we have the weak c6-square to work with. }
