[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... f5
{ Black wants to play in the spirit of the Classical Dutch. Since our knight is not on f3 yet, the main follow-up of this move with Nf6, b6-Bb7 is highly ineffective: we can just play f3 with perfect central control. }
4. a3 { Gaining the bishop pair or forcing this bishop to go backwards. } 4...
Bxd2+
{ 4...Be7  would be a serious mistake:  5.e4!  and we can occupy the centre for free.  5...fxe4  6.Nxe4  Nf6  7.Bd3±  The position is similar to what we can get in the Dutch Defence when Black is playing with ...e6. This is even better for us, since our bishop is on c1, so we can continue the game without exchanging on f6. }
5. Bxd2 Nf6 6. f3
{ Restricting the knight, and not giving Black any chance to create some counterplay using the e4-square. }
6... O-O 7. e3 d6 8. Bd3 e5 9. Ne2
{ With short castle to follow, we keep our small but stable advantage because of the pair of bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... Nf6
{ By playing this move, Black is saying that they are ready to enter the main lines of the Bogo-Indian Defence. }
4. a3
{ Instead,  4.Ngf3  or  4.g3  would transpose to huge main lines. We don't want any of that. :@@EndBracket@@ }
4... Bxd2+
{ Giving up the pair or bishops will again offer us a nice advantage without doing anything special. }
5. Bxd2 O-O
{ 5...d6  doesn't change much. Our plan is Bd3-Ne2-Nc3 and then building the centre.  6.e3  e5  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Ne2⩲  Black has no compensation for the bishop pair, and White will build a nice centre with f3-e4.   5...b6  6.Qc2  Bb7  7.f3  is transposing tothe 3...b6 line. Here Black can try  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/P7/1PQBPPPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  7.dxc5  bxc5  8.e3  Against the bishop on b7, the knight normally doesn't want to go to f3.  8...Bb7  9.Ne2  O-O?!  Maybe somewhat inaccurate but the alternative is not much better.  10.Ng3!⩲  The knight on g3 prevents ...Ne4 ideas and makes it possible for the bishop to go to c3. After Bc3 we can simply continue developing with Be2, since taking on g2 would be way too dangerous for Black. Then we'll just castle.   Black can trade our bishop but will still have a lot of problems to solve on the d-file: @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pb1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/2P5/P3P3/1PQBNPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne4  10.Nc3  Nxd2  11.Qxd2  O-O  12.O-O-O⩲  White has a pleasant edge. It is not easy to develop because of the backward d-pawn and, after playing f3 and restricting Black's bishop, White can even start pushing the h-pawn and create some play on the kingside. }
6. Bg5
{ Black should quickly do something in the centre or look for some counterplay. If we finish development, we will just have a clear advantage with the bishops. And since Black can't really do anything, this is exactly what will happen. :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... d6 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Ne2
{ The knight is much better on c3 than on f3. There, it will control the most important squares in the position, e4 and d5. Also, on c3 it is not in the way of building our centre with f3-e4. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 b6 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. f3
{ We have a clear edge with the bishop pair and the space advantage in the centre. }
*

