[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Keres Defence"]
[Black "Keres Defence: 3...Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... Nf6
{ By playing this move, Black is saying that they are ready to enter the main lines of the Bogo-Indian Defence. }
4. a3
{ Instead,  4.Ngf3  or  4.g3  would transpose to huge main lines. We don't want any of that. :@@EndBracket@@ }
4... Be7 5. e4 { Occupying the centre with the immediate threat of e5. } 5...
d5
{ Black is fighting back in the centre. From here on, the game will get very sharp. }
6. e5 Nfd7
{ 6...Ne4?  is just a big mistake:  7.Qg4!  gives White a large advantage. For example,  7...Nxd2  8.Qxg7!  Rf8  9.Bxd2  dxc4  10.Nf3+-  . }
7. Qg4
{ Instead of this move, White has tried  7.b4  ,  7.Ngf3  and  7.cxd5  as well. All those are much more positional approaches, but I believe  7.Qg4  allows us to create quite serious concrete problems for Black. }
7... O-O
{ If  7...g6  , then we already managed to provoke quite a serious weakness on the kingside, so we can take the time to prevent Black's counterplay with  8.b4!  @@StartBracket@@so there is no ...c5 for now@@EndBracket@@ and after  8...a5  9.b5  c5  10.Bb2  cxd4  11.Bxd4  we keep the centre under control, while Black has issues on the kingside. }
8. Ndf3
{ With the huge threat of Bh6! You can check the gameLaznicka-Thavandiran in the Model Games section to see how play can go on. }
8... Re8
{ On  8...Kh8  , we can continue with  9.Qh5!  . With the attacking ideas of Bd3 or h4-Ng5 to follow, Black's position is critical.   Black's centre is losing its flexibility after  8...f5?  Now one of Black's main defensive resources, ...f6!, is gone too  9.Qg3  Kh8  10.Nh3+-  With a strategically winning position for White. The knight will be super strong on f4 and h4-h5 is also coming. }
9. Nh3
{ With the rook gone from f8, we want a knight on g5, as then Qh5 would be a decisive double attack on f7 and h7. }
9... c5 { Black has to go for central counterplay! } 10. Nhg5 Nf8
{ 10...cxd4??  would be a short game, since we have  11.Qh5!+-  . } 11. Qh5
{ Attacking f7 and forcing a weakening move. } 11... g6
{ Instead,  11...Bxg5  12.Bxg5  Qb6  13.O-O-O  just gives White a big advantage. }
12. Qh6
{ With h4-h5 coming, this attack is very dangerous. Indeed, Black has to play a couple of only moves to stay in the game. I'll show you the best line according to the engine. Despite perfect defence, Black will still be worse.   12...Nc6!  @@StartBracket@@everything else is +- according to the engine@@EndBracket@@  13.dxc5  f6!  14.h4  fxg5!  15.h5  Qc7  16.hxg6  Bd8!  17.Bd3  Nxe5  18.gxh7+  Kh8  19.Bc2  Nxf3+  20.gxf3  Qe5+  21.Kf1⩲  with Rg1 and Bxg5 to follow in the final position, Black is still in danger at the end of this crazy line. }
