[Black "Keres vs. 3...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+
{ The starting position of the Keres Defence, also known @@StartBracket@@for some reason@@EndBracket@@ as the Kangaroo Defence. This opening could have an independent value but, for example, if Black plays with ...Nf6 at some point, then there is a big chance that it will transpose to a Nimzo-Indian or Bogo-Indian. }
3. Nd2
{ This move was an easy choice for me. If  3.Nc3  , then Black can play  3...f5  and that is exactly the variation I wanted to avoid in theClassical Dutch chapter by starting with 3.a3!   If  3.Bd2  , then Black has 5 different options to address the threat on their bishop @@StartBracket@@...a5, ...c5, ...Qe7, ...Be7, ...Bxd2+@@EndBracket@@ and most of those lines are leading us into Bogo-Indian territory.   We don't want this at all, since we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  and allow the Nimzo Indian, but not the Queen's or Bogo-Indian. }
3... c5
{ The most logical move. Black understands that they will have to take on d2 at some point, so they are starting the fight in the centre even before that exchange takes place. }
4. a3 { We are gaining the bishop pair. } 4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 cxd4 6. Nf3
{ If we took  6.Qxd4  , then after  6...Nf6  at some point ...Nc6 can come with a tempo. That's why we prefer to recapture on d4 with the knight. }
6... Nf6
{ 6...Nc6?!  is inaccurate:  7.Nxd4  Nf6  8.Nxc6!  bxc6  9.c5!  With Qc2 and Bf4 to follow, Black has problems on the dark squares. }
7. Nxd4 d5
{ Black can start with this move instead of castling. Our reaction will be very similar. }
8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. f3 { We want to play e4! } 9... e5 10. Nc2
{ Probably should be trainable as well. } 10... Qe6
{ The queen looks strange on e6. White should be able to achieve some advantage here. }
11. e4 { We go on with our plan. } 11... O-O 12. Qc3
{ Opening the diagonal for the c1-bishop. } 12... Nc6 13. Be3 Rd8 14. b4
{ Gaining space on the queenside. If we manage to play b5, then we can activate our knight via b4. }
14... a6
{ Black stops our b5 idea but weakens some dark squares.  14...Bd7  15.b5!  Creating the b4-square for the knight.  15...Ne7  16.Nb4  Rdc8  17.Qd2  Black's minor pieces are very passive, so the next move is very logical.  17...a6  18.bxa6  bxa6  19.Nd3⩲  However, with the trade of the b-pawns the position has become more open, which favours the bishops. White will soon castle and c5 is a very nice square for our pieces.  19...Bb5  20.a4  Bc4??  Unfortunately for Black, this move is not possible.  21.Nc5+-  White is winning material as both the queen and the bishop are attacked. }
15. Bb6 Re8 16. Bc4 Qe7 17. O-O
{ We are finishing the development, and the next step is to bring our knight towards d5/f5. }
17... Be6 18. Bc5
{ The queen would be more comfortable on e6 than the rook, so it is worth inserting this little move. }
18... Qc7 19. Bxe6 Rxe6 20. Rfd1
{ With Ne3 to follow, White has some pleasant pressure in this position. } *

