[Black "Philidor & Pirc: 2...g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6
{ A very flexible first move, and quite an annoying one against some particular repertoires. 'Unfortunately', ours is one of those repertoires.   Black is keeping a lot of options with this move. For example, if  2.c4  they can play  2...e5  , which is quite a double-edged system giving serious counterchances for Black. Also  2.c4  f5  is possible as well, transposing the game into Dutch territory, where we play with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  and not with  2.c4  .   The main move 1.d4 players are playing here is  2.Nf3  , preventing ...e5 and allowing some minor defences like  2...Bg4  . That is not an issue for us, but  2...Nf6  is! Black will play the KID and, since our knight is already on f3, we can't playthe Averbakh system against it. So, we pretty much have no other real choice than playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e4  and go to 1.e4 territory, allowing our opponent to play the Pirc or the Philidor Defence. }
2. e4 g6 3. h4
{ As we can see inthe 1...g6 chapter, this is how we go when our opponent wants to play the Modern Defence. }
3... h5
{ Stopping h5, but weakening the g5-square.   Instead,  3...Bg7  4.h5  is already a transposition tothe 1.d4 g6 chapter, while  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pp1p/3p2p1/8/3PP2P/8/PPP2PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  will be analysed viathe classical Pirc move order 2...Nf6. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nc3
{ 5.Ng5  is also possible, but we are not afraid of ...Bg4, quite the contrary! }
5... Nf6
{ This move basically invites Ng5, and we have no reason not to play it. } 6.
Ng5 O-O 7. f3
{ We have a very strong attacking position, with g4 as a potential break on the kingside. Therefore, Black has to do something in the centre very quickly to have some counterplay. }
7... e5
{ This move offers us the chance to enter a highly advantageous endgame. Instead,  7...d5?!  is probably even worse, just provoking White to start a very strong attack.  8.e5  Nh7  9.g4!  and Black is in great danger. }
8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Bc4
{ The bishop is not only super-strong on this diagonal, but even coming with a tempo. }
10... Rd7 11. Be3
{ Rd1 is a serious threat because of the weakness of the f7-pawn. If Black can solve it somehow, then we can just play a4-a5 and gain more space on the queenside. }
