2. e4 g6 3. h4
{ As we can see inthe 1...g6 chapter, this is how we go when our opponent wants to play the Modern Defence. }
3... h5
{ Stopping h5, but weakening the g5-square.   Instead,  3...Bg7  4.h5  is already a transposition tothe 1.d4 g6 chapter, while  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pp1p/3p2p1/8/3PP2P/8/PPP2PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  will be analysed viathe classical Pirc move order 2...Nf6. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nc3
{ 5.Ng5  is also possible, but we are not afraid of ...Bg4, quite the contrary! }
5... a6
{ Our knight went to c3, so finally, this move is quite legit, with the idea of ...b5-...Bb7-...b4.   5...Bg4  stops Ng5 for the moment, but eventually, it will create a powerful centre for us.  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Qd2  and Ng5 is already coming in the next move.  Bxf3  8.gxf3±  Our light-squared bishop will be a huge asset, not to mention our centre. f4-e5 is coming very soon, with a clear advantage. }
6. Ng5 b5 7. e5
{ A very strong move. Qf3 is a huge threat, attacking both f7 and the a8-rook. }
7... Nh6 { Instead,  7...Bb7?  is unplayable because of  8.e6!  . } 8. Qf3
{ The queen is coming into the game with tempo. As Black has to close the long diagonal in order to protect their rook, the ...Bb7 idea is gone. }
8... c6 9. e6 { A nice temporary sacrifice to create a weakness on g6. } 9...
Bxe6
{ 9...fxe6  is no better. We play  10.Qe4!  with a double attack on the e6 and g6 pawns.  10...Nf5  11.Nxe6  Bxe6  12.Qxe6±  and the g6-pawn is falling in the next move. White has a clear advantage because of the weakness of Black's king. }
10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Bxh6
{ So Black can't play ...Nf5 anymore to protect the g6-pawn. } 11... Bxh6 12.
Bd3
{ White has a huge initiative. Black's position is extremely weak on the light squares and, unfortunately for our opponent, those are not just 'empty' squares, but pawns as well. }
