1. d4 d6
{ A very flexible first move, and quite an annoying one against some particular repertoires. 'Unfortunately', ours is one of those repertoires.   Black is keeping a lot of options with this move. For example, if  2.c4  they can play  2...e5  , which is quite a double-edged system giving serious counterchances for Black. Also  2.c4  f5  is possible as well, transposing the game into Dutch territory, where we play with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  and not with  2.c4  .   The main move 1.d4 players are playing here is  2.Nf3  , preventing ...e5 and allowing some minor defences like  2...Bg4  . That is not an issue for us, but  2...Nf6  is! Black will play the KID and, since our knight is already on f3, we can't playthe Averbakh system against it. So, we pretty much have no other real choice than playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e4  and go to 1.e4 territory, allowing our opponent to play the Pirc or the Philidor Defence. }
2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ The starting position of the Pirc Defence. Since this is a 1.d4 repertoire, obviously I'm not going to recommend any of the main lines. Instead, my choice is like the 10th most common move in this position, but still perfectly compatible with our repertoire. }
4. h4 { We do this often, so why not here as well? } 4... Bg7
{ Black can calmly continue with this move, as h5 was not a threat yet because of the knight on f6. Instead,  4...h5  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Ng5  is discussed viathe 2...g6 3.h4 h5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.Ng5 move order. }
5. Be2 { Preparing for h5! } 5... h5
{ 5...h6  6.h5!  we go for our usual break.  6...g5  7.f4!⩲  Black's kingside will be broken and White should be at least slightly better. }
6. Nf3 { If Black stops h5, we go for the g5-square! } 6... Bg4 7. Ng5 Bxe2 8.
Qxe2 { The e5-push is already in the air! } 8... Nc6
{ We have some issues with the protection of the d4-pawn. That will force us to give up our dark-squared bishop. }
9. Be3 Ng4 10. O-O-O Nxe3 11. Qxe3
{ Even though Black has managed to take a very important white piece, their issues are not solved because of our very strong centre. e5 is a big threat now. }
11... e5 { The only way to prevent our e5 push. } 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. f4 Ng4 14.
Qf3
{ The e5-push is coming next, no matter what Black does. That and it will give us a nice initiative combined with the struggles of Black's queen. }
