[Black "Philidor: 3...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6
{ A very flexible first move, and quite an annoying one against some particular repertoires. 'Unfortunately', ours is one of those repertoires.   Black is keeping a lot of options with this move. For example, if  2.c4  they can play  2...e5  , which is quite a double-edged system giving serious counterchances for Black. Also  2.c4  f5  is possible as well, transposing the game into Dutch territory, where we play with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  and not with  2.c4  .   The main move 1.d4 players are playing here is  2.Nf3  , preventing ...e5 and allowing some minor defences like  2...Bg4  . That is not an issue for us, but  2...Nf6  is! Black will play the KID and, since our knight is already on f3, we can't playthe Averbakh system against it. So, we pretty much have no other real choice than playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e4  and go to 1.e4 territory, allowing our opponent to play the Pirc or the Philidor Defence. }
2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ Here we have a choice between Nf3 and taking on e5. However, Nf3 would mean that we have to learn 2 different lines against the Philidor. Therefore, even though that is probably the most challenging move, theoretically speaking, I would rather go for the endgame. Here we don't have to learn a lot, but will be still a little bit better. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6
{ The most common move in this position. However, I find this surprising, as it guarantees a slight edge for us thanks to our better pawn structure, even if we do everything wrong from this moment on. :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ A nice move that will allow us to manoeuvre our c3-knight to a better square. }
8... Bd6 9. Nh3 Ke7 10. Nf2
{ Since the e5-pawn is our main target here, ideally we want to have one knight on d3, the other one on c4, and then put the bishop on the long diagonal. }
10... Nbd7 11. a4
{ We are not in a rush: securing some space on the queenside is always good. Next is Nd1-e3, Nd3 and slowly bring the pieces to attack the e5-pawn. }
