[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "36) Modern Defence (1.d4 g6 2.e4)"]
[Black "Modern Defence 3...h6?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4
{ My choice against 1...g6 is very direct and doesn't give Black many options to go wrong or to avoid our preparation. Of course, 1.d4 players are expected to play  2.c4  but, for us, it is not so easy: Black could still transpose to the Dutch with  2...f5  , where we play with 2.Nc3 and not 2.c4.   Also, I found many little lines for Black which we have to meet differently. To show you a few examples:  2.c4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  f5  . If we want to avoid this line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  , then Black can play  3...Nc6  , which is a rare but interesting line, or  3...d6  4.Nc3  e5  . }
2... Bg7 3. h4
{ A very direct way. Our main goal is to push this pawn up to h6 and force Black's bishop back to f8. }
3... h6
{ Black wants to meet h5 with ...g5, but in those cases we very often have a strong follow-up which we will be able to observe in this variation as well. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. h5
{ After one useful developing move, we are already going for our kingside break! }
5... g5 6. f4
{ This is the typical attack against Black's kingside: h5 immediately followed by f4! breaking Black's pawn chain. }
6... gxf4 7. Bxf4 Nd7
{ With the idea of pushing ...e5 or ...c5 in the next move. } 8. Nf3 c5
{ Black would like to transpose to some kind of Sicilian Dragon type of position, where their bishop on g7 would be really strong, but we will not allow this.   After  8...e5  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Bg3  keeping an eye on the e5-pawn, so Ngf6 is not so easy for Black.  10...c6  11.Qd2±  White has a very pleasant advantage because of Black's numerous weak pawns and squares, and O-O-O and then Be2 and Rhf1 will follow. }
9. e5
{ Black has to go for simplifications in the centre, since they can't increase their pressure. }
9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bb5+
{ The tactical justification of the 9.e5! move! } 12... Bd7 13. Bxe5
{ We are controlling the long diagonal and will play O-O-O in the next move. Black's position is not very appealing to the eye. }
*

