[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4
{ My choice against 1...g6 is very direct and doesn't give Black many options to go wrong or to avoid our preparation. Of course, 1.d4 players are expected to play  2.c4  but, for us, it is not so easy: Black could still transpose to the Dutch with  2...f5  , where we play with 2.Nc3 and not 2.c4.   Also, I found many little lines for Black which we have to meet differently. To show you a few examples:  2.c4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  f5  . If we want to avoid this line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  , then Black can play  3...Nc6  , which is a rare but interesting line, or  3...d6  4.Nc3  e5  . }
2... Bg7 3. h4
{ A very direct way. Our main goal is to push this pawn up to h6 and force Black's bishop back to f8. }
3... c5
{ Black is trying to open the long diagonal and meet a flank attack with some central play. This is absolutely principled, but here not completely correct. }
4. dxc5
{ Very strong! Black will need some time to recapture this pawn, and then we can return to our h5-idea. }
4... Qa5+ 5. c3 Qxc5 6. h5 { And h6 is coming! } 6... Nf6
{ If instead  6...d6  , then we play  7.h6!  Bf6  . Even though Black managed to keep their bishop on the long diagonal, now the knight can't move from g8, and the bishop can also be exposed to g4-g5 ideas. For example,  8.Be3  Qc7  9.Nh3  @@StartBracket@@to control the g5-square@@EndBracket@@  9...Nc6  10.g4  already looks pretty unpleasant for Black. }
7. h6 Bf8
{ We managed to achieve our goal of pushing the pawn to h6. Now we can start developing, a not so easy task for our opponent. }
8. Be3 Qc7 9. Nd2
{ With Ngf3 and Bg5 coming, it is not so easy to see how Black will solve the problem of the f8-bishop: ...e6 is not a good fit with ...g6 due to the weakness on the dark squares. }
*

