[White "36) Modern Defence (1.d4 g6 2.e4)"]
[Black "Modern Defence 3...d5! #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4
{ My choice against 1...g6 is very direct and doesn't give Black many options to go wrong or to avoid our preparation. Of course, 1.d4 players are expected to play  2.c4  but, for us, it is not so easy: Black could still transpose to the Dutch with  2...f5  , where we play with 2.Nc3 and not 2.c4.   Also, I found many little lines for Black which we have to meet differently. To show you a few examples:  2.c4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  f5  . If we want to avoid this line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  , then Black can play  3...Nc6  , which is a rare but interesting line, or  3...d6  4.Nc3  e5  . }
2... Bg7 3. h4
{ A very direct way. Our main goal is to push this pawn up to h6 and force Black's bishop back to f8. }
3... d5
{ The best move in the position. Black is immediately counterattacking in the centre. }
4. e5
{ It was not in our interest to play  4.exd5  and after  4...Qxd5  enter a very weird Scandinavian where we played h4 for basically no reason. }
4... c5 5. Nc3
{ The main move is by far  5.c3  , but I tried to remain faithful to the approach chosen at move 3, so we are going for the most direct way, leaving our opponent less room for mistakes. }
5... Nc6
{ Black is putting maximum pressure on our centre. Instead,  5...cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bb5  Bd7  is just transposing to 5...Nc6, while if Black tried to meet  6.Qxd4  with  6...e6  , that is simply too passive: we can just continue with  7.h5!  since on  7...Nc6  we still have  8.Bb5! }
6. Bb5
{ Basically the only move. We have to neutralise the c6-knight somehow, as otherwise our centre is just collapsing. }
6... f6 { Putting more fire into the position! } 7. h5
{ We do the same! The position is very complex and there are no OTB games yet, so I'll just show 1-2 possible continuations from here. }
7... fxe5 8. dxc5
{ Black has a very strong centre, but we are ready to attack it! } 8... d4 9.
h6 { Very strong intermediate move. } 9... Bf8
{ An excellent move. Black has to keep the f6-square available for a knight.   Instead,  9...Bf6  is wrong and after  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Ne4  Bf5  12.f3±  we have a clear advantage because of that very unfortunate knight on g8. }
10. Bxc6+
{ It is important not to forget about this move, since  10.Ne4??  is losing the bishop to  10...Qa5+  . }
10... bxc6 11. Ne4 Nf6 12. Qe2
{ With an extremely unusual and complicated position. The computer gives some edge for White, but I wouldn't say it matters much. We just have to maintain our control over the central squares and then, thanks to our better structure, we have good long-term chances. }
