[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "37) The Norwegian Rat"]
[Black "The Norwegian Rat 3...Nd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 Nf6
{ A very provocative and objectively dubious system, originally called the Horseshoe variation or the Norwegian Defense, but the most well-known name of the opening for a long time was the North Sea Defence.Magnus Carlsen started to employ it, probably because of the connection to Norway, since the opening doesn't really have any other merits if White plays well. He likes to call it 'the Norwegian Rat' and the new name became fashionable. }
3. e5
{ Of course, there is no reason not to attack that adventurous knight right away! }
3... Nd5
{ Black moves his knight like in the Alekhine Defence, with the major difference that there, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  then  3...d6!  is an absolutely crucial move to undermine White's strong centre. Since here Black already used that move for 1...g6, they lack that option. :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. c4 Nb6 5. c5
{ Gaining a lot of space in the centre, and harassing that unfortunate knight. }
5... Nd5 6. Bc4 { Developing with tempo. } 6... c6
{ Looks more natural and less weakening than the alternative way to defend the knight  6...e6  . The moves ...e6 and ...g6 don't usually work well together because of the weakening on the dark squares.  7.Nd2  Bg7  8.Ne4  The knight stands very well on e4, and it is also preventing Black's ...d6 freeing idea.  8...h6  9.Nf3  b6  Black is trying to do something with our massive central advantage, but we don't even have to react now.  10.O-O  Bb7  11.Re1  O-O  12.h4→  With a very promising kingside attack to follow. Our next moves are a3-Bd3-Bc2-Qd3. Black has a tough time creating any play. }
7. Nf3 b6
{ Unfortunately for Black, it's too early for  7...d6?  because after  8.exd6  exd6  9.O-O→  A very unpleasant check is coming on the e-file. }
8. Nc3 { Increasing our lead in the development. } 8... Nxc3
{ The journey of the knight finished, and we can't really call it a successful one. }
9. bxc3 Bg7 10. Ng5 { We can start an immediate attack against Black's king. }
10... O-O 11. h4 { We are not intending to castle! } 11... bxc5 12. h5 d5 13.
Bd3
{ Black managed to chase away our bishop from the a2-g8 diagonal, but it is still not clear how can they defend against the threat of Nxh7. }
*

