4. c4 Nb6 5. c5
{ Gaining a lot of space in the centre, and harassing that unfortunate knight. }
5... Nd5 6. Bc4 { Developing with tempo. } 6... c6
{ Looks more natural and less weakening than the alternative way to defend the knight  6...e6  . The moves ...e6 and ...g6 don't usually work well together because of the weakening on the dark squares.  7.Nd2  Bg7  8.Ne4  The knight stands very well on e4, and it is also preventing Black's ...d6 freeing idea.  8...h6  9.Nf3  b6  Black is trying to do something with our massive central advantage, but we don't even have to react now.  10.O-O  Bb7  11.Re1  O-O  12.h4→  With a very promising kingside attack to follow. Our next moves are a3-Bd3-Bc2-Qd3. Black has a tough time creating any play. }
7. Nf3 b6
{ Unfortunately for Black, it's too early for  7...d6?  because after  8.exd6  exd6  9.O-O→  A very unpleasant check is coming on the e-file. }
8. Nc3 { Increasing our lead in the development. } 8... Nxc3
{ The journey of the knight finished, and we can't really call it a successful one. }
9. bxc3 Ba6
{ It looks like Black is getting something against our centre with  9...bxc5  but in reality, our opponent is just lost by force!  10.Ng5!  e6  11.Qf3  Qe7  12.Ne4+-  Black can't prevent all of White's threats like Nd6/Nf6 or Bg5.   Against  9...Bg7  we can start an immediate attack against Black's king:  10.Ng5  O-O  11.h4  We are not intending to castle!  11...bxc5  12.h5  d5  13.Bd3  Black managed to chase away our bishop from the a2-g8 diagonal, but it is still not clear how can they defend against the threat of Nxh7. }
10. Bb3
{ We are not interested in trading our great bishop, and helping Black develop at the same time. The only drawback could be that we can't temporarily castle but now we want to checkmate Black, not castle! }
10... bxc5 11. Ng5 c4 { Black was building his defense on this move. } 12. Qf3
{ Again a mate-in-1 threat. } 12... f6 13. exf6 { And again! } 13... exf6 14.
O-O
{ A very nice move to play with 2 minor pieces hanging. White is just finishing development and the arrival of the rook to the e-file will be decisive. }
14... Be7
{ Black is trying to complete development, but the king will not find safety even on  g8  . If instead  14...fxg5  15.Re1+  Be7  16.Qf6  the queen is entering Black's camp with tempo.  16...Rf8  17.Qg7  cxb3  18.Bxg5  Even though Black is 2 pieces up at the moment, they are completely helpless against our attack.Let me show you one way to regain all the material and more:  18...Rf7  19.Qg8+  Rf8  20.Qxh7  Rf7  21.Qg8+  Rf8  22.Qxg6+  Rf7  23.Bxe7  Qxe7  24.Qg8+  Rf8  25.Rxe7+  Kxe7  26.Re1++-  With the f8-rook falling in the next move, Black has to resign.   Alternatively,  14...cxb3  15.Re1+  Be7  16.Qxf6  Rf8  17.Qg7+-  and with Nxh7-Qxg6 to follow, Black is completely lost. }
15. Bc2 fxg5
{ 15...O-O  runs into  16.Nxh7!  This nice move is basically finishing the game. Black's kingside is falling apart.  16...Kxh7  17.Qh5++-  . }
16. Re1
{ We are down a piece @@StartBracket@@which is hardly visible if we look at Black's not-so-active queenside pieces@@EndBracket@@ but Bxg5 is an unstoppable threat, and Black has no defense here. }
