[White "37) The Norwegian Rat"]
[Black "The Norwegian Rat 3...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 Nf6
{ A very provocative and objectively dubious system, originally called the Horseshoe variation or the Norwegian Defense, but the most well-known name of the opening for a long time was the North Sea Defence.Magnus Carlsen started to employ it, probably because of the connection to Norway, since the opening doesn't really have any other merits if White plays well. He likes to call it 'the Norwegian Rat' and the new name became fashionable. }
3. e5
{ Of course, there is no reason not to attack that adventurous knight right away! }
3... Nh5
{ Strangely enough, this odd-looking knight move is Black's best here. Black is hoping that White will be tempted to immediately punish it.Instead,  3...Ng8  can't really be serious. White will just gain a big edge with the most natural moves.  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  Bg7  6.O-O±  Black has wasted a lot of time with the knight and gained nothing in return. }
4. Be2 { The main line, but I find it completely unnecessary. } 4... d6
{ Black wants to sacrifice a pawn and get counterplay on the g-file and against our centre. }
5. Bxh5 gxh5 6. Qxh5 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ Or  7.Qxe5  Rg8⇆  when White is up a pawn, but Black has very decent compensation for it. }
7... Qd5 8. Nf3 Qe4+ 9. Be3 Qxc2 { Black is too active here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "37) The Norwegian Rat"]
[Black "The Norwegian Rat 3...Nh5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 Nf6
{ A very provocative and objectively dubious system, originally called the Horseshoe variation or the Norwegian Defense, but the most well-known name of the opening for a long time was the North Sea Defence.Magnus Carlsen started to employ it, probably because of the connection to Norway, since the opening doesn't really have any other merits if White plays well. He likes to call it 'the Norwegian Rat' and the new name became fashionable. }
3. e5
{ Of course, there is no reason not to attack that adventurous knight right away! }
3... Nh5
{ Strangely enough, this odd-looking knight move is Black's best here. Black is hoping that White will be tempted to immediately punish it.Instead,  3...Ng8  can't really be serious. White will just gain a big edge with the most natural moves.  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  Bg7  6.O-O±  Black has wasted a lot of time with the knight and gained nothing in return. }
4. Nf3
{ Just playing a normal game and completely ignoring Black's knight provocations is our best strategy here. After  4.g4?!  Ng7⇆  Black is building up some counterplay based on ...d6 or ...h5. }
4... d6
{ 4...d5?!  allows White free development.  5.c4  c6  6.Nc3  Ng7  At some point Black has to do something with that knight. We can see it is struggling if we don't take it.  7.Qb3  e6  Black's position is full of weak dark squares.  8.h4  Nd7  9.Bh6  Nf5  10.Bxf8  Nxf8  11.g4  Ne7  12.O-O-O±  White has a clear advantage, with much more space and ideas like h5. On the other hand, Black is struggling with very passive minor pieces. }
5. Bc4 d5
{ Black is winning a tempo compared to 4...d5?!, but that will not fundamentally change the position. White has space advantage and easy development. }
6. Bb3 Bg4
{ 6...Ng7  tries to bring back the knight into the game.  7.c4  It makes sense to use our development lead and start concrete play in the centre.  7...c6  8.cxd5  cxd5  9.Nc3  Developing with tempo, and forcing Black to make a huge concession and weaken the dark squares.  9...e6  10.Bh6  Nf5  11.Bxf8  Kxf8  12.Qd2  h5  13.Bc2+-  With ideas like O-O-O and h3-g4 to follow, Black's position is critical. This is basically a French Defence gone badly wrong. }
7. Nbd2 { We want to change the guard on f3. } 7... Ng7 8. h3 Bf5 9. c4
{ Opening the position a little bit, and trying to exploit the Black's minor pieces are still just looking for good squares. }
9... c6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nb1
{ With the idea of improving our worst piece and forcing the weakening ...e6 from Black. }
12... Bxb1 13. Rxb1
{ White has a clear advantage with the bishop pair. We can continue with moves like Qd3 and Bd2, but pushing g4 and completely restricting the g7-knight is an idea as well. }
