1. d4 g6 2. e4 Nf6
{ A very provocative and objectively dubious system, originally called the Horseshoe variation or the Norwegian Defense, but the most well-known name of the opening for a long time was the North Sea Defence.Magnus Carlsen started to employ it, probably because of the connection to Norway, since the opening doesn't really have any other merits if White plays well. He likes to call it 'the Norwegian Rat' and the new name became fashionable. }
3. e5
{ Of course, there is no reason not to attack that adventurous knight right away! }
3... Nh5
{ Strangely enough, this odd-looking knight move is Black's best here. Black is hoping that White will be tempted to immediately punish it.Instead,  3...Ng8  can't really be serious. White will just gain a big edge with the most natural moves.  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  Bg7  6.O-O±  Black has wasted a lot of time with the knight and gained nothing in return. }
4. Nf3
{ Just playing a normal game and completely ignoring Black's knight provocations is our best strategy here. After  4.g4?!  Ng7⇆  Black is building up some counterplay based on ...d6 or ...h5. }
4... d6
{ 4...d5?!  allows White free development.  5.c4  c6  6.Nc3  Ng7  At some point Black has to do something with that knight. We can see it is struggling if we don't take it.  7.Qb3  e6  Black's position is full of weak dark squares.  8.h4  Nd7  9.Bh6  Nf5  10.Bxf8  Nxf8  11.g4  Ne7  12.O-O-O±  White has a clear advantage, with much more space and ideas like h5. On the other hand, Black is struggling with very passive minor pieces. }
5. Bc4 Nc6
{ This move fits the best with the spirit of this opening. Black is trying to put some pressure on White's centre but it will not be easy.  5...Bg7?  Black continues with the development but this move nevertheless makes a very strange impression with the knight on h5.  6.Ng5  Combining the threat of g4 with the attack on the f7-pawn and it is already too late to stabilize the position!  6...O-O  7.g4+-  and Black is losing a piece, so they should go for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/4P1Nn/2BP4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  7.Qf3!  dxc4  8.Qxf7+  Kd7  9.Qxc4  c6  Black has to take care of the king but in the meantime, we will win back the piece.  10.g4+-  .   5...dxe5?!  It is not very logical to invite the knight to e5 with tempo.  6.Nxe5  e6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Be3  By this point it is already clear that Black hasn't achieved anything with the knight on h5.  8...Nd7  9.g4  Nhf6  10.Qe2±  We can castle long and then start pushing our h-pawn. White has a very serious advantage.   5...c6  has been played only 3 times, but all the games are from Richard Rapport!  6.O-O  Bg7?  Again this is very bad and not working at all with the knight on h6.  7.h3!  We have the winning threat g4.  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  After the queen trade, the g4-idea is still there.  9...f5  10.Ng5+-  Black's position is full of holes. It will be tough to avoid material losses in the next couple of moves. Black's best is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2pp2p1/4P2n/2BP4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  and that's why 5...c6 doesn't really deserve a trainable. Conceptually, it is very similar to 5...d5.  7.Bb3  Bg4  8.Nbd2  The knight is pretty strong on f3, so we are planning to replace it after the trade.  8...Bh6  9.h3  Be6  Very awkward, but at least not developing White.  9...Bxf3  10.Nxf3  Bxc1  11.Qxc1±  With Qh6 or c4 coming in the next move, White has a great position.  10.c3  Na6  11.Re1  Intending to play Nf1.  11...Nc7  12.Nf1  Bxc1  13.Qxc1  We have managed to trade Black's most active minor piece, and now our opponent is left with passive pieces and no real pawn breaks.  13...Qd7  14.Qh6±  After Bd1, g4 will be an idea to win the knight on h5, since the sacrifice on g4 will not work anymore for Black. Also, we can freely push our queenside pawns to gain more space and to prepare for an attack if Black's king goes there. }
6. c3
{ A rare, but very strong move. White is supporting the d4-pawn and also opening up the b3-square for the queen. It is really tough to find a good solution for Black after this. }
6... dxe5
{ The only challenging reply.  6...Bg4??  is very logical. Black is increasing the pressure on the d4 and e5-squares. The only problem is that it is losing in 2 different ways.  7.Qb3!+-  The strongest, according to the computer, and indeed it looks very good. White is winning material.  7.Bxf7+  This typical tactical resource is working here.  7...Kxf7  8.Ng5++-  .   6...Bg7?  This is just bad, again and again.  7.Ng5!  O-O  and Black is losing a piece after  8.g4  dxe5  9.gxh5  exd4  10.O-O+-  .   6...Na5  Chasing away the bishop from this nice diagonal, and trying to make the f7-square less vulnerable.  7.Be2  Nc6  8.Qb3  Very unpleasant! We are setting up a reversed battery and unfortunately for Black, it will be tough to chase away the queen.  8...Na5??  9.Qa4+  And Black is losing a lot of material.  9...Nc6  fails to  10.d5+-  and after  9...c6  10.b4  Nc4  11.Bxc4  b5  12.Bxb5  cxb5  13.Qxb5+  Bd7  14.Qe2+-  With 2 extra pawns, White is completely winning.   6...Qd7  With the idea of covering the f7-square from d8 with the knight. This looks anything but good.  7.Qe2  Nd8  8.exd6  Using the fact that Black can't take back with a pawn. We enter a very nice position slightly resembling the Scandinavian.  8...Qxd6  9.O-O  Bg7  10.Re1  c6  11.Nbd2±  Bb3-Nc4-Bg5 are our next moves, with some serious pressure on Black's position. Notice that Black is losing a piece after  @@StartFEN@@r1bnkb1r/pppqpp1p/3P2p1/7n/2BP4/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd6??  9.Bb5!  Nc6  10.d5+-  . }
7. Qb3 { Of course! We are not interested in trading queens. } 7... e6
{ The more human approach. } 8. dxe5 a6
{ Intending ...b5 to develop the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9. Qc2
{ The queen was not doing much on b3 anymore, and sometimes it could be vulnerable to ...Na5 ideas. }
9... b5 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O Bg7 12. Rd1
{ 12.g4??  seems to win a piece, but it is rather losing the game!  12...Nxe5!  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.gxh5  Bxh2+!  and Black is mating.  15.Kxh2  Qh4+  16.Kg1  Qh1  . }
12... Qe7
{ Both sides are developing normally. Black would have a quite acceptable position if not for the knight on h5. }
13. Bg5
{ 13.g4?  is not losing by force now, but it's still very bad.  13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  O-O-O∓  Black is down a piece but our queenside is just a spectator in this game, while our king is completely alone. }
13... f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nbd2
{ With a serious structural advantage. White can be pretty optimistic about the future. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "37) The Norwegian Rat"]
[Black "The Norwegian Rat 3...Nh5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 Nf6
{ A very provocative and objectively dubious system, originally called the Horseshoe variation or the Norwegian Defense, but the most well-known name of the opening for a long time was the North Sea Defence.Magnus Carlsen started to employ it, probably because of the connection to Norway, since the opening doesn't really have any other merits if White plays well. He likes to call it 'the Norwegian Rat' and the new name became fashionable. }
3. e5
{ Of course, there is no reason not to attack that adventurous knight right away! }
3... Nh5
{ Strangely enough, this odd-looking knight move is Black's best here. Black is hoping that White will be tempted to immediately punish it.Instead,  3...Ng8  can't really be serious. White will just gain a big edge with the most natural moves.  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  Bg7  6.O-O±  Black has wasted a lot of time with the knight and gained nothing in return. }
4. Nf3
{ Just playing a normal game and completely ignoring Black's knight provocations is our best strategy here. After  4.g4?!  Ng7⇆  Black is building up some counterplay based on ...d6 or ...h5. }
4... d6
{ 4...d5?!  allows White free development.  5.c4  c6  6.Nc3  Ng7  At some point Black has to do something with that knight. We can see it is struggling if we don't take it.  7.Qb3  e6  Black's position is full of weak dark squares.  8.h4  Nd7  9.Bh6  Nf5  10.Bxf8  Nxf8  11.g4  Ne7  12.O-O-O±  White has a clear advantage, with much more space and ideas like h5. On the other hand, Black is struggling with very passive minor pieces. }
5. Bc4 Nc6
{ This move fits the best with the spirit of this opening. Black is trying to put some pressure on White's centre but it will not be easy.  5...Bg7?  Black continues with the development but this move nevertheless makes a very strange impression with the knight on h5.  6.Ng5  Combining the threat of g4 with the attack on the f7-pawn and it is already too late to stabilize the position!  6...O-O  7.g4+-  and Black is losing a piece, so they should go for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/4P1Nn/2BP4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  7.Qf3!  dxc4  8.Qxf7+  Kd7  9.Qxc4  c6  Black has to take care of the king but in the meantime, we will win back the piece.  10.g4+-  .   5...dxe5?!  It is not very logical to invite the knight to e5 with tempo.  6.Nxe5  e6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Be3  By this point it is already clear that Black hasn't achieved anything with the knight on h5.  8...Nd7  9.g4  Nhf6  10.Qe2±  We can castle long and then start pushing our h-pawn. White has a very serious advantage.   5...c6  has been played only 3 times, but all the games are from Richard Rapport!  6.O-O  Bg7?  Again this is very bad and not working at all with the knight on h6.  7.h3!  We have the winning threat g4.  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  After the queen trade, the g4-idea is still there.  9...f5  10.Ng5+-  Black's position is full of holes. It will be tough to avoid material losses in the next couple of moves. Black's best is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2pp2p1/4P2n/2BP4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  and that's why 5...c6 doesn't really deserve a trainable. Conceptually, it is very similar to 5...d5.  7.Bb3  Bg4  8.Nbd2  The knight is pretty strong on f3, so we are planning to replace it after the trade.  8...Bh6  9.h3  Be6  Very awkward, but at least not developing White.  9...Bxf3  10.Nxf3  Bxc1  11.Qxc1±  With Qh6 or c4 coming in the next move, White has a great position.  10.c3  Na6  11.Re1  Intending to play Nf1.  11...Nc7  12.Nf1  Bxc1  13.Qxc1  We have managed to trade Black's most active minor piece, and now our opponent is left with passive pieces and no real pawn breaks.  13...Qd7  14.Qh6±  After Bd1, g4 will be an idea to win the knight on h5, since the sacrifice on g4 will not work anymore for Black. Also, we can freely push our queenside pawns to gain more space and to prepare for an attack if Black's king goes there. }
6. c3
{ A rare, but very strong move. White is supporting the d4-pawn and also opening up the b3-square for the queen. It is really tough to find a good solution for Black after this. }
6... dxe5
{ The only challenging reply.  6...Bg4??  is very logical. Black is increasing the pressure on the d4 and e5-squares. The only problem is that it is losing in 2 different ways.  7.Qb3!+-  The strongest, according to the computer, and indeed it looks very good. White is winning material.  7.Bxf7+  This typical tactical resource is working here.  7...Kxf7  8.Ng5++-  .   6...Bg7?  This is just bad, again and again.  7.Ng5!  O-O  and Black is losing a piece after  8.g4  dxe5  9.gxh5  exd4  10.O-O+-  .   6...Na5  Chasing away the bishop from this nice diagonal, and trying to make the f7-square less vulnerable.  7.Be2  Nc6  8.Qb3  Very unpleasant! We are setting up a reversed battery and unfortunately for Black, it will be tough to chase away the queen.  8...Na5??  9.Qa4+  And Black is losing a lot of material.  9...Nc6  fails to  10.d5+-  and after  9...c6  10.b4  Nc4  11.Bxc4  b5  12.Bxb5  cxb5  13.Qxb5+  Bd7  14.Qe2+-  With 2 extra pawns, White is completely winning.   6...Qd7  With the idea of covering the f7-square from d8 with the knight. This looks anything but good.  7.Qe2  Nd8  8.exd6  Using the fact that Black can't take back with a pawn. We enter a very nice position slightly resembling the Scandinavian.  8...Qxd6  9.O-O  Bg7  10.Re1  c6  11.Nbd2±  Bb3-Nc4-Bg5 are our next moves, with some serious pressure on Black's position. Notice that Black is losing a piece after  @@StartFEN@@r1bnkb1r/pppqpp1p/3P2p1/7n/2BP4/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd6??  9.Bb5!  Nc6  10.d5+-  . }
7. Qb3 { Of course! We are not interested in trading queens. } 7... Bg7
{ The best move according to the engine. :@@EndBracket@@ It is not easy to give up the f7-pawn with a check. }
8. Bxf7+ Kf8 9. Bc4
{ Since of course by now we are not following any kind of theory, I chose the most practical move. This is the easiest to play without remembering much. Both  9.Nxe5!?  and  9.Ng5!?  are maybe even stronger and both worth investigating. }
9... Na5
{ Black absolutely has to take the light-squared bishop for their king to get some kind of safety. }
10. Qa4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 exd4 12. cxd4 Bg4
{ Black is creating counterplay against the d4-pawn. } 13. Ng5
{ But we have stronger threats. } 13... Qe8 14. Nc3 h6 15. h3
{ Useful intermediate move, before centralising the knight. } 15... Bd7 16.
Nge4
{ Black has a weaker king and a worse structure and has clearly failed to reach the active counterplay usually aimed at in this opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Malinoise Defence: 1.d4 c6 2.c4 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c6
{ It is a rare first move, but there is nothing wrong with it. Black offers White the chance to go for the Caro-Kann with  2.e4  d5  or, if we play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  , after  2...d5  the game would just transpose to the Slav Defence. }
2. c4 b5
{ Black doesn't want the Slav. Instead, we enter the Malinoise Defence. Black is attacking the centre from the flank, but even though they will be able to get rid of the c4-pawn, White will retain control over the middle of the board. }
3. cxb5 cxb5 4. e4 { Of course, there is no reason to refrain from this move. }
4... Bb7 5. Bd3
{ Instead,  5.Bxb5  would be a great exchange for Black after  5...Bxe4  : a central pawn for a b-pawn. }
5... Nf6 { Black keeps attacking on e4. } 6. Nd2
{ Very important move!  6.Qe2  looks also very natural, but the point of the knight move is providing a retreat square for the light-squared bishop on b1! After Qe2, Black can play  6...Nc6!  7.Nf3  Nb4!  and take our bishop. }
6... Nc6 7. Ngf3 Qb6
{ Instead,  7...Nb4  wouldn't make much sense now, since we can just play  8.Bb1  and then kick back the knight with a3. }
8. d5 Nb4 9. Bb1 e6
{ Black is playing very aggressively, challenging our centre with every move. }
10. O-O exd5 11. e5
{ Even though Black has managed to win a pawn, they have lost piece coordination. Also, the extra pawn on d5 is not a particularly strong asset. }
11... Ne4 12. Nb3
{ White has a very nice position with easy developing moves to follow. } *

