[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Saint George Defence: 1...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 a6
{ The St. George Defence. Of course, not the best possible first move for Black, but shouldn't be underestimated either. Black just wants to play a game without any theory. }
2. e4 e6
{ Of course, it is extremely unlikely to face this position. Still, it deserves a short line to show how to react, because we have a good chance of ending up in some interesting French territory if we are not careful. }
3. Nf3
{ My recommendation is to stay flexible: even though Black played ...e6, that doesn't mean they had to play ...d5 in the next move. }
3... d5
{ If instead  3...b5  , then we can react as in the main line with  4.a4  Bb7  5.Nbd2  b4  6.Bd3  and we are transposing tothe 2...b5 line. }
4. exd5
{ The easiest solution is to go for the Exchange French, since here, in contrast with closed positions in the French, the ...a6 move is not useful at all, just a waste of time. }
4... exd5 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Be7
{ Black already can't put this bishop on the more active d6-square, because of the Re1 check. }
7. Re1 O-O 8. h3
{ And we have a small but pleasant advantage by playing moves like Bf4, Nbd2, c3, Qc2, and eventually putting the knight on e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Saint George Defence: 1...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 a6
{ The St. George Defence. Of course, not the best possible first move for Black, but shouldn't be underestimated either. Black just wants to play a game without any theory. }
2. e4 b5 3. a4 Bb7
{ If instead  3...b4  , then after  4.Nf3  Bb7  5.Nbd2  we are back to the 3...Bb7 line anyway. }
4. Nd2
{ The best way to protect the pawn because, if the knight went to c3, Black always has the b4 idea, and if Bd3, then we can't react with e5 so easily anymore because the pawn on g2 would be hanging. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 { Now the bishop does a really good job on f1! } 5... Nd5 6.
Ngf3
{ Now the pawn on b5 is finally dropping for free! In case of  6.axb5  axb5  7.Rxa8  Bxa8  8.Bxb5  , Black has the very nice  8...Ne3!  with Bxg2 next and a very messy position. }
6... b4 7. Bd3 e6
{ 7...Nf4?  looks tempting, but the knight will have no way back if it takes on g2!  8.Be4!  Nxg2+  Otherwise Nf4 didn't make any sense  9.Kf1  Bxe4  10.Nxe4+-  and with this recapture, the knight's escape route via f4 is under control. }
8. Ne4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. c4 bxc3 11. bxc3
{ We have built a perfect centre. Next is active play against the black king, highlighted by moves like Bc2 and Qb3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Saint George Defence: 1...a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 a6
{ The St. George Defence. Of course, not the best possible first move for Black, but shouldn't be underestimated either. Black just wants to play a game without any theory. }
2. e4 b5 3. a4 Bb7
{ If instead  3...b4  , then after  4.Nf3  Bb7  5.Nbd2  we are back to the 3...Bb7 line anyway. }
4. Nd2
{ The best way to protect the pawn because, if the knight went to c3, Black always has the b4 idea, and if Bd3, then we can't react with e5 so easily anymore because the pawn on g2 would be hanging. }
4... b4 5. Ngf3 e6 6. Bd3
{ Our setup is the same as againstthe 4...Nf6 line. These are simply the best squares for our pieces. }
6... c5
{ With this move the position will have a Sicilian Defence type of character, where Black is seriously behind in the development. }
7. O-O cxd4 { 7...d6?  is featured and convincingly punished inLi-Wheeler. } 8.
Nxd4
{ If Black played now  8...Nf6  , then we play  9.e5  with Nc4 and Qg4 to follow. Therefore, as usual in the Sicilian, Black first makes a move to prepare Nf6. }
8... d6
{ Or  8...Qc7  9.Re1  @@StartBracket@@Preparing to meet Nf6 with e5.@@EndBracket@@  Nc6  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a5±  Isolating Black's queenside pawns and creating a nice square for the knight on b6. }
9. c3
{ Black has just made another pawn move so, since we are much better developed, we start to open the position before Black can finish development. }
9... bxc3 10. Qb3
{ With a huge initiative for White. One possible continuation of the game is  10...cxd2  11.Qxb7  dxc1=Q  12.Rfxc1  Nd7  13.Nc6  Qc8  14.Bxa6  and White is winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Polish Defence: 1.d4 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b5 { This is the so-called Polish Defence. } 2. e4 Bb7
{ Instead of protecting the pawn with a6, Black is counterattacking on e4. } 3.
Bxb5
{ I believe this is the easiest way to play for White. Normally this shouldn't be such a great exchange for us, the e4-pawn for the b5-pawn, but here dynamics will also come into play. Despite Black having an extra pawn in the centre, it will still be White who can get some space advantage there. }
3... Bxe4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black can also start with  4...e6  , but it will not change much. After  5.O-O  Nf6  6.c4  we are back to 4...Nf6. }
5. c4 { We want to play with Nc3 and d5. } 5... e6 6. O-O Bb7 7. Ba4
{ A very important move to remember! When we are ready to play d5, the move to check is c6! If our centre disappears, then we have no advantage.   Instead,  7.d5?!  would be an instructive mistake:  7...c6!  8.dxc6  Nxc6  with an equal position. }
7... Be7 8. Nc3 { Transposes tothe 6...Be7 line. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Polish Defence (and other quick ...b5 ideas)"]
[Black "Polish Defence: 1.d4 b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b5 { This is the so-called Polish Defence. } 2. e4 Bb7
{ Instead of protecting the pawn with a6, Black is counterattacking on e4. } 3.
Bxb5
{ I believe this is the easiest way to play for White. Normally this shouldn't be such a great exchange for us, the e4-pawn for the b5-pawn, but here dynamics will also come into play. Despite Black having an extra pawn in the centre, it will still be White who can get some space advantage there. }
3... Bxe4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black can also start with  4...e6  , but it will not change much. After  5.O-O  Nf6  6.c4  we are back to 4...Nf6. }
5. c4 { We want to play with Nc3 and d5. } 5... e6 6. O-O Be7 7. Nc3 Bg6
{ This diagonal is pretty empty. It's not surprising that by far  7...Bb7  is the main move. }
8. Ne5 O-O 9. Re1 { We are centralising and improving our pieces. } 9... c6 10.
Ba4 Qc7 { Black is preparing to push ...d6. } 11. Qf3 { Not yet! } 11... Rc8
{ Now ...d6 will come, but Black had to misplace the rook for this to happen. }
12. Bf4 d6 13. Nxg6 hxg6
{ Black is just about to finish the development but, before that, we can gain some big positional advantage. }
14. d5 e5
{ Instead,  14...cxd5?  is not good, because after  15.cxd5  e5  16.Bxe5  dxe5  17.d6!  we are taking the rook on a8. }
15. Bd2
{ Since the bishop on g6 was taken, Black has big issues on the light squares. }
15... cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5
{ We can freely start pushing our queenside majority. } *

