3... Bxe4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black can also start with  4...e6  , but it will not change much. After  5.O-O  Nf6  6.c4  we are back to 4...Nf6. }
5. c4 { We want to play with Nc3 and d5. } 5... e6 6. O-O Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Ba4
{ Not only we can never blunder Black's ...c6 trick: sometimes the bishop can be useful on the b1-h7 diagonal, and also steps away from the advance of the b-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. Re1
{ 9.d5  was already good, but this waiting move is extremely effective, since it is very tough to play anything else than ...d6 here with Black. Then, d5 is not only gaining space, but basically breaking through because of the weakness of the e6-square. }
9... d6
{ If instead  9...Na6  , then simply  10.a3!±  with the idea of b4 and the knight is doing nothing on a6.   Against  9...d5  we play  10.c5!  creating some big space advantage on the queenside and also making both black bishops very bad; after Bf4 we will start pushing our queenside pawns.   9...c6  is an attempt to keep the position and stop d5.  10.Bf4  d6  Black can't really push any of their central pawns.  11.b4  a5  12.a3±  We will play h3 next, to keep the bishop on that unpleasant diagonal, and then will start active operations on the queenside. }
10. d5 { Black has to react. } 10... e5
{ If  10...exd5  11.cxd5  then the knight will come to d4 very soon, which is not a good development for Black. }
11. c5 { Continuing the aggressive approach. } 11... dxc5 12. Nxe5 Nxd5 13. Qf3
{ With a better structure and more active pieces, White can be pretty optimistic at this point. You can find the gameDi Caro-Tomescu in the Model Games section to see how play can go on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "39) Queen's Knight Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Knight Defence: 3...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6
{ The Queen's Knight Defence, a very provocative opening, but much worse than its 'twin' opening, the Alekhine Defence, probably because the pawn Black is provoking to go forward is already protected by the queen. }
2. d5 Ne5 3. e4
{ We are controlling the centre with two pawns, whereas Black only has an unstable knight there. }
3... Nf6 { This is way too provocative! } 4. f4 Ng6 5. e5 Ng8
{ The knight has to go back. If instead  5...Ne4?  , then  6.f5  Nxe5  7.Qd4+-  is winning a piece. }
6. Nf3 { Black's opening play has failed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "39) Queen's Knight Defence"]
[Black "Queen's Knight Defence: 3...e6 4.f4 exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6
{ The Queen's Knight Defence, a very provocative opening, but much worse than its 'twin' opening, the Alekhine Defence, probably because the pawn Black is provoking to go forward is already protected by the queen. }
2. d5 Ne5 3. e4
{ We are controlling the centre with two pawns, whereas Black only has an unstable knight there. }
3... e6
{ Finally controlling the centre with a pawn as well. Instead,  3...Ng6  4.f4  would lead to the same thing as the main line, since Black plays  4...e6  or  4...e5  and in both cases we answer with  5.dxe6  .   3...d6?!  isn't challenging the centre and gives us a very easy opening play:  4.f4  Nd7  5.Nf3  c6  6.c4  Ngf6  7.Nc3±  With Bd3 and O-O coming, White just has a very comfortable advantage because of the centre. }
4. f4 exd5 5. Nc3
{ An important move. The knight is covering the e4-square and the queen on d1!   5.fxe5?  Qh4+  when the king can't hide from the checks:  6.Ke2  Qh5+  7.Kd2  Qh6+  8.Kc3  Qc6  with a perpetual check.  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/8/3pP3/4P2q/8/PPP3PP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  was not possible because of  6...Qxe4  . }
5... Bb4 6. fxe5
{ In this case we can already take, since the knight is not controlling the e4-square because of the pin, but it will protect the queen in the crucial moment. }
6... Qh4+ 7. Ke2 Bxc3
{ If instead  7...Qh5+  , then we can just play  8.Kf2  thanks to our knight on c3, and we are just up a piece. }
8. bxc3 Qh5+ 9. Ke1 Qh4+ 10. g3 { The idea is to trap the queen on h1! } 10...
Qxe4+ 11. Kf2 Qxh1 12. Nf3
{ And Black doesn't have the bishop anymore to stop our plan of Qd2 and Bg2. }
*

