1. d4 Nc6
{ The Queen's Knight Defence, a very provocative opening, but much worse than its 'twin' opening, the Alekhine Defence, probably because the pawn Black is provoking to go forward is already protected by the queen. }
2. d5 Ne5 3. e4
{ We are controlling the centre with two pawns, whereas Black only has an unstable knight there. }
3... e6
{ Finally controlling the centre with a pawn as well. Instead,  3...Ng6  4.f4  would lead to the same thing as the main line, since Black plays  4...e6  or  4...e5  and in both cases we answer with  5.dxe6  .   3...d6?!  isn't challenging the centre and gives us a very easy opening play:  4.f4  Nd7  5.Nf3  c6  6.c4  Ngf6  7.Nc3±  With Bd3 and O-O coming, White just has a very comfortable advantage because of the centre. }
4. f4 exd5 5. Nc3
{ An important move. The knight is covering the e4-square and the queen on d1!   5.fxe5?  Qh4+  when the king can't hide from the checks:  6.Ke2  Qh5+  7.Kd2  Qh6+  8.Kc3  Qc6  with a perpetual check.  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/8/3pP3/4P2q/8/PPP3PP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  was not possible because of  6...Qxe4  . }
