[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6
{ The Queen's Knight Defence, a very provocative opening, but much worse than its 'twin' opening, the Alekhine Defence, probably because the pawn Black is provoking to go forward is already protected by the queen. }
2. d5 Ne5 3. e4
{ We are controlling the centre with two pawns, whereas Black only has an unstable knight there. }
3... e6
{ Finally controlling the centre with a pawn as well. Instead,  3...Ng6  4.f4  would lead to the same thing as the main line, since Black plays  4...e6  or  4...e5  and in both cases we answer with  5.dxe6  .   3...d6?!  isn't challenging the centre and gives us a very easy opening play:  4.f4  Nd7  5.Nf3  c6  6.c4  Ngf6  7.Nc3±  With Bd3 and O-O coming, White just has a very comfortable advantage because of the centre. }
4. f4 Ng6 5. dxe6 fxe6 6. h4
{ A very rare move, played only in 6 OTB games, but it looks very effective and principled to play h4-h5 against the knight on g6! }
6... Nxh4
{ Accepting the pawn, but Black can't keep it for long.   6...h5?  stops our pawn, but weakens every other possible square.  7.Bd3  Bc5  8.Nc3  d6  9.Nf3+-  Black has so many weaknesses that their position is close to completely lost. }
7. Qg4 Ng6 8. Rxh7
{ There are many good ways for us, but why not to play with even material if we can still keep our positional advantages?! }
8... Qf6 9. Rxh8 Nxh8 { 6 moves with this knight, to reach h8 from b8! } 10.
Nc3
{ With Nf3-Be3 and long castle coming, the future doesn't look bright for Black's knights. }
