[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "40) Mexican Defence"]
[Black "Mexican Defence: 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5-square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... d6
{ Black insists on playing ...e5, but it is not the same as in the previous move, since the d6-pawn blocks the diagonal of the f8-bishop and it can't come to its ideal c5-square. }
4. Nc3
{ 4.d5  is a move I don't like so much because we would only help Black to solve the issue of the f8-bishop.  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Nc3  e6!  and Black's position is perfectly playable, with the bishop coming to c5 or b4. }
4... Bg4
{ This move is dubious. Taking on f3 is not really a threat since it can invite a very strong attack with the kingside pawns. Also, it was already possible to play with ...e5, so this move was not necessary for that reason either. }
5. d5 Nb8
{ 5...Bxf3?  This move will only give us an extra tempo to develop our kingside initiative.  6.exf3  Ne5  7.f4  Ned7  8.g4!  with a huge initiative on the kingside and Qf3-Be3-h4-g5-Bh3 coming. Black's position is already lost, according to the computer. }
6. Qb3 { Another downside of the ...Bg4 move: the pawn on b7 is vulnerable. }
6... Qc8 7. h3
{ Clarifying the situation with the bishop. Then, we can start our kingside play. }
7... Bxf3 8. exf3 g6 9. g4 Bg7 10. h4 { We want to play h5! } 10... h5 11. g5
{ Black stopped h5, but with that they also weakened the g6-square, so the f4-f5 idea will be even more unpleasant for them. }
11... Nfd7 12. Bh3
{ With O-O and f4-f5 coming very soon, Black is in very bad shape. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "40) Mexican Defence"]
[Black "Mexican Defence: 3...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5-square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... d6
{ Black insists on playing ...e5, but it is not the same as in the previous move, since the d6-pawn blocks the diagonal of the f8-bishop and it can't come to its ideal c5-square. }
4. Nc3
{ 4.d5  is a move I don't like so much because we would only help Black to solve the issue of the f8-bishop.  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Nc3  e6!  and Black's position is perfectly playable, with the bishop coming to c5 or b4. }
4... e5
{ This is Black's main idea in this opening, but it's a passive setup. } 5. d5
{ We are forced to block the centre, but we have a nice space advantage. } 5...
Ne7 6. e4 g6
{ If we are not careful here, but just continue with  7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  , then we are already in the starting position of the main line of the KID!This position is usually reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Be2  e5  7.O-O  Nc6  8.d5  Ne7  .  We don't want to go for this, as our anti-KID system isthe Averbakh. }
7. c5
{ This is a good move! We can immediately start playing on the queenside using the fact that, as the bishop is not on the long diagonal yet, the e5-pawn is hanging after ...dxc5. }
7... dxc5 8. Nxe5 Bg7 9. Bb5+ c6
{ If instead  9...Nd7  , then we can develop our last minor piece.  10.Bf4  O-O  11.Bxd7  Bxd7  12.O-O±  and we have a clear advantage with a dominant central control. }
10. dxc6 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 O-O
{ Black has the ...Nxe4 idea to highlight the unprotected position of our knight on e5. }
12. Re1
{ It will be not easy for Black to prove some compensation for the missing pawn. }
*

