{ We are forced to block the centre, but we have a nice space advantage. } 5...
Ne7 6. e4 g6
{ If we are not careful here, but just continue with  7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  , then we are already in the starting position of the main line of the KID!This position is usually reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Be2  e5  7.O-O  Nc6  8.d5  Ne7  .  We don't want to go for this, as our anti-KID system isthe Averbakh. }
7. c5
{ This is a good move! We can immediately start playing on the queenside using the fact that, as the bishop is not on the long diagonal yet, the e5-pawn is hanging after ...dxc5. }
7... Bg7 8. cxd6 cxd6
{ Normally, White needs a lot of preparation and precise play to achieve such a pawn structure in the main line of the King's Indian. Here, we did it in the easiest possible way. }
9. Qa4+
{ Another unpleasant move to face. Black has to solve concrete problems before they can castle. }
9... Bd7
{ If instead  9...Nd7  , then  10.Qa3!  is annoying for Black. We don't go to b4 this time, so we can meet ...Nc5 with b4 anytime. }
10. Qb4 Qb8
{ 10...Qc7  is even worse, walking into tempi: first from the knight and then from the rook.  11.Nb5!  Bxb5  12.Bxb5  Nd7  13.Bg5±  with Rc1 coming next. }
11. a4
{ Securing our queenside space, so Black can't even dream of eventually playing with ...a5-...b5. }
11... O-O 12. Be2
{ We have clear targets on the queenside: the d6-pawn and the c-file with the entry square on c7. Black has to try to create something on the kingside. }
12... Nh5 13. O-O Nf4
{ 13...f5  14.Ng5!  using the weakness of the e6-square. } 14. Bc4
{ We have clear targets and play on the queenside, while it is very difficult for Black to make progress on the kingside.   For instance,  14...Kh8  15.Be3  and  15...f5  still doesn't work because of  16.Bxf4!  exf4  17.e5!+-  and White is crushing in the centre because of the unprotected knight on e7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "40) Mexican Defence"]
[Black "Mexican Defence: 3...d6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5-square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... d6
{ Black insists on playing ...e5, but it is not the same as in the previous move, since the d6-pawn blocks the diagonal of the f8-bishop and it can't come to its ideal c5-square. }
4. Nc3
{ 4.d5  is a move I don't like so much because we would only help Black to solve the issue of the f8-bishop.  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Nc3  e6!  and Black's position is perfectly playable, with the bishop coming to c5 or b4. }
4... e5
{ This is Black's main idea in this opening, but it's a passive setup. } 5. d5
{ We are forced to block the centre, but we have a nice space advantage. } 5...
Ne7 6. e4 Ng6
{ The knight is protecting the e5-pawn, so we can't play c5 that quickly. On the other hand, this setup is very passive from Black. Their bishop can't go to g7 and, besides protecting the pawn, the knight on g6 is not doing much good. }
7. h4 { Typical play against a knight on g6! } 7... h5
{ Black stops h5, but gives up the g5-square.   If  7...Bg4  we continue typically restricting the g6-knight with  8.g3  Be7  9.Be2⩲  with the idea of regrouping our knight to e3. Then we can start our play on the queenside. }
8. Ng5 Be7 9. Be2 Bg4 10. g3
{ The knight is horrible on g6. We will continue with f3 and O-O and start playing on the queenside. }
*

