[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "40) Mexican Defence"]
[Black "Mexican Defence: 3...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5-square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... e6 { Black's main move by far. } 4. a3
{ Stopping ...Bb4 and preparing to play Nc3. With this, we don't allow Black to play in Bogo Indian-style with ...Bb4, ...d6-...e5 and so on. Instead, they will have to develop the bishop on g7 and play a King's Indian type of position. }
4... d5
{ Surprisingly, played in a lot of games. ...Nc6 fits much better with ...d6-...e5 ideas, where the knight can be much more useful in the fight for the centre. }
5. Nc3 Be7
{ Instead,  5...Bd6  is worse because we can play  6.Bg5!  and create an unpleasant pin.  6...dxc4  7.e4  e5  8.d5  Ne7  9.Nd2±  with Nxc4 to follow. We have a stable advantage. }
6. Bf4 dxc4
{ This is not a problem. We can quickly regain the pawn by simple tactical means. }
7. e4 Na5 8. Bxc4 Nxc4 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qxc4
{ We have full control over the centre, and the black bishops are struggling to find diagonals. }
*

