1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Mexican Defence. Black wants to play ...e5, forcing us to play d5, then manoeuvre the knight to e7-g6, and have the g1-a7 diagonal for their bishop thanks to the control over the c5-square. }
3. Nf3 { The most popular response from White, stopping Black's ...e5 idea. }
3... e6 { Black's main move by far. } 4. a3
{ Stopping ...Bb4 and preparing to play Nc3. With this, we don't allow Black to play in Bogo Indian-style with ...Bb4, ...d6-...e5 and so on. Instead, they will have to develop the bishop on g7 and play a King's Indian type of position. }
4... d6 5. Nc3 g6 6. d5
{ A rare move, but it is the most compatible with our repertoire. If instead  6.e4  or  6.g3  , then we will enter a King's Indian Defence with an extra tempo since Black is going to play ...e5 in 2 moves and not in 1.Having said that, we used that extra tempo to play a3, which is definitely somewhat helpful in many lines, but it doesn't make as big a difference as to make it worth it to learn a completely new system against the KID. }
6... Ne7 7. dxe6
{ We don't want to wait for Black to play ...e5 and transpose into the KID! }
7... fxe6 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O
{ This position is almost completely unexplored, but I like that our bishops will be great on the long diagonals, whereas Black will not have the usual KID-type of counterplay against our king. }
