[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "41) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit: 2...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. It has become quite popular in recent years, mainly thanks to the fact that chess is played online more often than ever, and that bullet experts are premoving this move against anything. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2. dxe5
{ A central pawn for free. This gambit just can't be good for Black. On the other hand, it is maybe the toughest opening to analyse. It is very hard to make a move for White which will not give a decent advantage, so picking from 15 possible moves is not easy. }
2... d6 3. Nf3 { Developing and protecting the pawn. } 3... Nc6 4. Bg5
{ Again, let's just develop. Many other moves are good too, but if we can develop so freely against a gambit, then it is losing its power. }
4... Qd7 5. exd6 Bxd6 6. Nc3
{ With e3-Be2-O-O to follow, I don't see any compensation for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "41) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit: 2...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. It has become quite popular in recent years, mainly thanks to the fact that chess is played online more often than ever, and that bullet experts are premoving this move against anything. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2. dxe5
{ A central pawn for free. This gambit just can't be good for Black. On the other hand, it is maybe the toughest opening to analyse. It is very hard to make a move for White which will not give a decent advantage, so picking from 15 possible moves is not easy. }
2... Bc5
{ Not a good move. It just involves a famous trick that is often used in bullet games. }
3. Nf3 d6 4. Bf4
{ The original trick happens after  4.exd6  , but I would suggest again that, if we can, let's just develop first. }
4... Ne7 5. exd6 Nbc6
{ The main idea of the move is for me to illustrate the only trick behind the 2...Bc5 move :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. e3
{ With a clear advantage for White, thanks to the extra pawn.   If instead  6.dxe7??  then Black can play  6...Bxf2+  and win! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "41) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit: 3...Qe7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. It has become quite popular in recent years, mainly thanks to the fact that chess is played online more often than ever, and that bullet experts are premoving this move against anything. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2. dxe5
{ A central pawn for free. This gambit just can't be good for Black. On the other hand, it is maybe the toughest opening to analyse. It is very hard to make a move for White which will not give a decent advantage, so picking from 15 possible moves is not easy. }
2... Nc6 3. Nf3 Qe7
{ The main line of the Gambit; Black is trying to take the pawn on e5, and also introduces ...Qb4 ideas to the game. }
4. Bf4
{ The simplest move, in my opinion. There is no reason to give our nice e5-pawn back. }
4... Qb4+ 5. Bd2 Qxb2
{ Black has moved their queen 3 times out of the first 5 moves, has taken a pawn on b2, and is not even up a pawn. It doesn't sound very appealing to me. }
6. Nc3
{ I believe this is the only moment when we can seriously go wrong.  6.Bc3??  would be a huge mistake and Black is not just better after  6...Bb4  , but the game is actually over! The prettiest line is  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1  checkmate. }
6... Nb4 7. Nd4
{ The only good move against ...Nb4, but it is winning, and not so hard to find. :@@EndBracket@@ }
7... c5 8. Rb1 { Again the only move for us, but completely winning. } 8... Qa3
9. Ndb5 Qa5 10. a3
{ Black is playing with only 2 pieces, and now the knight can't move because then Nd5 and the game is over after some Nc7+. }
10... a6 11. axb4 cxb4 12. Ra1
{ We will play Nd5 against anything in the next move, and Black has to resign. }
*

