{ I believe this is the only moment when we can seriously go wrong.  6.Bc3??  would be a huge mistake and Black is not just better after  6...Bb4  , but the game is actually over! The prettiest line is  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1  checkmate. }
6... Bb4 7. Rb1 Qa3
{ Instead, Black has two alternative ways to sacrifice the queen.   7...Qxc3  is the best one because, even though here Black gets less material in return, they will have more positional control.  8.Bxc3  Bxc3+  9.Nd2  Nxe5  , but of course 2 minor pieces and a pawn should not be enough compensation for the queen. The game can continue, for example,  10.e3  Nf6  11.Rb3  Ba5   @@StartBracket@@  11...Ne4  is losing on the spot to  12.Rxc3  Nxc3  13.Qa1+-  @@EndBracket@@  12.Rb5  Bc3  13.Bd3±   7...Bxc3  is the worst version for Black:  8.Rxb2  Bxb2  9.c3!  forcing the bishop to move again and escape,  9...Ba3  10.Qb3  Be7  11.e4  and White is winning, as Bc4 is coming in the next move. }
8. Nd5 { Black has huge problems with the protection of the c7-square. } 8...
Ba5 9. Rb5 { Threatening to take on a5 and then on c7. } 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2
Kd8 11. e4 { Let's not forget that the material is equal! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "41) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit: 3...Qe7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. It has become quite popular in recent years, mainly thanks to the fact that chess is played online more often than ever, and that bullet experts are premoving this move against anything. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2. dxe5
{ A central pawn for free. This gambit just can't be good for Black. On the other hand, it is maybe the toughest opening to analyse. It is very hard to make a move for White which will not give a decent advantage, so picking from 15 possible moves is not easy. }
2... Nc6 3. Nf3 Qe7
{ The main line of the Gambit; Black is trying to take the pawn on e5, and also introduces ...Qb4 ideas to the game. }
4. Bf4
{ The simplest move, in my opinion. There is no reason to give our nice e5-pawn back. }
4... Qb4+ 5. Bd2 Qxb2
{ Black has moved their queen 3 times out of the first 5 moves, has taken a pawn on b2, and is not even up a pawn. It doesn't sound very appealing to me. }
6. Nc3
{ I believe this is the only moment when we can seriously go wrong.  6.Bc3??  would be a huge mistake and Black is not just better after  6...Bb4  , but the game is actually over! The prettiest line is  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1  checkmate. }
6... Bb4 7. Rb1 Qa3
{ Instead, Black has two alternative ways to sacrifice the queen.   7...Qxc3  is the best one because, even though here Black gets less material in return, they will have more positional control.  8.Bxc3  Bxc3+  9.Nd2  Nxe5  , but of course 2 minor pieces and a pawn should not be enough compensation for the queen. The game can continue, for example,  10.e3  Nf6  11.Rb3  Ba5   @@StartBracket@@  11...Ne4  is losing on the spot to  12.Rxc3  Nxc3  13.Qa1+-  @@EndBracket@@  12.Rb5  Bc3  13.Bd3±   7...Bxc3  is the worst version for Black:  8.Rxb2  Bxb2  9.c3!  forcing the bishop to move again and escape,  9...Ba3  10.Qb3  Be7  11.e4  and White is winning, as Bc4 is coming in the next move. }
8. Nd5 { Black has huge problems with the protection of the c7-square. } 8...
Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Qxa2 10. Rd1 Kd8 11. e4
{ Black is up a pawn here, but that's pretty much all the good things we can say about our opponent's position. Be2, O-O, attack and win is more or less our plan. }
*

