1. Nf3 b5 2. e4 Bb7 3. Bxb5 Bxe4 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4 e6 6. c4 Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7 8.
Ba4 O-O 9. Re1 d6 10. d5 e5 11. c5 dxc5 12. Nxe5 Nxd5 13. Qf3
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 13... c6
{ Logical move, neutralising the pressure on the long diagonal; however, the b7-bishop is not so happy about this development. }
14. Bc2
{ The bishop had lost its purpose on a4, and from c2 it sets up a nice trap. }
14... Nb4
{ Black is forcing the bishop to b1, but... from there it is as effective as from c2.   A@@EndBracket@@  14...Nd7  Unfortunately for Black, this natural move is losing material.  15.Qh3!  N7f6   15...N5f6??  It is very easy to refute this move.  16.Nxd7!  Qxd7  17.Qxd7  Nxd7  18.Rxe7+-  And Black lost a piece.  16.Nd7!  A very nice move, White wants to decoy/trade both black knights to give checkmate on h7.  16...h6  Relatively the best, but Black is just down an exchange for no compensation.   16...Bc8??  Allowing White to execute the plan.  17.Nxd5  cxd5  18.Nxf6+  Bxf6  19.Qxh7  17.Nxf8  Qxf8  18.Bd2+-  White's position is technically winning.   B@@EndBracket@@  14...Bf6  15.Ng4!  The bishop is not very well placed on f6, and Black still can't finish the development.  15...Bd4   15...Nd7  This move fails to a very nice refutation.  16.Nxd5  cxd5  17.Qf5!  Now the only move to avoid the checkmate is  17...g6  but that loses a lot of material:  18.Qxd7  Qxd7  19.Nxf6+  Kg7  20.Nxd7+-  .  16.Nh6+!  Another nice tactical shot from White!  16...gxh6  17.Qf5  There is no ...g6 now to protect the king.  17...Nf6  18.Bxh6+-  White has too many threats, starting from Qg5, or in case of ...Kh8, Bg5 and Ne4 are coming.   C@@EndBracket@@  14...Bd6  Trying to disturb the knight from another square is also losing on the spot.  15.Nxd5!  Eliminating the knight, which could be the main defender of the king after retreating to f6.  15...cxd5  16.Qh5  Black's kingside is falling apart.  16...g6  17.Nxg6  fxg6  18.Bxg6  hxg6   18...Qd7  This move also can't stop the rook to enter and decide the game.  19.Re6+-  .  19.Qxg6+  Kh8  20.Qh6+  Kg8  21.Re6+-  . }
15. Bb1 Nd7 16. Qh3
{ Again this tactical trick is winning material for White. } 16... Nf6 17. Nd7
g6 18. Nxf8 Qxf8 19. Bh6 Qd8 20. Qf3 Nfd5 21. h3
{ This move is okay, but White had faster ways to finish the game.  21.a3!  Na6  22.Ba2+-  . }
21... Nc7 22. Rd1
{ 22.a3  Nbd5  23.Ba2+-  This would have been the ideal square for the bishop in this structure. }
22... Nbd5 23. Be4 Qc8 24. Rac1
{ White finished the development, and converted his material advantage confidently. }
24... Qe6 25. Re1 Qf6 26. Qxf6 Bxf6 27. Na4 Ne6 28. Nxc5 Nxc5 29. Rxc5 Bxb2 30.
Bxd5 cxd5 31. Rb5 Bc3 32. Reb1 *

