1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. a3 Be7 5. e4 d5 6. e5 Nfd7 7. Qg4 O-O 8. Ndf3
{ All this has been coveredhere. } 8... Kh8 9. Nh3
{ My recommendation in the chapter is  9.Qh5!?  , but this move is also very interesting, Black's king is in big trouble either way. }
9... h6
{ Pretty much losing on the spot.  9...dxc4  is trying to do something in the centre, but White can keep everything under control.  10.Bxc4  c5  11.Bd3  cxd4  12.O-O  Nc6  13.Re1→  Qh5 is coming next with a huge attack.   Black has to try something in the centre. Otherwise, he will get checkmated without a fight.  9...c5  10.Bd3  f5  11.exf6  Nxf6  12.Qh4  Ne4  13.Bg5!  Bf6!  The only move for Black.  14.Bxf6!  White is switching to positional play.  14...Qxf6  15.Qxf6  Rxf6  16.Bxe4  dxe4  17.Ne5±  With a much better structure, White is looking forward to a clearly better endgame.   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1r1k/pp2b1pp/4p3/2pp2B1/2PPn2Q/P2B1N1N/1P3PPP/R3K2R b KQ - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxg5?  leads to very spectacular variations:  14.Nhxg5!  h6  15.Qh5  Qg6-h7 is coming.  15...Bxg5  16.Qg6  Kg8  Black's king is starting a long journey.  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Ne5+  Ke7  19.Qxg7+  Kd6  20.dxc5+  Kxc5  21.b4+  Kd4   21...Kb6  22.c5  22.Nf3+  Kxd3  23.Qd4+  Kc2  24.Ra2+  Kb3   24...Kc1  25.Qa1  25.Qb2+  Kxc4  26.Qe2+  Kb3  27.Qc2  A long but forced checkmating sequence.   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1r2/pp3kpQ/4p2p/2ppN1b1/2PP4/P2B4/1P3PPP/R3K2R b KQ - 5 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Ke8  or  18...Kf6  wouldn't have changed anything because of  19.Qg6+  Ke7  back to the main line.   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1r1k/pp1nbppp/4p3/2ppP3/2PP2Q1/P2B1N1N/1P3PPP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qe8  is not really a human move... and even this is not saving Black.  11.Bxh7!  f5!  The point behind ...Qe8.  12.Qg6  dxc4  13.Qxe8  Rxe8  14.Bg6  Rf8  15.d5!  Creating a very strong pawn on e6! @@StartBracket@@Or, if Black doesn't take, on d6.@@EndBracket@@  15...exd5  16.e6  Nf6  17.Nf4±  Bf7 + Ng6 is the main threat, but pushing the h-pawn doesn't look bad either. }
10. Qh5 { The sacrifice on h6 will decide the game. } 10... Kg8
{ 10...f5  doesn't help either, just loses differently.  11.Bxh6  gxh6  12.Qxh6+  Kg8  13.Nf4  Nb6  14.Qg6+  Kh8  15.h4+-  Ng5 is unstoppable and Black is getting checkmated. }
11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Qxh6 f5
{ 12...f6  There are quite a few ways for White to win here. Let's see an example:  13.Qg6+  Kh8  14.Bd3  f5  15.g4  Opening the kingside, so the rook on h1 can join.  15...Qe8  16.Qh6+  Kg8  17.gxf5+-  . }
13. Qg6+ Kh8 14. Nhg5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Qe7 16. O-O-O { Rd3-Rh3 is the idea. }
16... f4 17. Rd3 f3 { Black stops it, but now the g-file is opening up. } 18.
Rxf3 Rxf3 19. gxf3 *

