1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Bg5 8. Bxg5
Qxg5 9. Qg4 Qxg4 10. hxg4 f6
{ This is already a serious mistake from Black. The idea of the move is to play ...Nh6 next and stop g5 from White at that moment. The issue of Black's position however is rather the h7-pawn, and the problem of it will not be solved with this manoeuvre.   10...h6!  It is better to protect the h6-pawn right away and free the rook from this task.  11.a4  Nd7  12.a5  a6  13.Be2±  White's position looks very pleasant to me: the knight is going to c4 and we can also use the 3rd rank with our rooks. More on this linehere. }
11. a4 Nh6 12. f3 Kd7
{ Not a very natural square for the king. In case of a5 it will be very difficult to stop a6 because the knight is coming to b6 with a tempo.   12...a6  Probably the correct way to stop a5-a6 from White.  13.a5!  Nd7  14.Nd1  The knight is going to e3 and then not necessarily immediately to c4 because the f5-square is also very nice.  14...Kd8  15.Ne3  Kc7  16.c3±  Black's knights are suffering, while White has many ideas, such as transferring the bishop to a4, playing b4 at some moment, or placing the knight on c4 or f5. }
13. a5 Nf7
{ 13...a6  looks very ugly, but allowing a6 is even worse.  14.Na4  Now we can see that ...Kd7 was far from ideal.  14...Kd8  15.Nb6  Ra7  16.c3  Nd7  17.Nc4±  The bishop is going to a4 and then we are going to play b4 and also bring the rooks to the b and c-files. Black's position is horrible but not as losing as after allowing a6!   @@StartFEN@@rn5r/1p1k2pp/p2p1p1n/P1pPp3/N3P1P1/5P2/1PP3P1/R3KB1R b KQ - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kc7  15.Nb6  Ra7  16.b4!  With this nice temporary sacrifice we can solidify the knight on b6.  16...Nd7   If  16...cxb4  17.Rb1  17...Nd7  18.Rxb4+-  Black can't take on b6.  17.bxc5!  dxc5  18.Rb1+-  Black is playing without a rook, so it is time to turn our attention to the kingside and win the game there. }
14. Kd2 { Of course a good move, but  14.a6!  was already decisive. } 14... h6
15. a6 Kc8
{ 15...Nxa6  16.Bxa6  bxa6  17.Rxa6+-  Black is losing the a7 or the d6-pawn. @@StartBracket@@Eventually, both will drop.@@EndBracket@@   15...b6  is probably the best defensive try, but it looks anything but good.  16.Nb5  It is impossible to challenge this knight on b5.  16...Kd8  17.g3  Nd7  18.Bc4+-  The c3-b4 or the f4-e5 breakthroughs are going to win the game for White eventually. }
16. axb7+ Kxb7 17. Ra3 a6 18. Nd1
{ The knight is going to e3, and then we'll line up against the a6-pawn. }
18... Nd7 19. Ne3 Nb6 20. Be2 g6
{ 20...Ra7  Only way to protect a6.  21.Rha1  Rha8  22.Nf5  But now Black is losing the game on the other side of the board.  22...g5  23.Ne7  Nd8  24.Rh1+- }
21. Rha1 Kc7 22. Bxa6
{ White has won the pawn and converted it without any problems. } 22... Ra7 23.
Bb5 Rxa3 24. Rxa3 Ra8 25. Bc6 Rxa3 26. bxa3 Nc8 27. Be8 Nh8 28. Kc3 Kd8 29. Bb5
Nf7 30. a4 Ne7 31. a5 Kc7 32. Be8 Ng5 33. Kc4 Kd8 34. a6 Kc7 35. Kb5 Nh7 36.
Nc4 *

