[Black "4) Peter Meister vs. Norbert Roth, Germany 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ne4 4. a3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Qc2 Bf5 7. Nc3 Ng3 8. e4
Nxh1 9. exf5 dxe5 10. Be3 Be7
{ Black is trying to finish the development, but even if he manages, White will have a winning position by simply taking the knight on h1.   The alternative  10...Nd4  is coveredhere. }
11. Rd1 Qb8
{ Looks very ugly. The point is that after an eventual Nxe7+ the king and the queen will not get in a fork.   11...Qc8  This move doesn't help much either.  12.Qe4  To set up a battery against the h7-square.  12...O-O  13.Bd3  13...f6  Stopping the immediate checkmate attack, so we switch to plan B, and take the time to take the knight on h1.  14.Ke2  Nd4+  15.Nxd4  exd4  16.Qxd4+-  With a decisive material advantage for White. }
12. Nd5 O-O 13. Nxe5
{ Black was preparing for this move by playing ...Qb8 earlier. } 13... Nxe5 14.
Nxe7+ Kh8 15. f6
{ Before Black could play ...f6 himself, White is weakening the king's position. }
15... Rd8 16. Bg5 { Bringing a new piece to the attack! } 16... Rxd1+ 17. Qxd1
Ng6
{ 17...c5  Opening some space for the queen, but it is too late already.  18.fxg7+  Kxg7  19.Qh5  Threatening mate in 2 with Qh6+ and Bf6.  19...Kf8  20.Nd5+-  Even if by some miracle Black survives this attack, we can still take the knight on h1 and win the endgame. }
18. fxg7+ Kxg7 19. Qd4+
{ The queen is coming into the game with a tempo, and Black is helpless against White's attack. }
19... Kf8 20. Nxg6+ fxg6 { 20...hxg6  21.Qh8 } 21. Qf6+ Kg8 22. Qe6+
{ Black resigned here, since a forced checkmating sequence was coming:  22.Qe6+  Kg7  23.Bf6+  Kf8  24.Qe7+  Kg8  25.Qg7 }
