[Black "5) Jaromir Jambrich vs. Garvin Gray, ICCF e-mail 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. Nf3 Bc5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Ngxe5 7. Nxe5 Nxe5
8. f4 Nc6 9. Bd3 d6 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 a5 12. Kh1 Bd7
{ It is rather a waiting move from Black than a developing one, it is not clear what the bishop is exactly doing on d7, although it is hard to suggest a more active move.   12...Re8  is coveredhere. }
13. Qc2
{ Forcing some decisions from Black, who has to make some concessions on the kingside. }
13... f5
{ 13...h6  This move was also possible. The problem is that it will be harder to move the f-pawn after this because of the weakness of the light squares around the king.  14.b3  Ne7  15.Rf3  Kh8  16.Bb2±  The next move is probably Rg3 attacking the g7-square, and once Black plays ...f6 we can see the problems that ...h6 created. }
14. Rb1
{ More ambitious than simply playing  14.b3  , which is also perfectly fine, but if possible White also wants to gain some space on the queenside by playing b4. }
14... Qc8
{ This move again says a lot about Black's position. It is simply very hard to find any active play.  14...Ne7  This allows b4 immediately and would be very similar to the game.  15.b4  axb4  16.axb4  Bb6  17.Rf3±  . }
15. b3 { Playing b3 doesn't mean that White gave up on b4! } 15... Ne7
{ 15...Re8  Black can try this waiting move.  16.Rf3  but their next waiting move is not clear. :@@EndBracket@@ }
16. b4 { White succeeds with his queenside plan. } 16... axb4 17. axb4 Bb6 18.
Bb2 Rf7
{ 18...Bxe3??  It was impossible to take this pawn because of the problems on the e-file.  19.Rbe1+-  White is winning a piece. }
19. Rbd1
{ A very strong move. White has c5-ideas and in that case the rook will be perfectly placed on the open d-file. }
19... Be6
{ Black is controlling the a2-g8 diagonal, therefore anticipating the c5-break.   19...Bxe3  It is a more serious try from Black now, since the e7-knight is protected. However, it is still very dangerous and objectively bad.  20.Rde1  Ba7   20...Bd4??  Loses on the spot to a simple tactical shot.  21.Rxe7!  Rxe7  22.Nd5+-  The rook is hanging with a check on e7, so the game is decided.  21.c5!  Opening up the a2-g8 diagonal for the bishop.  21...d5  Of course, Black is not interested in seeing a bishop on c4.  22.Rxe7!  After this exchange sacrifice all White's pieces are going to become very active.  22...Rxe7  23.Nxd5  Rf7  24.Bc4  White has many threats, and most probably the rook on a8 + the bishop on a7 will not help much anymore in this game.  24...Be6  25.Re1!  Bringing the last piece into the game!  25...Kh8  26.Qe2  Black is losing a lot of material or will get checkmated.  26...Bxd5  27.Bxd5  27...Rf8  28.Bxg7+!  Kxg7  29.Qe7++-  With checkmate to come very soon. }
20. Nb5 { With the idea of pushing c5 next. } 20... Nc6
{ Attacking b4 and slowing down White's c5 idea.   20...Bxe3  is again pretty easy to refute.  21.Qe2  Bb6  22.Rfe1  Bd7  The bishop has to leave the diagonal, so c5 is coming with big power.  23.c5+-  . }
21. Qd2 Qf8 22. Rf3
{ The rook is going to g3, where it will aim at the nice focal point g7 with the bishop on b2. }
22... Ne7
{ The knight is going back and forth, first helping to stop the c5-break, and now to cover the g7-square. }
23. Rg3 Ng6 24. Be2 { With the idea of pinning the knight from h5. } 24... Rd7
25. c5 { This pawn sacrifice is connected with a queen sacrifice as well! }
25... dxc5 26. Qxd7 Bxd7 27. Rxd7
{ The combined attack of the bishops and rooks against the black king is very powerful. }
27... Kh8 28. Bc4 Ra4 29. h4
{ The key move of White's concept: in order to have a successful attack, White has to eliminate the g6-knight, and it is a very nice bonus that it also opens the back rank. }
29... Rxb4 30. h5
{ Black can choose which bishop to take, but he is losing after both captures. }
30... Rxc4
{ 30...Rxb2  31.hxg6  Rb4   @@StartBracket@@  31...h6  32.Rh3+-  Rxh6 with Rh7 to follow is unstoppable.  @@EndBracket@@  32.Rf7  Qg8  33.Be6!  The bishop is a key piece for White's attack.  33...Rxb5  34.Re7  Qf8  35.Rh3+-  With checkmate to follow. }
31. hxg6 hxg6 32. Rxg6 { Black is falling apart on g7. } 32... Rd4
{ A very spectacular move. The rook can be taken in 4 different ways, but it will be not taken at all. :@@EndBracket@@ }
33. Rdxg7 Qxg7 34. Rxg7 Rb4 35. Bc3 Rxb5 36. Rxc7+ Kg8 37. Rxb7
{ The pin on the b-file is decisive. } 37... Kf8 38. g3 Rb1+ 39. Kg2 Rb5 40.
Kf3 Ke8 41. g4 *

