1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 3. Nf3 Nbd7 4. Nc3 e5 5. e4 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2
a6 9. Rd1 Qc7 10. a3 b5 11. h3 Bb7 12. Be3 Rac8 13. Rac1 Qb8 14. b4
{ For more information, checkthis variation. } 14... Rfe8
{ With this move Black is hoping for some counterplay on the e-file against the e4-pawn, so I believe it was best to immediately prevent those ideas. }
15. Qb3
{ 15.d5!  Now there will be no issues on the e-file, for sure.  15...bxc4  16.dxc6!  An important intermezzo.  16...Rxc6  17.Qa2  Rec8  18.Nd2±  Black can't keep his extra pawn for long, and with the queenside majority and the weakness of d5 and f7, White has a nice advantage.   If instead @@StartFEN@@1qr1r1k1/1b1nbppp/p1pp1n2/3Pp3/1Pp1P3/P1N1BN1P/2Q1BPP1/2RR2K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bxc4?!  cxd5  17.Nxd5  Nxd5  18.exd5  Nf6⇆  Black is doing pretty OK here. He can put big pressure on the d5-pawn or also double the rooks on the c-file. }
15... Bf8
{ Too slow, giving White a second chance to close the e-file.  15...exd4!  Black had to take on d4 right away.  16.Nxd4  Bf8⇆  With a complicated position where Black has decent counterplay against the e4-pawn. }
16. d5
{ 16.dxe5!  is maybe even stronger than the game continuation, since after the exchanges the b4-pawn will be protected by the queen, so White can push a4 immediately and gain serious initiative on the queenside.  16...Nxe5  17.Nxe5  dxe5   17...Rxe5?  is very bad for Black:  18.Bf4!  Re6  19.c5+-  Black is falling apart on d6.  18.a4↑  White's position looks very attractive to me. }
16... cxd5
{ It is strategically very dubious to allow a strong pawn on d5.   16...bxc4!  was definitely the correct way for Black to play.  17.Bxc4  cxd5  18.Nxd5!  Nxe4  leads to big complications where Black has his chances as well.   18...Nxd5  19.exd5⩲  19.Nc7!  Re7  20.Nxa6  Bxa6  21.Bxa6  Rxc1  22.Rxc1  If White could retreat the bishop anywhere, the position would just be very bad for Black, but there is a nice trick.  22...Nec5!  Thanks to the undefended queen, Black is taking our bishop pair.  23.Qc4  d5!  This central push comes with a tempo.  24.Qe2  Nxa6  25.Qxa6  d4  26.Bd2⩲  Probably White keeps a slight advantage here, but all 3 results are possible. The position is very double-edged.   @@StartFEN@@1qr1rbk1/1bNn1ppp/p2p4/4p3/1PB1n3/PQ2BN1P/5PP1/2RR2K1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Rxc7??  would just lose an exchange for no compensation.  20.Bxf7+  Kh8  21.Rxc7  Qxc7  22.Bxe8+- }
17. cxd5 Rc7
{ 17...Rxc3!?  I don't think that Black will get enough compensation for the exchange, but it is at least some practical try. In the game, he didn't really have any chances.  18.Qxc3  Nxe4  19.Qb3  f5  20.a4±  . }
18. Nd2 { The pawn is protected on e4, so ...Rxc3 is not an option anymore. }
18... Rec8 19. Qb2
{ Protecting the rook on c1 and getting ready to push a4 while also freeing the b3-a5 route for the knight. }
19... Ba8 { A mistake in a strategically very difficult position. } 20. a4 bxa4
21. Bxa6 Bb7 22. Bb5 Ba8 23. Bxa4 Nc5 24. Bc2 Na6 25. Na2
{ White stabilised his position and converted the extra pawn without problems. }
25... Rb7 26. Rb1 Nd7 27. Ba4 Ndc5 28. Bc6 Rb6 29. Bxa8 Qxa8 30. Qa3 Nd7 31.
