1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 b4 5. e4 d6 6. a3 bxa3 7. Rxa3 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7
9. Be2 O-O 10. Nf3 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 12. Qd1 Bg4 13. Bf4 a6 14. Qd2
{ All this has been covered in the course. I recommend  14.h3  herein the chapter, but of course, this is not a big difference. The character of the game will remain the same. }
14... Ne8
{ Generally speaking, d7 is a much more normal square for the knight in the Benkő.  14...Nd7  15.h3  Bxf3  16.Bxf3  Re8  Black is preparing to push ...e6 and create some counterplay in the centre.  17.Bg5  Qc7  18.Bg4  We are placing the bishops on more active squares, and also getting ready to push f4 once Black is opening the position.  18...e6  19.dxe6  fxe6  20.f4⩲  Our bishops are great, whereas it is not exactly clear what type of counterplay Black created by playing ...e6. }
15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3
{ Once Black is trading his light-squared bishop, the ...e6 or ...f5 breaks lose a lot of power because of the potential weakness of the light squares. }
16... Rb8 17. Rd1
{ A very nice idea from White. He is saying that Black is so passive that his only counterchances lie in playing ...e6/...e5 at some moment, so he is preparing for this. If this comes true, he can start developing his own play on the kingside. }
17... Qb6
{ Of course, if Black provokes e5, White should not have anything against playing that move.  17...Nf6  18.e5  dxe5  19.Bxe5  Ne4!  Without this move 17...Nf6 would be just a clear strategical mistake. Now at least Black can exchange the strong e5-bishop.  20.Qf4  Bxe5  21.Qxe5  Nd6  22.Be2±  With h4-h5 to follow and we can easily bring the rook to help the attack on the 3rd rank. }
18. h4 { Starting the kingside attack. } 18... Nc7
{ Against  18...e6  or  18...e5  , our reaction would be the same:  19.dxe6  That's why White put the rook on d1.  19...fxe6  20.Bg4±  Black has big problems to protect his central pawns. }
19. Bg4 { Ne2-h5-Rh3 and the attack starts to look pretty dangerous! } 19... e5
{ This is not working, but the whole position was pretty bad for Black. } 20.
dxe6 Nxe6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Bxd6 Rbd8 { Black put his hopes on this pin. } 23.
Na4 { White is just taking more material. } 23... Qc6 24. Nxc5 Be5 25. Bxf8
{ Two rooks for the queen is not bad at all for White. } 25... Rxd2 26. Rxd2
Bf4
{ 26...Kxf8  27.Nd7++-  is winning back the bishop with a completely winning position. }
27. Rd8 Bc7 28. Rc8
{ Even stronger according to the engine was  28.Rd7!  28...Bh2+   28...Kxf8?  is not working because of a simple tactic:  29.Rxc7+-  .  29.Kxh2  Kxf8  30.Rf3+  Ke8  31.Rff7!  A very nice idea: White is sacrificing the knight, but the king will get checkmated.  31...Qxc5  32.Rxh7+-  . }
28... Bh2+ 29. Kxh2 Qxc8 30. Rf3 e5
{ Losing on the spot, but even with the best defence the position was lost for Black.  30...Qc7+  31.Kh3  e5  32.Kh2+-  Going out from the h3-c8 diagonal, so White can play Ne6 next. }
31. Be7 Qg4 32. Rf8+ Kg7 33. f3 *

