Bd7 9. Qb3 Qc7 10. e4 O-O 11. Nd2 Nh5 12. Be3 f5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Be2 Nf6 15.
Nc4 Ne4 16. O-O Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nd7 18. Bf4 Rf6 19. Bg3 Nb6 20. Ne3
{ We are not exchanging the knight, but want to kick it back to d7, so our knight can also return to c4. All this has been coveredhere. }
20... Bd7
{ 20...c4  An interesting positional pawn sacrifice from Black. I highly doubt that it is very appealing to human players, but since the engine recommends it, let's take a look:  21.Nxc4  Nxc4  22.Bxc4  Rc8  23.Be2  Rf7   23...Qxc3?!  24.Qxb7±  Black is still pretty active here, but it is rather a clean extra pawn for White than anything else.  24.Rac1⩲  Black's position is pretty solid, but after all, he is down a pawn, and just waiting is not so easy here.  24...Bxc3?  Taking back the pawn is not really good, because the pin on the c-file is very unpleasant and White will have the opportunity to take on d6 and regain the extra pawn as well.  25.h3!  White has a lot of time. Black has to do something about the pin.  25...a6  26.Rfd1  Protecting the d5-pawn and getting ready to take on d6.  26...b5  27.Bxd6  Just before Black could protect his bishop with ...b4!  27...Qxd6  28.Rxc3  Rxc3  29.Qxc3±  With a healthy extra pawn for White.   20...Re8  is not really changing the character of the game. White can continue with his standard plan.  21.a4  Rff8  22.a5  Nd7  23.a6!  Preparing some nice squares for the bishop as well!  23...b6  24.Rae1⩲  Bb5 and then Nxf5 is a pretty serious positional threat. Black is weak on the light squares. }
21. a4 Re8 22. a5 Nc8 23. Rfb1 b6
{ Everything was great so far, but here White was somewhat inaccurate. } 24.
Bb5
{ 24.axb6!  clarifying the situation on the queenside and creating a clear target was the most precise way here.  24...axb6  25.Ba6±  Now the b6-pawn is in immediate danger, but after Nc4 the d6-pawn will also be in very bad shape.   @@StartFEN@@2n1r1k1/p1qb2bp/1P1p1rp1/2pP4/8/1QP1N1B1/4BPPP/RR4K1 b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Nxb6  25.Ra3±  Protecting the c3-pawn @@StartBracket@@in case of the f6-rook moves, this is very useful@@EndBracket@@ and also preparing to triple on the a-file and attack the a7-pawn. }
24... Rf7
{ 24...bxa5!  Black is creating a weakness on a7 with this move, but the knight is already on c8 to protect this pawn, and the queen will also be more active on d7 than on c7.  25.Bxd7  Qxd7  26.Rxa5  Bh6⇆  We can already see one nice advantage of the queen being on d7 and not on c7: Black can activate his bishop and attack the knight because the g4-square is under control.   @@StartFEN@@2n1r1k1/p1qb2bp/3p1rp1/pBpP4/8/1QP1N1B1/5PPP/RR4K1 w - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Nc4  Bxb5  26.Qxb5  Rff8⇆  Black has decent counterplay against the 'c' and d-pawns. }
25. h3 { It is very useful to have the back rank open. } 25... Rfe7 26. Bh4
{ The second inaccuracy.  26.axb6!  It was still not late to go for this idea.  26...axb6  27.Ba6±  The b-pawn is pretty weak.   @@StartFEN@@2n1r1k1/p1qbr1bp/1P1p2p1/1BpP4/8/1QP1N1BP/5PP1/RR4K1 b - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Nxb6  27.Bf1±  Ra3 and the lining up on the a-file is coming. }
26... Re4 27. Ra4 bxa5
{ Black played this great idea, and now has a good position. } 28. Bxd7 Qxd7
29. Rxe4 Rxe4 30. Qb8
{ White probably built his play around this move. The threat of Rb7 is huge, but Black has a defence. }
30... Re8
{ 30...Bxc3!  is keeping the position balanced.  31.Rb7  Rb4!  The key move of Black's defense.  32.Rxd7  Rxb8  33.Rd8+  Kf7  34.Rd7+  Kg8=  White has nothing better than a perpetual check.   30...Rxh4  is not working because White will win back the knight on c8.  31.Rb7  Qd8  32.Rc7+- }
31. Rb7
{ Black resigned here, and indeed the position is lost.  31.Rb7  Nb6  was most probably Black's idea, but unfortunately, the knight leaves the protection of the a7-pawn.  32.Qxa7+-   @@StartFEN@@1Qn1r1k1/pR1q2bp/3p2p1/p1pP4/7B/2P1N2P/5PP1/6K1 b - - 3 31@@EndFEN@@  31...Qa4  32.Qc7+- }
