1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bd3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Ne2
Nbd7 9. h3
{ Not necessary at this moment, but it is always a useful move in this variation.  9.c4  is the more natural move order. }
9... Ne4 10. c4
{ Now it is important to have h3 in the position, since we need a retreat square for the bishop in case of ...g5. Also, this move is basically stopping Black from playing ...g4. We have reachedthis line. }
10... g5 11. Bh2 Bd6
{ 11...g4?  Black's position will be in ruins after this move.  12.hxg4  fxg4  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Ne5+-  Most probably both the e4 and g4-pawn will fall, Black's c8-bishop is nowhere near entering the game and, as a result of this attack, the black king became weaker than its colleague. }
12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. c5
{ Not the only move. The computer prefers to keep the tension in the centre for a while, but it seems to me that thanks to the space advantage and clear play on the queenside, White will have a stable edge after this move. Also possible are  13.Qc2!?  and  13.Rc1!?  . }
13... Nf7 14. Nd2
{ Preparing to close the kingside with f4, and for the moment White can completely ignore the control over the e5-square because the f5-pawn is not protected. }
14... b6
{ A defensive approach from Black. He wants to exchange his bad bishop on a6, and he is saying that with only one weakness on c6, he should be able to hold the position.   14...e5?  just drops a pawn:  15.Bxf5±  .   14...Nf6  The bishop is covering the f5-pawn, so ...e5 is a threat now.  15.f4!  g4  16.b4  Kh8  Black is looking for counterplay on the g-file.  17.h4!  White wants to completely close the kingside by playing g3 in the next move.  17...g3  The best try from Black, but White can still keep the upper hand.  18.Rf3  Ng4  19.Rxg3  Qxh4  20.Nf3⩲  Kicking back the queen, and White has managed to deal with Black's potential counterplay on the kingside. }
15. b4 a5 16. a3
{ Of course White is maintaining his space advantage on the queenside. } 16...
Ba6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. f4
{ Since the bishop disappeared from d3, e5 was again on the agenda, because the f5-pawn was not hanging anymore. }
18... h6 19. Qc2 axb4
{ Releasing the tension too quickly will give White control over the a-file.   19...Qe7  was a better move, although it is not so easy to understand unless you are a computer. :@@EndBracket@@  20.Rfb1  A better try to keep the advantage.   20.cxb6  Looks like a clean pawn for White, but Stockfish sees further! :@@EndBracket@@  20...Nxb6  21.bxa5  Rxa5  22.Qxc6  Would be a normal moment for a human to reject this line for Black.  22...Qd6=∞  A very strong move, and after the queen exchange Black has enough compensation for the missing pawn.  20...Rfa8  21.cxb6  Rxb6  22.bxa5!  Rba6  23.a4⩲  White keeps a small advantage here.   @@StartFEN@@5rk1/3nqn2/rpp1p2p/p1Pp1pp1/1P1P1P2/P3P2P/2QNN1P1/RR4K1 b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...b5?  would be a typical mistake. If Black could close the queenside by playing ...a4 next, then he is just fine, but it will not happen.  21.a4!  Breaking through on the queenside!  21...axb4  22.axb5  Rxa1  23.Rxa1  cxb5  24.Qb2±  White has a huge advantage, thanks to the protected passed pawn on c5, while Black's b-pawns are very weak. }
20. axb4 Qa8 21. Nb3 { Securing the control over the a-file. } 21... Rxa1 22.
Rxa1 Qb7 23. Qa2 Rb8 24. Qa7 bxc5
{ Losing on the spot because of an intermediate move, but Black's position was anyway very difficult.   24...Qc8  25.cxb6!  Opening the way for the b3-knight.  25...Rb7   25...Nxb6  26.Qe7+-  Ra7-Nc5 or Qf6 are coming next. Black's position is just collapsing.  26.Qa6  Qb8  27.Nc5  Rxb6  28.Qa8  28...Nxc5  29.dxc5+-  The difference between the knights is decisive in this variation. Of course, it also helps that White will take the c6-pawn. :@@EndBracket@@ }
25. Qxb7
{ The precise move order.   25.Nxc5  Nxc5  26.bxc5  Qb2!  And suddenly Black has some counterchances. }
25... Rxb7 26. Nxc5 Nxc5 27. Ra8+
{ Most probably the move Black missed when playing 24...bxc5.   27.bxc5  Kf8!  Now the king will reach d7, protecting the weak c6 and e6-pawns, while the knight can guard the pawn on h6. }
27... Kg7 28. bxc5 Rc7
{ Rc8 was a huge threat, so Black has to defend passively. } 29. Re8 Kf6 30.
Ng3 { After Nh5 and then g4, Black can't protect his pawn on e6. } 30... g4 31.
hxg4 fxg4 32. Rg8
{ White is winning a pawn and enters a technically winning endgame. } 32... Ra7
