14. cxd5 exd5
{ This move is already losing material for Black.   14...cxd5  Not ideal to open the c-file for White, but nevertheless necessary.  15.f3  Kicking back the knight.  15...Nef6  16.Rac1  It's hard for Black to hope for any counterplay, because if ...g4 happens, the knight can jump to f4 with great force.  16...Qh6  17.Qb3  Qg7  18.Rc2±  White has a nice initiative on the queenside, while Black can only passively defend without chances for counterplay.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1n3p/3bpn2/3pNppq/3P4/3BPP1P/PPQ1N1PB/2R2RK1 b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bxe5?  The only possible way to take on e5 leads to a horrible position for Black:  17.dxe5  Ne8  18.Nd4+-  It is true that our h2-bishop is not so great, but the same can be said about all Black's pieces! }
15. f3 { Because of the weakness of the f5-pawn, White is winning material. }
15... Nxe5
{ 15...Nef6  16.Bxf5+-  and White is crushing.  15...Nec5  is tricky, but not so much:  16.Bxf5!  Nxe5  17.Bxc8  Raxc8  18.dxe5+-  With a healthy extra pawn for White. }
