1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nd2 d5 5. Nh3 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 c6 8. Nf3
Ne4 9. Qc2 Nd7 10. Nf4 Qf6 11. Nd3 g5 12. b3
{ In our repertoire we reach this position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  e6  4.Nbd2  f5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Ne1  Nbd7  9.Nd3  Ne4  10.Qc2  Qe7  11.Nf3  g5  12.b3  . Seethis line. }
12... f4
{ Black is trying to do something active on the kingside, but he doesn't have enough pieces there and White doesn't have weaknesses. Without these two factors, the chances of success are not too high. }
13. Bb2
{ Preparing to put the knight on e5 and then kick Black's knight with f3. }
13... Qf5
{ Black is going out from the fork, since he wants to take on e5 with the knight. }
14. Nfe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5
{ Taking with the knight would be a perfectly good choice from a positional perspective, but it has a tactical flaw now:  15.Nxe5?  Nxg3-+  . }
15... Be7 16. g4
{ Closing the f-file and placing the e4-knight into a very dangerous situation. }
16... Qg6
{ Black is using the unprotected situation of our queen to avoid losing a piece right away. There won't be enough compensation for the piece after  16...Qxg4?  17.f3  Qf5  18.fxe4  dxe4  19.Nf2  e3  20.Ne4+-  It is rather White who is attacking here.   16...Qf7  simply drops the knight on e4.  17.cxd5!  exd5  18.f3+-  . }
17. Rac1
{ Now the queen is protected, so the f3-idea is coming.   Black's idea is  17.cxd5  exd5  18.f3?  Nc5!  , where he is doing completely fine. }
17... Bd7 18. cxd5 cxd5
{ 18...exd5??  19.f3+-  is a full piece for White now. } 19. Qc7
{ Black can save the knight and have a better position in case of  19.f3?  Rac8∓  . }
19... Rfd8 20. f3
{ Interesting play from White.  20.Qxb7!  According to the engine, there was nothing wrong with taking this pawn. }
20... Rac8 21. Qxd7
{ The point of White's play!  21.Qxb7?  would allow Black to get a great position.  21...Nc5  22.Nxc5  Bxc5+∓  White's bishops are horribly passive here. }
21... Rxd7 22. Rxc8+ Kg7 23. fxe4 dxe4 24. Nf2
{ White has some material advantage and his task now is to stop Black's dangerous central pawns. }
24... f3
{ 24...e3  25.Ne4  h5  26.Nf6  White is going for counterattack and Black's position is collapsing.  26...Bxf6  27.exf6+  Kf7  28.Bf3+-  Black has no counterplay at all: White will win by playing Rfc1-R8c7. }
25. exf3 e3 { White will easily stop Black's passed pawn. } 26. Ne4
{ The knight is blocking the queen very well. } 26... e2
{ 26...Bd8  27.Re1  h5  28.Bc1+-  and White is just picking up the pawn, not blundering  28.Rxe3  Bb6  . }
27. Re1 Bb4 28. Rxe2 { The rest is easy. } 28... Rd1+ 29. Bf1 Ba5 30. Rc1 Rd3
