1. e4 a6 2. d4 b5 3. a4 Bb7 4. Nd2 b4 5. Ngf3 e6 6. Bd3 c5 7. O-O d6
{ Even though  7...cxd4  leads to a very dangerous Sicilian-type of position for Black, it is still a much better choice than giving up the c4-square for free for White's knight and also the possibility to push e5 anytime he wants.  8.Nxd4  is coveredhere. }
8. dxc5 dxc5 9. Nc4
{ A wonderful square for the knight. It can't be attacked by pawns, and it is not easy to challenge it with some minor piece either. }
9... Nf6
{ An extremely risky move, inviting e5 with tempo.   9...Nc6  10.e5  This move is not coming with tempo now, but nevertheless it is very strong. Black is facing huge issues with the development of the g8-knight because of the Nd6+ idea.  10...Qc7  11.c3  A logical positional move, covering the d4-square and also having the option of opening the game with cxb4 at any moment.  11...Na5  Black is challenging the c4-knight.  12.Nfd2!  Of course, we want to recapture with the knight and not with the bishop.  12...Nxc4  13.Nxc4  Bd5  14.a5+-  Fixing the weakness on a6, which we will attack with Qe2 very soon, and Black's kingside development is still nowhere. }
10. e5 Nd5
{ 10...Nfd7  This move keeps the d5-square free for the bishop, but of course, that bishop alone will not be able to save Black's position.  11.Ng5!  Attacking the weak squares in Black's camp, and also opening the way for the queen.  11...Bd5  12.f4  A nice multi-purpose move. White is protecting on e5, therefore Ne3 and eliminating the bishop from d5 is an idea now. Also, playing f5 and involving the rook in the game is in the air.  12...h6  13.Qh5!  Of course! We are not going backwards in such a dominating position.  13...g6  14.Bxg6!  This combination is picking up Black's queen.  14...hxg5  15.Bxf7+  Ke7  16.Qxg5+  Kxf7  17.Qxd8  Bxc4  18.Be3  Bxf1  19.Rxf1+-  Regarding the material Black is doing pretty well, the problem is that after f5 our opponent will get mated.   @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/3n1ppp/p3p3/2pbP1N1/PpN2P2/3B4/1PP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  12...Nc6  13.Ne3!  Exchanging Black's best piece.  13...Be7  14.Nxd5  Bxg5   14...exd5?  15.e6+-  And Black is already falling apart on the light squares.  15.Be4!  Now our light-squared bishop is dominating the board.  15...exd5  16.Qxd5  Rc8  17.fxg5  Qe7  18.Qd6!  The easiest: the queen trade will keep Black's king in the centre.  18...Ndxe5  19.Qxe7+  Kxe7  20.Be3+-  The material is even, but Black is completely lost.   @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/p3p3/2p1P1N1/PpN5/3B4/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Be7  12.Qh5!  g6  13.Qh6  Bf8  Looks like Black can chase away White's queen, but the tactics are already working for the attacker.  14.Nxe6!  fxe6   @@StartBracket@@  14...Bxh6  15.Nxd8  Bxc1  16.Nxb7+-  Black is down a pawn and will lose more material very soon.  @@EndBracket@@  15.Bxg6+  hxg6  16.Qxg6+  Ke7  17.Bg5+  Winning the queen and the game.  17...Nf6  18.Bxf6++-  . }
11. Ng5
{ Not only attacking the light squares in Black's position, but also having the option to play Ne4-d6. Black is already losing after 11 moves! }
11... Nb6
{ Losing on the spot, but the alternatives were not better.   11...Be7  12.Qf3!  Using the power of the Nd6 check.  12...Bxg5  13.Nd6++-  .   11...Nc6  12.Ne4+-  The knight on d6 will be decisive. }
12. Nxf7 { Winning a lot of material. } 12... Kxf7 13. Bg6+ Ke7 14. Bg5#
{ Checkmate on the board after 14 moves! Very rare on GM/IM level. } *

