[Black "13) Denis Rombaldoni vs. Miragha Aghayev, Padova 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. h4 d5 4. e5 c5 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. Qxd4 a6
{ By moving the a-pawn, Black loses the possibility to play ...Qb6 straight away at one point.  7...Bd7  is better,as mentioned in the course. }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. h5
{ Already a pretty unpleasant position for Black, it is difficult to handle White's h-pawn. }
9... e6
{ 9...h6  Stopping h6, but weakening the g6-square.  10.hxg6  fxg6  11.Nf3  The e5-pawn is very strong now. Black can't challenge it with his f-pawn anymore.  11...Bf5  12.Na4  The knight is going for the c5-outpost. The c2-pawn is not too important for us: in a sense, it is even good that Black takes it since our rooks can use the c-file later.  12...Bxc2  13.Nc5  Bf5  14.g4!  Forcing the bishop to a very passive square.  14...Bc8  15.Nh4±  Black's position is very ugly and passive.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/4p1b1/p1p3pp/3pP3/3Q4/2N2N2/PPP2PP1/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb8  12.Be3!  Preventing ...Qb6 and getting ready to play O-O-O.  12...Rxb2  13.O-O  Rxc2  14.Qc5+-  Black took a couple of pawns, but it shouldn't end well for him, since one rook is fighting against the whole white army.   9...gxh5  Black is ruining his structure, but at least will not have to worry about the h6-push later.  10.Rxh5  Rb8  There would be no need for this move if the pawn were still on a7.  11.Nf3   11.Be3  Now this move doesn't work well at all, since our king is in the centre and Black can achieve serious counterplay by playing ...Qa5.  11...Rxb2⇆  11...Qb6  12.Qa4!  Yeah... the engine is very strong. It is not obvious at all why we have to force the bishop to d7 instead of playing Qf4 right away.  12...Bd7  13.Qf4  Why it is so good for White to have an extra Bd7 in the position?  13...Qb4  14.Qg3  Bf8  . Instead,  14...Qg4??  15.e6!  This tactical trick is the answer to the point of 12.Qa4. Now the bishop is hanging on d7 with an intermediate check.  15...Bxc3+  16.bxc3  Qxe6+   16...Qxg3  17.exd7+!  Kxd7  18.fxg3+-  Our structure is not perfect :@@EndBracket@@, but a piece is a piece.  17.Be3  White is threatening Qxb8 and Rxh7 followed by Qxg8.  17...Qd6  18.Qg7  Qf6  19.Bd4+-  Winning the rook and the game. }
10. Nf3 Nh6
{ Black's position is already lost after this move, but it is not easy to recommend something much better.  10...Rb8  11.Na4  Preventing ...Qb6 and also preparing to play b3.  11...Ne7  12.b3±  Ba3 and O-O-O are coming, while it is not clear what Black should do. }
11. Bg5
{ 11.hxg6!  This move is more precise according to the engine, but White also played very well in the game.  11...hxg6  12.Bg5  Qa5  13.O-O-O  and Black's position is falling apart on the h-file.  13...Nf5  14.Rxh8+  Bxh8  15.Qf4+-  . }
11... Qa5
{ 11...Nf5  doesn't help Black much.  12.Qd2+-  White will play g4 and Bf6 next. }
12. Qf4 Nf5 13. g4 h6
{ 13...Ne7  is already losing a lot of material:  14.Bxe7!  Kxe7  15.h6  Bf8  16.Qf6++-  . }
14. hxg6 { This intermediate move is deciding the game. } 14... hxg5
{ 14...fxg6  15.gxf5  hxg5  16.Rxh8+  Bxh8  17.Qxg5+-  is also completely lost for Black. }
15. Rxh8+ Bxh8 16. gxf7+ Kxf7 17. Nxg5+
{ White will win back the piece, and will continue the attack with equal material. }
17... Kg6 18. gxf5+ exf5 19. Qh2 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 Kxg5 21. O-O-O *

