1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4 e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4 c6 7. Bd2 d5 8.
exd5 { 8.O-O-O  is my recommendation inthe Philidor & Pirc chapter. } 8... Bc5
9. Qd3 O-O 10. O-O-O cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qc7 13. Bc3 Qxf4+ 14. Kb1 Be3
{ Black is preventing Ng5. If he could finish development, then he would be more or less fine, but White will not allow that. }
15. g3 { Forcing the queen to a less ideal square. } 15... Qh6
{ 15...Qg4  16.Bc4+-  The queen is pretty vulnerable on g4: h3 and then Nh4 can come with a tempo, and Black still can't finish the development.  16...Nb6??  17.Qxf7+  A nice checkmate!  17...Rxf7  18.Rd8  .   15...Qc7  16.Qe4!  Attacking the bishop, but also eyeing the h7-pawn.  16...Qb6  17.Bc4  Nf6  Finally Black could move the knight, but he still can't take it back normally...  18.Bxf6  gxf6  19.Nh4+-  With Bd3 and a decisive attack to follow.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqn1ppp/8/8/4Q3/2B1bNP1/PPP4P/1K1R1B1R b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bb6??  allows Ng5 and loses on the spot.  17.Ng5  g6  18.Nxh7+-  and the game is over. Black can't take back the knight because of Qh4+.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqn1ppp/8/8/4Q3/2B1bNP1/PPP4P/1K1R1B1R b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bh6  17.Bd3  Developing with a mate-in-1 threat is nice.  17...g6  18.Qd4  f6  With these pawn moves, the black king is getting weaker and weaker.  19.Bc4+  Kh8  20.Rhe1+-  White's position is perfect, while Black couldn't finish the development and his position is full of weaknesses. }
16. Bc4 { Bb4 is a huge threat now, to exploit the weakness of the f7-square. }
16... Qc6
{ It is very important that both  16...Nb6  and  16...Nf6??  fail to the same checkmating idea:  17.Qxf7+  Rxf7  18.Rd8+  Ne8  19.Rxe8  . }
17. Qxc6
{ 17.Rhe1!  is even stronger according to the engine, but there were at least 10 good moves for White from now on at each turn. His position is just completely winning with such a huge development lead. }
17... bxc6 18. Rhe1 Nb6
{ 18...Bb6  19.Nd4  Bb7  20.Ne6!  is one nice way to win, amongst many others.  20...fxe6  21.Rxd7+-  . }
19. Bb3 Bc5
{ 19...Bf2  20.Rf1  Bc5  21.Ne5  Nd5  Black is protecting on f7 with great difficulties, but now the position will fall apart on c6.  22.Bd4!  Bxd4  23.Rxd4+-  . }
20. Ne5 Bb7 { 20...Nd5  21.Ba5+-  . } 21. a4
{ 21.Rf1!  This move was winning a lot of material on the spot.  21...Nd5  22.Nd7  Picking up an exchange.  22...Nxc3+  23.bxc3+-  . }
21... Nd5 22. Nd7 Bf2 23. Rf1 Rfd8 24. Bxd5 Rxd7
{ 24...cxd5  25.Nf6+!  An important intermediate move. All the black pawns are going to be weak in this endgame.  25...gxf6  26.Rxf2+-  . }
25. Bc4 Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Rf8 27. Rd7 Bc8 28. Rc7 Bb6 29. Bxf7+
{ White is picking up material, and the rest was pretty easy. } 29... Kh8 30.
Re7 Bc5 31. Re8 Rxe8 32. Bxe8 Bg1 33. h4 c5 34. Bc6 Bf2 35. Be5 Kg8 36. Bd5+
Kf8 37. Kc1 Ke7 38. Kd2 Bg4 39. a5 g6 40. Bb8 Bc8 41. Bxa7 Ba6 42. b4 Kd6 43.
c4 *

