[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d5 6. b4 c6 7. Nbd2 a5 8. b5 c5
9. c4 Nbd7 10. Bb2
{ We reach the same position via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nbd2  g6  5.e3  Bg7  6.Be2  O-O  7.O-O  Nbd7  8.b4  a5  9.b5  c5  10.Bb2  move order. Seethis line. }
10... cxd4 { Black is immediately releasing the tension in the centre. } 11.
Bxd4
{ Of course, we take like this and not with the knight, to keep the e5-square under firm control. }
11... b6 12. cxd5
{ Preparing the c4-square for the knight. Keeping the central tension for a while also looks pretty good for White:  12.Qc2  Bb7  13.Qb2  Rc8  14.Rac1⩲  Rfd1 is coming next, and there is an unpleasant pressure on Black's position. }
12... Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nc4 Bb7 15. Qd4+
{ Centralising the queen with tempo. } 15... f6
{ It is not clear what Black missed. Ng5 is a very tempting and strong response to this move.  15...N7f6?  leads to a very bad position for Black because this knight belongs to c5!  16.Nfe5!  Black is under huge pressure: he can't really move his minor pieces.  16...Rc8  17.a4  Qc7  18.Rac1  Qc5  19.Qa1+-  A very strong move. Black is helpless against the various threats.  19...Rc7  even allows the queen to be trapped:  20.Nd3+-  .   @@StartFEN@@r2q1r2/1b1nppkp/1p4p1/pP1n4/2NQ4/4PN2/P3BPPP/R4RK1 b - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Kg8  doesn't solve Black's problems:  16.Nfe5±  Bf3 and Rad1 are coming with a huge pressure on Black's position.   @@StartFEN@@r2q1r2/1b1nppkp/1p4p1/pP1n4/2NQ4/4PN2/P3BPPP/R4RK1 b - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15...N5f6!  is the only good way to block the check.  16.g4!?  This is the recommendation of the engine. In some lines it is advantageous for White to force a black pawn to g5.  16...h6  17.h4  g5  18.Rfd1  Qc7  19.Rac1  Rfd8  20.Qb2  Nc5  Everything is going in the same way as in the 16.Rfd1 line below.  21.hxg5  hxg5  22.Qe5  The difference is only clear now. In the other variation, Black can take on d1 and play ...Qd8! which is not possible here because the pawn on g5 is hanging with a check.  22...Rxd1+  23.Bxd1!  Qxe5  24.Nfxe5  Nd5  The second difference compared to the 16.Rfd1 line is that, since we could recapture with the bishop on d1, the rook is doing a great job on c1, making a tactical trick possible.  25.Nxb6+-  .   @@StartFEN@@r2q1r2/1b1nppkp/1p3np1/pP6/2NQ4/4PN2/P3BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Rfd1  This human move also gives White a slight advantage.  16...Qc7  17.Rac1  Rfd8  18.Qa1  Going away from the file of the d8-rook.  18...Nc5  Black is also making it safer for his king.  19.Nd4⩲  Our knights are well placed, and there is only one weak pawn in the position, the b6-pawn.   19.Qe5  Now this move doesn't really give White anything special.  19...Rxd1+  20.Rxd1   20.Bxd1  Qd8⇆  Black is fine, there is nothing to take on g5 now.  20...Qxe5  21.Nfxe5  Nd5⇆  Because the rook is on d1,  22.Nxb6??  is not working for White. }
16. Ng5 Nc5
{ 16...Nc7?  is even worse for Black:  17.Nxb6  Nxb6  18.Qxb6  Bxg2  19.Qxc7+-  White is winning a lot of material. }
17. Qxc5 bxc5
{ Keeping the queens on the board would favour White:  17...fxg5  18.Qd4+  Kg8  19.Rfd1+-  Bf3 is coming next and Black's position is collapsing. }
18. Ne6+ Kf7 19. Nxd8+ Rfxd8 20. Bf3 { Good move, not allowing ... Nc3. } 20...
e6
{ 20...a4!  is not solving all the problems of the position at all, but at least the b5-pawn will not be a protected passer.  21.Rfd1  Rab8  22.Rd3±  Doubling on the d-file or attacking on a4 with Bd1 is coming next. }
21. Rfc1
{ Somehow the players agreed that playing a4 is not a threat for White, even though it looks pretty logical to create a protected passer on b5.   21.a4!  looks pretty nice for White:  21...Ke7  22.Rac1  f5  23.Rfd1+-  Black can't really move his pieces, while White can do many things here. For example, asking some questions on the kingside or pushing e4 at some point. }
21... Ke7 { 21...a4! } 22. a3 a4 23. Rab1 Rdb8 24. h4
{ 24.e4!  was winning material on the spot:  24...Nf4  25.Nb6  Bxe4  Probably this was Black's idea, but it simply doesn't work.  26.Bxe4  Ne2+  27.Kf1  Nxc1  28.Nxa8  Nb3  29.Ke1  f5  30.Bf3+-  and Black will remain a piece down, since the knight has a way out of a8. }
24... Nc7
{ Black is trying to ease the pressure with exchanges, but actually it will only make the conversion easier for White. }
25. Bxb7 Rxb7 26. b6 Nd5 27. e4
{ Forcing the knight further away from the queenside. } 27... Nf4 28. Kf1 Ra6
29. Rb5 Nd3 30. Rcb1 Rb8 31. Na5 Ke8 32. Nc6 Rb7 33. Ke2 Nf4+ 34. Kd2 e5
{ 34...Nxg2  is not really counterplay, but rather taking irrelevant pawns.  35.Kc3  Nxh4  36.Na5  Rb8  37.b7+-  Rc5-Rc8 is coming and White will queen the pawn. }
35. Kc3
{ The position is technically winning for White, and although not without some adventures, he converted it into a full point. }
35... Kd7 36. Na5 Rb8 37. b7 Ne6 38. Kc4 Kc7 39. Rd1 h5 40. g3 Re8 41. Rd5 Kb8
42. Rd7 f5 43. Kc3 fxe4 44. Nc4 Rd8 45. Nb6 Ka7 46. Kc4 Re8 47. Nc8+ Kb8 48.
Nd6 Rd8 49. Rxd8+ Nxd8 50. Nxe4 Ne6 51. Rb2 Nd4 52. Nxc5 Rd6 53. Nxa4 Ne6 54.
Rb6 Rxb6 55. Nxb6 Kxb7 56. Nd7 g5 57. Nc5+ *

