1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3 Qc7 8.
Nb5 Qc6
{ This move is not solving Black's problems, the queen is very awkward on c6.   8...Bb4+  is coveredhere. }
9. e3 Qd7
{ Strange move. Even though insufficient to achieve a good position, definitely the critical move to try was  9...a6  10.Qd5!  An unusual way to protect the knight on b5. :@@EndBracket@@  10...Bb4+  The best for Black is to develop with tempo.   @@StartBracket@@  10...axb5??  11.Bxb5+-  @@EndBracket@@  11.Nd2  Qxd5  12.Nc7+  Kd8  13.Nxd5  Nc6  14.Bc4⩲  White has a nice initiative and the Black's king situation is far from ideal.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p1q5/1N1Qp3/8/1N2P3/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qxd5  11.Nc7+  Black's king will not be able to castle, and also the b6-square is very weak.  11...Kd8  12.Nxd5  Nc6  13.Nb6  Bb4+  14.Ke2  Rb8  15.Nxc8  We don't have any immediate win, so the best is to go for a clear endgame advantage with the pair of bishops.  15...Rxc8  16.g3±  . }
10. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Unfortunately for Black, he has to take like this, since the c7-square needs control. }
11. Bc4 a6 12. Nc3 Ke8 13. Nd5 { Black has to solve problems in every move. }
13... Ra7 14. Nb6 Bb4+ 15. Ke2
{ Allowing a nice trick for Black to stay in the game.  15.Bd2!  was basically winning for White.  15...Bxd2+  16.Nxd2  Bf5  17.Bb3!  Freeing the c4-square for the d2-knight, from where it will attack the e5-pawn and also the d6-square.  17...Ke7  18.Ndc4  Nc6  19.O-O-O  Black has no defence against Nd6, which will attack his bishop and his f7-pawn. Also, Ndc8+ will be a threat.  19...Nf6  20.Nd6+- }
15... Bg4+ 16. f3 Nd7 { Nice defence from Black! } 17. Nxd7
{ 17.Nd5  It was probably better not to trade the d7-knight.  17...Be6  18.e4±  White still has a clear advantage with the more active pieces. }
17... Bxd7 18. e4 b5 19. Bd3 Nf6
{ 19...Ne7  The knight absolutely had to go to c6, to block the c-file. This was Black's best chance in the game, but even this leads to a clearly worse endgame.  20.Be3  Rc7  21.Rhc1  Rxc1  22.Rxc1  Nc6!  23.a3  Bd6  24.Nc5  Bxc5  25.Bxc5⩲  Not a dream position for Black, but for the first time in the game, he has realistic chances to hold the position. }
20. Be3 Rc7 21. Rac1 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Ke7
{ 22...Bd6!  was a better defensive try, but not really changing the evaluation of the position.  23.Nc5  Ke7  24.Rc3±   24.Nxa6?  would be a big mistake, giving Black activity on the a-file.  24...Ra8⇆  . }
23. Nc5
{ White will gain the pair of bishops and also Black's king will be in a very unfortunate position. }
23... Ra8 24. a3 Bxc5
{ 24...Ba5  Trying to keep the bishop on the board would lose even quicker.  25.Nb7!  Bd8  26.Bc5+  Ke6   26...Ke8  Now the easiest way is to pick up the e5-pawn.  27.Nxd8  Rxd8  28.Bd6+-  .  27.Bb1  The king is not comfortable on e6!  27...Be8  28.Rd1+-  and Ba2+ will end the game in the next move. }
25. Bxc5+ Ke6 26. Bb1 Ne8 27. Rd1 Bc6 28. g3
{ Preparing f4, and also anticipating Black's king running forward. } 28... g5
29. Ke3 Rc8 30. b4
{ 30.Bb4!  was the cleanest way to win, preparing to pin the king to the defence of the e5-pawn and then winning it with f4.  30...Kf6  31.Bc3+-  . }
30... Kf6 31. Ba2 Kg7 32. Be7 h6 33. h4 gxh4 34. gxh4
{ Opening the g-file for the rook. } 34... Rc7 35. Rg1+ Kh7 36. Bc5 Rd7 37. Bf8
Bb7 38. f4 { Making more diagonals available for the bishops! } 38... f6 39.
fxe5 fxe5 40. Be6 Rc7 41. Bf5+ Kh8 42. Rg6 h5 43. Be6 Rc3+ 44. Kd2 Rc7 45. Kd3
Bc6 46. Bb3 Bb7 47. Re6 Rd7+ 48. Ke3 Nc7 49. Rxe5 *

