1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5 3. cxd5 Bxb1 4. Rxb1 Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ 5.a3  is our move inthe Baltic Defence chapter, denying Black the a2-pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. a3 O-O-O 7. Qc2 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. g3 e6 10. b4 Qg4
{ White stopped the offer of the queen exchange from c5, and now Black wants to offer it from g6.  10...Qd5  is coveredhere. }
11. Bg2 Qg6 12. e4
{ No exchange. White is playing for an attack against the black king! } 12...
Bd6 13. Be3
{ Normally when you attack a flank pawn, it is not always a must to protect it, because the bishop can easily get stuck. Here the situation is different: if Black tries to trap this bishop by playing ...b6 after Bxa7, then because of the pin on the c-file, the bishop can take that pawn as well. }
13... Kb8 14. O-O e5
{ 14...Ne7  The knight is going to c8 to defend the a7-pawn.  15.Qa4  Nc8  16.e5!  Very strong, opening up the long diagonal.  16...Be7   16...Bxe5??  is losing immediately:  17.Qb5+-  White is winning a piece because of the double attack.  17.Rbc1  Now Bxb7 is the threat, with Qc6+ to follow.  17...Qd3  18.Rfd1  Qa6  19.Rxd8  Rxd8   19...Qxa4  20.Rxh8  Qxa3  21.b5+-  The queen can't really create counterplay with such passive minor pieces.  20.Qc2+-  Black will have to protect c7, so he has no time to protect his kingside, where he will lose the game.   @@StartFEN@@1knr3r/ppp1bppp/4p1q1/4P3/QP6/P3B1P1/5PBP/2R2RK1 b - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nb6  is losing on the spot because of the Bxb7 idea.  18.Bxb6!  cxb6  19.Bxb7!  Kxb7  20.Qc6+  Kb8  21.Qc7+  Ka8  22.Qxe7+-  Rc7 is coming, and White is not even down a pawn for such a huge attack. }
15. a4
{ Good move, but I prefer the alternative solution.   15.Qa4!  b6  First creating the hook and then pushing the a-pawn seems to me even more effective.  16.Qa6→  . }
15... Ne7 16. b5 Nd5
{ Forcing the dark-squared bishop away from the diagonal temporarily is not a big success for Black.  16...h5  does nothing: we can simply stop this try from Black.  17.h4!  . }
17. Bd2 Ne7 { 17...Nf6  18.a5→  . } 18. a5 Qe6 19. Be3
{ No Nd5 anymore, so the bishop can safely return to this diagonal. } 19... h5
20. Rfc1
{ Normally,  21.h4  is the simplest reaction from White to Black's ...h5, but now we don't even have to take the time for that, since Rfc1 is creating concrete threats. }
20... Rc8
{ 20...h4  21.Bxa7+!  Kxa7  22.b6+  Ka8  23.bxc7  Bxc7  Black has to give back the piece.   23...Rc8  24.Qb2+-  The game is pretty much over here.  24.Qxc7  Rd7  25.Qc5±  The contrast in king safety gives White a huge advantage here. }
21. h4
{ Now White plays this logical move, and it is not only defensive, because Kh2-Bh3 is an idea as well! }
21... f6 22. Qa4
{ 22.Kh2!  Maybe it is even more precise to first force the closing of the kingside and then play Bf1.  22...g5  23.Bh3  g4  24.Bf1+-  . }
22... g5 23. Bf1
{ Black resigned here. It certainly looks too early, but since it was an e-mail game, probably both players saw pretty well how the game could end.   23.Bf1  gxh4  24.b6  White's attack is simply much stronger because it is supported by all his pieces.  24...hxg3   24...a6  25.Bxa6!  Destroying Black's king defenses.  25...bxa6  26.bxc7+  Ka8  27.Rc6+-  .   24...cxb6  25.axb6  a6  26.Bxa6  This thematic sacrifice is again decisive.  26...Rxc1+  27.Rxc1  bxa6  28.Qxa6  28...Qd7  29.b7+-  .  25.bxa7+  Ka8  26.Qb5  gxf2+  27.Kxf2  b6  28.axb6  cxb6  29.Qxb6  Qd7  30.Rxc8+  Rxc8  31.Ba6  Rc2+  32.Ke1+-  is one of the many possible ways for White to win. }
