[Black "18) Ruslan Shcherbakov vs. J. Deepan Chakkravarthy, Raipur 2002"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. e3 e5 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 exd4 8.
Ne2 Nge7 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxd4 O-O { 11...f6  is coveredhere. }
12. Rc1 c6 13. Be2 Be6
{ The first critical moment of the game: how to protect the a2-pawn? } 14. a3
{ 14.b3?  is a very instructive mistake:  14...a5⇆  and Black has a lot of counterplay on the queenside by playing ...a4 next.   14.Bc4?  Of course, it is not that horrible if we have to exchange bishops at some moment during the game, but to give this exchange as a present for Black is certainly not the way to go.  14...Bxc4  15.Rxc4  b6  . }
14... Nf5 15. Bc5
{ Of course, we are keeping the pair of bishops. In general, it is a very nice technique to keep the bishop 2 squares away from the knight, because then we can control most of the knight's possible squares to go to. }
15... Rfd8 16. g4 Nh6
{ Quite a strange square, but doesn't change the evaluation much.  16...Nd6  17.f3⩲  . }
17. Rg1
{ Black was not very enthusiastic about playing ...f5 here because the g7-pawn could become potentially very weak.   17.f3  was also good, since after  17...f5  we are not forced to make the structure on the kingside less flexible:  18.h3!  Probably what Black wanted by playing ...Nh6 was  18.g5  Nf7  , to setup some sort of a blockade on the kingside. }
17... b6
{ 17...f5  18.g5  Nf7  19.g6±  Indeed, this looks pretty dangerous for Black. White could also play  18.h3!?  . }
18. Bd4 c5 19. Bc3 Kf8 20. f3
{ No rush, just preparing the f2-square for the king. } 20... Ng8 21. b4
{ A very instructive move. White is allowing Black to create a protected passed pawn on c4, but that pawn is not going anywhere, because we already blockade it with the bishop. Playing ...c4 with Black will also seriously reduce the scope of the e6-bishop. Last but not least, once White is starting to push in the centre with e4, Black's knight will not have an outpost on d4. }
21... c4
{ Now White can prepare e4. No need to worry about Black's passed pawn. It is well blocked and it blocks its own bishop. }
22. Kf2 b5 23. e4 Ne7 24. Rgd1
{ Exchanging heavy pieces when having the pair of bishops is a well-known technique to make the bishops stronger, and to highlight the issues of the knight, which needs a lot of moves to switch from one side of the board to the other to have an impact, contrary to the bishops. For example, from the e3-square a bishop can control both flanks. }
24... Nc6 25. f4 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Rd8 27. Rxd8+ Nxd8 28. Ke3 { 28.g5! } 28... Nc6
29. g5
{ Fixing a weakness on g7, or forcing ...g6 to weaken a lot of dark squares. }
29... g6 30. h4 Bc8 31. h5 a6 32. Bd1 Ke8 33. Kf3
{ So far White had played a fantastic game, but this is a mistake, underestimating the power of pawns in the endgame. I believe  33.h6!  was the best move, just to fix the pawn on h7, and Black can just wait here while White executes the winning idea.  33...Bd7  34.Bc2  Bc8  35.f5  The first step is to play f5, putting pressure on g6, and improving the king by moving it to f4.  35...Bd7  36.Kf4  Kd8  37.Bd1  Ke8  38.Bf6  Bc8  39.Bh5!!  Using the power of the advanced h-pawn.  39...gxh5  40.g6+-  The h-pawn will be a queen. }
33... Ke7
{ Black is missing his chance now, and in the following moves as well.  33...gxh5!  looks very ugly, and probably not a move in a middlegame, when for example a rook can easily take care of such a pawn. However, in an endgame, everything is more concrete: since this pawn can't be taken immediately it will offer Black serious drawing chances.  34.f5  Stopping ...Bg4, but now the bishop will come from another diagonal.   34.Kg3  Bg4!  Using the ugly h-pawn to achieve a huge strategic goal, the exchange of a pair of bishops.  35.Bxg4  hxg4  36.Kxg4  Ne7⩲  Black has excellent drawing chances in this position.  34...Bb7!  35.Kf4  h4  Yes! This is the problem: the pawn will eventually fall but before that, it will cause White a lot of trouble.  36.Kg4  Ne7  37.Bc2  Nc8!  38.Kxh4   38.e5  Ne7  39.Kxh4  Bf3⇆  With Be2-Bd3 coming, this position looks very close to a draw.  38...Nd6  39.e5  Be4=  This nice intermediate move is completely equalising the game for Black. }
34. Bc2 Kd6 { 34...gxh5! } 35. Ke3 Bd7 { 35...gxh5! } 36. Be1
{ After this move,  36...gxh5  is not a big deal anymore. } 36... Bc8 37. f5
Ke7 38. Bc3 Ke8 39. Kf4 Ke7 40. Bd1 Ke8 41. Bf6 Bb7 42. h6
{ Fixing a weakness on h7. Also, tactical ideas with Bxg6 will be in the air from now on. }
42... Kf8 43. Bg4 Kg8 44. fxg6 hxg6
{ 44...fxg6  is also losing:  45.e5  c3  46.Ke3  The king is catching the c3-pawn, while the bishop is winning the game with the help of the e-pawn.  46...Nd4  47.e6  Nf5+  Black is trying to escape by entering an opposite-coloured bishop endgame, but White's pawns are very far advanced, so he has no real chances.  48.Bxf5  gxf5  49.g6!  hxg6  50.Bg5+-  White has a long but unstoppable winning plan of bringing the king to d8, and promoting the e-pawn. }
45. Bd7 Nb8 46. Be8 Bc6 47. Bxf7+ *

