[White "Model Games"]
[Black "19) Stefan Salzmann vs. Brian Jones, ICCF e-mail 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e5 4. dxe5 d4 5. g3 Nge7 6. Bg2 Ng6 7. O-O Ngxe5 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Na3 Be7 10. Nb5 O-O 11. Nxd4 Nxc4 12. Qd3 Ne5 13. Qe4 Bf6 14. Rd1
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 14... Qe7 15. f4
{ The queen is standing a little bit strange on e4, so it makes sense to exchange it and also start to push our central majority. }
15... Nc4
{ 15...Ng4  is not really an improvement. The knight will be not so great on f6.  16.Qxe7  Bxe7  17.h3  Nf6  18.e4⩲  White has a pleasant advantage because of the central majority. }
16. Qxe7 Bxe7 17. b3 { Kicking back the knight to a more passive square. }
17... Nb6
{ 17...Nd6  18.Ba3⩲  The knight is very strange on d6, and it will be also unstable once we attack the c-pawn with Rac1. }
18. h3
{ Preventing ...Bg4, which could be really unpleasant if we just played  18.e4  Bg4  . }
18... Rd8
{ 18...c6  It is logical to block the diagonal of the g2-bishop but, in this case, Black is not in time to create counterplay with ...a5-a4.  19.e4  a5  20.a4⩲  The bishop is coming to e3 and White has a clear advantage since Black's queenside pawns are not going anywhere. }
19. e4 a5
{ 19...c5  White had to be ready for this serious threat.  20.Ba3!  Pinning the bishop and also protecting the rook on d1.  20...Kf8  21.Nb5  Bd7  22.Nd6  It looks like Black's position is collapsing, but there is a nice counter trick.  22...Bxh3!  23.Bxc5  Bg4  24.Rd2⩲  White is still better here because of the more active pieces, but Black also has reasonable chances to hold this position. }
20. Be3 a4 21. Nb5
{ White is taking advantage of his better development and the awkward position of the b6-knight. }
21... axb3 22. axb3 Rxa1
{ 22...c6  This move leads to a minor piece endgame where the black pieces, especially the bishops, are going to be very passive.  23.Rxd8+  Bxd8  24.Rxa8  Nxa8  25.Nd6  Nb6  Black is not losing material because he can take back with a check on b6.  26.Kf2  Bc7  27.Ne8  Bd8  28.f5±  The black bishops are suffering, while White is going to start to push the majority on the kingside. }
23. Rxa1 Rd3 24. Bf2 Rxb3 25. Nxc7
{ The material is quite limited, but the difference between the pieces is huge, so White is going to increase his advantage by keeping the initiative going. }
25... Bf8 26. Rd1
{ The bishop left the protection of the d8-square, so the rook is trying to enter using that square. }
26... Be7 27. Rc1
{ Now the idea is to attack the bishop on e7 with a Nd5 tempo, and enter via c8. }
27... Ba3 28. Rc2 Rb4 29. Rd2
{ Once again aiming at d8, but now the bishop can't protect that square anymore. }
29... Nd7 30. Nd5 Rb1+ 31. Kh2 b6 32. e5
{ Even if Black could somehow stop White's very strong initiative, losing the b-pawn is very likely, which means a long and unpleasant defence in a 4 vs 3 endgame. }
32... Bf8 33. Ra2
{ Finally the rook is invading, providing White with a decisive advantage. }
33... g6 34. g4 Rb5 35. Ra7 { Rxd7 is a huge threat now. } 35... Rb2 36. Bd4
Rc2 37. Kg3 b5 38. Be3
{ 38.Rxd7?  was also possible in the previous move, but the refutation is the same:  38...Bxd7  39.Nf6+  Kg7  40.Nxd7  Rd2  41.Ba1   41.Nxf8??  Rxd4-+  is even winning for Black.  41...Rd1!  and Black keeps attacking the bishop and holds the draw.  42.Bb2  Rd2=  . }
38... Kg7 39. Be4 Rc4 40. Bd3 Ra4 41. Rc7 Ra3 42. Bxb5
{ The pawn has fallen, but the initiative continues. } 42... Nb6 43. Nxb6 Rxe3+
44. Kf2 Rb3 45. Bc4
{ Black resigned, since White will be 2 pawns up very soon.  45.Bc4  Rxb6  46.Rxf7+  Kg8  47.Re7+  Kh8  48.Re8+-  . }
