1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 c5 4. d5 e6 5. Bxc4 Nf6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 8.
Bxd5 Be7 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Na6 11. Bf4 Nc7 12. Nc3
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bd6 14. e5 Bb8
{ 14...Bc7?  This is a more active square for the bishop, but has a tactical flaw.  15.e6!  Bxf4  16.e7  Bxh2+  17.Kh1±  So the queen can't come out from the fork with a check. White is winning material. }
15. Qb3 { Preparing to bring the rook to the d-file. } 15... Be6 16. Rad1 b6
17. Bg3
{ Moving the kingside majority with f4-f5 is White's idea with this move. }
17... Bc7
{ 17...Qe8  doesn't change so much compared to the game. Basically, the queen will be on e8 instead of e7, which is hardly an improvement for Black.  18.f4  Bc7  This move is a must for Black anyways. Otherwise, the rook can't come into the game.  19.f5  Bxd5  20.Qxd5  Rd8  21.Qe4±  White has a nice advantage here: the queen is misplaced on e8. }
18. f4 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Qe7 20. f5 Rad8
{ Exchanging pieces is the correct strategy from Black. Even though White's position looks very promising to the eye thanks to the central control, he has to be very precise to demonstrate some advantage because of the limited material on the board. }
21. Rfd1
{ This leads to further exchanges. Therefore, I would like to suggest a possible improvement at this moment.  21.Re1!?  We admit that we can't win the game on the d-file and instead we will try to push e6 or f6.  21...Qg5  22.Rxd8  Rxd8  23.Qf3  So, we gave up the control over the d-file, and our pieces are just supporting the advance of the central pawns.  23...Qd2  24.Kh1  Useful prophylaxis, stepping out from any possible checks on the g1-a7 diagonal.  24...h6  25.Qc6  Bb8  26.f6!  Creating weaknesses around the black king.  26...gxf6  27.Qxf6⩲  White has better chances here with a much safer king.   @@StartFEN@@3r2k1/p1b2ppp/1p6/2p1PP2/8/5QB1/PP1q2PP/4R2K b - - 3 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Qxb2??  is too greedy, and it is not the first time in chess history that the b2-pawn was poisoned!  25.e6!  A huge tempo on the c7-bishop.  25...Bxg3  26.e7!  Re8  27.Qc6+-  With the king on g1 we would lose to ...Qf2+, so we can see one of the points of Kh1 now.   Trading rooks is premature because the queen can enter Black's position: @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/p1b1qppp/1p6/2pRPP2/8/1Q4B1/PP4PP/4R1K1 b - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Rxd5?  22.Qxd5  Rd8  23.Qb7±  There are serious problems on the 7th rank. }
21... Rxd5
{ 21...h5!?  Black could have also opened the back rank before trading everything on the d-file. }
22. Rxd5 Rd8 23. Qd3 Rxd5 24. Qxd5 h6
{ 24...h5!  is probably better. Black can sometimes count on ...Qg5-...h4 ideas.  25.Bf4  c4  Black can create enough counterplay to secure equality here.  26.g3  b5!  The bishop is coming to b6 and finally will take part in the game.  27.Qxb5  Bb6+  28.Kf1  Qb7  The black pieces are very active and White's king is exposed now.  29.Qxc4  Qh1+  30.Ke2  Qxh2+  31.Kd3  Qxb2=  Black should be able to give a perpetual check here. }
25. Bf4 Kh7
{ Too slow. It was time for Black to start the counterplay.   25...c4!  The same idea as one move earlier. Black should activate his bishop.  26.Kf1  The king steps away from ...Bb6+, but Black has other resources to create counterplay.  26...b5  27.Qxb5  Qd8!  The checks on the d-file are going to be unpleasant.  28.Qxc4  Qd1+  29.Kf2  Bb6+  30.Kg3  h5⇆  White is still okay, but in a practical game it is much easier to play with Black now. }
26. g3 g5
{ Black wanted to undermine White's strong centre like this, but it creates a passed pawn for White. }
27. fxg6+ fxg6 28. g4
{ The g5-push was coming, so White had to prepare a square for the bishop on the diagonal. }
28... Kg7 29. Kg2 b5 30. Bg3 Kh7 { Black is just waiting. } 31. h4
{ White is just improving his position, but it was already time for concrete action.  31.e6!  Taking on c7 and playing Qd7 is the winning threat.  31...Bxg3  32.Kxg3  Kg7  33.Kf4!  The king comes to the game and Black can't defend against it.  33...Qf6+   33...Kf6??  34.Qe5  .  34.Ke4+-  Qd7+ is coming or, if the queen retreats, then the white king will simply enter via e5 or, after Qe5+, via d5. }
31... a6 32. g5 hxg5 33. hxg5 c4 34. a3 Kg7 35. Bf4 Kf8 36. Kf3 c3
{ Looking for counterplay, but first exchanging queens was necessary.  36...Qd8!  37.Ke4  Trying to get a better version of the bishop endgame, but Black is not forced to take on d5!   37.Qxd8+  Bxd8  38.Ke4  Ba5=  Black can trade all the queenside pawns and make a comfortable draw.  37...Qc8⇆  Black has enough counterplay to make a draw. }
37. bxc3 Qxa3 38. Qc6
{ Probably the move Black missed. The queen is dominating on c6, protecting c3 and attacking the enemy pieces. }
38... Bd8 39. e6 { Bd6 is unstoppable. Black has no defence here. } 39... Kg8
40. Bd6 *

