1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 Bg4 5. Bxc4 e6 6. O-O Nbd7 7. h3 Bh5 8.
Nbd2 Bd6 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Qe7 11. Be2 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5
Qxe5 15. Bxh5 Nxh5
{ It is probably better for Black to enter the endgame right away, but it is still far from clear equality.  15...Qxh5  16.Qxh5  Nxh5  17.Rac1  c6  18.Nc4⩲  White's majority on the kingside is much more mobile than Black's on the queenside, also the white knight has a potentially nice outpost on d6, so Black will have to fight for the draw in this endgame. }
16. Nc4 Qc5 17. Qf3
{ A very annoying move, attacking b7 while still keeping an eye on the h5-knight. All this has been coveredhere. }
17... c6
{ In this particular case, Black is not in time to stop the knight invading d6. This is a worse option but definitely a more human move than  17...b6  . It looks scary to weaken the c6-square and also leave the way open for the queen to enter to b7, but Black needed to play like this.  18.Rac1  Nf6  Both the queen and knight are misplaced, so Black is relocating those pieces.  19.e4  Qe7  20.e5  Nd7  21.Qg3⩲  With f4-f5 coming, White still keeps a nice advantage, but Black is also pretty solid. }
18. Rfd1 { Preparing to play Nd6! } 18... Nf6
{ 18...Rad8  would be the natural equaliser for Black, but it simply doesn't work.  19.Rxd8!  Exploiting the h5-knight's unlucky position, White is gaining the d-file by very simple means.  19...Rxd8  20.Rd1  Rf8  It would be a big surprise if Black could hold the position with such passive moves.  21.Rd7  b5  22.Na5!  Nf6  23.Rd1  Qc2   23...Rc8?  Black still can't protect on c6 by simple means because of the weak back rank.  24.Qxc6+-  24.Nxc6  Qxa2  25.e4!  White's coordination is perfect and a huge initiative is coming in the centre.  25...a5  26.e5  Ne8  27.e6  Nf6   27...fxe6??  28.Ne7++-  A quick checkmate.  28.e7  Re8  29.Rd8+-  With Qxf6 coming next, Black has no defence.   @@StartFEN@@3r2k1/pp3ppp/2p5/2q4n/2N5/1P2PQ1P/P4PP1/3R2K1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Rxd1+  21.Qxd1  If Black could play ...Qe7 in this position, then he would be a favourite to get a draw, but unfortunately it is not possible because the knight is hanging on h5.  21...h6  22.Qd7  b5  23.Nd6  Qd5  24.Qc8+!   @@StartBracket@@  24.e4!?  is also very promising and strong, according to the engine.  @@EndBracket@@  24...Kh7  25.Qf5+!  Simplifying to a knight endgame is winning material for White straight away.  25...Qxf5  26.Nxf5  a6  27.Ne7!  Nice square for the knight, attacking the c6-pawn and also temporarily blocking the king's ways into the game.  27...c5  28.Nd5  Nf6  29.Nc7  c4  30.bxc4  bxc4  31.Nxa6+-  With a winning endgame for White. }
19. Nd6 Rab8
{ 19...Rad8  This was also possible, but would lead to long suffering in a 4 vs 3 ending.  20.Nxb7  Rxd1+  21.Rxd1  Qc2  22.Na5  Qxa2  23.Nxc6  Qxb3  24.Nxa7±  Of course, this pure rook endgame would be a theoretical draw, but since we have still queens and knights, it will be anything but easy to hold this position with Black. }
20. Rac1
{ A little bit inaccurate. The queen is better on e5 than on c5, so White should have doubled the rooks right away.  20.Rd4±  . }
20... Qe5 21. Rc2 g6 22. Rcd2 Qe7
{ It is still okay, but now or in the next move Black had a chance to enter a very unpleasant but probably holdable position.  22...Nd5  23.Nc4  Qe7  24.e4  Nf6  25.e5  Nd5  26.Ne3!  The only way to try to break Black's position.  26...Qxe5  27.Nxd5  cxd5  28.Rxd5  Qb2  29.a4⩲  I won't argue with the engine that this position is most probably holdable, but I don't want to play this as Black. :@@EndBracket@@ }
23. e4 Rfd8
{ 23...Ne8  leads pretty much to the same thing as 22...Nd5.  24.Nc4  Nf6  25.e5  Nd5  26.Ne3! }
24. Qg3
{ Very strong. Now Black is in serious trouble because of many tactical tricks. }
24... Nh5
{ 24...Ne8??  would be the most natural move, but it is just losing on the spot.  25.Nf5!  Qf6  26.Nh6+  Kf8   26...Kg7  27.e5+-  The queen has to guard the rook on d8, but it can't go to e7 due to the Nf5 fork.  27.Rd7+-  Black is falling apart on d7. }
25. Nf5 { Nice counterattack! } 25... Qf6
{ 25...Qe8  26.Qc7!  26...Rxd2  27.Ne7+!  The point of White's play!  27...Kf8  28.Rxd2  Nf6  29.f3+-  Black is paralyzed, and White even has an e5-threat.   @@StartFEN@@1r2q1k1/ppQ1Np1p/2p3p1/7n/4P3/1P5P/P2r1PP1/3R2K1 b - - 1 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Qxe7  28.Qxb8+!  One more intermezzo and now it is simple.  28...Kg7  29.Rxd2  Qxe4  30.Kh2+-  White is winning with a clear exchange up. }
26. Nh6+ Kg7
{ 26...Kf8  is no better.  27.Qc7!  Rdc8  28.Qa5+-  Rd7 is coming, the a7-pawn is hanging, and if that were not enough White also has a Ng4 idea: if then the queen leaves the long diagonal, Qc3 is very unpleasant. }
27. e5 Qe6 28. Qe3 { Black's knight is completely sidelined. } 28... Rxd2
{ 28...Re8  29.Rd7!  Re7  30.Rxe7  Qxe7  31.g4+-  Highlighting the unfortunate location of the knight. }
29. Rxd2 Re8 30. Ng4 Kg8 31. Qh6
{ 31.Rd3+-  Keeping all the options and threatening Qd2 was even stronger. Black can't really defend then against the Rd7-Nh6+ idea. }
31... Qe7 32. g3 Rd8 33. Rxd8+ Qxd8 34. Qe3 b6
{ 34...Qb6!  would have kept Black in the game, but still with a miserable position.  35.Qd3  Qc7  36.e6!  Weakening the black king.  36...fxe6  37.Qd4  e5  38.Qxa7±  Still with excellent chances of winning the game. }
35. e6 f5
{ Ideally Black should take this pawn, but now the c6-pawn drops:  35...fxe6  36.Qxe6+  Kg7  37.Qxc6+-  . }
36. e7 Qe8 37. Qe6+ Kg7 38. Qe5+ *

