1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Be2 Rd8 11. Ne5 Be7 12. Ndc4 Rxd1+ 13. Bxd1 Nbd7 14.
Bd2 { All this has been coveredhere. } 14... Ne4 15. Ba5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bf6 17.
Nc4 Bd7
{ The other way for Black to try and finish the development is  17...b5  18.Nb6  Rb8  19.Rc1!  The rook is coming to the open file with a tempo.  19...Bd8   19...Bb7  20.Nd7!  White is securing the 2-bishop advantage and even exchanges the rooks along the way.  20...Rc8  21.Nxf6+  Nxf6  22.Rxc8+  Bxc8  23.f3±  The position is very simplified and very unpleasant for Black. Both of his minor pieces will be seriously restricted after White's next move, which is going to be e4, and then the king is marching towards the queenside on the dark squares.  20.Bf3  Bb7  21.Nd7  Ra8  22.Bxe4  Trading off the bishops and securing a good knight vs not so good bishop endgame.  22...Bxe4  23.Bxd8  Rxd8  24.Rc7⩲  Our knight will be really strong on c5.   @@StartFEN@@1rbb2k1/5ppp/pN2p3/Bp6/4n3/4PB2/PP3PPP/2R3K1 b - - 5 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nf6  Here White has at least 2 good ways to play:  21.Bb4!  A remarkable tactical idea. Black obviously can't take with the rook on b6 because of Rxc8, but ...Bxb6 is not possible either because Bd6 is trapping the rook.  21...a5!  Only move for Black to avoid immediate defeat.  22.Bxa5  Ba6  23.Rd1±  Another nice move. The idea is to play Nc4, protect the bishop on a5 and counterattack on d8.   A simple way to play is @@StartFEN@@1rbb2k1/5ppp/pN2pn2/Bp6/8/4PB2/PP3PPP/2R3K1 w - - 6 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Rxc8  Rxc8  22.Nxc8  Bxa5  23.Bb7  Bd8  24.Bxa6  b4  25.Nd6±  With only opposite-coloured bishops on the board Black's drawing chances would be extremely high here. Now it is not the case at all, it is rather 50-50 if White can win this position or not. }
18. Bf3 Bc6 19. Rc1
{ There is no entry square on the d-file. White's idea is to play Na5 at some moment, and then he can either gain the pair of bishops or enter via c7. }
19... Rb8
{ Trading the bishops rather helps White with the Na5 idea.  19...Bd8  20.Bxd8  Rxd8  21.h4⩲  Opening the back rank and introducing the Na5 idea.  21...Bd5?  Black can't keep the c-file under control like this, because we have a simple tactical trick.  22.Nb6!  Bc6  23.Rxc6!  bxc6  24.Bxe4±  White has excellent winning chances in this endgame.   If Black could make one more move here, and move his light-squared bishop to d5,  19...Rc8  would be excellent, but now it is rather just a blunder:  20.Nb6  Rd8  21.Na4!  The rook has to stay on the d-file to prevent the Rxc6 idea by means of the back rank mate on d1.  21...Rd5   21...Rd3  22.Bxe4+-  Now Black has problems on the back rank!  22.b4!  Black is losing material here.  22...Bxa4  23.Bxe4  Rd1+  24.Rxd1  Bxd1  25.Bxb7+-  With an easily winning endgame. }
20. b3
{ The knight is free to move now. Also, if the other black bishop is coming to d5, it will be well restricted by the pawns on a2 and b3. }
20... h6 21. h3
{ Both sides are opening the back rank. These moves are useful for the tactical fight which may happen in the near future. }
21... Bh4 22. g3
{ The main goal of Bh4 is to have the bishop and the pawn unprotected for a second, so Black's next move is too slow and allows the bishop to retreat to the protected g2-square. }
22... Bf6
{ 22...Bd8!  Black absolutely had to try this move now, while the bishop on f3 and the pawn are not protected.  23.Bxd8  Rxd8  24.Bg2!  Preparing Na5/Ne5 and Ng5 will not come with a tempo anymore.   24.Ne5  Bd5  25.Rc7  The rook enters the 7th rank, but Black can create counterplay.  25...Ng5=  Black is fine here.  24...Bd5  25.Nb6  f5!  Protecting the knight, so Rc7 doesn't make too much sense now, since Black can reply with ...Bc6 @@StartBracket@@Rxc6 is not an idea anymore, because the knight is not hanging on e4@@EndBracket@@ and our rook doesn't do much on c7.  26.Nxd5  exd5  27.Rc7  d4!  Black is looking for active counterplay.  28.Bxe4  fxe4  29.exd4  Rxd4  30.Kf1!  With this move White keeps more winning chances.   30.Rxb7  Leads to a 3 vs 2 endgame, which is a simple draw for the defender.  30...Rd1+  31.Kg2  Rd2  32.Re7  Rxa2  33.Rxe4  Ra3  34.Rb4  a5=  Black will trade the pawns on the queenside and will make the draw easily.  30...Rd2  31.a4  b5  32.axb5  axb5  33.Rc5  e3!  Black is getting rid of one of his weaknesses.  34.fxe3  Rd3  35.Rxb5  Rxe3  36.Kf2±  The position should be a draw, but White still keeps realistic winning chances. }
23. Bg2 Bd8
{ Black just lost a very valuable tempo.   23...Kf8??  He can't bring the king closer.  24.Nb6+-  Now Rxc6 can be followed not only by Bxe4 but also by Nd7+.   23...g5  24.g4  With the idea to play f3 in the future.  24...Kg7  25.Bb4±  The knight is restricted and in danger of getting trapped in the middle of the board. }
24. Bxd8 Rxd8 25. g4
{ Making ...f5 much less appealing for Black.   25.Ne5  Against this move Black could still achieve a decent position.  25...Bd5  26.Rc7  Ng5!  Again Ng5 is providing counterplay.  27.h4  Bxg2  28.Kxg2  Ne4  29.Kf3  f5⩲  White is better, but Black has good chances to hold. }
25... f5 26. Na5 Rd6
{ 26...Bd5  27.gxf5!  That's why g4 was very good. Now we can destabilise the bishop on d5.  27...exf5  28.Rd1!  Nxb7 is a huge threat.  28...Rd6  29.Kh2!  Bxe4 is a threat now, because ...Rg6 is not coming with a check.   29.Bxe4  was not working yet.  29...fxe4  30.Nxb7??  Rg6+-+  And Black is winning the game.  29...b5  30.Bxe4!  fxe4  31.Nb7  Rb6  32.Rxd5  Rxb7  33.Rd6  a5  34.Ra6+-  White will have an extra pawn on the queenside and Black has a second weakness on e4, so the position is technically winning for White. }
27. Nxc6
{ White is simplifying to a winning bishop vs knight endgame. Black's structure will be very bad. }
27... Rxc6 28. Rxc6 bxc6 29. Bf1 fxg4
{ 29...a5?  30.Bc4+-  Black is losing material. } 30. Bxa6
{ 30.hxg4??  would throw away the advantage.  30...a5= } 30... gxh3 31. a4 Kf7
32. a5 { The passed a-pawn gives White a winning advantage. } 32... Ke7 33. Bb5
{ Not necessarily bad, but not needed at all.   33.Bd3!  This was a much simpler way to win, forcing the knight into passive defence.  33...Nd6  34.a6  Nc8  35.Kh2  Kd6  36.Kxh3+-  The king will enter the kingside and take the pawns. }
33... Nc3 { 33...cxb5??  34.a6+-  The pawn is too fast! } 34. Bxc6 Kd6 35. Be8
Nd5 36. Bf7
{ This mistake gives Black the chance to draw the game.   36.Bh5  Kc5  37.Be2±  Was still a very promising endgame for White. }
36... Nc7 37. Bh5 Kc5 38. Be2 Kb4 39. a6 Ka5 40. b4+ Kb6 41. b5
{ The black king is stopping our passers, Black should create a fortress on the kingside with the rest of his pieces and make a draw. }
41... e5
{ 41...g5!  Black could have set up a blockade with this move.  42.Kh2  Ne8  43.Kxh3  Nf6= }
42. Kh2 *

