1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. h4 h5 10.
Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O { This has all been coveredhere. } 12... Nbd7
13. e4
{ White plays e4 right away.  13.f3!?  first was an interesting alternative. White is planning to take back with the pawn on e4.  13...Nb6  14.Kb1  Bd6!  Black is slowing down e4 a little bit, but it will eventually come.  15.Nge2↑ }
13... dxe4
{ The engine likes  13...Nb6!?  but it is scary for a human to play like this and allow e5 with a tempo.  14.e5  Ng4  15.Rdf1  We have to take the time to play this move, because of the Nf2 threat.  15...Bxh4  16.Nce2  Renewing the threat of f3.  16...Qe7  17.f3  Nh6  18.Nxh5!  This unusual tactical idea gives White a great position.  18...gxh5  19.g3  Bg5  20.Rxh5  Bxf4+  21.Nxf4  O-O-O  22.Rfh1±  White will take back the knight either immediately, or if  22...Qf8  , will do it after g4-g5.   Unfortunately @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp3p2/1np3p1/3pP2p/3P1Bnb/2NQ2N1/PP3PP1/2K2R1R w kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.f3?!  is not working tactically:  16...Bxg3!  17.Bxg3  Qg5+!  Black's play is risky, but it is just working.  18.Kb1  Ne3  19.Bh4  Qf5⩱  Black is exchanging the queens, and he will enter the endgame with an extra pawn. }
14. Ngxe4 Nxe4
{ It was better to castle, even though the position remains risky for Black.  14...O-O  15.f3→  Kb1 and g4 are coming and White's king is much safer, which is the most important factor in positions where opposite side castling happened. }
15. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Already a losing mistake, but Black's position was critical even after correct play.  15...Nb6!  16.Be5  Rh7!  This strange move is relatively the best for Black.   16...f6??  was losing on the spot.  17.Nxf6+!  Bxf6  18.Qxg6++-  White is winning back the bishop on f6 with 2 extra pawns.   16...O-O  is not safe once Black put the knight on b6 :@@EndBracket@@  17.g4!  hxg4  18.h5→  The attack looks decisive.  17.g4!  Using the advantage in the development and the shaky position of the black king.  17...hxg4  18.h5  Rxh5  19.Rxh5  gxh5  20.Re1→  White has a very strong, according to the computer, winning attack. }
16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Qa3
{ Preventing O-O. Now Rhe1 is coming with big power.   17.Rhe1+?  leads nowhere: Black's king will be perfectly safe on g7.  17...Kf8= }
17... Qd5 18. Rhe1+ Kd7 19. Be5
{ Black is losing material, he can't protect the bishop and obviously also can't exchange on e5, because then he would lose the queen. }
19... Be7 20. Qh3+ f5 21. Bxh8 Rxh8
{ White is winning, but he didn't play very accurately in the next few moves. }
22. b3
{ 22.Kb1!  looks like a much better move, keeping the 3rd rank open and also not weakening the dark squares.  22...Bf6  23.Qa3  This move is already a nice plus compared to the positions with b3.  23...a6  24.g3+-  Qc5 is coming next and White is completely winning. }
22... Bf6 23. Qg3 Rg8 24. Re5
{ A nice move to win a tempo, but the plan with the move was wrong. } 24... Qd6
25. Ra5 { The simple retreat  25.Re2  was much stronger.  25...Qd5  26.Kc2+- }
25... a6 26. Qxd6+ Kxd6
{ Even though White has managed to exchange the queens, his coordination is not good, and suddenly he is facing technical problems. }
27. g3 Re8 28. Ra4 Kd5 29. Rd2 Re4 30. Kc2 Rg4
{ Black is correctly not taking on d4, once the d2 rook can get active, the game should be lost again for Black.   30...Bxd4??  31.f3+-   30...Rxd4  31.Raxd4+  Bxd4  32.Re2+- }
31. Ra5+ Kd6 32. d5 c5 33. Ra4 Rxa4
{ Opening the b-file was the decisive mistake.  33...Re4  would still pose White serious problems.  34.Rxe4  fxe4  It is not easy to find a way to activate the rook.  35.Kd1  Bc3  36.Rc2  Bd4  37.Ke2  Kxd5±  White has to work hard to convert this position into a full point. }
34. bxa4 Bd4 35. a5 { Fixing the weakness on b7! } 35... Kxd5 36. Re2 Be5 37.
f4 Bc7 38. Re7 Bxa5 39. Rxb7 Be1 40. Rd7+ Kc4 41. Rd6 Bxg3 42. Rxg6 Bxh4 43.
Rh6 Bg3 44. Rxh5 a5 45. Rxf5 Kd4 46. Rf8 Kd5 47. f5 Bf2 48. Re8 Bd4 49. Re6 Bg7
50. a4 Bf8 51. Ra6 *

