1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Bf5 6. e3 Nf6 7. Nge2 Qb6 8. Qd2 Ne4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4
10. a3 Nd7 11. Nc3 { This has all been coveredhere. } 11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ White is aiming for a position with opposite-coloured bishops. } 12... Be7
{ One needs a strong stomach to play positions like  12...Bg6  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.h4  h5  15.g3⩲  White has a free advantage with a much better structure. }
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bc4
{ The point of White's play is that for the time being Black has an isolated pawn on e4, since it will take time to play f5, and even when it happens White's bishop will be stronger than Black's, which is well restricted by the f2-e3-d4 pawn chain. }
15... O-O 16. b4 a5
{ The most solid and probably the best option for Black was  16...Kh8  , immediately starting to prepare a pawn push to f5.  17.O-O  Be7  18.Rab1  f5  19.a4⩲  Now Black is solid in the centre, but White is still better because he has the space advantage and the initiative on the queenside. }
17. O-O Be7
{ Allows White to take the e4-pawn for the b-pawn, giving White a serious advantage in the centre.   17...axb4  18.axb4  g6  19.Rab1⩲  Black's position is still not easy, but now at least he will be in a time to protect the e4-pawn. }
18. Qc2 axb4 19. axb4 Bxb4
{ This loses the f7-pawn, while the e4-pawn will remain weak.  19...Qxb4  was much better, with the idea of transposing into a pawn down endgame with decent drawing chances.  20.Rab1!  Qa4  Now White can choose the type of position he wants to enter with an extra pawn. The safer and more practical choice is  21.Qxa4   21.Qxe4  Qxc4  22.Qxe7  b5  23.Rbc1  Qa2  24.Rxc6  Rfb8⩲  Long-term, for example in a simple rook endgame, White is easily winning such position, but for now the b-pawn provides real counterplay for Black.  21...Rxa4  22.Rxb7  Rxc4  23.Rxe7  Rc3  24.Rxe4  c5  25.g4±  White has serious winning chances, but since the pawns are on the same flank, Black also has decent drawing chances.   @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p2bppp/2p5/8/1qBPp3/4P3/2Q2PPP/1R3RK1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qd6  could be also a very interesting try, but it has a serious tactical flaw at the critical moment.  21.Rxb7  Rfb8  22.Rxb8+  Rxb8  23.Qxe4  This looks bad for Black, but if he can trade off his weak c-pawn, then suddenly the drawing chances are very real.  23...c5  24.dxc5!  Qxc5  25.Bxf7+!  This move refutes Black's 20...Qd6 idea.  25...Kxf7  26.Qf4++-  . }
20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Qb3 Qa5
{ 21...Rf8??  22.Rb1+-  White is winning the bishop. } 22. Rb1 b5 23. Bxf7+ Kh8
24. Qd1
{ Most probably aimed against ...Be1, but that was not a real threat. More useful was  24.g3!  opening the back rank.  24...Rf8   24...Be1  25.Kf1!  White can kick out the bishop immediately, so no tricks with Rf8-Bxf2 are working.  25.Qxb4  The rook endgame is going to be very tough for Black because besides being down a pawn, he will also have an isolated pawn on e4.  25...Qxb4  26.Rxb4  Rxf7  27.d5!  cxd5  28.Rxb5  Black is losing the d5-pawn because of his weak back rank.  28...g6  29.Rxd5  Re7  30.g4±  should be a technically winning endgame for White. }
24... Rf8 25. Bb3 Bc3 26. Qe2 b4 27. Qg4 Re8
{ 27...Qf5  was probably better, but the endgame is not really a tempting option for Black.  28.Qxf5  Rxf5  29.Bc2  c5  30.Bxe4  Rh5  31.dxc5  Rxc5  32.g3±  The bishop will blockade the b-pawn, and then White can push his extra pawns in the centre. }
28. Bf7 Rf8 29. Qxe4 b3
{ Desperation. The only way to stay in the game was  29...c5  30.dxc5  Qxc5  31.Bd5±  . }
30. Bxb3 Be1 31. f4 Qd2 32. Qf3
{ White is easily defending against all the threats. } 32... Qc3 33. Bd1 g5 34.
Qe4 c5 35. Bc2 *

