[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. dxc5 d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 Qxc5
10. e3 dxe3 11. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 Nge7 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 14... Be6
{ Instead of playing against the pair of bishops, GM Fridman decides to play with a weakness on e6, and as we know, one weakness is not enough to win, so this move is perfectly playable, but the problem is, that this position is just never equal, as long as Black has a weak pawn on e6. }
15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Rfe1 Nd5 17. Bd2
{ We have already seen this motif in other model games before. } 17... Rfe8 18.
Rac1 h6 19. Rc4 { The rook can be used quite nicely on the 4th rank. } 19...
Rad8 20. a3 Rd6 21. h3 a6 22. Kf1
{ White's approach is very instructive, since he has no clear plan on how to break Black's position @@StartBracket@@because such a plan doesn't exist@@EndBracket@@ he is just playing very slowly, and improving his position step by step, and it is also worth noting that it is easier to commit a mistake at move 70 than at move 25. }
22... Kf7 23. g3 Rdd8 24. Kg2 Rd6 25. Re2 Rdd8 26. h4
{ One small question for Black: maybe White wants h5, or maybe not? } 26... Nf6
27. Bc3 Nd5 28. Bd2 Nf6 29. Bf4 Nd5 30. Bc1 Rc8 31. Bf4
{ Another small question: does Black really want to take this bishop? } 31...
Nce7
{ It would not be good to take it:  31...Nxf4+?!  32.Rxf4+  Ke7  33.h5±  Now White has another potential target, the g7-pawn, and also the knight can go to g6, which looks pretty unpleasant. }
32. Rce4 Ng6
{ 32...Nc6  33.Be5  and playing g4-Kg3 is a possible way to progress in this position. }
33. Bd6 Nf6 34. Rb4
{ Another little change in the position, Black will have to push his b-pawn forward. }
34... b5 35. a4 Red8 36. Be5 Rc5 37. axb5 axb5
{ White has two potential targets, of course, the position is still equal, but a little bit more complicated already. }
38. Bd4 Rcd5
{ 38...Rc4?  is not possible because White has an intermediate move:  39.Bxf6  gxf6  40.Rxb5±  . }
39. Bc3 Rb8 40. Rb3 Nd7 41. Rb4 Rb6 42. Rbe4 Nf6 43. Rd4 Rb7 44. Rb4 Nd7 45.
Rbe4 Rb6 46. Re1 Nf6 47. R4e3 b4
{ The move is perfectly fine, but again, it is an unnecesarry change in the position and it is not easy to make such decisions. }
48. Bd4 Rbd6 49. Bxf6 gxf6 50. Rb3 Rb6 51. Re4 Rdb5 52. Rc4
{ Finally White has a real threat, although it is quite easily addressed by Black. }
52... e5 53. Rd3 Ne7 54. Rd1 h5 55. Rdc1 Rb7 56. Nd2 Nf5 57. Ne4 R5b6 58. Rc6
Nd4 59. Rc8 Kg6 60. Rg8+ Rg7 61. Ra8 Kf5 62. f3 Kg6 63. Kf2 Ne6 64. Rcc8 Rc7
65. Rg8+ Rg7 66. Rgb8 Rxb8 67. Rxb8
{ Black was defending excellently, but White still managed to create some imbalance. Of course, the game is still very close to a draw, but probably in time trouble, Black goes wrong. }
67... Rc7
{ Going for a pawn down rook endgame was the correct decision:  67...f5!  68.Rb6   If  68.Nd6  f4!  Creating the f4-square for the knight.  69.Rxb4  fxg3+  70.Kxg3  Kh7+  71.Kf2  Nf4=∞  and Black's activity is enough to make a draw.  68...fxe4  69.Rxe6+  Kf5  70.Rb6  exf3  71.Kxf3  e4+  Black just has to take the pawn on g3, and he will reach a drawish rook endgame.  72.Kf2  e3+  73.Kf3  e2  74.Kxe2  Rxg3  75.Rxb4  Rh3=  Black's rook is very active, White has no real chances to win this endgame. }
68. Rxb4 Rc2+ 69. Ke3 Rg2
{ 69...Rc6⩲  Being down a pawn and going back to defend the 6th rank is anything but easy. }
70. Rb6 Kf7 71. f4 exf4+ 72. gxf4 Ng7
{ The decisive mistake.  72...Rg1!  would have still given Black chances to save the game.  73.Nd6+  Ke7  74.Nf5+  Kd7  75.b4  Rf1⩲  . }
73. Kf3 Rh2 74. Rxf6+ Kg8 75. b4 { 75.Nf2! } 75... Rxh4 76. Nf2
{ White traps the rook, so the game is decided. } 76... Ne8 77. Rc6 Ng7 78. Rg6
Kf7 79. Rxg7+ Kxg7 80. Kg3 *

