1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 dxe4 9. Bb5+
Nc6 10. Nxe4 Qf4 11. Qe2 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. dxc5 Bd5 15. Rfe1
{ Black has different ways to take back the pawn here, but since his queenside structure is compromised, in any case, White can keep the game going and put pressure in the endgame. This has all been coveredhere. }
15... Rfe8
{ 15...f5  16.Nd6  Bxd6  17.cxd6  Qxd6  18.Nd4  It is good to move this knight and build a g2-f3 chain to restrict the bishop on d5.  18...Qg6   The knight is unprotected, but if  18...Bxg2?  White has a strong intermezzo!  19.Qe6+!  Qxe6  20.Nxe6±  White is winning an exchange.  19.f3⩲  . }
16. Qd2 Qxd2 17. Nfxd2 f5 18. Nd6 Bxd6 19. cxd6 Red8
{ Black is winning back the pawn on d6 and entering an endgame which is 0.00 for the engines but never equal for humans. :@@EndBracket@@ }
20. Nb1
{ A very strong move, putting the knight to the stable c3-square, and later it can go further to a4 and c5. }
20... Rxd6 21. Nc3 Be6 22. f3 Kf7 23. Re2 a5 24. Na4
{ Setting up a strong blockading position on the queenside, and not letting any counterplay for Black. }
24... Rb8 25. b3 Rb5 26. Rc1 Rbd5 27. Kf2 f4
{ Black is defending well, he has a light-squared bishop, so he wants his pawns on dark squares. }
28. Nc3 Rc5 29. Rcc2 Rd3 30. Ne4 Rxc2 31. Rxc2 Bd5 32. Nc5 Rd4 33. Ke2 Ke7 34.
Rd2 Rb4
{ It would be a huge mistake to take, since White will have an outside passed pawn.  34...Rxd2+?  35.Kxd2  g5  36.Nb7  a4  37.bxa4  Bxa2  38.a5  Kd7  39.Nc5+  Kc7  40.Kc3+-  White's king will enter the kingside and take all the pawns. }
35. Kd3 Kd6 36. Na4
{ Black was playing really well up to this moment, but as you can see he still didn't manage to 'straighten' his structure on the queenside, which is an annoying thing for a human. }
36... c5
{ Perfectly logical, and...bad!  36...g5  would have kept the position under control.  37.Kc3  Rb8  38.Re2  The engine is still not impressed, saying just zeros, but the game is still going on. }
37. Kc3 Kc6
{ Probably Black's intention was  37...c4?  , but White prepared a nice trick against it.  38.Nb6!  Rxb6  39.bxc4±  and White has a winning rook endgame. }
38. Nb2 { Controlling both the a4 and the c4-square. } 38... g5
{ 38...Rb8  was still kind of okay for Black, but extremely difficult to see why.  39.Nd3  a4!  40.b4!  Bg8!  Amazing defensive resource. Putting the bishop away from the checks into safety, so it can help with the counterplay on the queenside.  41.bxc5   White should be better after  41.Nxc5  a3=∞  , but Black's position is not hopeless at all.  41...Rb1=∞  Not easy to make a progress here with White. }
39. Nd3 Rd4
{ This makes it very easy, but the game was lost anyway.  39...Rb8  40.Ne5+  Kd6  41.Nc4+  Ke6  42.Nxa5+-  . }
40. Ne5+ Kd6 41. Rxd4 cxd4+ 42. Kxd4 h5 43. Nc4+ Ke6 44. Nxa5 g4 45. fxg4 hxg4
