1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5
10. a3 Qe7 11. Bg5 O-O-O 12. e3 Bf5 13. Qb3 h6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Be2
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 15... Bxe3
{ An interesting try from Black, but objectively it is just losing. } 16. fxe3
Qxe3 17. Rf1
{ A very strong defensive move: the rook goes to f2, and the king can hide behind it on f1 if needed. }
17... Ne5
{ A@@EndBracket@@  17...Rhe8  doesn't pose any particular challenge for White:  18.Rf2+-  The king is walking away, and White is completely winning.   B@@EndBracket@@  17...Be4  A tricky try. Rf2 is not working so well against this move.  18.Qxf7!  It is good to take one more pawn, but the main point of this move is to go away from the pin. This way we can use the c3-knight, and also Qe6+ will be available in the future, so the queen can help in the defence too.  18...Rhe8  After this move the point of Qxf7 is very clear.  19.Nxe4  Rxe4  20.Rf2+-  With Kf1 and a winning position for White to follow.   18.Rf2?  Bxf3!  Black is getting counterplay here.  19.gxf3   @@StartBracket@@  19.Rxf3  Qg1+  20.Rf1  Qxg2=∞  Our king will be not safe for quite a while.  @@EndBracket@@  19...Rhg8→  The engine even prefers Black already, the attack is very dangerous.   @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/pp3Q2/2n2p1p/8/4b3/P1N1qN2/1P2B1PP/R3KR2 b Q - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Bxf3  19.Rxf3  Qg1+  20.Rf1  Qxg2  21.Rd1+-  The goal will be to eventually hide on the queenside with the king.   C@@EndBracket@@  17...Rhg8  18.Rf2  We wanted to play this move anyways.  18...Bd3  But here we have to be careful.  19.Qd1+-  With the idea of challenging the queen on e3 in the next move with Qd2 or Qc1. White's position is simply winning: Black can't really create threats.   19.Kf1??  It would be very logical to step out from the pin, but this is a very serious mistake.  19...Rxg2!!  After this nice sacrifice, Black is doing very well.  20.Kxg2  Bxe2→  Despite being a full rook down, and even the bishop on e2 is hanging, it is rather White who has to be very careful here.   @@StartFEN@@2kr4/pp3p2/2n2p1p/8/8/PQNbqN2/1P2BRrP/R4K2 w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Rxg2?  This capture is already losing for White:  20...Bxe2+  21.Rxe2  Qxf3+  22.Ke1  Qh1+  23.Kf2  Qxh2+  Black can even take one extra pawn before winning back the rook on a1.  24.Kf1  Qh1+  25.Kf2  Qxa1-+ }
18. Nxe5
{ This move means our king will have to go to f3 for a moment, but there is no problem with that. :@@EndBracket@@ }
18... Qd2+ 19. Kf2 Qd4+ 20. Kf3 fxe5
{ 20...Qxe5  21.Qb5!  The easiest. Black has only one move to keep the queens on the board and protect the bishop on f5 at the same time.  21...Qe6  22.Kf2+-  The king is going to safety, and White is just a piece up. }
21. Qc4+
{ Forcing the exchange of queens, and simplifying to a winning endgame. } 21...
