1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6
10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Nh4 Be7 12. Ne2
{ This was almost a novelty at the time of the game, only once this move was tried before. }
12... Nb6
{ Already a serious inaccuracy. It was figured out later that the correct way for Black is to play  12...f5!  which makes the bishop extremely ugly and passive, but at least doesn't allow the knight to f5. }
13. Ng3
{ Strategically an already very difficult position for Black, because White has the f5-square under control. }
13... Bb4+
{ Based on a miscalculation, but it is hard to suggest serious improvements for Black.  13...Nc8  is a standard regrouping idea. Black's knight stands well on d6 in these structures.  14.f4!  Very strong, exploiting the bad situation of the g6-bishop.  14...Be4   14...h6  15.f5!  Bh7  16.Nh5+-  The h7-bishop is not really strong here.  15.Nxe4  dxe4  Black's structure gets even worse, now he has a pawn on e4 to take care of as well.  16.g3  Nd6  17.Bh3±  Nf5 is coming soon, and White will sooner or later pick up one of the weak pawns. }
14. Kd1 Na4
{ This was Kramnik's idea, looking for active counterplay, but after Carlsen's next move we will see that the whole idea doesn't work at all. }
15. Ngf5 { All this has been coveredhere. } 15... Kd7
{ It is not good to take on b2:  15...Nxb2+?  16.Kc2  Nc4  17.Bxc4  dxc4  18.Rhb1±  Black can keep his extra pawn for one more move if he wants with  18...a5  , but after  19.a3  White will take on b7 with a huge advantage.   @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp3p1p/2p2pb1/3p1N2/1b1P3N/4P3/PnK2PPP/R4B1R b kq - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Na4??  17.Kb3!  The king is winning material!  17...Bc3  18.Rc1  b5  19.Rxc3  Nxc3  20.Kxc3+-  With a winning position for White. Black is left with his worst minor piece, and while he has the extra pawn, he just created a weakness there on c6. }
16. Rb1 Ke6 17. Bd3
{ Stabilising the knight on f5, Black has no counterplay at all. } 17... Rhc8
18. Ke2 Bf8 19. g4
{ Now the h4-knight doesn't have just to sit and wait for the f5-knight to be captured, but also can go to an active square, for example to f4. }
19... c5
{ It is completely understandable that Kramnik wants to do something, but this will not change much in the character of the game. If Black is doing nothing and just playing useful waiting moves, White still can execute a simple winning plan.  19...a5  20.Ng2  Bd6  Preventing Nf4, but White had another idea too.  21.h4!  h5  22.Nxd6  Simplifying the position and achieving a very clear advantage.  22...Kxd6  23.Bxg6  fxg6  24.gxh5  gxh5  25.Nf4  Rh8  26.Rhg1±  Kd3 and b3 will come next, and then the white rooks are entering on the g-file. }
20. Ng2 cxd4
{ 20...Bd6  was maybe a slightly better move, but Black's position is lost anyways.  21.h4!  h5  22.Ng7+!  Ke7  23.gxh5  Bxd3+  24.Kxd3+-  White has an extra pawn and still keeps the positional dominance. }
21. exd4 Bd6 22. h4 h5 23. Ng7+ Ke7 24. gxh5 Bxd3+ 25. Kxd3
{ Black has no compensation for the pawn, and Carlsen converted his advantage with perfect technique. }
25... Kd7 26. Ne3 Nb6 27. Ng4 Rh8 28. Rhe1 Be7 29. Nf5 Bd8 30. h6 Rc8 31. b3
