1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ Once Black decides not toaccept our Queen's Gambit,  2...e6  and  2...c6  are the most principled options. The text move allows the development of the dark-squared bishop but locks the c8-bishop inside the pawn chain. }
3. Nc3
{ White's main move. Our g1-knight may go to f3 or e2, depending on Black's setup. As we will see, againstthe Slav 2...c6 we prefer to develop that knight immediately while the b1-knight can stand better on d2. }
3... Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 O-O 8. Rc1 c6 9. Ng3 Bg6 10.
h4 h6 11. h5 Bh7 12. Bd3
{ With this exchange White is preparing the f5-square for his knight. This has all been coveredhere. }
12... Bd6 13. Bxh7+ Nxh7
{ It was better to recapture with the king  13...Kxh7!  because at least now the queen can't come to g4 as it did in the game.  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  15.Nf5  Qe6  16.Qd3  Kg8  17.f3↑  White has a very nice initiative on the kingside with moves like g4-Kf2, and then Ne2-f4 to follow. }
14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nf5 Qf6 16. Qg4
{ Instead of the pawn, the queen is arriving at g4, which is a serious improvement for White, and Black also can't be too proud of his h7-knight. }
16... Ng5
{ Black can't finish the development because of tactical reasons:  16...Nd7?  17.Nxg7!  The knight on d7 is not protected.  17...Qxg7  18.Qxd7  Rad8  19.Qf5±  A healthy extra pawn for White.  19...Qxg2??  would lead to a quick game.  20.Ke2+-  Black is losing a lot of material on the g-file. }
17. f4 Ne6
{ 17...Ne4  creates a weak pawn on e4.  18.Nxe4  dxe4  19.Rc5!  A very unusual and straightforward rook manoeuvre: the rook will be untouchable on e5 because once the d-pawn recaptures the queen can't hold on to the g7-square.  19...Na6  20.Re5  Nb4   Black can protect the e-pawn, but then he will have problems on g7:  21.Rh3+-  Rg3 is coming, and Black can't defend his position.  21.Rxe4  Rfe8  22.Re5±  The rook will just stay there on e5, while the other rook is going to decide the game by joining via h3-g3. }
18. Rd1
{ Black is overprotecting on d4, so he is getting ready to push e4 in the next move. }
18... Re8
{ Black could prepare to defend the g7-square with the rook by means of  18...Kh8  19.e4!  dxe4  20.Nxe4  Qd8  21.Nc5  Trying to decoy the defender of the g7-square.  21...Rg8  22.O-O↑  Black has managed to avoid immediate capitulation, but his position is very passive, and White's initiative will continue.   18...Nd7!  looks very scary for Black, but this was the best way to prepare for e4.  19.e4   Since the arising complications don't give White a big advantage,  19.O-O!?  is a very serious alternative, with the idea of slowly progressing with the attack on the kingside.  19...Kh8  20.Qh3→  Playing g4 next, and then Rd2-Rg2, White has a pretty dangerous attack.  19...dxe4  Black can't allow e5, because it would be total domination for White, but this move seems to be blundering a pawn...  20.Nxe4  Qd8  21.d5  The best try from White, but Black is more or less okay even here.  21...cxd5  22.Rxd5  Rxd7 followed by a Nf6 fork is a huge threat now.  22...Kh8!  A calm defensive move.  23.O-O  Nf6  24.Rxd8  Nxg4  25.Rd7  b6⩲  White is very slightly better in this endgame, but Black has all the chances to hold this position.   Black will have enough counterplay after  21.Nxh6+  Kh8   21...Kh7??  is just losing:  22.Qf5+  Kxh6  23.g4+-  Black's king is getting checkmated.  22.Nf5  Nf6  The queen will return to f6, the attack is over, and Black has counterplay against the d4-pawn.  23.Nxf6  Qxf6  24.O-O  Rad8=  .   Taking one more pawn is even losing: @@StartFEN@@r2q1r1k/pp1n1pp1/2p1n2N/7P/3PNPQ1/8/PP4P1/3RK2R w K - 1 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Nxf7+??  Rxf7  23.Qxe6  Qe8-+  The knight on e4 is lost because of the pin. }
19. O-O { White is not forced to play e4 right away! } 19... Nc7
{ Seemingly this move stops e4, but it is not the case at all. Now  19...Nd7?  is not working well at all because the rook has left the protection of the f7-square, so the king will have to guard that pawn.  20.e4  dxe4  21.Nxe4  Qd8  22.Nxh6+  The king can't go to the h-file now.  22...Kf8  23.f5  Nxd4  24.f6+-  Black is getting checkmated very soon. }
20. Rf3
{ 20.e4!?  was actually the easiest way for White to win.  20...dxe4  21.Rde1  Ne4 is coming now, Black has only one move to stop it.  21...e3  22.Rf3  Nd7  23.Rexe3  Again Ne4 is coming.  23...Ne6  24.Ne4  Qd8  25.Nxh6++-  . }
20... Kh7 21. Rg3 g6
{ 21...Rg8  Passive, but it was the only fighting chance for Black.  22.e4!  Nd7  23.e5  Qe6  24.Qh3→  Black's position is still extremely difficult, but at least now he is not losing on the spot. }
22. hxg6+ fxg6 23. Nh4 Rg8 24. f5 { White is breaking through. } 24... g5 25.
