{ Once all the pieces are optimally placed, Eljanov fixes the pawn structure. }
28... Nc7 29. e4
{ This move is possible thanks to some tactics, but even if it weren't, White could increase the pressure with Nde2-Nf4. }
29... Rd7
{ 29...dxe4?  is very bad because Black will lose all his pawns on the kingside.  30.Nxc6+!  bxc6  31.Rxd8  Rxd8  32.Rxd8  Kxd8  33.Bxf7+-  The endgame is easily winning for White.   29...a6  A somewhat tricky move.  30.Kg3  Now White is threatening to take on d5 because Rc2 will not come with a check.  30...Ne6  31.Nxc6+  bxc6  32.exd5  cxd5  33.Bxd5±  with a clean extra pawn for White.   Going for the d5-pawn immediately would only lead to a drawish endgame: @@StartFEN@@2r5/ppnrkp2/2b2np1/3p3p/3NP2P/P1N2P2/BP1R1KP1/3R4 w - - 1 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Nxc6+?  bxc6  31.exd5  cxd5  32.Nxd5+  Ncxd5  33.Bxd5  Nxd5  34.Rxd5  Rxd5  35.Rxd5  Rc2+=  . }
30. e5
{ White obtains a kingside majority while keeping all the black pieces passive. }
30... Nh7 31. b4
{ Not a bad move, but I believe there was something easier.  31.f4+-  Keeping the queenside completely safe and protected and winning the game on the kingside, where Black has almost no pieces at all. }
