1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Rd1 Nc6 12. Be2 Qa5 13. Rc1
{ Black is preparing for the endgame with ...Qa5, so now we obviously don't castle, but again, by using the flexibility of Rd1, we can keep our king in the centre. }
13... Rd8 { Exchanging the queens followed by ...Nxd4 is the threat now. } 14.
Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Kd2
{ The e3-square is perfect for the king, it can defend both central pawns from there. }
15... Bd7 16. Ke3 Rac8 17. h4
{ Gaining space on the kingside. This has all been coveredhere. } 17... Kf8 18.
g4 { The threat is g5 to fix a weakness on h7. } 18... h6
{ Good defensive move from Black. Now, in case of  19.g5  , he can just trade the problematic h-pawn. }
19. Ne5 Nc6
{ 19...Be8  20.f4  could easily transpose to the game, but in any case, White's play is the same: push the kingside pawns. }
20. f4 Be8
{ 20...Nxe5!  looks very dangerous because the d-pawn can easily become a protected passer on d6, but since Black is holding the bishop endgame, this move was the best in the position.  21.fxe5  Rxc1  22.Rxc1  Rc8  and now the best try to play for a win is  23.Rb1  b6!  24.Rb3  stopping ...Rc3 and preparing Ra3.   If  24.Kd2  f6!  Black is undermining our strong centre.  25.exf6  gxf6=  and Black has no problems.   24.d5  leads to a double-edged play, but it is rather White who has to be careful:  24...Rc3+  25.Kd4  Rc2  26.Bc4  exd5  27.exd5  Rg2⇆  24...Rc2  25.Ra3⩲  White has a slight advantage here, but Black is very solid.   @@StartFEN@@2r2k2/pp1b1pp1/4p2p/4P3/3PP1PP/4K3/P3B3/2R5 w - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Rxc8+  looks scary for Black, but White can't break through in this endgame.  23...Bxc8  24.g5!  We need the pawns on the dark squares.   24.d5?!  g5=  Here there is not much to hope for, Black is easily stopping the d-pawn.  24...b6  25.d5  hxg5  26.hxg5  Ke7  27.Kd4  g6  28.d6+  Kd8=  White did everything correctly, creating a strong passed pawn on d6 and fixing the black pawns on light squares, but there is simply no way to increase the advantage here: the king can't enter Black's position. }
21. g5 Nb4
{ 21...Nxe5?  is now just a mistake, since it is essential for Black to trade rooks after this exchange.  22.fxe5±   21...Ne7  intends to trade rooks on the c-file but Black is not in time anymore with this.  22.Bg4!  Rxc1  23.Rxc1  f6  24.Nd3⩲  White has managed to create targets in Black's camp.   Unfortunately for Black, @@StartFEN@@3rbk2/pp2npp1/4p2p/4N1P1/3PPPBP/4K3/P7/2R5 b - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Rc8?  has a concrete refutation:  24.Rxc8  Nxc8  25.d5!  Ke7  26.g6+-  Black is losing his e6-pawn, and then with the connected passers in the centre, White will have a winning advantage. }
22. Bc4
{ Nxa2 and also Nc2+ was a threat, so playing this move was a must for White. }
22... Ba4
{ Renewing the threat of ...Nc2+, but underestimating White's strong reply.   22...f6  kicks back the knight, but creates many weaknesses.  23.gxf6  gxf6  24.Ng4±  Black can't really protect all his pawns.   22...Ke7  was probably the best move, guarding the e6-pawn, so the g6-idea is not so dangerous from White now.  23.a3  Nc6  24.d5!  White still keeps a nice advantage with the strong d-pawn.  24...exd5  25.exd5  Na5  26.Ba2⩲  Without rooks Black would be completely fine, but now it is possible to exchange one pair, and the other one will remain passive for Black. }
23. g6 { Breaking Black's structure on the kingside. } 23... fxg6
{ 23...Nc2+?  simply didn't work:  24.Rxc2  Bxc2  25.gxf7+-  Bxe6 or Rg1 are coming next. Black can't do anything against White's central dominance. }
24. Rhg1 b5
{ 24...Nc2+  is a much better try now than it could have been in the previous move because White will not have a pawn on f7.  25.Rxc2  Bxc2  26.Nxg6+  Kf7  27.Ne5+  Kf8  28.Bxe6  White is obviously better here, but the position is not hopeless for Black.  28...Rc3+  29.Kd2  Rc7  30.Bd5⩲  . }
25. Bxe6 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 Nc2+ 27. Rxc2 Bxc2 28. d5
{ White's king will be able to join as well, so the position looks lost for Black. }
28... Bb1 29. a3 a5 30. Nc6 Re8 31. e5
{ Giving up too early the possibility of playing f5.   Better was  31.Kd4!  . }
31... Ba2
{ The easiest way for Black to reach a drawish endgame was  31...Rxe6!  32.dxe6  b4  33.axb4  axb4  The problem is that White can't save the e6-pawn.  34.Kd4  b3  35.Kc3  Be4  36.Nd4  Bd5  37.Nxb3  Bxe6  38.Nd4  Ba2=  White has a symbolic advantage, but it is not enough to win the game, the material is too limited. }
32. Kd4 Ra8
{ The losing move.  32...Rxe6  was a little bit more complicated than a move before, but still good enough to reach the draw.  33.dxe6  b4!  It is essential for Black to trade off everything on the queenside.   After  33...Bxe6?  34.Nxa5+-  Black is losing because of the weakness of the b5-pawn.  34.e7+  White can keep the e-pawn, but still there will be no way to make further progress.  34...Ke8  35.axb4  axb4  36.Nxb4  Bf7  37.Nc6  Kd7  38.Kc5  Be8=  Black will just wait with Bf7-Be8 and White can't do anything. }
33. Bd7 { The passed pawns are winning the game for White. } 33... b4 34. axb4
a4 35. e6 a3 36. e7+ Kf7 37. d6
{ Black is helpless against Nd8+ and then e8Q. } *

