1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. e4 dxe4 8. Nxe4
Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 O-O 12. O-O-O c5 13. Nf3
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 13... Qa5 14. Bd3 Nf6
{ 14...g6?  is so weakening that we don't even have to take time to protect on a2, but can start the attack right away.  15.h4→  . }
15. Qh4 Qc7
{ Black is preventing g4 thanks to the Qf4+ idea.   15...Qxa2?  It is just a pawn, the white king is not in danger.  16.Ne5!  Ng4 or g4-g5 are huge threats.  16...Qa1+  17.Kc2  Qa5  18.g4  Rd8  19.g5  Rxd4  20.f4+-  White is simply winning here.   15...cxd4?  16.g4!  Very simple and very strong: Black can't do much about the g5 threat.  16...h6  17.Rhg1+-  Black is helpless against White's attack.   15...b5!?  One of the top choices of the machine, but White keeps the advantage even after this move.  16.g4  bxc4  17.g5!  This is the point! We don't have to recapture on c4 or move the bishop.  17...Nh5!   17...cxd3?  18.gxf6→  Black has very good chances of getting checkmated very quickly.  18.Bxh7+  Like this, we can move the bishop!  18...Kxh7  19.Qxh5+  Kg8  20.Qh4±  Preparing to play g6. It was not good to push immediately because Black could take with a tempo, so we would be not able to follow it up with Ng5. }
16. Rhe1
{ White is bringing a new piece into the game, with the idea of playing Ne5 @@StartBracket@@covering the f4-square@@EndBracket@@ and then pushing g4-g5. }
16... cxd4 17. Ne5 b5
{ Black immediately has to look for counterplay because g4-g5 is very quick. }
18. c5
{ Excellent! White will be down 2 pawns but keeps the queenside and the centre closed and can continue his kingside attack without problems. }
18... Qxc5+ 19. Kb1 h6
{ 19...Bb7??  was losing on the spot:  20.Nd7+-  Decoying the knight to deliver mate on h7.   19...Re8  makes Ng4 less effective...  20.g4!  but does nothing against this move. White's attack is crushing. }
20. g4 Nd7 21. f4 { White is going forward with every move! } 21... Nxe5 22.
Rxe5 Qc7 23. g5 f6
{ 23...f5  was maybe a better defensive try, but Black's position is close to lost anyways.  24.gxh6  g6  25.Qg5  Kh7  26.h4→  The attack is continuing and White can take back the material anytime he wants. }
24. gxh6 { Very strong play by White! } 24... fxe5 25. Rg1
{ All white pieces are fantastic, while the rook on a8 and the bishop on c8 can't take part in the defence. }
25... Rxf4
{ 25...Rf7  26.hxg7  26...Rxg7  27.Qh7+  Winning all the material.  27...Kf8  28.Qh8++-   25...g6  26.Rxg6+  Kh8  27.Rg7  Rf7  allows a forced checkmate:  28.Rxf7  Qxf7  29.Qd8+  Qg8  30.Qf6++-  . }
26. Qh5 e4
{ 26...Bb7  27.hxg7  Rf1+  Even giving back the rook Black can't prolong the game too long.  28.Rxf1  Qxg7  29.Qd1+-  Rg1 is coming with decisive power. }
27. hxg7 { White is taking back all the material and some more. } 27... Bb7 28.
Qh8+ Kf7 29. Qxa8 Bxa8 30. g8=Q+ Ke7 31. Rg7+ Kd6 32. Rxc7 Kxc7 33. Qxe6 *

