1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. Rc1 Be6 7. e3 dxc4 8. Ng5
Bd5 9. e4 h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Bb3 Nc6 14. d5 Nd4
15. O-O Qd7 16. h4 Rfe8 17. a3 Nxb3 18. Qxb3 e6
{ 18...Rad8!?  is the other continuation for Black and it also gives him a decent position. This has all been coveredhere. }
19. dxe6 Qxe6
{ 19...Rxe6  is somewhat unnatural and gives White some hope to get an advantage.  20.Rfd1  Rd6  21.a4!  A typical idea against the knight on b6.  21...a5  22.Nb5⩲  White has some initiative here.   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pppq1pb1/1n1r2p1/6B1/P6P/1QN5/1P3PP1/2RR2K1 b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Bxc3  The engine offers this move very often for Black, but as long as White can keep the queens on the board, this looks too risky for me.  22.Rxd6  Qxd6  23.Qxc3  Nxa4  24.Qf3=∞  This position looks much easier to play with White because of the weakness of the black king. }
20. Qxe6 Rxe6
{ 20...fxe6?  looks ugly, and indeed a very bad move, creating weaknesses for no reason.  21.Rc2±  . }
21. Nb5 Bxb2
{ 21...Nd5!?  leads to a most probably drawish endgame, but if your opponent is not someone from the absolute top level, I don't see many players willingly entering such positions.  22.Rxc7!  a6  23.Rc5  axb5  24.Rxd5  Bxb2  25.Rxb5  Bxa3  26.Rxb7⩲  There is nothing left on the queenside. The drawish tendencies of this position are very high, but White can try to win this position for 100 moves. }
22. Nxc7 Bxc1
{ 22...Rc8  could lead to the same thing as the text, it just gives White the option to keep the rooks on the board.  23.Nxe6  Bxc1  24.Bxc1!?  I believe we should take this chance, since normally the R+B team is operating better than R+N.  24...fxe6  25.Be3⩲  . }
23. Rxc1 Rc8 24. Nxe6 Rxc1+ 25. Bxc1 fxe6 26. Kf1
{ The pawns are on the 2 sides of the board and we have the bishop, so for sure we have some advantage. However, it has to be said that with perfect play, because of the limited material, such positions should end with a draw, but as we can see even close to 2700 level players can lose such endgames. Therefore, to draw this with Black is definitely not a walk in the park. }
26... Nd5 27. Ke2 b5 28. Bd2
{ The usual technique: a 2-square distance from the knight! } 28... Ne7 29. Kd3
Nc6 30. Bc3 { Again! } 30... Kf7 31. g4 a5 32. Bb2
{ Preventing Black's b4 idea, if he can exchange our a-pawn, then basically the winning chances are gone. }
32... Kg8 { 32...b4??  33.a4+-  is easily winning for White now. } 33. Ke4 Kf8
34. Kf4 Kf7 35. f3 Ne7 36. Ke4 Nc6 37. Ba1 Kg8 38. Bb2 Kf7 39. f4 Kg8 40. f5
{ This is the only winning idea for White: creating a passed pawn on the h-file and trying to win the game on the queenside while Black is bothering with the h-pawn. }
40... exf5+
{ It would be very bad to allow White to have connected passed pawns:  40...Kf7?  41.fxg6+  Kxg6  42.Bc1  b4  43.h5+  Kh7  44.g5+-  The pawns are going to queen with the help of the bishop. }
41. gxf5 Kf7 42. fxg6+ Kxg6 43. Kd5
{ The king is entering the position, but of course it shouldn't be enough, since White has only one winning asset, the a3-pawn. }
43... Ne7+ 44. Kc5 Nf5
{ 44...b4  was also good enough for a draw, but the game continuation is simpler.  45.a4  Nf5  Black is taking the pawn with the knight, so his king will remain closer to the queenside.  46.Kb5  Nxh4  47.Kxa5  Kf7  48.Kb6  Nf5  49.a5  Nd6  50.a6  Ke6  51.Kc6  Nc8  52.Kc7  Na7  53.Bd4  b3=  The b-pawn secures the draw. }
45. Kxb5 Nxh4 46. a4 Kf7 47. Kxa5 Nf5
{ So far Black did everything correctly, but this is already the losing mistake!  47...Ke6  48.Kb6  Kd7  Now White has two different tries, but in both cases Black is in time to make the draw.  49.Kb7  Nf5  50.a5  Nd6+  51.Kb8  Kc6  52.a6  The only try.  52...Nc8!  A very spectacular way to make the draw.  53.Bd4   53.Kxc8  Kb6=  53...Kb5  54.Kb7  Nd6+  55.Ka7  Nc8+=  .   @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/1K6/8/P6n/8/1B6/8 w - - 3 49@@EndFEN@@  49.a5  Kc8  50.Be5  We can't allow the king to the corner, because then Black doesn't even need the knight to achieve the draw.  50...Ng6  51.Bd6  Ne7!  Using the fact that it's the the wrong corner for White.  52.Bxe7  Kb8=  Theoretical draw. }
48. Kb6 Nd6 49. Be5 { Very nice play from White! } 49... Nc4+ 50. Kb5 Na3+
{ Black is not in time to catch the pawn after capturing the bishop:  50...Nxe5  51.a5  Ng6  52.a6  Ne7  53.a7  Nd5  The last trick.  54.Kc6   54.a8=Q??  Nc7+=  54...Ne7+  55.Kb7+-  . }
51. Kc5 Ke7 52. a5 Kd7 53. a6 Kc8 54. Bd6
{ Zugzwang! Either the knight or the king has to go to a worse square than the current one. }
54... Nc2 55. Kb6 Ne3 56. a7 Nd5+ 57. Ka6
{ And Black resigned. Just out of interest I checked what happens if White blunders ...Nc7. Fortunately, the position is still winning.  57.Kc6  Nc7  58.Kb6  Na8+  59.Ka6  Kd7  60.Bb4  The bishop is going to a5, and Black will be in zugzwang again.  60...Kc7  61.Ba5+  Kc6  If it were Black's turn here, then he would be lost, so White just has to lose a tempo with the bishop and he is winning the game.  62.Bd8  Kd7  63.Bb6!  Kc6  64.Ba5+-  Kb7 next is winning. }
*

