1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ 3. Nd2 c5 4. a3 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 cxd4 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Nxd4 O-O
8. f3 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. e4 Ne7 11. b4 { All this has been coveredhere. }
11... a5 12. b5
{ White is not allowing ...axb4 so Black can't make his position easier with exchanges over there. }
12... a4
{ Pretty logical. If Black allows White to play a4, then ...a5 was quite useless.   12...Nd7  13.a4±  With Ba3 coming next, White is doing very well with the pair of bishops. }
13. Bb2 e5 14. Nc2 Nd7
{ Again the most logical move from Black.  14...Qxd2+  Exchanging queens or heavy pieces when the opponent has the pair of bishops is not advisable, as it seriously limits the chances for counterplay.  15.Kxd2  Ng6  16.Ne3  Be6  17.Rc1  Nd7  18.Kc3±  The king will have a perfect square on b4, hiding from the checks, and also attacking the a4-pawn. }
15. Qb4
{ A good move. The engine likes some other moves better, such as  15.Rd1!?  or  15.O-O-O!?  , but I don't see anything wrong with Qb4. }
15... Ng6 16. O-O-O Qc7
{ Black could also try the more active-looking  16...Qb6  , but even when the queen reaches f2, it does not do much harm to White's position.  17.Rd6!  Qf2  18.Kb1  Nf6  19.Qd2  Offering the trade, which Black can't really avoid.  19...Qxd2   19...Qc5  20.Bc3+-  With Bb4 to follow, Black's position is critical and also very passive.  20.Rxd2±  With a clear advantage for White because of the pair of bishops and the weak e5-pawn. }
17. Kb1 Nc5
{ Black wants to finish the development, but this move fails tactically, which went unnoticed during the game. }
18. Ne3
{ 18.b6!  After this, White's advantage is already decisive.  18...Qc6  19.h4!  Black has no good ways to protect the e5-pawn.  19...h5   19...f6??  is losing a lot of material.  20.Bb5  Qxb6  21.Bc4++-  20.g4!  hxg4  21.h5  Nf4  22.h6+-  White's attack on the h-file combined with the weakness of the e5-pawn is deciding the game here. }
18... Be6 19. b6 Qc6 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. Bc4
{ With the idea of playing Nd5 next. } 21... Qe8 22. Bxe6
{ It is somewhat strange to exchange the bishops now.  22.Bb5!  Qf8  23.Rhd1  Bb3  24.Rd2+-  Black can hardly move and Nf5 is coming next. }
22... Nxe6 23. Nd5 Qd7 24. g3
{ Useful move for restricting the knights, and also keeping the f4 idea in the air. }
24... f6 25. h4 h5 26. Rhd1 Rxc1+ 27. Rxc1 Kf7
{ The king is too open here.  27...Kh7  28.Rc4⩲  Black is certainly worse, but very much still in the game. }
28. Qc4
{ 28.f4!  was very strong.  28...f5  The only way to stop White's f5, but now Black's position loses all its stability.  29.Rd1+-  Black is collapsing. }
28... Ra5 29. Qa2 Rc5 30. Rxc5 Nxc5 31. Qc4 Ne6 32. f4 exf4 33. gxf4 Nxh4
{ The losing mistake. Black still would have some chances to save the game after  33...Ne7  34.f5  White is winning a piece, but there will be some technical difficulties.  34...Nxd5  35.fxe6+  Kxe6  36.exd5+  Qxd5  37.Qxa4  g5±  Probably this is winning for White, but certainly not easy. }
34. f5 Nf3 35. Ka2 Nfg5 36. Qe2 Nxe4 37. Qxe4 Ng5 38. Qc4 Kf8 39. Bc3 Qxf5 40.
Qc5+ Kf7 41. Qc7+ *

