1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 c5 5. dxc5 Nc6 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8.
Nxd2 Bxc5 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rac1 Rc8 13. Qc2 Be7 14. Rfd1
Qc7 15. Nde4 a6
{ Black prevents Nb5, but allows Nd5!   15...Rfd8?!  16.Nd6!  A nice move, putting Black under serious pressure.  16...Ra8   If  16...Rb8??  17.Ncb5+-  The queen is trapped!   After  16...Bxd6?  it will be tough to challenge the knight on d6.  17.Nb5  Qb8  18.Nxd6  Rc7  19.Bxc6!?  Intending to stabilise our knight on d6.  19...Bxc6  20.f3±  Black is very passive, while White has clear ways to improve the position.  17.a3  Preparing b4.  17...a6  The d6-knight is hanging now because Black covered the b5-square.  18.Nxb7  Qxb7  19.b4  b5  20.c5⩲  White has a much stronger bishop and also the clear plan of putting the knight on d6.   The engine likes  15...Nb4  , but I believe Black will remain under pressure here as well.  16.Qb3  Bxe4  17.Bxe4  Rfd8   The pawn is poisoned:  17...Qxc4??  18.Nd5+-  and the intermediate check Nxe7 will win material for White.  18.Qa4↑  Nb5 is coming next, and also Black's knight is quite misplaced on b4. }
16. Nd5
{ A nice tactical idea, better known when the pawn is already on d6. In that case, of course, it is even more effective, but even now it is pretty strong. }
16... exd5 17. cxd5 Qe5
{ 17...Qb8  was also possible, and then the queen can protect the b6-pawn so Black can recapture on c6 with the pawn and keep a healthy structure.  18.dxc6  dxc6  19.Qb3  Ba8  The point behind 17...Qb8.  20.Rd7  Rc7  21.Rcd1  c5!  Activating the a8-bishop.  22.Qe3⩲  With ideas like Rxe7 and then Nf6+, White keeps the initiative. }
18. dxc6 Bxc6
{ 18...dxc6?!  is now a serious inaccuracy.  19.Rd7  Ba8   19...Rc7??  loses on the spot to  20.f4+-  .  20.Qb3!  With the double threat of taking on b6 and playing f4.  20...b5??  21.f4+-  Black is losing a piece. }
19. Nc3
{ White has a small but clear advantage now because of the weak d7-pawn and the d5-square. This has all been coveredhere. }
19... g6 20. Qd3 b5 21. b3
{ It was better to protect the pawn with the rook and already prepare for doubling on the c-file.  21.Rc2!  Kg7  22.Nd5  Bxd5  23.Bxd5  Rxc2  24.Qxc2  White has the c-file under control, and retains the better chances.  24...Bf6  25.b3⩲  . }
21... Ba3 22. Rc2 Rfe8 23. e3 Rc7
{ 23...Bxg2  is liked by the engine but it is hard to believe it can be good. Instead of opposite-coloured bishops, Black is going for a good knight vs not-so-good bishop position.  24.Kxg2  Re6  25.Nd5  Rxc2  26.Qxc2  Rd6  27.Nf4  Rxd1  28.Qxd1⩲  Black still has to fight to reach equality. }
24. Nd5 Bxd5 25. Bxd5
{ With this move White is allowing Black to transfer the rook to c7, where it is much better than on e8, and thus losing all his advantage.   After  25.Rxc7!  Qxc7  26.Bxd5  White's bishop is clearly dominating the position. Black has a couple of weak pawns, and also the weaker king, so Kg2-h4-h5 can be also an idea for White.  26...Rc8  Black is not in time with the ...Qc2 idea.  27.Qe4±  Qc2??  28.Bxf7+!  White is winning on the spot.  28...Kxf7  29.Rxd7+  Kf8  30.Rd8+!  Kg7  31.Qd4+  Kf7  32.Qd7++-  White is winning the rook and the game. }
25... Rec8 26. Rxc7 Rxc7
{ The rook is excellent on c7, protecting the weak pawn on d7, and also controlling the c-file. }
27. Qd2 Kg7 28. Qa5 Qd6
{ Very precise, Black is simplifying to a drawish endgame. } 29. Bf3 Rc1 30.
Rxc1 Bxc1 31. Qc3+
{ White could take an extra pawn, but because of the opposite-coloured bishops, he has no realistic chances to win this position.  31.Bb7  Bd2!  32.Qxa6  Qxa6  33.Bxa6  b4=  with a comfortable draw for Black. }
31... Qf6 32. Qxc1 Qxf3 { The queen endgame is just completely equal. } 33.
