1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Nf6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 O-O 8.
Bd3 c5 9. Ne2 b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. f3 Re8 12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Bb2 h5
15. Rae1 h4 16. Nf5 { This has all been coveredhere. } 16... Nh5
{ Not a nice square for the knight. } 17. e4
{ Once White can play this move without any problems in this variation, normally he is much better. This game is no exception. }
17... h3
{ With this move Black is preparing ...Ne7, since the h4-pawn will not be hanging.   A@@EndBracket@@ Transferring the knight to the e6-square looks reasonable, but it is very slow and does nothing about White's massive central control:  17...Nf4  18.Qd2  Ne6  19.e5!  The central advantage is solidified and the knight has a wonderful outpost on d6.  19...Qg5  Black has to exchange queens to avoid bigger problems.  20.Qxg5  Nxg5  21.f4  Ne6   21...Ne4  Very nice square for the knight: it can't be attacked by a pawn, and it is also covering the d6-square.  22.c4!  But it can be easily undermined! Black's position is falling apart.  22...Nd2  23.cxd5  Nxf1  24.dxc6  Nd2  25.d5+-  White's pawns are somewhat strong. :@@EndBracket@@  22.Nd6  Re7  23.f5  The pawn storm is continuing.  23...Ng5  24.Bc1  The bishop is coming to a more active diagonal.  24...Nh7  25.Rd1±  White has a huge advantage with such an impressive centre.   B@@EndBracket@@  17...cxd4  18.cxd4  dxe4?  19.fxe4+-  Taking twice in the centre didn't do Black any good: all White's pieces are very good and Black is simply losing here.   C@@EndBracket@@  17...Qf6  Black wants to play Ne7 now and exchange the strong knight on f5.  18.Bc1  The bishop was doing nothing on b2 anymore, so it is time to return to a more useful diagonal.  18...Ne7  19.Nxe7+  Black has managed to exchange our strong knight, but he still has serious issues with the h4-pawn and with his knight, and also f4-f5 is coming very soon.  19...Qxe7  It is better to take like this because e5 is not coming with a tempo.  20.e5  g6  Black is organising a blockade on the f5-square.  21.f4  Ng7  22.f5!  To completely open Black's king is worth an exchange.  22...Nxf5  23.Rxf5  gxf5  24.Rf1→  Black will have a tough time surviving this attack.   @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/p3Npp1/1p3q2/2pp3n/3PP2p/P1PQ1P2/6PP/2B1RRK1 b - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Rxe7?  20.e5!  Qe6  21.Bg5  Rc7  22.f4!  Not giving Black time to organise any defensive setup.   22.Bxh4?  would be a mistake, as Black can greatly improve his piece coordination.  22...cxd4  23.cxd4  Nf4  24.Qe3  Qh6=∞  Rac8 and Ne6 coming, and Black has a quite serious activity for the missing pawn.  22...g6  23.f5  gxf5  24.Rxf5+-  Black's king is extremely weak. }
18. g3
{ Not allowing the knight back via f4, and we can take on h3 later, that is rather a weak than a dangerous pawn now. }
18... Ne7 19. e5 Qd7
{ Taking this knight was a better option but it is still just an extra pawn for White.  19...Nxf5  20.Qxf5  g6  21.Qxh3±  Bc1 and g4 are coming, so we can attack with having an extra pawn. }
20. Nd6 { Black is losing the game on the f7-square. } 20... Rf8 21. Nxf7 c4
{ 21...Rxf7  22.e6+-  is a full extra exchange for White. } 22. Qc2 Rxf7 23. e6
Qd6 24. exf7+ Kxf7 25. Re5 *

