1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 g6 6. h4 Bg7 7. Be2 h5 8. Bg5 a6 9.
Qd2 Nbd7 10. f3 Nf8 11. Nh3 N8h7 12. Be3 { All this has been coveredhere. }
12... Bd7 13. Nf2 Qe7 14. g4
{ Even though White is starting to push the pawns on the kingside, it is still much better for Black to castle short because he has no pieces on the queenside. }
14... O-O
{ 14...O-O-O??  15.g5!  Closing the kingside with the idea of quickly winning the game on the queenside.  15...Ne8  16.b4!  We don't even need any preparation, this break is coming with huge power.  16...b6   16...cxb4  17.Ncd1+-  Qxb4-Rab1-c5 and Black can't really bring more defensive power to help the king.  17.Qb2  Kc7  18.Rb1  With such simple moves we can checkmate Black's king.  18...Rb8  19.Nd3  19...f6  20.bxc5  dxc5  21.Nxc5+- }
15. O-O-O
{ It is always a question of whether to play  15.a4!?  in such positions or not. Personally, I would go for it, and then Kd1-Kc2. But since the main point of Black's position is that it is hard to break, provoking b5 also makes a lot of sense, as White can have targets later on the queenside as well. }
15... b5 16. Rdg1 bxc4 17. Bg5
{ With the idea of taking on h5 and the knight can't recapture. } 17... Qe8
{ 17...Rfb8  18.gxh5  Nxg5  19.hxg6!   19.hxg5??  It would be a huge mistake to allow Black to close the kingside.  19...Nxh5∞  19...fxg6  20.hxg5  Nh5  21.Nfd1±  The knight will recapture on c4, and another idea is to exchange our bad bishop by means of Bf1-h3. }
18. Nfd1 hxg4
{ 18...Rb8  Black can't hope for much counterplay on the b-file.  19.Ne3  Rb7  20.Nxc4  Qb8  21.Qc2±  Black is stuck here. White can improve his position by playing Kb1-a1 and also, since the queen is protecting the e4-pawn, the c3-knight is ready to go to e3 and we don't have to be worried about ...hxg4 anymore. }
19. Bxf6 { 19.fxg4  was also good, and similar to the game. } 19... Bxf6
{ 19...Nxf6  20.fxg4→  Ne3 and h5 are coming. White has a dangerous initiative. }
20. fxg4 Bg7 21. g5
{ 21.Ne3!  was probably better, keeping our options, and then we can still decide whether to push g5 or h5. }
21... f6 22. h5
{ Very nice! Opening the kingside and weakening the light squares. } 22... fxg5
{ At least White can't force Black's queen to the h-file after this recapture.  22...Nxg5  23.hxg6  Qxg6  24.Bh5  Qh6  25.Ne3+-  Basically White can win the queen anytime he wants. }
23. hxg6 Qxg6 24. Bh5
{ Precise! Ne3 would allow Rf4 and Black finally has some active pieces.  24.Ne3?  Rf4⇆ }
24... Qf6 25. Ne3 Rab8 26. Rg2
{ Controlling the second rank, and also preparing to double on the g- or h-file. }
26... Rb7 27. Rgh2 g4 28. Bxg4 Bxg4 29. Nxg4 Qg5
{ 29...Qf4  was better for Black according to the computer, but there is no real big difference compared to the game.  30.Qxf4  Rxf4  31.Rg2±  The g7-bishop is extremely bad and Black has very few drawing chances here. }
30. Ne3 Rf3 31. Nxc4 Bf6 32. Kc2 Qxd2+ 33. Rxd2
{ With 2 pawn weaknesses and an extremely bad minor piece, this position is technically lost for Black. White nicely converted his advantage. }
33... Be7 34. Rg2+ Kh8 35. Nd1 Rf4 36. Kd3 Bf8 37. Nde3 Rd7 38. Nf5 Rf3+ 39.
Ke2 Rf4 40. Ke3 Rf7 41. Ncxd6 Bxd6 42. Nxd6 Rg7 43. Rxg7 Kxg7 44. Nf5+ Kg8 45.
Ne7+ Kg7 46. Rg1+ Kf6 47. Ng8+ Kf7 48. Nh6+ Ke8 49. Rg8+ Nf8 50. Ng4 *

