1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qd2 e5 8. d5
Nc5 9. f3 a5 10. g4
{ I recommend  10.h4!?  in the chapter, but the main point to show in this game is what happens if White manages to close the kingside. }
10... h6 11. Be3 Ne8
{ A very serious mistake.  11...h5!  Black shouldn't allow White to close the kingside as happened in the game. Also possible is  11...c6!?  . }
12. h4 Kh7 13. h5 g5 14. Nh3
{ Black is strategically losing here. He will have absolutely no counterplay on the kingside, while White already has a clear advantage on the queenside because of the space advantage provided by the d5-pawn. }
14... Bf6 15. Nf2 Be7 16. Kf1 Nf6 17. Kg2
{ White doesn't have to rush anywhere. If Black moves something on the queenside, that is good for us because we will have more targets. }
17... Nfd7 18. Rab1 Na6 19. a3 c5 20. Bd1
{ The passive bishop is threatening to go to a4. } 20... Nb6 21. Qd3 Bd7 22.
Bc2 Rh8 { Black has nothing better to do... } 23. Bd2
{ The bishop will help with the b4-break, and also frees the e3-square for the knight to use it to jump to f5 at any moment. }
23... Nc7 24. Nfd1 Nc8
{ Allowing the exchange of the bishops is not favourable for Black, to say the least. Black can try  24...Ra7  25.Ne3  a4  but it will not prevent the breakthrough on the queenside.  26.Nf5  It is not easy to take this knight, because then the other knight will come to e4, which is also a very strong square.  26...Rg8  27.b3  axb3  28.Rxb3  Na4  29.Nxa4  Bxa4  30.Rb6±  and Black didn't manage to solve his problems of weak pawns on d6 and b7. }
25. Ba4 Na7 26. Bxd7 Qxd7 27. Ne3 b5
{ In general, it is not advisable to play where the opponent is stronger, but it is hard to recommend better moves for Black here.   27...Rhb8  The waiting strategy also doesn't look very good.  28.b4  axb4  29.axb4  Na6  30.bxc5  Nxc5  31.Qc2  b5  32.Ne2±  Very tough to defend this position with Black. }
28. b4 { Opening the position favours the side with the more active pieces. }
28... axb4 29. axb4 cxb4
{ Better, but not good for Black, was  29...Rhb8  30.bxc5  dxc5  31.cxb5  Naxb5  32.Nc4±  Weak pawns and passive pieces in Black's camp. }
30. Rxb4 Na6 31. Rb2 Nc5 32. Qb1 bxc4 33. Nxc4 Nc8 34. Qc2 Rd8 35. Be3 f6 36.
Bxc5 dxc5 37. Rhb1
{ Black is lost, and White very confidently converted this into a full point. }
37... Ra7 38. Nd1 Nd6 39. Nde3 Rc7 40. Nxd6 Bxd6 41. Nc4 Bf8 42. Rb6 Kg7 43. d6
Ra7 44. Ne3 Qe6 45. Nf5+ Kh8 46. Qxc5 Ra2+ 47. R1b2 Bxd6 48. Qc2 Ra7 49. Qc6
