1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Qd2
exd5 9. exd5 Re8 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3
{ This has all been coveredhere. } 13... Qb6
{ Black is hoping for some ...Qb4 counterplay. } 14. Qc2
{ Nice move! Preventing ...Qb4 altogether. } 14... Kh8
{ Now Black wants some Ng8-Bh6 and exchange a few minor pieces. As we know, this is something White should avoid.   Black is losing a lot of material after  14...Qb4  15.Nb5+-  . }
15. Bd2 { Very precise! } 15... a6
{ 15...Ng8  16.g4!  White is gaining space on the kingside and preventing the exchange of the bishops.  16...Bh6  17.g5  Bg7  18.Kg2±  Black didn't achieve anything and White is just improving his position further. }
16. Rae1 { Exchanging heavy pieces is in White's favour. } 16... Rxe1 17. Rxe1
Re8 18. Bd1 { Preparing for f4 and g4, and also stepping away from ...Ne5. }
18... Rxe1+ 19. Bxe1 Qd8 20. Qe2 Ne8 21. g4
{ Gaining space on the kingside, where eventually White should win the game. }
21... Nc7 22. f4 Bd4+ 23. Kg2 Kg8 24. b3 Kf8
{ It is better to stay passive than to open the queenside for the white pieces.  24...b5  is not really a counterplay, but just making it easier for White to win the game.  25.Ne4  bxc4  26.bxc4  Qb8  27.Ba4!  White's worst minor piece is getting active.  27...Nb6  28.Bc6±  . }
25. Ne4 Qe7 26. g5 Ne8 27. h4 Ng7
{ Finally Black has some threat again: to put the knight on f5. } 28. Ng3
{ White is not allowing that! } 28... f6
{ It is very hard to decide what to do with the kingside pawns, but not moving them looks extremely passive:  28...Qxe2+  29.Bxe2  Bb2  30.h5  Bd4  Black is just waiting.  31.h6  Ne8  32.Bg4±  White can bring the king to e2, play Ba5 and Ne4 and at some point go for the f5-break. }
29. Qxe7+ Kxe7 30. Bg4
{ White's goal is to provoke ...f5, where he can sacrifice later and break through on the kingside. }
30... b6
{ 30...f5  31.Be2  Nf8  32.Bd3!  This is the precise move order. White will push h5 but if Black takes it, he will not recapture, but take on f5 instead.  32...Kf7  33.h5  b6   33...gxh5?  34.Nxf5  Nxf5  35.Bxf5+-  Black has no chances here: the h5-pawn will fall very soon.  34.h6  Ne8  35.Kf3±  White has two ways to play here: to sacrifice on f5 or to play for Bc2-a3-b4 and then Ba4. Both are extremely unpleasant for Black.   @@StartFEN@@5n2/1p2k1np/p2p2p1/2pP1pP1/2Pb1P1P/1P4N1/P3B1K1/4B3 w - - 2 32@@EndFEN@@  32.h5  would allow Black to set up a fortress:  32...gxh5!  33.Nxh5  Nxh5  34.Bxh5  Be3=  With ...Ng6 next and Black is holding this position. }
31. Bd2 a5 32. Ne2 Bb2 33. Kh3 Nb8
{ The knight is going to b4, where it will make it difficult for the light-squared bishop to attack the f5-pawn. }
34. Ng3 Na6 35. h5
{ Maybe the best course of action for White was  35.f5!?  Nb4  36.a4  Be5  37.gxf6+  Bxf6  38.fxg6  hxg6  39.Ne4±  Black has the 2 weaknesses, but because of the reduced material he still has chances to hold the game. }
35... gxh5
{ A very bad move. Instead,  35...f5!  would have kept Black in the game:  36.Bd1  Nb4  37.h6  Ne8  38.a4  Kf7±  It is still not trivial to win this position with White. }
36. Bf5
{ White will take on h7 first, and only then will collect the h5-pawn. } 36...
