1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O 6. Nf3 d6 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O
exd5 9. exd5 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7 12. Qd1 Nh5 13. Ne4 Be5 14. f4
{ All this has been coveredhere. } 14... f5
{ Black is initiating exchanges, but it will be not enough to achieve equality. }
15. fxe5 fxe4 16. Rxf8+
{ It is very important to start like this. White can't allow a strong black knight on e5.  16.Bxe4  Rxf1+  17.Qxf1  Nxe5⩱  Black's position is slightly preferable here because of the very strong knight on e5, and the not so strong bishop on e4. }
16... Qxf8 17. e6
{ Exchanging the d3-bishop for the d7-knight is great for White. This bishop was restricted by friend @@StartBracket@@c4-d5@@EndBracket@@ as well as enemy @@StartBracket@@g6-h7@@EndBracket@@ pawns. }
17... exd3 18. exd7 Qf5 19. g4
{ This is a must if we want to take the pawn on d3. } 19... Qxd7 20. Qxd3
{ 20.gxh5?  would be a huge mistake. For starters, Black has a perpetual check, but maybe he has even more for the piece.  20...Qxh3→ }
20... Nf6
{ The position has simplified, but Black still has problems because of the weak dark squares, the weakness of the d6-pawn, and for now the knight is also dominated. }
21. Qf3 Qg7
{ 21...Rf8  looks like the most natural way to protect the knight, but Black will get a very passive position after this move.  22.Bh6!  Rf7  23.Re1  The bishop on h6 is very unpleasant, and Black's king is in constant danger.  23...Ne8  24.Qe3  Ng7  25.b3±  Black has no counterplay, and even though it is not so easy to win such positions, they are even more difficult to defend.   21...Qf7  intending Nd7-e5.  22.Bg5  Nd7  23.Qxf7+  Kxf7  24.Rf1+!  Very precise, highlighting the weakness of the d6-pawn.  24...Kg8  25.Be7  Ne5  26.b3!  No rush. We are not interested in giving up any of our strong pawns for the weak d6-pawn.  26...Nf7  27.Rf6  Kg7  28.Re6  Re8  The only way to indirectly protect the pawn on d6 is losing an exchange and the game.  29.Bf6+  Kf8  30.Bg7++-   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp3q1p/3p1np1/2pP2B1/2P3P1/5Q1P/PP6/R5K1 b - - 4 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Rf8  23.Re1!  The rook is going to e6 to attack the d6-pawn.   23.Rf1?  allows further simplifications and gives Black excellent drawing chances.  23...Ne4!  24.Qxf7+  Rxf7  25.Rxf7  Kxf7=  Black is holding here.  23...Nd7  24.Qxf7+  Rxf7  25.Re6  Ne5  26.Bh6!  Rd7  27.b3+-  Black basically can't move here. In case of ...Kf7, then Bf4 is very unpleasant. }
22. Bd2
{ The only inaccuracy in the game from White.  22.Bf4!  was better, to attack the d6-pawn immediately.  22...Re8  23.Rf1!  Preparing to meet ...Ne4 with a small tactical trick.   23.Bxd6?  Ne4⇆  and finally Black gets real counter chances.  23...Ne4  24.Bh6!  Qe7  25.Kg2+-  With Qf4 and Re1 coming, Black is basically in zugzwang.   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp4qp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P2BP1/5Q1P/PP6/R5K1 b - - 4 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Nd7  Black is trading the d6-pawn for the c4-pawn, which would not be a bad deal. The problem is that this is also giving White access to Black's king.  23.Bxd6  Qd4+  24.Kh1!  Qxc4  25.Rf1  Kh8  26.Qf7+-  Black can't hold this position too long with such a king.   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp4qp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P2BP1/5Q1P/PP6/R5K1 b - - 4 22@@EndFEN@@  22...h5  Black is trying to get some activity, but it is always his king who will end up weaker.  23.gxh5  Nxh5  24.Bxd6  Qxb2  25.Rf1  Qd4+  26.Kh2±  The difference between the kings guarantees White a big advantage. }
22... Nd7 23. Bc3 Ne5 24. Qe4 Rf8
{ 24...Re8!  After this move Black would have excellent chances to hold the game.  25.Rf1  Qe7⩲ }
25. Rf1
{ White wants to go to a queen endgame, where he will be much better because of the protected passer on d5. }
25... Qe7
{ 25...Rxf1+  Keeping the knights on the board was a better fighting chance for Black, but the position remains very difficult.  26.Kxf1  Qf7+  27.Kg2  Nd7  28.Kg3± }
26. Rxf8+ Kxf8 27. Bxe5 dxe5
{ Only move, since the pawn endgame is completely hopeless for Black. } 28. Qe3
Qd6 29. Kg2 Kg8
{ This loses quickly, but the alternatives were not much better.  29...b6  30.g5  Ke8  31.Qe4  Kd7  32.Qg4+  Kd8  33.Qf3±  The queen is controlling the f-file and the king is going to e4. }
30. Kf3 Qa6 31. Ke4 Qxc4+ 32. Kxe5
{ Not only is the d-pawn dangerous, but Black's king is also in trouble. }
32... Qxa2 33. Ke6 Qxb2 34. Qf3 Kg7 35. g5 *

